<HEADLINE>
DODGERS ACQUIRE BOHANON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He doesn't have a well-known nickname like the
``Big Unit'' nor is he well known. But for the time being, the
Dodgers hope Brian Bohanon can fill a void in their starting
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Greg McMichael's short stay with the Dodgers came
to an end Friday when he was traded back to the New York Mets for
the left-handed Bohanon. The Dodgers also reinstated right-handed
reliever Darren Hall from the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon was 2-4 with a 3.15 ERA in 25 games for the Mets this
season. However, the Dodgers' new and possibly temporary fifth
starter has made just four starts this season and is 1-1 with a
3.00 ERA in those games. The 29-year-old is 20-23 in parts of nine
major-league seasons with Texas, Detroit, Toronto and the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Glenn Hoffman said Bohanon is expected to be at
Dodger Stadium today and pitch against the Padres on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good trade for both teams,'' said Hoffman, who spoke to
Bohanon on the phone. ``We're getting a left-hander who has done
some starting.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade was the second in the last seven days for Dodgers
interim general manager Tommy Lasorda, who sent
infielder/outfielder Paul Konerko and pitcher Dennis Reyes to
Cincinnati for All-Star closer Jeff Shaw on July 4. And for the
second straight day, Lasorda strongly denied any talks with Seattle
about ace Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I checked with a few guys about Bohanon and they say he is the
type of guy who gets batters out,'' Lasorda said. ``I also talked
to a couple of guys who played with him and they said the guy is a
pretty good pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon's spot as the Dodgers' fifth starter may not be etched
in stone. There is speculation the Dodgers are interested in
sending infielder Wilton Guerrero, who asked for a trade earlier
this season, for either Montreal left-hander Carlos Perez or
Cincinnati left-hander Mike Remlinger, both starters. Several other
teams are interested in Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   McMichael and pitcher Dave Mlicki were traded to the Dodgers
from the Mets for pitchers Hideo Nomo and Brad Clontz on June 4. In
12 games with the Dodgers, McMichael was 0-1 with one save and a
4.40 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fox people are going to turn (the Dodgers) around,'' said
McMichael, who is a good friend of Bohanon's. ``This is going to be
a real good team for years to come. I'm disappointed because I saw
that things were starting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is strange. I should ask (the Mets) for a raise for mental
stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall was 0-1 with a 12.00 ERA in two relief appearances this
season before being placed on the DL on April 8 to rehabilitate a
right rotator cuff tear. Either infielder Alex Cora or third
baseman Adrian Beltre will be demoted when Bohanon arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's willing: If Lasorda's interim label never becomes
permanent, Padres pitching coach Dave Stewart could emerge as a
candidate to be general manager. The four-time 20-game winner, who
pitched for the Dodgers from 1981-83, is in his first season as San
Diego's pitching coach after serving a year as assistant to Padres
general manager Kevin Towers.
</P>
<P>
   Although Stewart said he's ready for the challenge, the
African-American hasn't forgotten that there are no minority
general managers in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is the game is what it is,'' Stewart said.
``I've had a lot of ups and downs and you just ride it out and
eventually something will happen. In this world, think about it.
How many things surprise you about how minorities are dealt with?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
