<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAW LIKES TO PROVE THEM WRONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jeff Shaw is doomed to failure. He might never
earn another save. What worked in Cincinnati won't cut it in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   He hated to leave his hometown, the charmingly named Washington
Court House, Ohio, after being traded last weekend? Well, he might
as well go back, for all the good he'll do here.
</P>
<P>
   I say these things because I like Jeff Shaw _ having known him
since 5:30 p.m. Friday _ and I want to help.
</P>
<P>
   And the one thing that seems to help the Dodgers' new bullpen
ace more than anything else is hearing somebody say he can't do
something.
</P>
<P>
   One spring day in 1992, Cleveland Indians manager Mike Hargrove
sent Shaw back to the minor leagues and was kind enough to tell him
exactly why.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he was tired of seeing the same mistakes over and
over again, and he told me I didn't have the ability to pitch in
the big leagues,'' Shaw recalled before the Dodgers' game against
the San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw set out _ he went from Cleveland to the Montreal Expos to
the Chicago White Sox and then Cincinnati Reds _ to prove Hargrove
wrong. And after leading the National League in bullpen ``holds''
(22) in 1996 and saves (42) in '97, he can declare, ``I think I've
done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove, perhaps embarrassed by his misjudgment, denies making
the remark that Shaw remembers so vividly. The two men talked and
buried the hatchet last month after a Reds-Indians game in which
Shaw recorded his 17th save of the season and lowered his ERA to
1.03.
</P>
<P>
   ``He goes, `I don't remember saying it, but if I did, I
apologize,''' Shaw said. ``I said, `Well, that's something that's
driven me for the last (eight) years.'''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for the inspiration, Grover.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it hasn't been that simple. Along the way, there were
others to prove wrong.
</P>
<P>
   One spring day in '96, Reds closer Jeff Brantley went on the
disabled list and manager Ray Knight passed over Shaw to give the
temporary job to young Marcus Moore. Shaw assumed he was in
Knight's doghouse.
</P>
<P>
   At Brantley's behest, Shaw asked for a meeting with the manager,
and it lasted so long he was fined in kangaroo court for missing
batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   But that night, Shaw was given a chance to earn his first Reds
save and he came through with three perfect innings against the
Dodgers. Though Brantley healed and got his job back, when he was
injured again and lost for the season in May '97, Shaw became the
closer for good.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it hasn't been that simple. Even then, as a
31-year-old with 12 years in pro baseball, Shaw had to prove people
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said, `You've never closed before, can you handle the
pressure?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   How's this for an answer? He led the league in saves as well as
save opportunities (49) and saves percentage (85.7) last year. And
he was third in the league in saves (23) when the trade went down
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw won't intimidate anybody with his appearance. He's the size
(6-foot-2, 200 pounds) of a one-time three-sport star, and he
cracked a career-high 97 mph on the radar gun in his one-inning
All-Star Game appearance Tuesday. But his easy-going manner that
doesn't fit the ``closer'' template.
</P>
<P>
   Shake the hand the Dodgers hope will throw their next
championship-clinching strike, and he looks you square in the eye,
saying sure, he's got time for an interview, right after he takes
time for this other interview.
</P>
<P>
   His son Travis, 8, is with him at the park and fetches Dad a
soda while we talk. His wife Julie and their other child, Molli, 3,
are spending the next few weeks with him in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think closers get that label, that you've got to be a wild
man,'' Shaw said. ``I'm not that type of person. I'm actually a
nice guy.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as he disliked leaving the Reds, from whom he accepted a
below-market $2.8 million for three years to stay close to home,
being traded to the Dodgers had its plusses. Shaw was a Dodgers fan
growing up in the aura of the Big Red Machine. His ``A student''
tickets were always for Dodgers games.
</P>
<P>
   So how did the current Dodgers return the affection? With less
than unbridled enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers players were quoted wondering if the front office traded
away too much potential, in infielder Paul Konerko and left-hander
Dennis Reyes, to get Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as much as ever, there are people to prove wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, they liked those guys (Konerko and Reyes), and they
don't know me from Adam,'' Shaw said of his new teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until they get to know me and realize what kind of person I am
and what kind of driving force I have inside me, everybody's going
to have their opinion. But no comments are going to bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing Shaw, they'll only help him. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
