<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ, RED SOX FALL AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ For the second night in a row, Red Sox fans were
left to wonder how these Orioles possibly could be closer to last
place than first in the American League East.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Davis, one of seven current or former All-Stars who faced
Red Sox ace Pedro Martinez Friday night, hit a two-out home run in
the eighth inning, breaking a 2-2 tie and lifting the Orioles to
their second straight 3-2 decision over the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a team you want to be playing going down the
stretch,'' said Mo Vaughn, well aware that the Red Sox close the
season with four games at Fenway Park against the Orioles.
``Winning ain't going to be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a lot of guys with rings out there, a lot of
'em,'' said Vaughn, whose home run leading off the seventh had tied
the score at 2.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez allowed the Orioles just five hits in eight innings,
but two were home runs. Mike Bordick homered in the third and Davis
jumped on a hanging 1-and-0 curveball and hit it over the
center-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too bad I couldn't give up a double, or even a triple there,''
said Martinez, a loser for the first time in more than a month
(June 5), his record dropping to 11-3. ``Home run, I have to
swallow it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Orosco, the 40-year-old lefthanded reliever, who was on
the mound in Shea Stadium when the Mets won Game 7 of the '86
Series, retired Vaughn on a tapper and struck out Troy O'Leary
without O'Leary lifting the bat off his shoulder for the first two
outs of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles manager Ray Miller, playing the percentages, brought in
closer Armando Benitez to face John Valentin, who had two of
Boston's seven hits. Valentin fouled off several pitches, then
chased a 2-and-2 slider to strike out, as a sellout crowd of 48,043
in Camden Yards roared.
</P>
<P>
   ``One shot to win the ballgame, put the best pitcher you have
there, and Armando came through,'' said Miller.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, who entered the All-Star break having won five of
their last six and eight of 10, have lost their first two since
resuming play.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was in the game only because the Orioles' starting DH,
Harold Baines, who had singled and scored Baltimore's second run,
came out of the game with a strained hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of pride over here,'' said Davis, who hasn't
played in the outfield since being hit in the right elbow by a
pitch from the Mets' Rick Reed June 24. ``A lot of people haven't
been giving us a lot of credit, talking about how we haven't been
emotional enough, but that's the makeup of this ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never quit, our manager is not quitting, and nobody in the
clubhouse is going to quit.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, working with seven days' rest, having skipped
Tuesday's All-Star Game, was no worse for the layoff, throwing only
104 pitches in eight innings. But he was matched pitch for pitch by
Orioles rookie Sidney Ponson, who took a 2-1 lead into the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   But just when plans were being made to declare a national
holiday in Aruba for Ponson, the third native son of the island to
play in the big leagues, Vaughn squared matters in the seventh by
driving a ball into the left-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   The home run was Vaughn's first since June 20, his 22d of the
season, and 12th home run of his career in Oriole Park at Camden
Yards. Except for Vaughn's homer, the Red Sox managed just six
singles against Ponson and three relievers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to start hitting,'' Vaughn said. ``We will. A couple
days away, our timing's off. We got to get our feet on the ground.
We will.''
</P>
<P>
   In 12 of his 18 starts before Friday night, Martinez had allowed
two runs or fewer, including his last four before the All-Star
break, in which he allowed one run three times and shut out the
Montreal Expos for six innings in his last outing. In those 12
starts, Martinez's earned run average was 0.90.
</P>
<P>
   But the two homers he allowed Friday night made it a yield of 18
this season, two more than all of last season. Twelve of those
homers came in a span of four starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The balls they hit out, they hit out,'' Martinez said. ``I
don't have any complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're facing better power hitters in this league. You can't
pitch around one batter to get to another, because they're all good
hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Even here in Baltimore. Maybe especially here in Baltimore,
despite the 40-50 record, 13 1/2 games behind the Red Sox in the
wild-card hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're out of it,'' Martinez said. ``I think if
they try, they can get back in the race. But it's amazing to see a
team like that and they're not in first or second place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
