<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIPKEN HARDLY MEEK ON STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ If it makes you feel any better, Cal Ripken missed a
few days of school when he was a kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't one of those perfect attendance guys,'' Ripken said
before playing in consecutive game No. 2,568 Friday night, a 3-2
win over the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   His streak goes back to 1982 and it helped save baseball in the
dark summer of 1995. In an age of spoiled athletes who take the
money and lie down on the job, Ripken carries the work ethic of the
fans in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, now that the Orioles stink, the streak has become the
embodiment of everything that's wrong in Baltimore. Brooks Robinson
believes the streak is a mistake. Bob Costas says everybody can use
a day off. A Baltimore columnist wrote that the streak has become
more important than winning.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken and the Orioles have become prisoners of the streak.
There are fans and writers in Baltimore who think that Ray Miller
replaced Davey Johnson as manager because Johnson was not afraid to
end the streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always amazes me,'' Ripken said before Friday night's game
against the Red Sox. ``At a low point or a frustrating point, I
wonder, `Why do I have to sit here and actually defend the desire
to go out and play?' I think it should be the people that don't
want to play that should have to defend their position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the streak the reason why we're losing? Is the streak the
reason why we won last year? The answer to both is no. It kind of
makes me laugh a little bit the way it is brought up. The issue
should be performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller won't admit to any pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the time comes for him to sit down, he'll do it himself,
or I'll do it,'' said the manager. ``If I thought he was hurt to
the point where he couldn't help us, I'd sit him down. He was
probably one day away from taking himself out last year with his
back. Probably it'll be an injury or retirement. I wish I had 24
other guys with a two-week streak. We'd be in pretty good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Ripken, 38 next month, won't answer hypotheticals about how the
streak might end, but it's hard to imagine Miller, or any manager,
putting Ripken on the bench without the star's permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The streak, like everything else, will take care of itself,''
Ripken said. ``If something happens, it happens. It could end with
an injury. It could end in many different ways. When it presents
itself, who knows? How am I supposed to know how it will end?''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Palmer says it's not a matter of giving Ripken a day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``That won't do anyone much good,'' said the Hall of Fame hurler
who teamed with Ripken to win a World Series in 1983. ``It's more a
matter of looking at your lineup on a given day, and seeing if you
might have a lefthanded-hitting third baseman who has a better
chance against a hard-throwing righty that day. But this team
doesn't really have that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ripken's backup is Jeff Reboulet. Reboulet bats right and is
hitting .278 with no homers and three RBIs. Ripken entered Friday
night's game hitting .258 with seven homers and 37 RBIs, numbers
almost identical to those of Boston third baseman, John Valentin
(.263, 11, 37) who is 31 and just signed a four-year contract.
Ripken has three errors to Valentin's 12. Ripken delivered the
game-winning, two-out, two-strike single against the Red Sox
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to play every day, you have to be worthy,'' said
Ripken. ``If at some point, you're not worthy, it ends. But so far
it hasn't. When I no longer deserve to be the every-day third
baseman, it'll end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strip away everything and it's simple. I'm a baseball player.
I love being a baseball player. You have a small window in the
grand scheme of things to be a baseball player. You can't play
until you're 65. To me, I'm healthy and I want to play the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the good things that has come out of the streak is that
people relate to it and apply the same approach to what they do.
It's important to them, the same way coming to the ballpark and
being ready to play is important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   True. The hero in every household is the tired parent who hauls
his or her butt out of bed and goes to work ... every ... single
... day. Though Ripken is paid millions to play a kid's game, he
provides America's plumbers, teachers, painters, and factory
workers with a reason to believe in professional athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles play the Red Sox again Saturday at 1:15. Cal Ripken
is expected to be in the lineup.
</P>
</TEXT>
