<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ATHLETICS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS EDGE ATHLETICS, 1-0, ON BASES-LOADED WALK IN NINTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Rangers pitcher Rick Helling and Oakland's Tom
Candiotti waged a brilliant scoreless pitching duel for eight
innings last night.
</P>
<P>
   But when the managers had to go to the bullpen in the ninth
inning, Rangers manager Johnny Oates was able to call on All-Star
closer John Wetteland while Athletics manager Art Howe had to
settle for Bill Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Advantage Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers beat Taylor for the second consecutive day when
Kevin Elster drew a bases-loaded walk in the ninth inning to give
the Rangers a 1-0 victory at the Oakland Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland saved it in the ninth for Helling, who raised his
record to 12-4 and lowered his earned-run average to 4.12.
</P>
<P>
   Will Clark started the Rangers' winning rally with a single to
right and went to third on Juan Gonzalez's double into the
right-field corner. Luis Alicea ran for Clark and Rusty Greer was
intentionally walked.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor almost got out of the inning. With the infield in, Ivan
Rodriguez forced Alicea at home with a grounder to second baseman
Rafael Bournigal. Alicea, though, prevented a double play by
dumping catcher A.J. Hinch with a hard slide.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Stevens then flied out to short left, forcing Gonzalez to
stay at third. But Taylor walked Elster on five pitches to force in
the game-winning run.
</P>
<P>
   Helling held the Athletics to only four hits through seven
innings but made the mistake of walking Rickey Henderson to start
the eighth. Bip Roberts bunted him to second and Ben Grieve was
intentionally walked, putting runners at first and second for Matt
Stairs.
</P>
<P>
   Stairs worked the count full, then hit a line drive at second
baseman Mark McLemore, who made the catch and flipped to first to
double off Grieve.
</P>
<P>
   Candiotti also left after eight innings, holding the Rangers to
seven hits. He struck three and did not walk a batter.
</P>
<P>
   Candiotti and Helling dominated through eight innings, although
both teams did muster a couple of rallies. The Rangers got the
leadoff hitter on in three of those seven innings but couldn't get
them home.
</P>
<P>
   They also put runners at first and third with one out in the
seventh on consecutive singles by Rodriguez and Stevens. But
Candiotti got Elster to hit a grounder at third baseman Mike
Blowers to start an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers missed again on an equally enticing opportunity.
Rusty Greer started the inning with a grounder just inside the
first-base bag for a double and went to third on Rodriguez's long
fly ball to right. Candiotti came back to strike out Stevens on a
knuckler in the dirt, then retired Elster on a fly to left.
</P>
<P>
   Clark saved Helling in the fourth after Bip Roberts led off with
a walk. Roberts broke on a full-count pitch to Grieve, who smacked
a hard grounder down the first baseline. Clark made a nice
backhanded stop to take away a double and got the out at first.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts reached second, but Helling got Matt Stairs to foul out
and, after Jason Giambi was intentionally walked, Blowers grounded
out to the end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics started another rally in the fifth when singles by
Rafael Bournigal and Rickey Henderson put runners on first and
second with two out. This time, Helling retired Roberts on a high
pop to third baseman Fernando Tatis to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Miguel Tejada squelched a sixth-inning Rangers threat
with some fancy glove work. Tom Goodwin led off with a single to
right, but then Tejada made a nice backhanded grab of Mark
McLemore's one-hop smash to get a force at second. Candiotti
followed that by getting Clark and Juan Gonzalez on fly balls to
left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
