<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VAN-DEATHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO KILLED ON DAY TRIP FOR CHILDREN  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE LeDUFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two people died and 24 others were injured on Friday
night when an overloaded van carrying a group of Brooklyn children
from a day trip to a Pennsylvania amusement park flipped over,
scattering bodies across a highway, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The children were on a trip to the Knoebels Amusement Park in
Elysburg, Pa., with their day camp, sponsored by the Bedford
Stuyvesant Restoration Corp., a community development group.
</P>
<P>
   Victims of the accident were taken by helicopter to hospitals
near the accident site near Scotrun, Pa., where Interstates 80 and
380 merge near popular vacation spots in the Poconos.
</P>
<P>
   One of the victims was a child who was taken to Lehigh Valley
Hospital in Bethel and died shortly after 6 p.m., said Kristin
Hoffman, a hospital spokesman. Seven others were admitted. The
hospital would not release their conditions until their families
had been notified.
</P>
<P>
   The second person who died was taken to the Pocono Medical
Center, said Dawn Lusardi, an administrator with the hospital; that
victim's age and identity were not available on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The group left the Bedford Stuyvesant Restoration Center, at
1368 Fulton Avenue, with approximately 75 people around 7 a.m.
Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty children were loaded into a bus and 23 others were packed
into a blue van meant for 12 people, said Cpl. Charles Chaio, a
spokesman for the Pennsylvania State Police.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear why so many people were crammed into the van.
</P>
<P>
   After a day of roller coasters, Ferris wheels and the
merry-go-round at the Knobels Amusement Park, the group climbed
back into the vehicles and set out for Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   It was about 5:30 p.m, Chaio said, when the driver of the van
fell asleep and then rear-ended a blue Saturn Sedan.
</P>
<P>
   The driver, who suffered only minor injuries, lost control of
the van at junction of Interstates 80 and 380.
</P>
<P>
   The van then collided with a cement embankment, ricocheted off
the wall, flipped onto its side and skidded back onto the road.
Three children were trapped inside. The rest were thrown across the
highway and some into the gully that divides eastbound and
westbound traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The other bus from the center and its 54 children idled in the
traffic jam that reached five miles in length as the authorities
transported the bodies and swept the metal carnage from the
highway.
</P>
<P>
   Frantic relatives of the children who were injured traveled to
Pennsylvania hospitals in buses provided by the mayor's office.
Others, who were waiting at the Brooklyn center, burst into tears
when the large bus returned.
</P>
<P>
   Sabrina Johnson, an aunt of Jasmine Johnson, 12, who was on the
trip and rode on the bus said that although her niece could not see
the carnage on Interstate 80, she knew what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was traumatized,'' Ms. Johnson said. ``She said, `Auntie,
I swear, I never want to go on a bus to camp again in my life.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The director of the corporation, Roderick Mitchell, had little
to say except that ``our policy is to obey all state and federal
laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said he did not know who was driving the van or whether
he was an employee of the center.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators with the mayor's Office of Emergency Management
were interviewing the children inside the Brooklyn center Friday
night. Inside the building children were crying, others silent as
they wondered what had happened to their friends.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen of the injured children were being treated at the
Pocono Medical Center. Four were listed in stable condition and
were admitted. The others were being evaluated or waiting to go
home.
</P>
<P>
   Two other children were taken to Lehigh Valley Medical Center
and were still being treated in the emergency room Friday night.
They were said to be in stable condition.
</P>
<P>
   At Community Medical Center in Scranton, a 23-year-old woman and
a male 17-year-old were listed in guarded condition, said Gerry
Snyder, a spokesman for the hospital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 0237EDT &QL; 
