<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HONGKONG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: SO FAR, HONG KONG REMAINS LARGELY INTACT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By PHILIP M. BOFFEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, July 11:
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ _ This dynamic financial center has been under
Chinese control for a year now. There are new laws and a governing
structure that lay the groundwork for future repression should the
leadership in Beijing choose to get nasty. But for now virtually
none of the fears voiced at the time of transition from British
rule have come to pass.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no crackdowns on dissidents and no tanks or army
patrols in the streets. The press is more cautious and the courts
ducked a case involving mainland interests. But there has been no
overt censorship, no meddling in the courts or the civil service,
no interference with the city's rambunctious free markets. There is
distress over a plummeting economy, a result of the Asian economic
crisis rather than the takeover by China. But from all the casual
observer can see, the average citizen has just as much freedom now
as under the British.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials, businessmen, diplomats from the West and
human rights activists all voice relief that the first year of
transition has gone so smoothly. Human Rights Watch, whose office
some thought might be closed down because of its persistent
criticism of repression in mainland China, has instead found itself
invited to official government parties and showcase events.
</P>
<P>
   Just why China has kept hands off is a matter of speculation.
Some say President Jiang Zemin has been so intent on securing his
own power that he has little stomach for meddling in Hong Kong, or
that he wants to improve relations with the West and hence can't
look totalitarian, or that he hopes to persuade Taiwan to rejoin
the mainland by showing, through the experience of Hong Kong, just
how painless that transition can be. The more cynical say China has
done such a good job of rigging the governmental structure and
installing its sympathizers in power that it has no need to take
overt action. Others say China never intended to interfere with
such a valuable center of trade and finance.
</P>
<P>
   But surely one major factor in the benign turn of events is the
vigilance of Hong Kong activists and citizens in defense of their
freedoms. Voters turned out in surprising numbers for the recent
legislative elections and gave heavy support to democratically
oriented candidates. Activists continue to demonstrate at the drop
of a cause, sometimes by the thousands or even tens of thousands.
The more courageous elements of the press are quick to protest any
perceived sellout of historical freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   That will be an important trait in the years ahead, for there
have been some worrisome developments. The legislature has been
structured in such a way that democratically elected candidates
will not be able to gain dominance for at least 10 years. Laws have
been passed that make it easier for the government to crack down on
activists on national security grounds, and a pending proposal
would prohibit acts of treason, secession and subversion against
China in language so sweeping that political dissent and media
coverage of it might be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   The more immediate danger is that Hong Kong, eager to avoid
confrontation, will shackle itself without any prodding from
Beijing. The criminal justice system is accused of ducking when
asked to prosecute an agency of the mainland government and a
individual with strong mainland ties. Many Chinese-language
newspapers, which once routinely referred to the Tiananmen Square
``massacre,'' have now downgraded it to an ``incident'' or
``event,'' and the journalists' association decries frequent
self-censorship on such sensitive issues as Tibet, Taiwan and
separatist movements in Xinjiang Province. But even the new
chairman of the association, who describes himself as a strong
critic of China, gives credit to Beijing for ``bending over
backward not to interfere'' in Hong Kong's affairs, ``at least on
the surface.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
