A0358 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-KIDS-PROTECT-     07-11 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-KIDS-PROTECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PROTECTING NEW YORK'S CHILDREN  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, July 11:
</P>
<P>
   Two years after the creation of New York City's Administration
for Children's Services under the leadership of Nicholas Scoppetta,
child protection programs have improved but serious deficiencies
persist. The brutal sexual abuse of three children in Brooklyn and
the near-starvation of a 2-year-old boy in a Staten Island foster
home show recent reforms have not been swift or comprehensive
enough to protect these children who were under the city's watch.
</P>
<P>
   Now the agency faces a legal challenge that could result in
court-ordered intervention or even receivership control of the
child welfare system. Court management of the delivery of social
services is not a happy prospect because systematic reforms are
rarely possible without the willing cooperation of political
leaders and government agencies. But the upcoming trial will be
useful if it spurs the Giuliani administration to redouble its
efforts to implement reforms it has promised.
</P>
<P>
   On July 27, trial begins in federal district court in a
class-action lawsuit brought on behalf of more than 100,000 abused
or neglected children in New York City. The lawsuit, which was
filed in December 1995, charges the city and state with violating
state and federal law in failing to protect this vulnerable
population. Since Judge Robert Ward of the federal district court
has indicated that he will consider evidence of the system's
current performance, it behooves officials to show that conditions
are improving measurably.
</P>
<P>
   Some positive changes have been made since the notorious death
of 6-year-old Elisa Izquierdo in 1995, and the subsequent creation
of ACS. Hundreds more caseworkers have been hired, cutting average
caseloads from 27 to 16, and worker qualifications have been
raised. But extended training has been offered only to newly hired
caseworkers, and accountability measures are mostly nonexistent.
The monitoring system is still so lax that there is no way to track
whether caseworkers are making the home visits that are required by
law.
</P>
<P>
   The children in the Brooklyn and Staten Island cases were
supposed to be monitored by caseworkers, though now it appears some
required visits were not made and the caseworkers could not spot
evident abuse. Last September, a panel of experts appointed by Ward
to provide an evaluation of child welfare services for the lawsuit
issued a devastating account of the city agency's failures.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, the city will have the opportunity to
demonstrate whether its track record is improving. The court will
decide if those reforms are sufficient for the city to avoid legal
liability. The city may yet avoid court intervention by
demonstrating that the reforms underway, coupled with a strong
financial commitment to improving children's services, are
beginning to work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 0238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980711.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0360 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-MAZER-NYT &LR;      07-11 0337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MAZER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM MAZER, 92, LEADER IN CHARITY AND A PAPER COMPANY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ William Mazer, who made his fortune in the paper
industry and shared it with charities at home and in Israel, died
on Tuesday at Mount Sinai Medical Center in Manhattan. He was 92
and lived on the Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   Mazer embraced the philanthropic traditions and commitments of
his father, Abraham Mazer, founder of the Hudson Pulp and Paper
Corp., of New York. He also served from 1953 to 1963 as president
of the Muscular Dystrophy Associations of America, which was
founded by his brother-in-law Paul Cohen in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   He was president and treasurer of the William and Helen Mazer
Foundation, which the couple endowed in 1979. It gives primarily to
higher education, social services and Jewish funds, community
centers and agencies. He was a past chairman of the Greater New
York Committee of the Israel Bond Organization and chairman of the
pulp and paper division of the UJA-Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Mazer grew up in Brooklyn, graduated from New York University in
1926 and joined the growing family business in 1927. He helped
build it into one of the country's biggest producers of paper goods
like tissue, towels, bags and tape.
</P>
<P>
   He served as president from 1955 to 1973 and then as chairman
until 1981, two years after Hudson was sold to the Georgia-Pacific
Corp., of Atlanta. He also helped establish the American-Israeli
Paper Co.
</P>
<P>
   He was a past president of the America-Israel Cultural
Foundation, a trustee emeritus of Brandeis University and a past
president and board member of the Ackerman Institute for Family
Therapy in Manhattan. He was also a supporter of Hebrew University
in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Helen Cohen Mazer, died in 1990. He is survived by a
daughter, Linda Berkowitz, of Berkeley Heights, N.J.; two sons,
Frank, of Cambridge, Mass., and Robert, of Amherst, Mass.; seven
grandchildren; and three great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 0238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
