<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
 PM-NYT-BUDGET
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top stories from The New York Times News Service
report for PMs of Saturday, July 11.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, (212) 556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. ET. To get
story repeats before this hour, call (212) 621-1595 for reruns on
AP DataFeatures or (214) 980-8305 or 8306 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   ART ADV: Graphics and photos have been sent, as indicated below,
to NYT graphic and photo subscribers. Clients needing
retransmissions or information, or non-subscribers seeking to
arrange individual purchases, should call (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPINION _ COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ COMMENTARY: TINA AND DISNEY ELOPE. By
Frank Rich. (This week, as Tina Brown made her exit from the
editor's chair, New York's media world was once again consumed with
nostalgia about The New Yorker's history and florid speculation
about its future.)
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ COMMENTARY: OVER AND OVER AGAIN. By
Thomas L. Friedman. (If someone were to make a movie about the
Mideast peace process, there could be only one appropriate title:
``Groundhog Day'' _ where the same day, the same discussions, just
get repeated over and over. But even Groundhog Day eventually came
to an end. And so will the peace process version. It closes May 4,
1999 _ the day the Oslo agreement runs out.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IRS-TAXPAYERS (Undated) _ How the new tax law will affect the
taxpayer. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   FEC-BROWN (Washington) _ District Judge Stanley Sporkin orders
the Federal Election Commission to investigate whether the late
commerce secretary, Ron Brown, sold seats on foreign trade missions
in exchange for campaign contributions. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-LAWSUITS (Washington) _ Many of the nation's judges,
frustrated because they have no choice but to deny the damage
claims of people who have been harmed by their health plans, are
finding themselves sympathetic with efforts in Congress to revamp
the laws that protect HMOs and other insurance carriers from
lawsuits. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-IMPLANTS-ASSESS _ After 16 years of litigation and more than
a dozen major scientific studies, the longstanding controversy over
the safety of breast implants reached a milestone of sorts on
Wednesday, when Dow Corning Corp. agreed to pay $3.2 billion to
settle the claims of tens of thousands of women who said they had
become ill from their implants. But the agreement did not end the
conflict over implants. An analysis. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MATH-TEACHERS (New York) _ New York schools are looking
abroad to fill teaching positions in math classes. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE (New York) _ Her nickname was Zambi.
That's what her fellow dancers at Radio City called the petite
17-year-old from New Orleans with big dreams and bigger ambitions.
She was tough, she was flirtatious and she married well enough to
leave the arduous life of a seven-show-a-week music hall ballerina
far behind. But Irene Zambelli Silverman, the wealthy 82-year-old
widow who disappeared last Sunday from her East 65th Street mansion
and is now feared dead, never quite shook off the glitter of her
stage days.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IMF (Moscow) _ President Boris Yeltsin went over the head
of the International Monetary Fund on Friday and urged Western
leaders to support a multi-billion-dollar package of financial
assistance to defend the Russian currency. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-BOMB-PLOT (London) _ In a coordinated sweep, police in
Ireland and England arrested nine people Friday and said they had
foiled a plot to bomb central London with only moments to spare. By
Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Separatist rebels appear
to be holding their own in the ethnic war in Kosovo province,
promising a long battle for control in the region. By Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-MOOD (Paris) _ France is back after a long period of
querulous gloom, introspection and self-doubt. Many people give the
Socialist-led government of Prime Minister Lionel Jospin credit for
the change. With graphic. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA (Lagos) _ The scene at the Abiola residence erupts into
a stoning when the former vice president speaks eloquently about
opening up the country to democracy but is jeered by Abiola
supporters; other developments. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-IMPACT (Undated) _ The Asian economic crisis has brought
further weakness to the world's commodities markets, causing prices
to fall faster. That has been good news for consuming countries but
very bad news for the producing nations that depend on commodities
for much of their export revenues. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   VIAGRA-COST-ASSESS (Undated) _ When Kaiser Permanente announced
it would not pay for Viagra, it acknowledged that its decision was
based on the cost of the drug _ a rare instance in which a health
plan has conceded that cost considerations affected a treatment
decision. By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Digest of the day's financial stories.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ideas Page &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DAD-STUDIES (Undated) _ It seems self-evident to just about
anyone who has ever had a father: a caring, involved dad is good
for a child. But try proving it. Social science is filled with
research that documents the impact of mothers on their children.
Flip through the literature and you find studies in which every
single gesture between mothers and babies was videotaped and
analyzed. Turn to the father's side of the family ledger, however,
and two things become apparent. Little research has occurred. And
the studies that do exist fail to cast much light on why fathers
really matter. By Patricia Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   NANCY-DREW (Undated) _ After nearly seventy years, Nancy Drew is
still going out with Ned Nickerson, and Joe Hardy is still dating
his friend Chet's sister, Iola. There are certain things about the
Nancy Drew and Hardy Boys series that just never change. Yet these
wildly popular teen-age detective novels _ since they began in
1927, about 200 million volumes have been sold _ have nonetheless
been seen to reflect historical changes. By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   BEACH-STUDIES (Undated) _ His full-color business card shows him
on the white sands of Lanakai Beach in Oahu, wearing white shorts
and matching knit shirt, his shadow knifing out into the blue-green
waters. Shimmering above the water in print the color of the sand
is the simple identification ``Dr. Beach.'' But he's really Dr.
Stephen Leatherman, who is an example of the way a few media-savvy
academics manage to transform themselves from mere toilers in
arcane academic groves to mini-celebrities. By Peter Applebome.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other Culture &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TENORS-WORLD-CUP (Paris) _ The Three Tenors give big Eiffel
Tower concert on eve of World Cup final. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (``s'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports of The Times column on
Felipe Alou and how he has seen baseball change for Latin players.
By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WORLDCUP (Paris) _ Situationer on the French defense, which
is the key to the team's chances of beating Brazil in the World Cup
final on Sunday. By Christopher Clarey.
</P>
</TEXT>
