<SLUG> BC-BBN-SHAW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAW COULD FORCE A TRADE FROM DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   During an easy ninth inning in his Dodgers debut Friday, closer
Jeff Shaw was impressive. Despite Shaw's heroics, it's not certain
he will be in Dodger blue next season.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the basic agreement between owners and
players, the 32-year-old Shaw can demand to be traded after the
season, and if the Dodgers don't honor his request, he would become
a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh-year major leaguer has five years of service and was
traded while under a multi-year deal. Therefore, if Shaw, who has
two more years left on his contract, makes such a demand, the
Dodgers would have 15 days to trade him or he becomes a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   A source said Dodgers interim general manager Tommy Lasorda
didn't inquire about that possibility before making a deal on July
4 for the All-Star Shaw that sent promising infielder/outfielder
Paul Konerko and left-hander Dennis Reyes to Cincinnati. Also,
Cincinnati general manager James Bowden scoffed at Lasorda when he
called him back in anger after realizing he'd been had, a source
said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the possibility of Shaw leaving after the
season, Lasorda said, ``I'm not worried about that. No... No.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be the reason why Lasorda promised reliever Antonio
Osuna that he would not be traded and that he would get some save
opportunities. On Friday, however, Dodgers manager Glenn Hoffman
said Osuna would receive save opportunities only when Shaw, who has
23 saves this season, needs a rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything about that,'' said Shaw, as he hurried
to get a cab after the game with his family. ``I don't know how my
contract reads. All I know is I'm here right now to close some
games.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, Shaw signed a three-year contract extension worth $8.4
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
