<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS RALLY TO WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With their most vocal cheerleader loving every minute of it in
the press box, the Dodgers inched back a little closer in the
National League West race.
</P>
<P>
   Two reserves added surprising punch to help the Dodgers overcome
a one-run deficit and score five runs in the eighth inning en route
to a dramatic 6-2 victory over the division-leading San Diego
Padres in front of 53,245 at Dodger Stadium on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Down 2-1 in the eighth, pinch-hitter Wilton Guerrero started off
the Dodgers rally with a one-out single. Rookie Adrian Beltre, who
came in at the top of the inning, followed with a single that
pushed Guerrero to third. Eric Young followed by milking a 3-2
count off San Diego's Dan Miceli before hitting a grounder to third
baseman Ken Caminiti. As Guerrero streaked toward the plate,
Caminiti overthrew catcher Carlos Hernandez, who landed awkwardly.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre ran to the plate, Hernandez recovered and retrieved the
ball, but it was too late to prevent the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   An enthusiastic Tommy Lasorda punched his fist in the air in
excitement afterward in the press box. And when the Dodgers
followed with the first of their next three runs in the inning, the
interim general manager exclaimed, ``Yea, yea, yea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what I hope to see,'' said Dodgers manager Glenn
Hoffman. ``We are the ones chasing them and we need to do that the
rest of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The second straight victory over the Padres trimmed the Dodgers'
deficit to 11{ games behind their divisional foe. The Dodgers
(45-44) also moved a game over .500 for the first time since May 13
and have won six of their last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a good foot on the play,'' said Caminiti. ``The
ball was hit to my left and I didn't have a chance to set my feet.
It was an error. Two runs scored.... That's baseball.'
</P>
<P>
   San Diego manager Bruce Bochy said, ``It was the difference in
the game.'
</P>
<P>
   Closer Jeff Shaw was also impressive in his first appearance as
a Dodger in the ninth inning. After getting his first batter to
ground out and striking out the next, Shaw finished the game by
getting Tony Gwynn to pop out to center field. Reliever Antonio
Osuna (5-0) took the win after pitching just 2/3 innings in the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Padres starter Kevin Brown entered with a 7-0 record in his last
eight outings. But Gary Sheffield gave the Dodgers a 1-0 lead with
a first-inning RBI single off Brown. Sheffield's hit moved his
hitting streak to 10 games and he has an average of .387 during the
span.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing with a little more fire,'' Sheffield said.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers starter Darren Dreifort began strongly, allowing just
one hit during the first three innings. But in the fourth, the
Padres took a 2-1 lead after an RBI single by Caminiti and a
two-out fielding error by Dodgers shortstop Juan Castro helped Greg
Vaughn score from third.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort lasted six innings for the second straight outing and
allowed two runs and four hits while striking out five and walking
four. The right-hander, however, hasn't won a game at Dodger
Stadium since May 16 against Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew with Dreifort and Brown on the mound it would be a
tight game,'' Hoffman said. ``It was a good win for us and
hopefully we'll get more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
