<HEADER>
A0420 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VEGAS-BUFFET-LIFESTYL     07-11 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEGAS-BUFFET-LIFESTYLE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAS VEGAS BUFFETS FOR TOURISTS ARE A STAPLE FOR MANY RESIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By FRANK BRUNI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Any outsider would have mistaken Ty Seedig for a
waiter, so nimbly did he balance three full-size dinner plates in
one hand, so fleetly did he hurtle toward a table in the rear of a
restaurant at the Main Street Station hotel and casino here.
</P>
<P>
   But any local resident would have caught the longing in Seedig's
eyes and the delight on his lips and known exactly what he was: a
buffet hound, practiced at the trick of maximizing each trip down
the trough.
</P>
<P>
   On his latest foray, he had netted what looked like an entire
bed of clams, a wedge of ahi tuna, a slab of trout and, of course,
a gargantuan steak, this being T-bone night, which jacked up the
price all the way to $10.99. Normally, it was $9.99, already a tad
steep by Las Vegas standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do about six buffets a week,'' Seedig, 38, said Tuesday
night as he rotated the plates before him to get a better angle at
the T-bone, which was obstructed by several red potatoes and an ear
of corn. His trimness suggested a metabolism worthy of scientific
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``For being fast and cheap,'' he mumbled between forkfuls, ``you
can't beat a buffet.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be the motto for this desert city, the nation's
capital of gorging as well as gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Overstuffed, underpriced smorgasbords have long been a staple of
Las Vegas' tourist trade, an enticement and reward for spending
money in casinos. But a lure for heavy rollers is becoming a
lifestyle for heavy eaters as the city's resident population
swells, in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people who line up at the buffets in casinos away
from ``the Strip'' live in Las Vegas, and the buffets they
patronize are growing more absurdly, insanely bountiful.
</P>
<P>
   The one at Main Street Station takes so many twists and turns
along its odyssey from iceberg lettuce to carrot cake that a person
would be wise to leave a trail of multi-colored cheese cubes to
find the way back.
</P>
<P>
   But Marvin Faleck and Anthony Ippolito had no trouble with their
bearings. Since moving to Las Vegas from New York's Long Island two
years ago, they have been on something of a buffet safari.
</P>
<P>
   It has taken them to more than a dozen buffets both off and on
the Strip, including an Oktoberfest event at the Nevada Palace that
featured vats of sauerkraut and a polka band, all for $6.99.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think we've done the MGM buffet,'' Faleck, 40,
said Tuesday night as he munched on some of Main Street's
undeniably tasty fried chicken.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Oz buffet?'' Ippolito, 38, responded, nibbling pizza.
``Yes, we have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Luxor and Excalibur _ feh!'' Faleck said, dismissing two
buffets with one syllable. ``It's $5.99 at Excalibur; you figure,
how can you go wrong? Feh!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Monte Carlo wasn't feh,'' he added, moving onto another
buffet. ``It was eh.''
</P>
<P>
   One of their friends, Danny Schaeffer, swallowed part of a
burrito and chimed in that an unfortunate episode a few months ago
left him wary of how long the food is maintained at safe
temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that experience,'' he said, ``I never say a buffet is
good until I've gone home, slept through the night and gotten up in
the morning without anything going wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most ardent pilgrims to the buffets are retirees,
who get coupons, discounts and other breaks that often put the
price of a limitless meal for two below $10. That includes
non-alcoholic beverages and as much pie, cake and pastry as a body
can manage.
</P>
<P>
   The buffet mavens of Las Vegas manage a lot. And they know
exactly when and where to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gold Coast only charges something like $5.30 for its lunch
buffet,'' said Ted Morgenbesser, 61, who took an early retirement
from his insurance job in Manhattan last year and moved here with
his wife, Vicki.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it serves until 3,'' Morgenbesser said. ``So if you get
there at 2:30 and have your big meal for the day, it's basically $5
a person. The price goes up at least a dollar for dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the bigger houses and lower taxes that help lure thousands
of transplants to Las Vegas every month, the buffets feed
newcomers' faith in greater bounty and possibility here. That
expectation is grounded partly in reality, and partly in myth.
</P>
<P>
   While the buffets do essentially give away much of the food each
patron consumes, losing money in the process, they easily make up
the difference in the coins that patrons cannot resist dropping in
the thicket of slot machines they must penetrate to get to the
make-your-own-taco bar.
</P>
<P>
   Ippolito and Faleck blew $17 on slots as they left Main Street
Station. But Faleck explained that the appeal of buffets
transcended mere economics.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they are is a goof,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are Chinese buffets and Japanese buffets, breakfast
buffets and lunch buffets, buffets that operate 24-hours a day and
buffets that span half the distance of a football field.
</P>
<P>
   The World Carnival Buffet at the Rio Hotel is at least that
long, and it has more than seven different ethnic sub-buffets. Even
at 9:30 p.m. Tuesday, hundreds of people were zipping _ or, it must
be said, waddling _ from Italy to Mexico and back again.
</P>
<P>
   Some old-timers scoff at such clutter, preferring to stick with
what they know and like best. For Erne D. Vining, 64, that's fish,
and he nightly heads to whichever buffet is having its weekly
seafood special.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Monday I go to Orleans,'' said Vining, who has lived in Las
Vegas for more than three decades. ``On Tuesday, Boulder Station.
On Wednesday, Fiesta. On Thursday, Sunset. On Friday, Fremont.
Sundays is Silverton.''
</P>
<P>
   And what of Saturday? Does he fast?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' Vining conceded in an almost apologetic voice,
``I cook.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 1136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
