   E-mail: triggp(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL: &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-PLOT (Miami) _ A Cuban exile who has waged a campaign of
bombings and assassination attempts aimed at toppling Fidel Castro
says that his efforts were supported financially for more than a
decade by the Cuban-American leaders of one of America's most
influential lobbying groups. By Ann Louise Bardach and Larry
Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-BOMBS (Guatemala City) _ During the summer of 1997, bomb
explosions ripped through some of Havana's most fashionable hotels,
restaurants and discotheques, killing a foreign tourist and sowing
confusion and nervousness throughout Cuba. It was something
shocking and inexplicable in a police state notorious for its tight
security, and from one end of the island to the other, people
speculated about who might be responsible. At his office here in
the mountains of Central America, a Cuban-American businessman
named Antonio Jorge ``Tony'' Alvarez was certain he knew the
answer. By Ann Louise Bardach and Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IMF (Moscow) _ The international effort to calm Russia's
shaky financial markets began to fall into place Saturday, as
Russian and World Bank officials completed negotiations on a new
loan. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-HABIBIE (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ President B.J. Habibie
consolidated his hold over Indonesian politics Saturday when one of
his close advisers won a hotly contested vote to lead the country's
dominant political party. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-NAZI-GOLD (Washington) _ Late on a Friday night two weeks
ago, just before months of bitter negotiations between
Switzerland's three major commercial banks and Holocaust survivors
collapsed, one of the Clinton administration's most senior
diplomats placed an urgent call to Switzerland. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-ISRAEL-POLICY (Washington) _ It may be one of the longest
``endgames'' in recent diplomatic history, but Israeli and American
officials say they expect a conclusion to negotiations on an
Israeli pullback from the West Bank by the end of this month. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   BHUTAN-MONARCHY _ Bhutan, one of two remaining absolute
monarchies in Asia, has taken a major step toward constitutional
government with the election of a new Cabinet and a decision by the
king to test his rule in periodic votes of confidence. Although the
king will still be head of government _ there is no prime minister
or president _ the National Assembly now has the right to demand
his abdication. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-FINN-POL (Yugawara, Japan) _ For the last several months,
sleepy commuters in Kanagawa prefecture southwest of Tokyo have
been jolted out of their stupor by a strange sight: a dapper,
blue-eyed Caucasian bowing to them deeply and, in flawless
Japanese, exhorting them to vote for him on July 12. By Stephanie
Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL: &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FARMERS-WOES (Washington) _ With the national economy booming,
lawmakers have begun to focus on one of the few places in the
country where times are bad: the Northern Plains, where wheat and
livestock prices have plunged and many farmers are desperate. By
David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   VEGAS-BUFFET-LIFESTYLE (Las Vegas) _ Overstuffed, underpriced
smorgasbords have long been a staple of the Las Vegas tourist
trade, an enticement and reward for spending money in casinos. But
a lure for heavy rollers is becoming a lifestyle for heavy eaters
as the city's resident population swells, in more ways than one. By
Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   YEAR-2000-TEST _ For computer wizards on Wall Street, Monday
will be Dec. 29, 1999, a step into electronic time travel that will
be studied anxiously around the globe. After months of preparation,
the nation's leading brokers, the major exchanges, clearinghouses
and depository companies will begin mock trading in the
widest-ranging test yet by any industry of how well computers will
cope with the transition to the next century. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   TAXBREAK-MULTINATIONALS _ A lobbying blitz by some of the
biggest names in corporate America has succeeded in maintaining a
lucrative tax break for multinational corporations _ one that
allows them to avoid U.S. taxes and reduce their foreign tax bill,
too. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   GULF-SNAPPER-CRISIS (Orange Beach, Ala.) _ Accustomed to
weathering the occasional hurricane that barrels out of the Gulf of
Mexico, this bustling resort is now bracing for a potential
catastrophe of a different sort. Federal officials, saying the
Gulf's signature red snapper is as overfished as it is delicious,
are threatening to close down recreational angling for snapper as
early as Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-POSTNUCLEAR (Wiscasset, Maine) _ Things change when a
place goes post-nuclear. Almost a year ago, Maine Yankee, the
state's only nuclear plant and once New England's biggest
electricity producer, stopped generating power here for good, to
the joy of nuclear opponents, the regret of the townfolk who
depended on its taxes and jobs, and the pain of its hundreds of
workers. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   FISHING-DISABLED (Bemidji, Minn.) _ Fishing Has No Boundaries, a
nonprofit organization, was founded in 1986 in Hayward, Wis., and
held its first event there in 1988. The idea for the organization _
to take people with disabilities fishing _ was born after a fishing
guide, Bobby Cammack, broke his arm and discovered how difficult a
disability could be for a fisherman, said Tom Mansfield, the
national vice president of operations. By Carla Baranauckas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON: &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HANDGUN-POLITICS (Washington) _ The law requiring a five-day
waiting period to purchase a handgun is scheduled to expire in
November, and gun-control advocates are girding for a bruising
late-summer fight with the National Rifle Association and its
supporters in Congress over whether to extend it. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   DEECEE-VOTER-LAWSUIT (Washington) _ Seeking statehood did not
work. A constitutional amendment failed. Now officials in the
District of Columbia say they have finally found the best way to
gain voting rights in Congress for district residents. They plan to
sue the government. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-RETIRE-AGE (Washington) _ Given that people are living
longer, many politicians and economists think that gradually
raising the retirement age to 70 or even higher is a fair means of
reducing the financial strain that threatens the Social Security
system. Given that her bones ache after decades of hard work, Beth
Hamilton of Exeter, R.I., thinks otherwise. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS: &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN _ On Tina Brown leaving The New Yorker. By Maureen
Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN _ The Wrong Man at Rikers Island jail. By Bob
Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 12:30 p.m. ET.
</P>
