<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0437 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-IMF-NYT &LR;      07-11 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-IMF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA CROSSES FIRST HURDLE FOR GIANT LOAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The international effort to calm Russia's shaky
financial markets began to fall into place Saturday, as Russian and
World Bank officials completed negotiations on a new loan.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said they expected the loan would range
between $1 billion and $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That sum is a small part of the more than $20 billion the
Yeltsin government is seeking from international financial
institutions and Western commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
   But the success of the World Bank talks is a sign that headway
is being made toward assembling the larger loan package.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank accord requires the Russians to take steps to
introduce more competition in Russia's gas and electrical sectors,
which have been dominated by powerful monopolies. It also lays the
groundwork for reform of Russia's railways and and encourages more
privatization of state-owned enterprises, among other measures.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the urgency of Russia's financial crisis, Michael
Carter, the head of the World Bank office here, completed talks
with Sergei Vasiliev, his Russian counterpart, at 1 a.m. Saturday.
The accord was then e-mailed to Washington at 4 a.m. for formal
approval by the World Bank's management.
</P>
<P>
   As Russia's economy continues to deteriorate, Western and
Russian officials have stepped up their efforts to put together a
rescue package.
</P>
<P>
   Intensive talks continued Saturday with John Odling-Smee, the
lead negotiator from the International Monetary Fund, who arrived
in Moscow Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about the state of the Russian economy, the Clinton
Administration has urged that the negotiations be brought to a
close. The hope is that the IMF's negotiations will be completed
and a successful outcome announced before the financial markets
open on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The fund initially proposed $5.8 billion in new loans but has
rethought its position in response to pressure from the U.S.
Treasury Department, Western investors and the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials say they hope the IMF will provide at least
$10 billion in loans.
</P>
<P>
   When Russia's financial crisis deepened in May, Odling-Smee
indicated he did not see the need for more assistance. But
Saturday, Odling-Smee was described by one person taking part in
the talks as negotiating ``efficiently but without much pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   As the talks went into the evening, Russian and IMF officials
were said to be close to settling the paramount question of how
much and how quickly to cut the federal deficit. But there were
still differences over amendments to the tax code that were
proposed by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   Hammering out an agreement with the World Bank and the IMF is
just part of the Yeltsin government's problem. It still has to win
approval of many of the measures in the coming week from the
Communist-dominated Parliament. It is also trying to negotiate $10
billion in loans from Western commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
   President Yeltsin met Saturday at his dacha with top aides to
discuss political and economic strategy. The aides at the session
included Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko; Sergei Dubinin, the
chairman of the Central Bank; Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov;
and Anatoly Chubais, the lead negotiator with the IMF and the World
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president on the whole approved the progress of the talks
and instructed a completion of the talks in a compressed period,''
the Kremlin said.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank accord set Saturday would not require the breakup
of Gazprom, the giant natural gas monopoly. Gazprom is not only an
economic behemeth but one of the last symbols of Soviet power. The
Communists denounce suggestions that Gazprom be broken up to foster
competition as a Western plot to destroy what is left of Russian
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank accord, however, does seek to encourage more
competition and to curb Gazprom's powers. It would change the tax
system to make it easier for other gas producers to enter the
market. It also stipulates that other producers should have access
to Gazprom's pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   To make the company's finances more open, the accounting of its
gas production operation and its pipeline operations are to be
separated.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank accord also aims to limit the dominance of
Russia's electrical monopoly. And to encourage more privatization
generally, it would shorten the list of so-called state-run
strategic enterprises that cannot be sold off.
</P>
<P>
   Another aim of the accord is to encourage more efficient and
competitive rail transport. Russian passenger transportation has
been subsidized by freight tariffs and this has increased the
burden on the ailing industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the reforms being planned will take months, if not
years, to fully carry out and accomplishing them will be the litmus
test for the young Kiriyenko team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has been given a chance,'' one Western
specialist said. ``But now it has to make a sustained effort. The
key thing is to make this work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
