</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-ISRAEL-POLICY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
END IS NEAR FOR WEST BANK DEAL, BUT SUCCESS STILL UNCERTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It may be one of the longest ``endgames'' in recent
diplomatic history, but Israeli and American officials say they
expect a conclusion to negotiations on an Israeli pullback from the
West Bank by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   What they refuse to predict, though, is whether the conclusion
will be successful.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has spoken to Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu at least seven times in the last week,
and some of their conversations were heated, officials said. She
spoke to Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on Wednesday in what her
spokesman, James Rubin, called ``intensive endgame negotiations''
for a deal the United States has been pushing for nearly a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether we achieve success is very much an open question at
this time,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   To keep pressure on the Israelis, the Americans are resisting a
request from Netanyahu to send the special Middle East envoy,
Dennis Ross, back to the region. The Americans are concerned that a
Ross trip now will make it seem that a deal is nearly done, and it
is not, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Americans intend to make ``a real push'' for a deal
in the next 10 days or so, hoping to conclude one by the end of the
month, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The American plan calls for an Israeli withdrawal from a further
13 percent of the West Bank over 12 weeks, in return for specific
and measurable Palestinian actions against terrorism and an
immediate start to negotiations on a final settlement with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu has regularly said that 13 percent is a threat to
Israel's security. But he is expected to agree to a face-saving
formula that will leave the last 3 percent in a more transitional
status, preserving Israeli rights to provide security. This 3
percent includes some of the more isolated Jewish settlements and
other strategic locations.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Palestinians will agree to such a formula is another
question.
</P>
<P>
   But other important gaps with the Israelis still remain,
officials from both sides say. They include Netanyahu's insistence
that the Palestinians convene their main decision-making panel to
change their Covenant, removing clauses that call for the
destruction of Israel. The Palestinians argue that the changes have
already been made, as vouched for in a letter to the Americans, and
that nothing more is required.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu is also not satisfied with extradition procedures for
Palestinians charged with crimes by the Israelis. Currently, if a
Palestinian charged with a crime by the Israelis is also under a
Palestinian charge, there is no extradition, and the Israelis say
Arafat insures that there is always some pending charge against
anyone the Israelis want to extradite.
</P>
<P>
   There is also disagreement still on the amount of
``front-loading'' the Israelis want in return for their most
critical redeployments. In other words, such questions as when,
during the 12 weeks of the phased withdrawals, the Palestinians
must fulfill pledges to retrieve excess guns, for instance, or to
provide lists of security police in excess of the numbers allowed
under previous agreements are still to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel is trying to make the American proposals workable from
the standpoint of Israeli security,'' said Dore Gold, Israel's
ambassador to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   If those complications were not enough, it is not clear that the
Palestinians will agree to all the ``refinements,'' as American
diplomats call them, already worked out with the Israelis to the
original American plan.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, two Palestinian negotiators, Saeb Erekat and Nabil
Shaath, arrived in Washington on Thursday, invited by Albright. But
the Americans are also pressing Netanyahu and Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai to go over the changes themselves with
Palestinian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are arguing that Israelis and Palestinians will
have to talk about these issues at some time. But the Israelis say
that Washington should sell these refinements to the Palestinians,
since they emerged from American ideas. ``The Israelis are saying
to us, `Why don't you go sit on the Palestinians for the next six
months the way you've been sitting on us?''' an American official
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, officials say, both Albright and Netanyahu agreed to
make separate and presumably coordinated approaches to the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Albright made another appeal for Israeli-Palestinian
dialogue. ``We don't think that this impasse can be resolved if
they do not talk with each other,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 1228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
