<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980711.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0476 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CZAR-BURIAL-$ADV12-CO     07-11 1349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZAR-BURIAL-$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONTROVERSY WILL OUTLIVE BURIAL OF THE LAST CZAR
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, July 12 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ On Friday, Russia will hold a royal burial unfit for a
king.
</P>
<P>
   On the 80th anniversary of the murder of the last czar, Nicholas
II, by a Bolshevik firing squad, his charred bones and those of his
family will be laid to rest in the former imperial capital of St.
Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   The government had hoped it would be a day of national
reconciliation, a symbolic opportunity ``to stop the civil war
which has been smoldering in Russia since 1917,'' said the
government official in charge of the burial.
</P>
<P>
   This fractured society is still reeling from a brutal century of
imperial dictatorship, Communist revolution and rule, and the
difficult ongoing transition toward democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Early plans envisioned a majestic ceremony filled with Russian
pride and attracting royalty and world dignitaries such as Queen
Elizabeth II of Britain and First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it seems, the Kremlin simply wants the burial over.
</P>
<P>
   It has become a famous funeral few wish to attend, and a
powerful example of Russia's difficult struggle to resolve its
past.
</P>
<P>
   Neither President Boris Yeltsin nor Patriarch Alexy II, head of
the Russian Orthodox Church, plan to be there. Neither will some of
the more prominent direct descendants from the Romanov family,
including 16-year-old Prince Georgy, living in Spain, a leading
aspirant to the throne, should it ever be restored.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the disarray is the powerful Orthodox Church.
</P>
<P>
   Despite rigorous genetic testing of the remains, the church
expressed lingering doubts about the true identity of the bones
recovered from a shallow grave and publicly disclosed as the Soviet
Union collapsed in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Tiptoeing a fine theological line, the church has authorized
local priests to perform the burial rites, but has instructed
bishops and other church elders to shun the St. Petersburg
ceremony. The service will be intentionally ambiguous, since the
church questions whether it is entombing the genuine remains.
</P>
<P>
   The decision began a landslide of official reluctance to fully
support the royal burial.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin chose to skip the service and toned down initial plans
for an extravagant ceremony, apparently mindful of how such a showy
display would play among Russians suffering in the poor economy.
(Coal miners and other workers have been striking for weeks to
receive back wages as Russia seeks international financial aid to
avoid a economic collapse.)
</P>
<P>
   With the heads of state and the national church skipping the
ceremony, the anticipated throngs of dignitaries and royalty from
around the world are passing it up, too. Ambassador to Moscow James
Collins will represent the United States. Prince Michael of Kent
will be the unofficial representative of the British royal family.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government is spending less than $1 million on the
three-day event, which begins with the departure of the remains
from Yekaterinburg, the city where Nicholas, his wife Alexandria
and their five children were killed.
</P>
<P>
   It will be work as usual as since the government decided not to
declare Friday a national holiday. Even live television coverage
was scaled back, with Russian networks planning only to air
excerpts of the ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Duchess Maria Vladimirova, mother of Prince Georgy, called
the planned funeral, ``yet another insult to the memory of the
royal martyrs'' and said the family considers it only a temporary
interment until the controversy of identification has been settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of becoming an act of national conciliation and
repentance . . . the burial has provoked disputes and has become a
new reason for confrontation in Russian society,'' she told the
Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Communists, whose forebears shot Nicholas and his
family, had from the start opposed plans for a grand ceremony. They
recall the Romanov family's ruthless 300-year reign and now are
quietly gloating over the plagued burial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been nothing but a political embarrassment for the
government,'' said Sergei Bukin, a high-ranking Communist Party
official.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the ceremony still hold hopes that the
ever-capricious Yeltsin may decide to make the trip to St.
Petersburg. Yeltsin aides defend the scaled-down burial plans
saying the government is merely following the church's lead.
</P>
<P>
   After six years of thorough research, including DNA analyses by
U.S., British and Russian experts, a Russian government commission
concluded in January that the fragmented skeletal remains were
those of Nicholas, his wife Alexandra, three of their five children
and four family servants.
</P>
<P>
   The task required all that genetic research could muster. After
the family and attendants were shot by a firing squad in 1918,
their bodies were thrown into a mine shaft, later recovered and
burned, and then thrown into a shallow grave and covered with
sulfuric acid in attempts by the revolutionaries to destroy
evidence of the murders.
</P>
<P>
   The burial site was discovered in the 1970s and the bones
exhumed in 1991. The government study concluded that the remains
corresponded to five members of one family, and four people who
were unrelated. Of the five, three were the children of the two
parents. Genetic matching concluded that the mother was kin to the
British royal family, as was Alexandra, and the father was related
to several other living Romanovs who donated blood for the study.
The body of Alexei, the hemophiliac heir to the throne, is missing,
as is one of his sisters, either Maria or Anastasia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no doubts about the remains,'' said Viktor
Aksyuchits, the government official in charge of the arrangements.
``They are 100 percent the remains of the Romanov family.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orthodox Church is not so convinced. But the church's
decision to withhold its endorsement of the burial has more to do
with politics than science.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian church is seeking to mend relations with Orthodox
believers living in exile since the Bolshevik revolution. The
increasingly influential growing Orthodox Church Abroad,
established in the United States, already has conferred sainthood
on Nicholas. As a result, it tenaciously has refused to accept the
remains in Russia as those of the last czar.
</P>
<P>
   The Moscow patriarch also is considering canonizing the family,
but the process could last years. In the meantime, the Russian
church does not want to alienate followers who share the view of
the church in exile.
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop of knotty religion, politics and
symbolism, the remains on Wednesday will be placed in nine tiny oak
caskets -- each is just 48 inches long by 20 inches wide -- and a
short requiem will be sung at a local church. The next day, they
will be flown from Yekaterinburg to St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   There, a cortege will whisk the caskets from the airport to the
Cathedral of St. Peter and St. Paul. Original plans for an honor
guard to line the 18-mile route have been reduced to guards only at
the airport, the Winter Palace and the cathedral. At the cathedral,
the caskets will lay overnight in a pyramid formation: the four
servants on the bottom, three children in the middle, and the czar
and his wife at the top.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, wreaths will be laid, a choir will sing, cannons will
thunder and a short service will pray for the souls of the entire
family, including the two children whose bodies are missing.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at the Trinity-St. Sergius monastery near Moscow,
Alexy II, other church leaders and members of the Romanov clan will
gather for a rival service to memorialize the family and all
victims of the Communist era.
</P>
<P>
   Grand or not, the act will be significant, insists Aksyuchits,
the government organizer: ``We are witnesses to an historical event
-- a monarch being buried in a democratic Russian state.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
