<HEADER>
A0479 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-US-$ADV11-COX     07-11 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-US-$ADV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON HOPES TO BUOY YELTSIN AND IMPROVE U.S-RUSSIA RELATIONS
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-US-BOX-$ADV11.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, July 11 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ World leaders prefer to hold summits without surprises,
well-scripted meetings before the television cameras which portray
men of action, but where usually nothing much happens.
</P>
<P>
   However, the dangerous prospects of a Russian economic collapse
and a widening war in the Balkans forced U.S. President Bill
Clinton and Russian President Boris Yeltsin to wait no longer for a
chance at talks on an serene stage.
</P>
<P>
   The first U.S.-Russia summit in 18 months, announced this week,
is scheduled to take place in Moscow in September amid growing
uncertainty about Russia's future and increasingly strained
relations between Washington and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton understands that Yeltsin is in a very difficult
position domestically and the longer he waits to visit the riskier
the situation could become,'' said Viktor Kremenyuk, deputy
director of the USA and Canada Institute, a Moscow-based think
tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S.-Russian relations have been frozen over the past year,
nothing is happening, and that is a very dangerous thing,''
Kremenyuk added.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton accepted the invitation to visit Russia despite the
failure of the opposition-led Russian legislature to fulfill a
request to ratify the START II arms control treaty signed with the
United States in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   With Russia's mounting economic problems and the spreading
violence in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo, the White House
concluded it could no longer wait for a summit celebrating a START
II ratification that is no where in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin needs help, and Clinton has decided to come to his side.
Aides insist the two men enjoy a close, personal rapport,
exchanging telephone calls about once a month and meeting at
international forums, like the May summit of world leaders in
England.
</P>
<P>
   But while the two countries have grown closer since the days of
the Soviet Union and their Cold War rivalry, they are not staunch
allies, a fact clearly demonstrated by an array of foreign policy
differences.
</P>
<P>
   During his recently concluded trip to China, some critics
questioned whether Clinton was neglecting a more important
strategic relationship with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Since the last Clinton-Yeltsin summit in March 1997 in Helsinki,
U.S.-Russia relations have soured on issues including NATO
expansion in eastern Europe, international sanctions against Iraq,
and Russian arms and technology sales to Iran and other developing
nations
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton visit to Moscow is chiefly being characterized by
analysts here as an urgent mission of mercy intended to bolster
Yeltsin's image as a world leader, back his efforts at economic
reform and restore confidence in Russia's sagging financial markets
among foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   An all-out economic meltdown would send consumer prices
skyrocketing, further diminishing Yeltsin's clout and ruining
chances for more democratic and market reforms in the foreseeable
future, analysts predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West doesn't need Yeltsin, but it predicts chaos were he
to be forced from office before his term ended. They don't see a
figure reliable enough to substitute for the current leader,'' said
political scientist Alexei Bogaturov.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore is scheduled to travel to Moscow later
this month for meetings with Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko to
formulate and agenda for the Clinton-Yeltsin summit.
</P>
<P>
   But just how Clinton's visit will play in Russia is difficult to
predict, given the volatile economy, simmering nationwide labor
strikes and Yeltsin's low ratings in polls.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's early honeymoon years as a champion of Western-style
reform following the Soviet Union's collapse in 1991 have given way
to disillusionment as most Russians have seen their standard of
living diminished during the long, ongoing transition to democracy
and free markets.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's lower house of parliament, the Duma, controlled by
Communists and nationalists hostile to Yeltsin, is scheduled in
September to consider an unpopular, belt-tightening budget and the
long-delayed ratification of the START II agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Ryzhkov, a political moderate and the Duma's first
deputy speaker, warned that a contentious autumn is looming just as
Clinton arrives in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can safely say that unfortunately it will be a hot autumn,''
he told a news conference this week. It is already clear that
growing arrears on pensions, wages and the defense order will
exacerbate social tensions and popular discontent.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia is currently negotiating an aid package with the
International Monetary Fund to help it meet its short-term debt
obligations and strengthen the ruble. But some foreign investors
predict Russia may need $20 billion or mre to restore confidence
in the economy and prevent a devaluation of the currency.
</P>
<P>
   The Duma is scheduled to meet next Wednesday and Thurday to
consider a austerity measures prompted by the Yeltsin government
and considered necessary before the IMF approves an assistance
package.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian economic slide -- its markets have lost almost
two-thirds of their value in the past year -- may have prompted the
Clinton White House to abandon hopes of a START II ratification,
which the Duma has announced it will not consider before it
convenes for its fall session.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Senate ratified the arms control treaty in 1996. But
despite pleas from Yeltsin, the opposition-dominated Duma has
continually put off a vote on the treaty, which would cut Russian
and American nuclear arsenals to about 3,500 warheads apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Another pressing issue is Kosovo and the Serbian crackdown on
separatist ethnic Albanian forces. The Clinton administration has
pushed for tougher economic and military sanctions to temper
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and prevent a wider conflict
in the Balkans. Russia has opposed harsh steps against the Serbs,
whom they view as traditional allies.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the United States and Russia have confronted one
another at the United Nations over policy toward Iraq, another
traditional Soviet-era ally where Russia has potentially lucrative
economic interests.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's promise to continue pushing for enlargement of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization also has alarmed Russians, many
of whom regard NATO expansion as an implicit declaration that the
U.S. continues to consider Russia a potential enemy.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the U.S. Senate ratified a NATO agreement to admit three
former Warsaw Pact countries: Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic. Yeltsin is expected to reiterate Russia's opposition to
the expansion, and particularly proposed NATO membership for the
Baltic states of Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia, once part of the
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
