u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-US-BOX-$ADV11-     07-11 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-US-BOX-$ADV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISSUES TROUBLING THE U.S.-RUSSIA RELATIONSHIP
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-US-$ADV11.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, July 11 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Here are the issues facing U.S. President Bill Clinton
and Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who are scheduled to meet in
Moscow in September:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA'S ECONOMY: The prospect of a crash is spurring Clinton to
visit Moscow. Russia needs an international bailout. Yeltsin and
his democratic reforms could be in danger should the ruble crash
and poor Russians face skyrocketing inflation.
</P>
<P>
   THE BALKANS: The U.S. warns that a broader Balkans war is
possible unless international pressure is placed on Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to halt the Serbian crackdown on
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. Russia has resisted, regarding the
Serbs as traditional allies.
</P>
<P>
   NATO EXPANSION: The security organization designed to counter
Soviet aggression during the Cold War is looking to expand to
countries once behind the Iron Curtain, a move many Russians regard
as a threat. Invitations have gone to Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ARMS REDUCTION: In their last summit, Clinton and Yeltsin agreed
to pursue new strategic arms cuts as soon as the Duma ratified
START II, a treaty signed in January 1993. The Duma, Russia's lower
house of Parliament controlled by Communists and other Yeltsin
opponents, have withheld the political plum.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: Russia has been a leading voice in the United Nations to
relax economic sanctions and weapons inspections imposed on Iraq
since the 1991 Persian Gulf War. The U.S. wants to keep the
pressure on Iraqi President Saddam Hussein pending proof that he
has abandoned his weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: The U.S. wants Russia to curb its exports of nuclear and
missile technology to Iran. Yeltsin has offered assurances that
Russia will halt shipments that could help Iran become a nuclear
power, but U.S. intelligence reports indicate that the transfers
continue.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
