<DOCNO> NYT19980711.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0482 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-IRAN-$ADV12-C     07-11 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-IRAN-$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOREIGN JOURNAL: IRAN'S IMAGE A SOURCE OF TENSION IN THESE TIMES
OF REFORM
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    With IRAN-BACKLASH-$ADV12.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, July 11 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ These are dicey times for Iranians.
</P>
<P>
   On my trip last month, I could sense the difference from my last
visit in December.
</P>
<P>
   Then, reformers were gleeful about the prospects for changing
their fundamentalist nation under newly-elected President Mohammed
Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Iranians are channel-surfing between World Cup soccer games
and the trial of the popular Tehran mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Gholamhossein Karbaschi is accused of corruption, but most
Iranians think he was targeted by the religious hardliners who run
the courts because he managed Khatami's surprisingly successful
election.
</P>
<P>
   As in December, Iranians are still seeing increased freedom.
But, the Karbaschi trial is just one example that reform still has
its opponents.
</P>
<P>
   One of the issues causing friction is how Iran should show
itself to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   The day after watching a televised World Cup match with a group
of young Iranians, one called and asked that I not tell anyone I
was with there.
</P>
<P>
   These days, an evening with a foreign journalist can be
controversial, especially if the evening in question includes
cassettes of Western dance music.
</P>
<P>
   When hardliners in the Iranian parliament last month impeached
Khatami's top cabinet minister, Abdullah Nouri, they cited his
comments in the foreign press. There were too many outsiders, they
said, carrying news about Iran's private business.
</P>
<P>
   I got the same response when my translator tried to set up an
appointment with the head of the unofficial ``club wielders,'' the
hardline mobs that break up reformist demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do they want to know about our internal affairs,'' he
asked, saying it seemed like a form of ``espionage.''
</P>
<P>
   Iran's identity is built around martyrdom and persecution. Some
are afraid that if Iran opens up, people will see that Iranians are
not all stern religious zealots.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be a hard secret to keep. Iranians are, in fact, fun and
sophisticated, friendly and educated. Go to this capital city's
working-class south side and interview the grocery store owner, and
he'll want to treat you to lunch. The ice cream salesman insists
that you fill up while you ask him your questions.
</P>
<P>
   The many parks and shopping districts in Tehran are some of the
most fertile ground for interviews in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   For some, that's a problem.
</P>
<P>
   One western observer noted that hardliners are afraid Iran will
be perceived as ``the kind of country America doesn't have to worry
about.'' That would almost be contrary to Iran's national
mythology.
</P>
<P>
   But, the reformers are glad to have foreign journalists around.
</P>
<P>
   Moderate government officials, led by Khatami, are making it
easier for foreigners to get visas and are encouraging American
tourism.
</P>
<P>
   The average Iranian on the street wanted me to know that Iran is
changing, even as they are nervous about how far they will be
allowed to go.
</P>
<P>
   They told me not to pay attention to the people who shout
``Death to America'' at Friday prayers, saying it was passe
sloganism.
</P>
<P>
   One should not take this too far. Overall, Iranians still
believe in the basic principles of the Islamic revolution. The late
Ayatollah Khomeini is still beloved.
</P>
<P>
   But one intellectual also reminded me that, ever since the
Muslims conquered the country in the 7th Century, Iranians have
adopted stern public behaviors to satisfy their religious rulers,
while leading much more relaxed, accommodating, private lives.
</P>
<P>
   You can see, in the carousing described by the Persian poets
Omar Khayam or Hafiz, that Iran has always had many faces.
</P>
<P>
   You could have looked at the streets of Tehran after the
national team beat the United States in World Cup soccer. The team
is a patriotic phenomenon and has become a vehicle for Iranians to
test out new freedoms without fear of reprisal from the Islamic
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   It is too bad that hard-line Iranian officials made it difficult
for American networks to beam out much video of the jubilant soccer
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   The world would have seen happy Iranians having what any
American would consider clean fun. One clip that was censored
showed youths saying they were ready for good relations with
America.
</P>
<P>
   There was even one girl in the street stretching modesty laws by
wearing make up in public. She had the Iranian flag's red, white
and green painted on her face.
</P>
<P>
   What are the conservatives supposed to do about that?
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
