<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0487 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWISS-NAZI-GOLD-NYT &LR;      07-11 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISS-NAZI-GOLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW A SWISS BANK GOLD DEAL ELUDED A U.S. MEDIATOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Late on a Friday night two weeks ago, just before
months of bitter negotiations between Switzerland's three major
commercial banks and Holocaust survivors collapsed, one of the
Clinton administration's most senior diplomats placed an urgent
call to the president of Switzerland, Flavio Cotti.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomat, Stuart Eizenstat, the undersecretary of state for
economic affairs, told the Swiss president that the two sides were
narrowing their differences. But after rounds and rounds of talks
in New York and Washington, neither side was willing to move
further.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss government, Eizenstat said, had the power both to
speed a settlement and to end a 50-year-long chapter of its history
that tarnished Switzerland's reputation around the globe. He urged
Cotti to reverse a long-held position and have the Swiss government
contribute to a ``global settlement'' with Jewish groups and with
Holocaust victims and their heirs.
</P>
<P>
   He even suggested a figure: more than $300 million, a large sum
but only a fraction of the $2.8 billion in Nazi gold, measured in
today's values, that a Swiss historical commission recently
concluded was received on behalf of Nazi Germany by the Swiss
central bank.
</P>
<P>
   Cotti refused.
</P>
<P>
   While Eizenstat declines to discuss details of the discussion,
he said ``no common understanding was reached'' in the
conversation. ``It is our impression that the cycle of accusation
and counteraccusations had substantially hardened opinion in
Switzerland,'' said Eizenstat, who has led the State Department's
efforts to settle the contentious issue.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Borer, the Swiss ambassador for Holocaust issues, was
even more direct.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood in Switzerland has changed in the past year, and
Cotti explained this,'' Borer said in a telephone interview. ``Most
Swiss don't even want to talk about a global settlement. They know
that whatever we do, no one gets credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Several participants in the negotiations now say that
Switzerland's hard-line position _ a refusal even to consider
joining the private banks in settling the legal claims _ helped
scuttle an agreement in late June. And while a settlement is not
dead, it is clear that announcements this past spring that a
settlement was in the offing were premature.
</P>
<P>
   There are indications that talks could resume in a few months,
as New York and California begin to carry out sanctions against
Swiss businesses operating in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But Eizenstat's unusual, direct appeal to Cotti, and lower-level
talks between U.S. and Swiss diplomats, had echoes of an earlier
time. Nearly two generations ago, in 1946, the State Department
tried to get Switzerland to disgorge the huge profits it
accumulated when it served as banker to Nazi Germany, taking in
stolen gold, jewelry, art and other property.
</P>
<P>
   The result was an agreement called the Washington Accord, now
regarded as a diplomatic fiasco, in which Switzerland agreed to
turn over a small part of its holdings to repay countries invaded
by Germany and to aid refugees. But it never fulfilled major parts
of the accord, and it has resisted several efforts in the years
since to settle the accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss central bank did make a contribution of more than $70
million to a humanitarian fund, but it has said that was a one-time
act of compassion _ not something that will be repeated under legal
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato of New York, who has led the investigations
into the Nazi gold questions, has scheduled hearings for later this
month on the question of whether the United States should try to
reopen the Washington agreement, a step the Clinton administration
has been loath to take, saying that it would irreparably breach the
U.S. relationship with the Swiss.
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat has been scurrying for more than a year now to avoid
that. This spring he turned out a detailed study of how other
neutral nations dealt extensively with the Nazis during World War
II, a study that seemed intended to make the Swiss seem less of a
lone target.
</P>
<P>
   All spring, he acted as a go-between in the negotiations between
the three big private Swiss banks _ Union Bank of Switzerland,
Swiss Bank Corp. and Credit Suisse _ and the fractious group of
plaintiffs who are suing them. In early June, just before the New
York State Banking Commission was supposed to consider an
application for the merger of Union Bank of Switzerland and Swiss
Bank Corp., the banks began to offer larger settlements.
</P>
<P>
   But they had a condition: Before Eizenstat could convey their
offer of several hundred million dollars, the banking commission
had to approve the merger. The commission had suggested earlier in
the year that it might hold up the U.S. approval _ critical to
operating on Wall Street _ because the banks had not been diligent
enough in tracking down Holocaust-era accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that there was no legitimate regulatory objection
to the merger,'' said Roger Witten, the lead lawyer for the banks,
``and we wanted to make sure that we were free from efforts to use
that process to extort a result on another front.''
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat called the World Jewish Congress to say a major offer
was on the way, and sent a letter confirming that he was in
possession of ``a firm and concrete offer from the banks for
settlement of the class action litigation'' that would be conveyed
after the merger was approved. With that assurance, the Jewish
groups said they would drop their past objections to the merger.
</P>
<P>
   The banks, pushed further by Eizenstat, ultimately offered $530
million for a ``rough justice fund'' that would pay the plaintiffs
and be used to help indigent survivors of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came up with a reasonable estimate, based on the very
limited dealings the commercial banks had with German gold,''
Witten said. They then multiplied the figure several times, he
said, explaining how the banks came to that number.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish groups, however, were looking for something closer to
$1.5 billion, and dismissed the banks' offer as insulting. (In
addition to the $530 million, the banks previously pledged to pay
any amounts mandated by an independent commission headed by Paul
Volcker, the former Federal Reserve Board chairman, which is
reviewing long-dormant wartime accounts in Swiss banks.)
</P>
<P>
   Bitter charges were exchanged. Some of the plaintiffs charged
that the banks, having received the merger approval, were no longer
motivated to increase their offers significantly. The banks, in
turn, charged that the Holocaust survivors and Jewish groups, which
have fought among themselves over strategy, were trying to obtain
more money with threats of bad publicity and possible economic
sanctions against the banks.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a meeting to impose sanctions _ headed by Alan Hevesi,
the New York City comptroller _ loomed in late June, prompting
Eizenstat to call Cotti. He offered a rationale: The Swiss National
Bank, which is government-owned, received more than 85 percent of
the gold deposited by Nazi Germany. Commercial banks got just a
fraction.
</P>
<P>
   But Cotti refused even to bring the issue in front of the
legislature, saying it would only further inflame public opinion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
