<HEADER>
A0493 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEECEE-VOTER-LAWSUIT-     07-11 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEECEE-VOTER-LAWSUIT-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D.C. TO SUE U.S. FOR VOTING RIGHTS IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Md., S.C., Kan., S.D., Miss.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seeking statehood did not work. A constitutional
amendment failed. Now officials in the District of Columbia say
they have finally found the best way to gain voting rights in
Congress for district residents.
</P>
<P>
   They plan to sue the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other approaches made false assumptions,'' said John Ferren,
the corporation counsel for the district. ``The lawsuit is based on
the argument that citizens of the district are entitled to be
represented in Congress by the Constitution. It's strictly a
constitutional argument.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the district, where more than 500,000 people live,
say a lawsuit is being drawn up to be filed in U.S. District Court
here in September. They say they intend to argue that the equal
protection guarantees of the Constitution, including voting rights,
apply as much to residents of the district as to residents of the
states.
</P>
<P>
   The district is represented in Congress by only a nonvoting
member of the House, Eleanor Holmes Norton, who plans to introduce
legislation on Tuesday that will seek a second avenue of redress,
asking Congress to give the district full representation.
</P>
<P>
   Though the effort has nothing to do with more recent
controversial issues in the district _ like statehood, home rule or
the city's financial control board _neither Ms. Norton nor the
district lawyers expect much to come of it, especially with
Republicans controlling both chambers and the vast majority of
voters in the district registered as Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, they have concluded that the parallel effort of a
lawsuit, which is likely to reach the Supreme Court, would be the
best way to settle the issue for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has never been tried before,'' Ms. Norton said in an
interview. ``Perhaps it's time. Enough constitutional water has
flowed under the bridge, I think, to yield the result we want.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of voting rights for district residents has been
debated for nearly 200 years. Early residents of the city continued
to vote for congressional representatives in Maryland and Virginia,
the states from which the district was carved. But around 1800, the
states cut them off, saying Congress had the responsibility to
represent the local population.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing much happened until 1978 when both houses of Congress,
by two-thirds majorities, sent a constitutional amendment to the
states that would have created full representation in Congress for
the district. In the seven-year period for approval, the measure
was passed by only 16 states, well short of the 38 needed to enact
the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the House considered a bill that would have made the
district the 51st state, but it failed, winning only 153 votes, 151
of them cast by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   This latest effort evolved from a paper written by Jamin Raskin,
a professor of constitutional law at American University, who
traced the rationale for voting representation, in part, to two
Supreme Court cases that removed constitutional distinctions
between the states and the district for the application of federal
law.
</P>
<P>
   The first, Bolling vs. Sharpe, was a 1954 companion case to the
landmark Brown vs. Board of Education, which desegregated public
schools. Bolling was a challenge to racially segregated schools in
the district.
</P>
<P>
   The second was a 1970 case, Evans vs. Cornman, in which the
court upheld the right of residents of a federal enclave in
Rockville, Md., the National Institutes of Health, to vote in state
and federal elections in Maryland, because they were subject to
state laws, paid state taxes and sent their children to
state-supported schools.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The federal government already treats the district like a state
in many areas, including military service, federal taxes and
federal benefits like highways money and Medicaid, Raskin pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
   Raskin and the district lawyers insist that a constitutional
amendment is not necessary to give the city adequate representation
in Congress, stressing that those rights are already guaranteed by
the Constitution and have been upheld by the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, several influential lawmakers have agreed that the
district deserves equal representation in Congress. When the
constitutional amendment was proposed in 1978, Sen. Strom Thurmond
of South Carolina, a conservative Republican, said: ``I think it is
a fair thing to do. We are advocating one man, one vote. We are
advocating democratic processes in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Another supporter was former Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., who said,
``The absence of voting representation for the District in Congress
is an anomaly which the Senate can no longer sanction.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether similar sentiments now exist is uncertain. A spokesman
for Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the majority leader, said he
supported a constitutional amendment as the best way for the
district to gain voting representation. A spokeswoman for Sen. Tom
Daschle, D-S.D., the minority leader, said he was ``undecided on
the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Speaker Newt Gingrich said he deferred on
district matters to Rep. Thomas Davis III, R-Va., chairman of a
district subcommittee. Davis said he favored a voting member in the
House for the district but not two senators.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has offered its support for the district but
tied voting rights to statehood, which district officials are not
seeking. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
