<SLUG> BC-BHUTAN-MONARCHY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BHUTAN MOVES TOWARD A CONSTITUTIONAL GOVERNMENT
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map of Bhutan is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bhutan, one of two remaining absolute monarchies in Asia, has
taken a major step toward constitutional government with the
election of a new cabinet and a decision by the king to test his
rule in periodic votes of confidence. Although the king will still
be head of government _ there is no prime minister or president _
the National Assembly now has the right to demand his abdication.
</P>
<P>
   Bhutan is the last of a group of independent Buddhist kingdoms
in the Himalayas, which once included Tibet, Ladakh and Sikkim. All
the rest have been swallowed up over the last century by China and
India.
</P>
<P>
   Bhutan's efforts to preserve its distinct character have led to
clashes with non-Buddhist or non-Bhutanese minorities along the
country's southern border with India, who have demanded more
democracy. Tens of thousands of southerners have left the country
for refugee camps in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
   Only Brunei, on the island of Borneo in Southeast Asia, now
remains an absolute monarchy. Its Sultan, Hassanal Bolkiah, one of
the world's richest people, more or less owns the country and
brooks no democratic opposition and almost no political activity.
</P>
<P>
   Bhutan, a collection of landlocked territories ruled by warlords
until the late 19th century, has had a hereditary monarch for less
than a century. It also has a powerful but separate central
monastic assembly in the Tibetan model, which has often preferred
to keep the country isolated and its Buddhist religion in the
dominant position.
</P>
<P>
   Since he came to the throne at age 16, Bhutan's king, Jigme
Synge Wangchuck, 42, has been mulling over how to modernize and
democratize the rural, mountainous country without changing it
completely, he said in interviews. His father took the first steps
toward modernization, including opening secular schools and health
centers.
</P>
<P>
   The country has been very selective in development, rejecting
large foreign-aid projects as unsuitable for a country of fewer
than a million people, most of them living in small villages. It
has limited the number of tourists.
</P>
<P>
   In late June, the king surprised his subjects by dismissing an
appointed cabinet and sending a new list of nominees for most of
their jobs to the National Assembly. The delegates duly elected a
group of generally younger men, some with considerable foreign
experience.
</P>
<P>
   The country's new foreign minister, Jigmi Thinley, 48, has a
master's degree in public administration from Penn State. Since
1994, he has been the country's representative at the United
Nations in Geneva, where he also served as a roving ambassador to a
number of European countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an exciting moment in history,'' said Bhutan's only
newspaper, Kuensel, which is published weekly in English, Nepali
and Dzongkha, a Tibetan language. But its editorial page could not
resist a pang of nostalgia for years when prosperity grew with
Bhutan's growing exports of fruit, timber and hydroelectric power,
and most people were barely concerned with government and politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many of us,'' the newspaper said. ``the past decades may
have been the best years of our lives. They certainly have been
golden years in Bhutanese history.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
