<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0517 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCSEC-RETIRE-AGE-690     07-11 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-RETIRE-AGE-690(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIDES ARE SQUARING OFF ON RAISING RETIREMENT AGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: R.I., N.H., Mass.)  (lb) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Given that people are living longer, many
politicians and economists think that gradually raising the
retirement age to 70 or even higher is a fair means of reducing the
financial strain that threatens the Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   Given that her bones ache after decades of hard work, Beth
Hamilton of Exeter, R.I., thinks otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 62, Ms. Hamilton works full time in a group home
for mentally and physically disabled adults, lifting, bathing,
dressing and cleaning up after them. It is difficult and dirty work
that takes its toll; earlier this year she contracted pneumonia
from one of the people she looks after.
</P>
<P>
   Even if it was implemented so slowly as to not affect her, Ms.
Hamilton said, raising the retirement age would be unfair to her
younger colleagues and to future generations of people who do not
have the luxury of working behind a desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had all sorts of injuries,'' she said. ``Our backs are
hurting. We've been bitten and had hepatitis shots. The idea of
doing this until 70 is too much.''
</P>
<P>
   As they begin examining details of various plans for restoring
Social Security's long-term financial health, Clinton
administration officials, members of Congress and interest groups
say few issues will be more passionately debated _ or subject to
demagoguery _ than proposals to raise the age at which retirees can
claim full benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very visceral issue for a lot of people,'' said Warren
Rudman, the former Republican senator from New Hampshire who is
co-chairman of the Concord Coalition, a fiscal watchdog group that
favors a gradual increase. ``A lot of people can't conceive of the
notion that they will have to spend more time in their jobs than
they planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the impact of any change _ on individuals, employers
and the economy _ could be substantial, the issue has gotten
relatively little attention so far in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Many people appear unaware that under changes adopted in 1983,
the age at which retirees can claim full Social Security benefits
is already scheduled to increase. From 2003 through 2008 it will
gradually rise to 66 from 65. Then, from 2021 through 2027, it will
rise gradually to 67. (The early retirement age would remain 62,
but the benefits available at that age would decline as the full
retirement age increases.)
</P>
<P>
   Some of the plans being considered in Washington would
accelerate the existing timetable. Others would push the retirement
age even higher. A comprehensive plan developed by a bipartisan
commission working with the Center for Strategic and International
Studies, a research group, recommended in May that the retirement
age be raised to 70 by 2029, and be raised as needed after that to
account for further increases in life expectancy.
</P>
<P>
   Given that tough tradeoffs are going to have to be made to
ensure Social Security's long-term survival, increased life
expectancy alone makes raising the qualifying age for full benefits
fair game, said Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., who was a member of the
bipartisan commission. Life expectancy for males, which was about
60 at the time Social Security was created in 1935, is almost 73,
meaning that people are spending many more years in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   But Gregg said the commission's plan offsets the increased
retirement age in other ways, including removing the cap on how
much money retirees can earn before the age of 70 without reducing
their Social Security payments. That change might lead some people
to choose early retirement at reduced benefits in the expectation
that they would keep working part time.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, the centerpiece of the commission's plan _
private accounts that allow workers to invest a portion of their
payroll taxes in the stock market _ will provide a pool of wealth
beyond Social Security benefits that retirees will be able to tap
starting at age 60. Advocates of such accounts say they will more
than offset any reductions in benefits.
</P>
<P>
   And since the change would not take place for decades or affect
anyone near retirement age now, those who are affected will have
plenty of time to prepare, Gregg said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The proposal ``is tied to a system that gives you many more
options so that you can have a quality lifestyle if you retire
early,'' Gregg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``On substance,'' he said, ``this is a heck of a good approach.
On the demagoguing aspect, Social Security has always been
demagogued by people who are absolutely irresponsible and only look
to the next election.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions, as well as some Democrats in Congress, said it is
not a matter of demagoguery at all, just of understanding how
strongly working people feel about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done focus groups in which people reject resoundingly
some of the ideas that are taken for granted around here, like
raising the retirement age,'' said Gerry Shea, assistant to the
president for government affairs at the AFL-CIO. ``People don't
realize it's already going to 67, and when you tell them about
proposals to move it up to 70, their reactions range from
incredulity to `Who came up with that idea?'''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in the House see the issue as a potent one as they
draw distinctions between how they and the Republicans would deal
with Social Security. They are drafting a comprehensive Social
Security proposal that would not call for any further changes in
the retirement age.
</P>
<P>
   But for many people the issue is complicated, involving the kind
of work they do, changing cultural assumptions about when old age
begins, the value put on youth in the workplace, and their own
goals for financial security, career accomplishment and leisure
time.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemarie Cola, a 65-year-old retired employee-assistance worker
from New York City, said she thought raising the retirement age
might be a reasonable way to help ensure that Social Security will
be around in the future. But she wants to hear more about the
tradeoffs, and she said she wondered whether employers would be in
step with a movement toward having people work until they are 68 or
70.
</P>
<P>
   ``Older people are being pushed out of their jobs,'' she said.
``They have the biggest health benefits, the most vacation, the
biggest salaries. Employers want you out.''
</P>
<P>
   The group that has the most at stake in the debate _ generally
those who are 40 or under and would be most likely to feel the full
impact of any further changes _ appears most ambivalent.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I know where I'll be when I'm 65 or 67?'' said Mary
Ann Mroz, a 35-year-old college administrator from Somerville,
Mass. ``I don't think it's been fully thought through.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudman said that as the population ages, employers will face a
shortage of workers, and will increasingly seek to lure retirees
back into full- or part-time work. Moreover, he said, many people
realize when they reach age 65 or 67 that they are not ready yet to
stop working entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Yet although there are signs of more retirees from white-collar
jobs looking for full- or part-time employment, a trend toward
longer working lives would reverse decades in which there has been
a pronounced trend toward early retirement. In 1965, 30.2 percent
of the men who applied for Social Security retirement benefits were
under age 65. Since 1985, the figure has been around 66 percent,
and it is considerably higher for women.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hamilton, who attended a recent conference on Social
Security as part of a contingent of union members brought in by the
AFL-CIO, said she had been working since she was 14, and had been
eager to cut back to part-time this month when she turned 62.
</P>
<P>
   But when she went to her local Social Security office, she found
that her benefit would be $550 a month if she retired now, instead
of $730 if she retires at 65. Feeling that she could not afford to
live on the reduced benefit, she decided to keep working full time,
but she is already counting the days until July 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a job like Andy Rooney, I'd work until I'm 75,'' she
said. ``But right now I'm disappointed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
