<DOCNO> NYT19980711.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0525 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-FINN-POL-1STLD-     07-11 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-FINN-POL-1STLD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST CAUCASIAN EVER RUNNING FOR JAPANESE PARLIAMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs to correct spelling of Tsurunen throughout. No other
changes.)  (ART ADV: A map and a photo are being sent to NYT graphics/photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204, 1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   YUGAWARA, Japan _ For the last several months, sleepy commuters
in Kanagawa prefecture southwest of Tokyo have been jolted out of
their stupor by a strange sight: a dapper, blue-eyed Caucasian
bowing to them deeply and, in flawless Japanese, exhorting them to
vote for him on July 12.
</P>
<P>
   There's more than a little of Mr. Smith in Marutei Tsurunen.
Born a Finn, he overcame tremendous odds and obstacles to become a
Japanese citizen in 1979 and now hopes to become a member of
Japan's Upper House of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Why? ``I want to bring change to Japan,'' said Tsurunen, 58, who
is running as an independent. ``I want to open the political system
and make it work for the people who live here. And because I am
foreign and yet also Japanese, I think I can more easily push for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   His political opponents say he has invigorated local politics in
Kanagawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that his participation will increase voter
turnout overall, but it will encourage nonpartisan voters who
otherwise might not vote at all to get out and vote,'' said Tokuro
Kanbayashi, a representative of Keiko Chiba, a Democratic Party
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal Democrat and Democratic incumbents look likely to
secure their seats again. An analysis by the Asahi Shimbun, one of
Japan's leading newspapers, put Tsurunen's odds for winning the
third seat at 50-50, saying he was running neck-and-neck with the
Communist Party candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his strength is that his unique campaign is overcoming
existing party lines and that he's mobilizing people who are not
satisfied with the existing parties,'' said Shigeru Sakamoto,
campaign manager for Fumio Saito, an incumbent Upper House member
from the Liberal Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Tsurunen is no political novice. In 1992, he was elected to the
local assembly in Yugawara, the small, seaside resort town in
Kanagawa that is his home. He won despite a significant financial
disadvantage: Accepting only contributions from individuals, he had
only 360,000 yen at his disposal, compared to the millions of yen
spent by some of his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Shocked that the assembly met in plenary session for only two
days, he went public with details of the behind-the-scenes horse
trading between local government officials and assembly members
that had preceded the session.
</P>
<P>
   Nemawashi, as the closed-door wrangling is known, shields debate
_ and the deals made to resolve it _ from public view and is a
time-honored tradition in Japanese business and politics.
</P>
<P>
   But Tsurunen regarded it as stifling opposing points of view
that his electorate had a right to hear. So he went to the
newspapers, and now Yugawara has a plenary session that lasts at
least two weeks and the horse-trading is done publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided that there was really nothing I could do to clean up
the party itself, but that I could open the planning and
decision-making process to public view,'' he said, referring to the
Liberal Democratic Party, which has had a lock on power in the
postwar period with the exception of a few years. ``There's no real
democracy in Japan, because people can't get their opinions heard
in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from his assembly victory, Tsurunen aimed for a place in
the national political scene, running as an independent for an
Upper House seat in 1995. He came in fourth of 14 candidates, just
shy of winning one of Kanagawa prefecture's three seats.
</P>
<P>
   He is confident he will improve his showing in this election.
His 1995 campaign had little advance planning, no organization and
a lot less money.
</P>
<P>
   Now, more than 400 volunteers are working on his behalf, and he
has been campaigning for more than a year, waking at dawn to trek
to another station and hand out pamphlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 70 or 80 percent of them take it,'' he said of the
commuters he greets. ``No one really bothers us too much. I've only
been heckled a few times.''
</P>
<P>
   Tsurunen came here as a Lutheran missionary in 1967, working at
a home for children in Kyushu, the southern island in the Japanese
archipelago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The influence of the church here is very weak,'' he said. ``I
knew I would have to get out of the church to really have an impact
on social welfare in this country, although I'm still a
Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated, he left the ministry after six years.
</P>
<P>
   But with no affiliation to any corporate, religious or other
organization, he could not stay in Japan. One way he could remain
was to marry a Japanese. He divorced his wife and married a young
woman, Sachiko, whom he had counseled after she attempted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   He set himself up as a translator, opened an English-language
school in Yugawara and began pursuing Japanese citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the practical thing to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, foreigners were not eligible for public health
insurance or pensions and could not obtain housing loans. And
Tsurunen wanted to buy a house.
</P>
<P>
   Obtaining citizenship took some persistence. Immigration
authorities considered him a bit of a crackpot and initially would
not give him the application forms. He and his wife endured three
intensive interviews. His neighbors were interviewed. Immigration
officials visited his house to ascertain that he was indeed living
a Japanese lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in 1979, he became a Japanese citizen, with the
Japanese name Marutei Tsurunen instead of the Finnish Martti
Turunen, and eligible to run for public office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I feel Japanese?'' he said. ``No. I'm still a Finn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago, I wanted to be as Japanese as possible,'' he
continued. ``But I quickly realized that was impossible and not at
all necessary to achieve what I wanted to achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   If he wins, Tsurunen would be the first Caucasian to serve in
the Japanese Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I very often feel why in the world did I get into this,'' he
said. ``People are expecting so much from me, and if I win, I'll
always be in the spotlight. Everyone wants me to change politics,
and it's very hard for one foreigner to do that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 1405EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980711.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0527 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GULF-SNAPPER-CRISIS-A     07-11 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULF-SNAPPER-CRISIS-ART-NYTRNG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALABAMA RESORT FEARS BAN ON CATCHING RED SNAPPER
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 N.Y. Times Regional Newspaper Group    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORANGE BEACH, Ala. _ Accustomed to weathering the occasional
hurricane that barrels out of the Gulf of Mexico, this bustling
resort is now bracing for a potential catastrophe of a different
sort.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials, saying the Gulf's signature red snapper is as
overfished as it is delicious, are threatening to close down
recreational angling for snapper as early as Sept. 1. It is a
decision that could have a devastating economic impact on this
community that bills itself as ``the red snapper capital of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That would put me out of business,'' said Neal Grube, a
veteran charter captain who earns $750 a day and more from sports
anglers on his 38-foot boat, the Catch-it.
</P>
<P>
   He is not the only one. About 100 charter boats run out of the
marinas dotting the waterways of this fishing center on the eastern
end of the 32-mile island reaching from the Florida border to
Mobile Bay, informally called Pleasure Island.
</P>
<P>
   World-class fishing and sugar-white sand have helped Orange
Beach and the adjacent Gulf Shores blossom into a full-fledged
tourist destination. But fishing drives the economy and tourism
officials are busy estimating the potential losses in an effort to
persuade officials of the National Marine Fisheries Service to keep
the season open even if the agency determines that too many red
snapper are being killed in the nets of commercial shrimpers.
</P>
<P>
   A 1994 study put the direct financial impact of charter fishing
on the local economy at $35 million annually with an additional $10
million to $15 million attributed to the ripple effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fishing is a mainstay of the economy,'' said Herbert Malone
Jr., president of the Alabama Gulf Coast Convention and Visitors
Bureau. ``It not only fuels the fishing industry, the boats,
marinas and suppliers, but the same people who come and go fishing
shop in the retail stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobbi Walker, president of the Orange Beach Fishing Association
and wife of a local charter captain, could not agree more.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a single business on this island not touched by
the charter and recreational fishing,'' Mrs. Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   She said it was the lure of snapper fishing that drew visitors
to the area in the first place, with anglers in pursuit of the
brilliant rose-hued fish arriving with their families in tow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charter boat fishing really built this area,'' Mrs. Walker
said. ``Men would come down here to fish and their wives would
relax on the beach and that is still going on.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated two million people visit the resort island
annually, many of them returning year after year. Many of these
vacationers take a day or two out of their beach-going to cruise
aboard a charter 20 miles or more into the Gulf in pursuit of
snapper, which is now at the center of the conservation dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Once abundant, the snapper supported a thriving commercial
fishing industry as far back as 100 years. But in the 1980s, the
take of red snappers reached historical lows and worried federal
fishery managers began searching for solutions.
</P>
<P>
   The National Marine Fisheries Service imposed quotas on both
commercial and recreational fishing. This spring, after a decade of
deliberations and $10 million in research, the service went after
what it believed to be a major cause of the declining snapper
stock: the trawls of commercial shrimpers that ensnare and kill
inch-long snappers.
</P>
<P>
   To eliminate what it estimates is the loss of 35 million
juvenile snappers a year in shrimp nets, the fisheries service in
May began requiring shrimpers plying most Gulf waters to sew into
their nets a special device that is supposed to let trapped fin
fish escape. The agency is now monitoring use of the new gear. If
agency officials determine it is not sufficiently effective, they
could cut back or shut down recreational snapper fishing.
Commercial snapper fishing _ already suspended _ would not be
allowed to resume this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock is seriously overfished and I think you have to put
the emphasis on the word seriously,'' said Andrew Kemmerer,
southeast region director for the National Marine Fisheries
Service.
</P>
<P>
   But the charter boat captains say their experience suggests
otherwise. They say passengers on their boats easily catch their
daily four-fish limit of snappers.
</P>
<P>
   The fishermen and some biologists credit an ambitious effort to
build artificial reefs off the coast _ dropping everything from
surplus military tanks to old bridge spans into the Gulf _ with
helping the snapper rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Kemmerer and conservation advocates concede the snapper stock
appears to be recovering. But they say continued limits are
necessary to give the new fish the chance to reach their prime
reproductive years.
</P>
<P>
   The federal decision to link the fortunes of the shrimpers and
the snapper fishermen has the two factions sniping at each other.
The shrimpers, who already pull devices to save endangered sea
turtles, do not like the new gear and have filed a lawsuit in Texas
in an effort to get the regulation lifted.
</P>
<P>
   The snapper fishermen fault the shrimpers for the predicament,
saying the more powerful shrimp industry employed its ample
political clout to delay needed restrictions on fish ensnared by
accident while the snapper fishermen regularly absorbed limits on
their catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four snapper a person to me is fair,'' said Ben Fairey, who
captains the Necessity. ``But when you are talking about a closed
season in the middle of our tourist season, that is economic
disaster for us.''
</P>
