<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0543 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROSPERITY-HOUSING12-     07-11 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSPERITY-HOUSING12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home builder has never seen such a long stretch of ups
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Karl Zengel has been a home builder in this area
since the 1950s and he has seen a lot of ups and downs in the local
economy.
</P>
<P>
   He's never seen anything like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is good. Really it's so good that it scares you a
little bit,'' said Zengel, whose family-run business has a niche of
the present building boom.
</P>
<P>
   With generally low mortgage interest rates, around 7 percent or
lower, the United States is seeing record levels of new homes being
built. The number of new building permits is up 9 percent overall,
according to David Bohardt, executive director of the Home Builders
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Demographic projections are predicting even further growth. For
example, Claritas, a scientific marketing research firm in
Virginia, has conducted an in-depth study of Dayton and the Miami
Valley. Its results indicate that the number of houses valued in
excess of $500,000 will nearly double in five years, from 592 units
in 1997 to 1,001 in the year 2002. Houses in the $250,000 to
$499,000 range will see a similar leap, from 4,721 to 8,448.
</P>
<P>
   Claritas uses a variety of statistical methods, census data,
polling and credit reports and has proven to be quite accurate in
anticipating buying patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new construction is suburban, but the city of Dayton
has seen more new house permits as well. However, the city has more
than 10,000 vacant or boarded-up houses.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of his three brothers, John, George and Adam,
Zengel built his first house in 1957 and since has constructed 800
homes, apartments and condos. He has been through many economic
cycles: inflation, double-digit interest rates, the oil crisis of
the early '70s that cut off natural gas hookups. During the early
'80s he cut his workers back to three days a week to keep them
working.
</P>
<P>
   However, the economy started improving by the mid-80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since about 1986 we have had good times,'' Zengel said.
``That's 12 years. In my experience we've never had a stretch like
that. We are really sailing on uncharted waters now, so I don't
know what is going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The good stretch is reflected in the kind of houses Zengel
builds, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics show that the average family house is now 29 percent
larger than houses built two decades ago, averaging 2,400 square
feet. The housing market has changed dramatically, too. The average
price for a new home has climbed from $115,000 to $127,000 in the
past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '50s we were building basic shelter for families,''
Zengel said. ``When I started, you could drive down most streets
and see two, three, four, five kids in every yard. Now one of the
biggest areas is the move-up market, people whose average age is 50
or 60 who either have no kids or whose kids have left home.''
</P>
<P>
   Zengel said that while most of the houses he built in the 1950s
and '60s were well-constructed in the basics such as frame, heating
and electrical, they didn't have the luxury details that are almost
a requirement now _ things like cathedral ceilings over the family
room, large master bedrooms and baths with whirlpools, skylights
and elaborate decks.
</P>
<P>
   ``As people move up in the market, they have developed tastes
and demand for a lot of nice things,'' he said. ``There are a lot
more dollars out there now, but the market has also broadened quite
a bit. Profit margins are slimmer, which puts the burden on the
builder to find a way to survive with less.''
</P>
<P>
   Zengel said his company sells what it can build, not build as
many as it can sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We schedule to build only a certain amount and play it pretty
close to the vest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like others in construction, Zengel sometimes finds it difficult
to find skilled workers, noting that his younger brother, who is
68, can still be seen out driving a bulldozer. His two sons and
five nephews are also part of the business.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
