<DOCNO> NYT19980711.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0544 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROSPERITY-MAIN12-COX     07-11 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSPERITY-MAIN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Booming '90s creating generation of optimists
 &HT;    (Embargoed until Sunday, July 12.)
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It is not the Roaring Twenties, or the Fabulous
Fifties or even the Go-Go Sixties. The '90s have yet to get a name,
but for many of us _ perhaps even most of us _ it is a time of
unbridled optimism.
</P>
<P>
   The no-name '90s are not so much marked by downsizing, corporate
takeovers and plant shutdowns _ although there has been plenty of
that _ but by rampant consumerism.
</P>
<P>
   Try an experiment. Look around your house and make a mental note
of all the stuff _ CDs, computers, cell phones, microwaves, video
games. We have exercise bikes that tell us how far we've gone,
calculate our calories and monitor our hearts. We have televisions
that bring movies and sports on demand through coaxial cable wired
directly to our homes, or through satellite dishes mounted on our
roofs. And we watch in perfect, air-conditioned comfort without
having to get out of our chairs to change the channel.
</P>
<P>
   Now, consider this: Your parents, who wanted a better life for
you, never dreamed of any of this.
</P>
<P>
   This decade may end up outdoing all of the previous boom times
the country has seen. It's not that everybody is getting rich. In
the '90s a large and growing population was labeled with an
oxymoron: working poor. Wages and benefits are actually declining
for a fifth of the country's workers. There's a growing disparity
between rich and poor, with the latter nearly shut out of many of
the benefits and advantages prosperity offers.
</P>
<P>
   But the so-called economic recovery has gone on so long even
Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, says there's
been nothing like it in 50 years. Low inflation. Low unemployment.
Low interest rates. A stock market that mirrors a climber on Mount
Everest, going up, coming down then finding ways to go higher
still.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton Daily News conducted a poll in five southeast Ohio
counties in an area of the country known not so affectionately as
the Rust Belt. Fifty-eight percent of the residents rated the local
economy as good or excellent, while just 10 percent said it was
below average or poor. But here's the real kicker: 72 percent said
they were optimistic over the next five years, an indication that
folks here believe the best days are ahead.
</P>
<P>
   And why not. Inflation, ranging between 1.5 and 2.5 percent in
this area, mirrors the rest of the nation. Mortgage interest rates,
around 7 percent or lower, have caused home sales to soar, an
increase of 9 percent overall and 45 percent in some areas.
Builders report an upsurge in people in their 60s and 70s moving up
to more luxurious homes.
</P>
<P>
   Herman Castro of Springboro, Ohio, is one of those who has
parlayed the '90s economy into ultra-success. An immigrant who was
born in Bogota, Colombia, Castro left the restaurant business to
enter real estate 10 years ago. Last year, he sold 80 properties
worth a total of $10 million. This year he expects to do even
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fortunate to go into the business at the time I did,''
Castro said. ``I have experienced 10 years of growth. The economy
is good, but it is what you make of it.''
</P>
<P>
   They are still small in numbers, but the '90s economy has
produced an entirely new social class: the 401(k) millionaire.
These are not people who inherited their fortune or got rich
through executive salaries. They invested wisely. And those
investments are booming.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, the first year the Internal Revenue Service began
collecting such data, 883 taxpayers reported $1 million or more in
Adjusted Gross Income. By 1994, the number had reached 69,935. Two
years later, as the stock market continued its miraculous soar, the
number was estimated at 111,728 _ a million-a-year club the size of
Peoria, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Prosperity is not just measured in dollars and cents. While
comparisons to the booming '50s come to mind, today's society is in
many ways a more diverse and fair one than existed during the Cold
War and before the civil rights movement. Women and minorities
locked out of the job market in the '50s find fewer doors closed.
Quality of life is improving.
</P>
<P>
   But the '90s have also spawned an entire movement geared toward
simplification, as hectic lifestyles and crushing work schedules
take a toll on personal lives. All of which raises a question:
We're better off, but are we happier?
</P>
<P>
   The rising demand for health and social services also reveals a
mean undertow beneath the nation's wave of prosperity: the gap in
wages between skilled and unskilled workers continues to grow, and
so does the gap in their benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's prosperity, it ain't trickling down my way,'' said
Chuck Linville, a 29-year-old Waynesville, Ohio, resident who
builds wooden playsets for a local business. Linville says his
family's living expenses have gone up in the last year, but not his
wages.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't your father's prosperity, economists say. While real
wages doubled for American workers between the end of World War II
and 1973, gains since then have been smaller and less evenly
distributed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, the top tenth of employees earned an average of $24.80
an hour, or nearly four times the $6.28 an hour for workers in the
bottom tenth. By 1996, high-pay workers were averaging $25.74 an
hour, or nearly five times the $5.46 an hour of those at the
bottom. The figures are all in 1997 dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the broad upward mobility trend we used to see in
the '40s, '50s and '60s, when everyone's wages were going up and
there was structural mobility across all classes of people,'' said
Steven Dandaneau, an assistant professor of sociology at the
University of Dayton and a member of the Dayton Poverty Reduction
Task Force. ``It's almost an exception to the rule today when
people at the bottom are upwardly mobile.''
</P>
<P>
   Education still holds the key to higher earnings. Between 1980
and 1996, the earning power of workers with only a high school
diploma dropped by 6 percent, while those with college degrees saw
their salaries grow by 12 percent. But with skilled labor in demand
everywhere, trade schools and community colleges in many cases
offer a more direct path to prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Although prosperity has been the '90s calling card, not every
city has benefited. Many have watched as much of the private
investments and booming housing market takes place outside their
boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Cities such as Seattle, Chattanooga and Portland have been at
the forefront of a concept with a clunky catch phrase:
sustainability.The idea is that communities that build on their
strengths and shore up their weaknesses are most likely to ride the
prosperity wave the longest.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton formed the Council on Sustainable Development
in 1993 with the idea that communities have to look for ways to get
better, not just bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Like grandfather's advice, the founding principle of the council
is: ``Each generation is entitled to interest on the national
capital, but the principal should be handed down unimpaired to
future generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Sustainability could describe the economy as well, with
contributors such as Linda Baldwin of Kettering, Ohio, who has a
confidence that borders on boundless. Baldwin runs a financial
consultant business with her husband and sees no end in sight to
the growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect it to go on another 10 years,'' she said. ``Read the
book 'The Great Boom Ahead.' The baby boomers are all coming of
age. And they will be inheriting in the next eight to 10 years.
They will either save or pay off debt. Either one's good for the
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
