<DOCNO> NYT19980711.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0545 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-BOND-COX     07-11 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-BOND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bond returns to Atlanta for NAACP convention
 &HT;    By Christy Oglesby
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's been nearly 12 years since Julian Bond left
Atlanta after losing a congressional race so many thought he should
have won. His departure to Washington, D.C., came after two decades
of visible, and sometimes controversial, public service as a state
senator, civil rights leader and Vietnam War protestor.
</P>
<P>
   This week he returns to his home in the nationally prominent
office as chairman of the National Association for the Advancement
of Colored People, which is holding its annual convention here this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bond makes frequent trips to Atlanta to visit his
mother, five children and grandchildren, those visits are quiet and
family-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   This trip is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a kind of homecoming,'' Bond said of his six-day stay.
``I will see people I haven't seen for many years. ... There are
just many, many associations I have with a wide variety of people
there. I'm looking forward to seeing people from my time with the
(Atlanta) NAACP, the legislature, my movement friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond, an NAACP member since his youth, discussed his plans for
the country's oldest civil rights organization and how it plans to
continue facing new challenges.
</P>
<P>
   He succeeds Myrlie Evers-Williams, wife of slain civil rights
martyr Medgar Evers, who restored the organization's financial
stability during her tenure. Bond led the group that called for the
ouster Evers-Williams' predecessor, who was accused of padding his
expense account during the six years he served as NAACP chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Your convention theme this year is ``Preparing Tomorrow's
Leaders Today. What is your plan for grooming the next generation
of NAACP leaders?
</P>
<P>
   A. We have, since our inception, had a vigorous and active youth
membership. We now have about 350 high school, college and youth
chapters, about 75,000 youth members. Seven of the members of my
board of directors are youth. Young people exercise leadership
roles throughout the NAACP and always have. So we are helping
prepare them by offering them leadership opportunities today. You
scratch a grey-haired, 60-year-old NAACP member and you're going to
find somebody who joined the NAACP when he or she was a kid.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do feel that there is still an activist spirit among young
African-Americans that you can build upon or must you create one?
</P>
<P>
   A. I think that spirit is there, but I think it's a mistake to
compare today's youth generally, white or black, to '60s youth. If
you compare today's youth, black and white, with '60s youth, they
are going to be found wanting. But if you compare them with '50s or
'70s youth, I think you will find they are performing at the same
level or above. Now, it strikes me that the major difference
between modern day young people _ and here I'm speaking of black
and white and '60s young people _ is that today's young people seem
to me less eager to challenge authority. If you are collecting
blood for the Red Cross, they will be there. If you are building
houses for Habitat for Humanity, they will be there. If you are
collecting food or blankets or clothing for the homeless, they will
be there. But they don't often enough ask, `Why are these people
homeless? Why aren't there homes for people at the bottom of the
income scale? Why does private charity have to substitute for
public policy?' ... And we hope their NAACP experience leads them
to challenge authority.
</P>
<P>
   Q. We often hear about the NAACP in a reactive context after an
injustice has been committed or after a tragedy or that the
organization is battling or overcoming financial difficulty. Is
that the result of how the media cover the organization or has the
NAACP actually become reactive in its pursuits?
</P>
<P>
   A. It's a combination of those two factors and something more.
First, we are going to react. No one predicted that James Byrd
would be dragged until his body parts fell off. But we had to react
to that. Nobody predicted there would be this spate of church
burnings throughout the South a few years ago. But we had to react
to that. We were in a reactive mode. We had to be. But
unfortunately, the basis of journalism is that something is wrong.
And that colors the kind of coverage that we get. We also know
reporters who cover this convention are going to run out in the
street outside the World Congress Center and find some teenage kid
who is bouncing a basketball and say, `What do you think about the
NAACP?' and the kid will say, ``NAACP? What's that?' And the story
will be written, `Black youth alienated from NAACP.' Then another
reporter will go to one of these receptions that one of these
corporations is throwing for us and they will talk about the shrimp
and the pork cutlets. And then they will run over to Techwood Homes
and they will say, `Did you know that the NAACP is up there eating
broiled shrimp?' And the poor person in Techwood Homes will say,
`Oh my God! That NAACP is awful! And that will be the story.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What are you plans for the NAACP as chairman? Is it new
thrusts or is it strengthening what's in place?
</P>
<P>
   A. It's strengthening what's in place. I like to say, 'We don't
need to do many new things. We need to do the old things better.'
What are the things that have brought us this far? They are
mobilization, organization, litigation, coalition. We need to do
the basics better.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You've said that the NAACP needs to continue the direct
action it engaged in three decades ago. Why is it you think
picketing and boycotting are still effective tools to advance
African-Americans?
</P>
<P>
   A. They are always effective tools, not just for
African-Americans. They are effective tools for any group,
including many groups I despise. These are ordinary, American
pressure tactics that many, many groups have used in the past, many
will use in the future, and there's no reason for us to abandon
them.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How is the NAACP faring financially and how do you plan to
keep in economically strong and independent - the emphasis being on
independent when a large number of your contributions come from
large, white-controlled corporations? How can you tackle problems
within those companies when they offer you support?
</P>
<P>
   A. The bulk of our money, I think it's 60 percent, comes from
our membership. But we don't apologize for taking money from
corporations. We think we're doing America's work. And we want all
Americans to support us, so we have no apologies for taking money
from people who want to help us do America's work. There have been
occasions when we have returned money. Some years ago when we were
in awful financial straits, the dictatorship of Nigeria gave us
$100,000. And we returned it because we thought it was dirty money,
and it was money we did not want even though we needed it. I cannot
remember an occasion in which a donor said, 'I'm going to give you
some money if you do this' or `I'm not going to give you any more
money unless you do this.' If someone said that to me, I would say,
`Fine. Keep your money. We don't need it.'
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is the plan to get affluent African-Americans, more of
them, to become significant contributors?
</P>
<P>
   A. We're going to reach out to them as we have done in the past.
We're very pleased for example that Kobe Bryant (young Lakers
basketball player) is helping us in our stay-in-school program. And
he is an example we want to hold up to others like him.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How have the challenges threatening African-American's
advancement changed, now that racism isn't as blatant with ``white
only'' signs? And how does the NAACP meet that challenge of helping
people overcome those obstacles when they aren't as obvious?
</P>
<P>
   A. The major difference between yesterday and today is that
there is a body of law which, on its face, restricts racial
discrimination. It doesn't always work, but the law is there. So we
are not going to see any signs anymore. As a consequence, it's
sometimes harder to fight discrimination because it isn't as always
as evident. If I get turned down for an apartment, is that because
I'm black or is it because the apartment is rented? It's more
difficult for me to know now. It's important for me to find out.
Because if it's because I'm black, I have a remedy. If it's because
it's already rented, I have to go find another apartment. There
have been very successful tests involving identically qualified
white and black testers in apartment rentals with the black people
being turned away and the white people coming along an hour later
and being given the apartment. There are ample ways to test, it's
just not as easy to see on the surface now as was true 30 or 40
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
