<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, July 12, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unsettled weather will cover portions of the central states on
Sunday as several jet-stream disturbances press eastward across the
region. Very humid air surrounding a stationary front will help
fuel a cluster of showers and thunderstorms over Missouri on Sunday
morning. The cluster will then shift southeast into the upper
Tennessee and lower Mississippi Valleys by afternoon. Some
thunderstorms will contain hail and damaging winds, but the
greatest threat from the storms will be flooding from locally
torrential downpours.
</P>
<P>
   Another area prone to severe weather will be over the northern
Plains, where a line of potent thunderstorms will erupt ahead of an
approaching cold front. Winds changing direction and increasing
speed with altitude will induce a few of the storms to rotate.
These rotating storms, known as supercells, are capable of spawning
tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Abundant sunshine and low humidity will grace much of the
Northeast and Great Lakes as high pressure from Canada drifts over
the region. After a cool start, temperatures will rise into the
lower 80s by afternoon. Farther south, intervals of clouds and
sunshine will cover the Southeast with spotty afternoon
thunderstorms forming in the sultry air. Meanwhile, broiling
sunshine will continue to bake Texas as temperatures soar past 100
degrees in many locations. In the West, sunny and seasonably hot
weather will affect interior California with patchy morning clouds
and cooler air expected along the coast. Elsewhere, limited
sunshine and cool conditions will embrace the Northwest coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Stormy Northwest
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of trees were knocked down in eastern Washington state
on Friday evening by powerful winds generated from potent
thunderstorms. Hail and flooding rain along with a few small
tornadoes accompanied this bout of severe weather across the
interior Northwest. While the coastal Northwest sees most of its
thunderstorms in the winter, inland areas notice many storms in the
summer when surface temperatures reach into the 90s. A surge of
chilly air from the Pacific was partly blocked by the Cascades,
allowing the colder air to move in over the hot ground and
triggering the strong storms.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
