<DOCNO> NYT19980711.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0552 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NCAA-WOES-3TAKES-NYT     07-11 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCAA-WOES-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSISTANT COACHES TEACH STUBBORN NCAA A COSTLY LESSON
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MARCIA CHAMBERS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The vote at the National Collegiate Athletic Association's
convention in 1991 was overwhelming. In order to cut costs, the
NCAA had proposed severely limiting the salaries paid to certain
assistant basketball coaches. There was certainly no great debate.
And despite the presence of roughly 2,500 college administrators,
many of them lawyers, no one at the convention questioned its basic
legality.
</P>
<P>
   That moment seven years ago in the Opryland Hotel in Nashville,
Tenn., has come to haunt the NCAA, for it set in motion a series of
events that resulted in a roughly $80 million legal defeat, the
costliest such setback in the organization's history.
</P>
<P>
   An examination of the decision to limit the salaries of certain
coaches, and the lawsuit by the coaches it provoked, reveals a
strikingly dubious series of decisions on the part of the country's
leading amateur sports organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' Dennis Cross, a lead lawyer for the assistant coaches,
said of the verdict and its consequences, ``is a self-inflicted
wound. I am still amazed that the NCAA, through arrogance and
stubbornness, let it get this far.''
</P>
<P>
   When the NCAA adopted the rule in 1991 _ the organization
believed it had the educational authority to regulate virtually all
aspects of intercollegiate athletics _ it never checked whether it
violated antitrust law. The NCAA and its lawyers later infuriated
the federal judge overseeing the subsequent lawsuit by discouraging
schools from turning over relevant financial information, an action
the judge termed ``malicious.''
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, the NCAA, despite numerous adverse rulings, never
seriously engaged in settlement talks until the eve of trial.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA, which is appealing the federal jury's
multimillion-dollar damages verdict of last May, says it lacks
insurance to cover the damages and has only $10 million in reserve
to begin to pay the 1,900 assistant coaches in men's basketball,
baseball and other sports.
</P>
<P>
   To its critics, the NCAA's mishandling of the coaches' case
reflected some of the wider, longstanding flaws of the organization
_ institutional arrogance, questionable structuring of its legal
representation, anachronistic views of the college sports industry
_ and goes a long way toward explaining why it has suffered a
variety of defeats and come under additional assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, the NCAA, after losing at every judicial level,
agreed to pay Jerry Tarkanian, the former basketball coach at the
University of Nevada at Las Vegas, $2.5 million to settle his suit
charging the organization with having unfairly interfered with his
pursuit of employment. The NCAA settled only after three mock
juries had found for Tarkanian.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the NCAA also signed an agreement with the U.S. Justice
Department to amend its rules for athletic eligibility after they
were found to violate the Americans With Disabilities Act. And
there is, too, an unresolved lawsuit in Philadelphia that charges
the NCAA with discriminating against minorities in its use of
standardized test scores in determining athletic eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think because of the increasingly commercial nature of
intercollegiate athletics it makes it more and more difficult for
us to make some of the arguments that have historically been
successful,'' said Jim Delany, commissioner of the Big 10
Conference, alluding to the NCAA's prior ability to contend that
the amateur status of college athletes enabled it to regulate
sports with little limitation.
</P>
<P>
   If the multimillion-dollar defeat suffered by the NCAA last
spring highlighted some of the organization's shortcomings, there
had already had been some signs the NCAA was realizing it had to
change its ways.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, the NCAA has undergone a far-reaching
restructuring in governance, creating an executive committee of 20
members, primarily college and university presidents, to establish
budgets and set fundamental policies and strategies. Such a system
replaces the more unwieldy one that afforded all member schools a
vote on policy matters, and strengthens the authority of the most
powerful sports schools.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, in a world of college sports beset with deep conflict
between education and commercialism _ the recently signed
eight-year television contract for college basketball's
championship tournament netted $1.7 billion _ the NCAA appears to
have its hands full as never before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will take a full-scale look at every rule,'' said NCAA
president Cedric Dempsey. ``We are willing to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the organization's first changes was to hire its own
in-house lawyer to manage its legal affairs, a practical move many
thought was overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are putting our house in order,'' said Elsa Kircher Cole,
the NCAA's new general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the case brought by the assistant coaches shows how
costly it was for the NCAA not to have its house in order.
</P>
<P>
   Amateur Ideal vs. Big Business
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA, formed in 1906, is technically a nonprofit, voluntary
organization, and its members are the colleges and universities who
agree to be governed by the NCAA for intercollegiate competitions.
Its constitution says its central aims are ``to maintain
intercollegiate athletics as an integral part of the education
program,'' and ``retain a clear line of demarcation between
intercollegiate athletics and professional sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the NCAA generates millions of dollars each year as
income and a significant portion of that money is distributed back
to the schools. An $80 million defeat represents more than 50
percent of the 1996-97 payout of $145 million to Division 1
schools. Thus, over the years, the NCAA's original purpose _
amateur competition _ and its recent huge commercialism have
competed awkwardly with each other.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, the idea of balancing fair amateur college
sports competition and the reality of school sports as big business
was at the root of the decision to limit the salaries of certain
assistant coaches.
</P>
<P>
   The restricted earnings coaches' case began in 1989, when the
NCAA created a Cost Reduction Committee. Although the NCAA found
itself with vastly increased revenues, many schools were expanding
their programs and recruiting high quality head and assistant
coaches. Costs for some schools were therefor problematic, and in
an effort to curtail overall expenses, the NCAA proposed allowing
schools to limit the salary for a third men's or women's basketball
coach to $12,000.
</P>
<P>
   The rule later was applied to assistant coaches in other sports,
as well, except Division I-A football.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to have what amounted to entry-level coaches _ had
they simply been called internships some of the legal problems
might not have come up, Dempsey believes _ and the rule was passed
overwhelmingly at the NCAA convention in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amazing thing was that at the time when that was passed in
1991, we were in a full town hall kind of meeting _ some 2,500
people and many were lawyers,'' Dempsey said of the rule. ``And no
one ever raised a question that this was a potential violation of
antitrust.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole said no NCAA administrators ever checked either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have found no indication that there was either legal advice
sought or given,'' Cole said. She said lawyers regularly retained
by the NCAA ``did not automatically review everything that went
through.''
</P>
<P>
   The assistant coaches who would later join the suit, some of
whom had been earning up to $70,000 annually, tried to get the rule
reversed but failed. A year later, the NCAA, acting to close a
loophole that had allowed some wealthy schools to pad the salaries
of the assistant coaches with lucrative summer work, ruled that the
coaches could earn no more than $4,000 per summer.
</P>
<P>
   Move to Dismiss The Case Backfires  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1992, a group of the restricted earnings assistant
coaches consulted lawyers. They wrote to Dempsey's predecessor,
Dick Schultz, in March, saying they were ready to file an antitrust
action, but would not if the rule were rescinded. Schultz responded
by noting that the NCAA ``has never been unduly swayed by the
threat of litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   In November 1993, the basketball coaches filed an antitrust
lawsuit against the NCAA. Jack Kitchin of Kansas City, Mo., the
NCAA's longtime outside counsel, responded by filing a motion for
summary judgment to dismiss the case, seeking a quick, binding
ruling based on the law alone, without any factual inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The move backfired when, on May 24, 1995, U.S. District Court
Judge Kathryn Vratil, sitting in Kansas City, Kan., rejected the
NCAA's bid to dismiss the case. In fact, she went further and in
ruling for the coaches, concluded that the restricted coaches' rule
was in fact a restraint of trade that had artificially and
illegally affected the marketplace for the coaches. The assistant
coaches had won a major legal victory. With no factual issues in
dispute, the only thing left was to decide the extent of the NCAA's
liability.
</P>
<P>
   Cole, the current general counsel, concedes now that the NCAA's
outside lawyers working on the case were allowed to make far too
many independent decisions, a problem she said resulted from the
fact that the NCAA was a ``fairly amorphous client.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Kitchin nor William Barnard, the lawyer who handled a
subsequent appeal in the case, responded to requests for
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1995 ruling, the NCAA immediately sent a memo to all
of its athletic directors. It said that the part of the rule
dealing with limited salaries would be lifted, but that all other
parts of the rule, including, for example, limiting the coaches to
five years of service at a school, would remain in effect. The memo
said that if the judge's order was overturned, the committee might
well recommend that the membership again adopt the salary
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the NCAA, after losing the summary judgment motion,
never moved to settle. Instead, it appealed the case to the 10th
Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our attorneys kept saying they would prevail,'' Dempsey said.
``We had Kitchin come in on several occasions and talk to our
boards about where we were. He felt all along that we had good
percentages of being successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen persuaded the NCAA to hire a law firm with antitrust
expertise, Sommer &AMP; Barnard of Indianapolis, for its appeal.
Barnard thus became the NCAA's new lead counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA's legal reasoning in the case thus far was that the
organization had the right to limit the number of coaches its
member institutions could employ as a way of keeping a level
playing field for all schools, regardless of wealth. Both Kitchin
and Barnard relied heavily on a 1977 case, ``Hennessey vs. NCAA,''
which upheld an NCAA bylaw adopted in 1976 to limit the number of
Division I football and basketball coaches in order to preserve
amateurism.
</P>
<P>
   But the force of the 1977 case had long been open to question.
In 1984, for instance, the U.S. Supreme Court, in a landmark ruling
against the NCAA involving the televising of college football
games, held that the NCAA was not exempt from antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
   The case then moved into its most contentious stage.
</P>
<P>
   More Coaches Join Suit; Countless Delays Begin
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Vratil issued a permanent injunction barring the NCAA
from using the coaches' rule under any other name, and the judge
certified the case as a class action. Soon a total of 1,900
basketball, baseball and other coaches affected in some way by the
rule joined the suit.
</P>
<P>
   But Cross said he ran into countless delays in getting salary
and other financial information from the NCAA, and he later learned
that Dempsey, the NCAA chief executive, had sent a letter to more
than 300 presidents of Division I universities and colleges. The
February 1996 letter, which was drafted by Barnard, the lawyer,
sought financial information to aid the plaintiffs in the
calculation of damages against the NCAA
</P>
<P>
   But the letter noted that schools could avoid providing that
information and challenge the coaches' lawyers to subpoena them
individually. The impact of the letter on the plaintiffs and the
judge was immediate. Cross quickly moved for public sanctions
against the NCAA lawyers, saying they had deliberately flouted the
discovery process.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, after indicating that she had considered
disqualifying the NCAA's lawyers, eventually held that Dempsey's
memo was ``palpably and authoritatively intended to discourage
responses.''
</P>
<P>
   She termed the NCAA's behavior ``contemptuous, malicious and
calculated to severely delay and frustrate the discovery process.''
She then ordered the organization to pay the costs for the coaches'
lawyers to travel to all the schools and depose all of their
officials. She also publicly sanctioned its lawyers, Kitchin and
Barnard and their associates, although part of the sanction was
thrown out on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, lawyers at individual schools, coming to understand
the depth of their legal problems, expressed concern that the
NCAA's lawyers were out of control. ``He appeared not to take the
lawsuit as seriously as was warranted,'' Pamela Bernard, general
counsel for the University of Florida, said of Barnard.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for some schools soon urged their presidents and others
in positions of influence to pressure the NCAA to hire an in-house
lawyer to take charge of the organization's legal affairs. Seven
months later, in the spring of 1997, Cole became the NCAA's first
in-house counsel, although she did not replace the lawyers working
on the coaches' case at the time.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1997, as the damage portion of the case neared,
Vratil pressed everyone to settle. Barnard was unmoved. ``With all
due respect your honor, I mean, I can be ordered and will
participate in anything I am ordered to do, but I can't be ordered
to settle a case,'' he said. He said he was still waiting for a
decision on the organization's appeal of the judge's initial ruling
that the coaches' rule violated antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, Appeals Court upheld Vratil. Now, Cole removed
Barnard and replaced him with Alan Salpeter and Gregory Curtner.
</P>
<P>
   Mediation Comes Late, But to No Avail  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In late March, on the eve of jury selection, the NCAA for the
first time agreed to mediation. Former Federal Judge Arlin Adams
was named mediator. Both sides were far apart at the outset and at
the end. The last actual offer made was $8 million from the NCAA
and $48 million from the plaintiffs. Just before the trial, Adams
told the plaintiffs he could get the NCAA up to $18 million and the
plaintiffs told him they would agree to $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's the last we heard,'' Cross said.
</P>
<P>
   The damage trial lasted one month. The jury, finding that
schools had kept some part of the earnings limitations in force
even after the judge in 1995 found it in violation of the law,
totaled the damages at $22.3 million _ not so much more than the
NCAA's last settlement offer of $18 million. But because the NCAA
did not settle, went to trial and got an adverse judgment, the
$22.3 million was tripled to $67 million in accordance with
antitrust law. With legal costs, interest and other fees, the
NCAA's bill stands to be roughly $80 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wrongest part of the court's thinking is that the
conspiracy continued even after we lifted the rule in 1995,'' said
Dempsey, whose lawyers have appealed the damage award citing the
judge's bias against the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   Other school officials are more critical of the way the case was
handled.
</P>
<P>
   ``In hindsight, oversight of the management process is, I think,
legitimately open for question,'' said Andrew Geiger, athletic
director at Ohio State University. ``This is fair game. There is no
guarding against bad decisions or a well-meaning effort which turns
out to be untenable. Then you get out. Get out of the deal before
you get hammered.''
</P>
<P>
   The full fallout of the legal hammering remains unclear. NCAA
officials have informed the 306 Division I universities and
colleges, including the major collegiate sports powers, that they
would assume the greatest part of the legal bill if the case is not
overturned on appeal. But despite the NCAA's assertion that the
verdict could have serious consequences for individual athletic
programs and sports around the country, they may have a way of
softening the impact.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA could borrow some portion of the $80 million and spread
out the payments. It could take funds from their own revenues that
would usually go to schools. Or they can do a combination of the
two. Depending on how many schools absorb the liability, individual
institutions, primarily in Division I, could be facing costs of
anywhere from $72,000 to $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   However the financial ramifications play out, Dempsey, the NCAA
president, said he regarded the coaches' case as a watershed
experience for the organization, forcing it to find another way of
doing business. Others agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the silver lining in the whole thing,'' said Delany,
the Big 10 commissioner, ``is that it refocuses our attention on
regulating in areas that are defensible and getting out of areas
that are less defensible.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
