<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0560 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FISHING-DISABLED-ART-     07-11 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHING-DISABLED-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON LAKE IN MINNESOTA, DISABILITIES GET CAST ASIDE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Wis., Ariz., Ill., Ind., Ohio, S.D.)   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By CARLA BARANAUCKAS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEMIDJI, Minn. _ On the shore of Lake Bemidji, little more than
a long cast from the 18-foot-tall statue of Paul Bunyan, the mythic
logger claimed by several northern Minnesota towns, a line of 15
pontoon boats sat beached in the sand one recent morning.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 50 yards away, the commander of this unusual flotilla,
Jimmy George of Bemidji, issued instructions to the people who
stood ready to carry out the mission: taking 75 people with
disabilities fishing.
</P>
<P>
   In this town of about 11,000, where for many people fishing is
an activity only slightly less essential than breathing, George and
a small navy of volunteers for Fishing Has No Boundaries were
helping people who are rarely able to board a boat spend a weekend
in search of the elusive northern and walleye, and the
not-quite-so-elusive perch.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing Has No Boundaries, a nonprofit organization, was founded
in 1986 in Hayward, Wis., and held its first event there in 1988.
The idea for the organization _ to take people with disabilities
fishing _ was born after a fishing guide, Bobby Cammack, broke his
arm and discovered how difficult a disability could be for a
fisherman, said Tom Mansfield, the national vice president of
operations. Events are now held in Arizona, Illinois, Indiana,
Ohio, South Dakota and Wisconsin. Bemidji, which bills itself as
the first city on the Mississippi River, first played host to an
event in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The type of disability a fisherman has _ physical or mental _
makes no difference, George said. Everyone is welcome, including
people who use wheelchairs or crutches, those who are mentally
retarded and the elderly whose infirmities have developed over
time. If necessary, special gear is provided, he said, noting that
one year a boy with no arms or legs was able to catch a fish with
an electric rod and reel operated by mouth.
</P>
<P>
   All of this was of little consequence to the people who had come
to fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to catch fish,'' said Carl Halvarson, 88, who has
impaired vision. Halvarson's fishing buddy, 81-year-old Hugh Veit,
described his disabilities, ``just for starters,'' as a bad back
and a bad leg.
</P>
<P>
   George, who has been chairman of the Bemidji event since its
inception, continued with his instructions to the volunteer guides.
``If the weather gets bad, we'll know that ahead of time and we'll
call you in,'' he said. He explained that emergency medical workers
would be standing by on the shore and in boats.
</P>
<P>
   Any boat that found a hot fishing spot on Lake Bemidji, or the
Mississippi River (which runs through the lake), or upriver on Lake
Irving or Carr Lake, or downriver on Stump Lake was encouraged to
radio in and let others know.
</P>
<P>
   As each boat was boarded, a picture was taken and volunteers
shoved the pontoons out. Two boats had momentary engine trouble,
but volunteers, some with shoes still on, waded into the cold water
and pushed the boats back to shore for some quick adjustments. By
10 a.m. all the boats were on the water.
</P>
<P>
   Connie and Bill Kelm, who raise cattle just outside Bemidji,
were host to two mentally disabled women who brought their own
fishing equipment and beamed as the boat headed to a spot that had
been lucky for them before: Stump Lake.
</P>
<P>
   The women, Gail Platt and Suzie Takle, both 30, have fished
since childhood and decided to participate in the Bemidji event
instead of the Special Olympics in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kelm asked: ``Gail, is your rod ready to fish? What kind of
bait do you want?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Takle nudged her friend and said, ``She's willing to put
bait on it for you,'' incredulous at her host's willingness to
handle slimy worms and minnows.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kelm quickly added, ``I don't do leeches.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, a night crawler was just the thing to bring
Ms. Platt the first strike, a perch. ``Is he a keeper?'' Ms. Takle
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Platt answered by nonchalantly flipping the fish back into
the water.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the morning's catch was salad bar, as the group
called it, or weeds.
</P>
<P>
   At noon, instead of going back to shore with the rest of the
boats for a lunch of sloppy joes, the Kelms' party ate sandwiches
and fished on. With little to show from Stump Lake, they motored
over to Lake Bemidji. By 5 p.m. they were catching perch one after
the other off night crawlers and leeches, which Kelm had no problem
putting on the hooks.
</P>
<P>
   Faces painted red by the sun, the crew headed back to shore with
several nice-size perch and memories of dozens returned to the
lake.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers measured, weighed and cleaned the fish. The catch of
the day was a 24-inch walleye, caught by Julie Scherrer, 39. The
fish story of the day belonged to Derek McArthur, 22, who was
bitten on the finger by a northern as he helped Dennis Bachand, 40,
net the fish.
</P>
<P>
   Over a dinner of walleye, fry bread and wild rice, George told
the group, ``Well, hope for better weather tomorrow and better
fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   But one first-timer who was completely satisfied with the few
perch he pulled in was Don Matthews, George's half-brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the best time,'' said Matthews, who was paralyzed in a
car accident two and a half years ago and had not been in a boat
since. ``If I'm on the water, I love it.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
