<HEADER>
A0561 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-IMF-1STLD-WRIT     07-11 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-IMF-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF DOUBLES EXTENT OF LOAN IT OFFERS RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (UPDATES throughout with World Bank deal completed, details on IMF
loan. No pickup). 
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The international effort to calm Russia's shaky
financial markets began to fall into place Saturday, as negotiators
sought to complete talks on more than $12 billion in new loans.
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund has informed Russian officials
that it is now prepared to lend about $11 billion, Russian
officials said. About half the sum would be provided up front and
the rest would be disbursed by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   IMF officials initially discussed $5.6 billion in new loans. But
the fund increased its financing package under pressure from the
U.S. Treasury Department and Western investors.
</P>
<P>
   Russian and IMF officials said they hoped to complete their
talks before the financial markets open on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In parallel talks, the World Bank and Russian officials hammered
out an agreement Saturday on a new loan that will range between $1
billion and $1.5 billion, Russian and Western officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank accord requires the Russians to take steps to
introduce more competition in Russia's gas and electrical sectors,
which have been dominated by powerful monopolies. It also lays the
groundwork for reform of Russia's railways and and encourages more
privatization of state-owned enterprises, among other measures.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the urgency of Russia's financial crisis, Michael
Carter, the head of the World Bank office here, completed talks
with Sergei Vasiliev, his Russian counterpart, at 1 a.m. Saturday.
The accord was then e-mailed to Washington at 4 a.m. for formal
approval by the World Bank's management.
</P>
<P>
   The intensive round-the-clock negotiations have taken place
against a background of deep concern over Russia's financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Anxiety over rising interest rates, the backlog of unpaid wages
and shrinking Central Bank reserves has become so great that it has
begun to rattle the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin has gone so far as to issue public
warnings against coup attempts, asserting that he commands enough
loyalty from the military to put down any ``extremist'' challenges
to his power.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about the deteriorating Russian economy, the Clinton
administration has prodded the IMF to increase the size of its
loan, to keep its demand on Russians realistic and to bring the
negotiations to a close.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's main fear is that a devaluation of the ruble would
unleash a fresh round of inflation, undercut Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko and his team of reformers and destabilize Russia.
</P>
<P>
   But to negotiate agreements with international financial
institutions is just part of the problem the Kremlin has been
facing.
</P>
<P>
   The Yeltsin government must still win approval of its
deficit-cutting and tax-reform measures from the
Communist-dominated Parliament. It is also trying to negotiate $10
billion in loans from Western commercial banks, in hopes of
bringing the total financial package to more than $20 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin met Saturday at his dacha with top aides to discuss
political and economic strategy. The aides at the session included
Kiriyenko; Sergei Dubinin, the chairman of the Central Bank;
Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov; and Anatoly Chubais, the lead
negotiator with the IMF and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president on the whole approved the progress of the talks
and instructed a completion of the talks in a compressed period,''
the Kremlin said.
</P>
<P>
   The main focus Saturday was on the talks with the IMF. The lead
IMF negotiator, John Odling-Smee, arrived in Moscow on Friday
evening, and appears to have been locked in intensive negotiations
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Russian and IMF officials are near to settling a paramount
question of how much and how quickly to cut the federal deficit.
They have been trying to resolve differences over amendments that
the fund insists be attached to the tax code that the Yeltsin
government has submitted to Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   When Russia's financial crisis began to deepen in May,
Odling-Smee was openly skeptical of the need for more assistance.
And he was described by one person in the talks as negotiating
``efficiently but without much pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank accord concluded Saturday seeks to advance market
reforms in several respects. But it would not require the breakup
of Gazprom, the giant natural gas monopoly and one of the last
symbols of Soviet power. Suggestions that Gazprom be broken up to
foster competition have been denounced by the Communists as a
Western plot to destroy what remains of Russian industry.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank accord would, however, change the tax system to
make it easier for other gas producers to enter the market. It also
stipulates that other producers should have access to Gazprom's
pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   To make the company's finances more transparent, financial
accounting of Gazprom's gas production operation are to be
separated from the accounting for its pipeline operations. The
World Bank accord also aims to open Russia's electrical sector to
private investment.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage more privatization generally, the accord would
reduce the number of so-called strategic state enterprises that
cannot be sold off.
</P>
<P>
   Another aim of the accord is to encourage more efficient and
competitive rail transport. Freight traffic has subsidized
passenger transportation, and this burden has pinched the
industrial sector, which is already ailing.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these reforms will take months, if not years, to fully
carry out. Achieving them will be the litmus test for the young
Kiriyenko team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has been given a chance,'' one Western
specialist said. ``But now it has to make a sustained effort. The
key thing is to make this work.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
