<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0562 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-HABIBIE-1ST     07-11 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-HABIBIE-1STLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTE PLACES HABIBIE IN FIRM CONTROL OF INDONESIAN POLITICS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Subs to alter 4th graf and add new 6th graf on Suharto
children being dropped from party leadership. No other changes.)  (js) 
 By SETH MYDANS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Indonesia's new president, B.J. Habibie,
consolidated his hold over the country's politics on Saturday when
one of his close advisers won a hotly contested vote to lead the
country's dominant political party.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first electoral test for the man who was almost
nobody's choice to succeed President Suharto six weeks ago, and who
many people believed would hold office only fleetingly.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie's control over the party greatly improves his ability to
set the political agenda and remain in office at least until the
end of next year, when he has scheduled a parliamentary vote for a
new president.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie's candidate, Akbar Tanjung, who is his executive
secretary, defeated Edy Sudrajat, a former armed forces chief, who
according to some political analysts had the behind-the-scenes
support of Suharto. Suharto, who stepped down in May in the face of
widespread protests, is moving on several fronts to try to protect
his family's wealth and business interests, Indonesian officials
say. He has used the governing party, Golkar, as a vehicle to wield
his personal power since it was formed in 1964. Akbar vowed to
change things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promise to improve and reform Golkar and rid it of nepotism,
corruption and collusion,'' Akbar told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   In an immediate sign of change on Saturday, a son and daughter
of Suharto lost their posts in the party hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   The vote for Akbar among regional party delegates, at the end of
a three-day conference, was 17-10. It was the first time in three
decades that the party leadership had been decided by a vote,
rather than by Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his success on Saturday, Habibie has not yet won broad
backing within the political establishment and his continued tenure
is a source of discontent among many Indonesians who had hoped for
a clean break with the past.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what steps he has taken, many Indonesians just do not
think he is credible as a president. An aeronautical engineer who
served as Suharto's minister of research and technology, Habibie
was perceived by many people as a political lightweight. As
Suharto's longtime friend and hand-picked vice president, he is
seen by many as too closely associated with the 32-year rule of his
predecessor to be the standard bearer for reform.
</P>
<P>
   According to his own account, Habibie was as surprised as
anybody when Suharto resigned suddenly on May 21, leaving the
leadership of the world's fourth-most-populous country in his
hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is still in survivability mode,'' said Marzuki Darusman, a
leading human rights lawyer. ``Let's not talk about credibility
yet. We still have some way to go until we reach that point. But at
some point people will realize, `He's still here,' and that will
make him a bit more credible.''
</P>
<P>
   Habibie has been doing more than surviving. From his first day
in office he has set an energetic pace and a populist tone that are
in sharp contrast with the style and substance of Suharto. He has
amazed people with his enthusiastic public style of leadership,
visiting marketplaces, touring riot-damaged neighborhoods and
holding long news conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suharto just listened,'' said Donald Emmerson, an expert on
Indonesia who teaches political science at the University of
Wisconsin at Madison. ``You never quite knew what was going on in
his mind. Habibie just talks and talks and talks.''
</P>
<P>
   Habibie has freed some political prisoners and promised to free
more and he has opened a dialogue over the future of the disputed
territory of East Timor. He has reached out to the Chinese minority
that was victimized during rioting in May and he has made a show of
consulting with his critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the impression that he is sincere in trying to get as
much done as possible during his transition period,'' Marzuki said.
``He is in a very real way trying to pull himself away from his
original circle and reaching out to the public. So somewhere people
will just have to meet him halfway.''
</P>
<P>
   Habibie also benefits from the disarray of his many opponents,
who are reveling in the country's new political openness and are
pursuing a range of different agendas. In a country that for three
decades permitted only three political parties, more than 30 new
parties have registered in the last six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Habibie has without a doubt surprised his critics,'' said
Emmerson. ``The expectations that many observers had of him were
low. The expectations were that he would be a disaster, so from
that perspective he looks relatively good.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Habibie's hold on office remains tenuous. He has
virtually no independent political base and he faces an economic
disaster that has only grown worse since it contributed to the fall
of his predecessor. According to private estimates, inflation this
year could approach or surpass 100 percent and unemployment could
reach 20 percent. Close to half the population of 210 million is
predicted to fall below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
   The economy, which grew by nearly 8 percent a year over the last
decade, could contract by 10 percent to 15 percent this year,
according to the International Monetary Fund. And in what has
become the most symbolic indicator for Indonesian well-being, the
currency, the rupiah, has fallen to about 15,000 to the dollar,
from about 8,000 when Habibie took office. The declining value of
the currency is one of the most damaging signals for Habibie's
prospects and could ultimately be more significant than his
political victory on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with Indonesia is that we don't have confidence
because there is a debate over the legitimacy of the government,''
said Laksamana Sukardi, a leading economist. ``We might like to
give Habibie the benefit of the doubt, but he is not getting it
from the markets. The markets are the main constituent of the
Indonesian economy, and they still say Indonesia is not the place
to invest. They are waiting for the bottom. Where is the bottom?
Are we going to be like Somalia or what?''
</P>
<P>
   Habibie's economic team and international donors are now
concentrating on emergency measures in the face of looming food
shortages. Habibie drew gasps from economists last week when he
suggested that Indonesians fast two times a week _ as he does for
health and religious reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's desperation, when you're telling people to fast,''
Emmerson said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their calls for an early transition of power, Habibie's
opponents have offered few specific proposals for a mechanism for
change. When Suharto resigned, he left his ruling structure, and
its personnel, intact. The country faces a problem in which the
incumbent leadership must legislate its own replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie's plan is to draw up new electoral laws that would allow
more parties and revise the current system of representation, which
is geared to perpetuating Suharto's power. By December, he says, he
intends to convene a special legislative assembly to set a date for
elections, in May or June next year, moving up the date that is
currently set for 2003.
</P>
<P>
   In January, new electoral laws would be enacted and preparations
would begin for the spring vote. That vote would choose an
electoral assembly, which would meet before the end of the year to
choose the next president. Habibie has not ruled out running for a
new term. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 1511EDT &QL; 
