<HEADER>
A0575 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-COL-TRENTON-HISTOR     07-11 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-COL-TRENTON-HISTORY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A WITNESS TO HISTORY AT TRENTON'S FIVE POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ There is a place in Trenton called Five Points,
where Broad, Warren, Brunswick, Pennington and Princeton avenues
intersect at the top of a hill that slopes gently down to the
Delaware River a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   George Washington put his field artillery there after crossing
the Delaware in 1776, and in the Battle of Trenton on Christmas
Day, the Continental Army had its first big victory. In 1891, John
Duncan, the architect of Grant's Tomb, began work on a 150-foot
tower, topped with a heroic statue of Washington, to commemorate
the event. Two years later, President Grover Cleveland sent his
secretary of the Navy to the dedication of the new Trenton Battle
Monument, and the governors of eight of the original 13 states also
came.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than a week ago, Alfred Braxton, better known as
Trigger Braxton from his fondly remembered days as a hellion,
closed the heavy oak and brass doors of the Trenton Battle Monument
for the last time and, at the age of 81, walked away into
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Braxton was born eight blocks from Five Points, on Kossuth
Street, and for the last 25 of the monument's 105 years, he spent
his working days, Wednesday through Sunday, in a little alcove
inside those doors. He would ferry visitors up to the tiny
observation platform under Washington's vaguely gesturing arm,
sometimes smacking the old Otis elevator works back to life with a
broomstick when they got balky. ``You can put down anything you
want,'' he told a visitor, ``but I always put down `elevator
engineer.'''
</P>
<P>
   Washington saw a lot of history, and so in his way did Trigger
Braxton. Like so many veterans of this part of Trenton, Braxton
says the best views are toward the past, although he admits that
may be changing. ``Well, this used to be a nice place,'' he said
the other day as he sorted through some leftover items in his old
office _ a pair of sunglasses that looked like his daughter's, a
handful of battle-monument brochures he thought he'd keep for old
times' sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a movie house, the Rialto, on Pennington, and
restaurants and a furniture store _ there was a lot going on until
Martin Luther King died,'' he said. The riots that followed the
King assassination in 1968 burned through Five Points and left it
with little but a reputation as one of the toughest neighborhoods
in town. The Reading Railroad line that used to follow the Delaware
and Raritan Canal in front of the monument shut down, its tracks
were torn up, and its old depot a block from the monument became a
center for retirees, where Braxton has lunch and shoots an
occasional game of pool.
</P>
<P>
   The plate-glass factory closed, too, along with the E.L. Curran
bottling plant, celebrated among Trenton kids for paying a nickel
for returns instead of the usual 2 cents. The families that could
move out did, and the storefronts that lined the street near the
monument are now boarded up.
</P>
<P>
   Someone returned the sword blade that had been broken from the
hands of one of the bronze soldiers guarding the monument's
entrance, but it was never welded back, and without it the soldier
looks odd, like a boxer in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Braxton came to the monument a few years after the riots, and he
watched as the patriotic observations slowly faded away. ``They
used to have Christmas celebrations of the old battle, and we would
have cannons and Hessians all over,'' he said. ``Then the people
would come in, and I took them up to the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Other times, when things were slow, Braxton liked to ride to the
top of the monument alone, to follow Washington's gaze down to the
State House and the Delaware beyond it. That was always his
favorite view, he said. To Washington's back, Braxton could see the
new suburbs growing outward, away from Trenton, following the
direction that the general, emboldened by new victories, took
toward Princeton, New Brunswick and New York.
</P>
<P>
   But eventually the annual celebrations stopped, the visitors
became fewer and fewer, and the big monument waited for some of the
change going on around Trenton to come its way. Eventually, it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Whitman lady came by one day and told me they were going
to fix this place up,'' Braxton said, and just as Gov. Christie
Whitman announced, the fixing has begun.
</P>
<P>
   The land along Broad Street, across from the monument's little
park, has been cleared for 38 new three-bedroom town houses, called
Monument Crossing, with prices starting at $60,000. A block down
Broad, the exterior of the state medical school's new Addiction
Science Center is almost complete, and space is being plotted for a
new culinary school, an expanded health-care center and added
parkland nearby.
</P>
<P>
   These days, after lunch at the senior center, Trigger Braxton
walks back across Monument Park and up Broad Street to his
apartment. He stops and looks up at the great general atop the
great granite pillar, and at the work that is beginning, slowly, to
remake the ragged face of Five Points.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, he said, he wishes he were still on the job _ after
all, the state has no plans to replace him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 1527EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980711.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0576 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NY     07-11 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BILLIE JEAN KING, HELPING OTHERS IS HELPING HERSELF
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mother of modern sport _ that's a self-description _ is
still in the kitchen, stirring the pot, ladling out heaping
portions of vision, hard sell and encouragement, urging us to play
fair, shake our booties, treat everyone equally, find balance,
accept responsibility, eat, eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my issue, caregiving,'' said Billie Jean King last
week. ``I have to work on that, taking care of other people before
I take care of myself. Even when I go to fight for something, it's
because other people are suffering. But I'm getting better at it
now. Would you like something to drink? Water, soda? Are you
comfortable sitting there?''
</P>
<P>
   Billie Jean King's most consistently interesting vision, World
Team Tennis, began its 18th season last week, still a mostly unsung
stepchild of tennis, much less world sport. Its combination of
elite athletes having fun and families playing recreationally has
yet to catch on. Only the Mother would keep loving and feeding it.
King will be 55 years old this year, which is also the 25th
anniversary of her match with Bobby Riggs, the most spectacular
public event of the modern women's movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't about tennis, it was about social change,'' said
King, who still talks as though rushing to net. ``It was more than
a symbolic event, it was a common ground. When you change hearts
and minds, you get things done.
</P>
<P>
   ``People find ways to get around legislation, look at Title IX,
but I meet with women now, with male CEO's, people who make
decisions, people who were kids in 1973, whose perception of men
and women were changed forever when they saw that match.''
</P>
<P>
   Billie Jean King will have a prime spot in the pantheon of
sports heroes that every news media outlet seems to be erecting for
the century's end, but she will rarely be placed No. 1, which I
think she deserves. As she observes, with her usual amodest
clarity: ``People don't feel safe with people who stretch them.''
</P>
<P>
   Her attack on amateurism in tennis helped doom that secular
religion in all sports; no longer could entrepreneurs control a
sport without risk. Athletes and their agents became limited
partners in all games. As the Joan of Ace, beating Riggs in that
silly yet significant match at the Astrodome on Sept. 20, 1973, she
became the living example of gender equity.
</P>
<P>
   In World Team Tennis, founded with her former husband, Larry
King, she found an expression for all her ideas about making the
game accessible, from encouraging fans to cheer, putting names and
numbers on players' backs, allowing on-court coaching and playing
lets on serves, to setting up a national network of bowling-style
leagues for every level and age-group of recreational tennis.
</P>
<P>
   This year, WTT's seven-team, 49-match schedule is sponsored by
Du Pont, at least one reason for King's enthusiasm for clothing
made with Lycra and CoolMax (``Not true, I really like that stuff,
it feels good.'') Her own athleticism these days is limited to
rehab and treadmills; she underwent surgery in April for a detached
muscle in her shoulder, and will eventually need heart surgery to
correct arrythmia. She is on beta blockers now.
</P>
<P>
   King has always been a pinwheel of ideas, often first-draft,
usually cobbled together on the run from conversations, TV shows
and the self-help books she consumes like vitamin pills. Last week,
she talked about coaching as ``an unbelievable woman's thing, we
are taught to be such nurturers''; the tendency of male agents to
ask for less than their female clients are worth on the market, and
why ``seeing white'' during fear can be a prelude to defeat or
disaster (``the absence of color means you're paralyzed, you better
start slow breathing right away.'')
</P>
<P>
   King says she wants to ``get beyond tennis'' which has never
treated her, as has the larger society, as prophet and pioneer. One
plan in progress is a foundation, probably bearing her name, that
would concentrate on health and youth issues, including an attempt
to stem the rise in suicides among gay and lesbian teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Her great power now, she says, is that ``I get to all those
people who can make things happen with a stroke of their pen.''
Many of them, of course, want to talk about Bobby Riggs and about
tennis before they sign checks or legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I ever write another book,'' she said, ``I know what the
first line will be: `Tennis is the best thing that ever happened to
me and the worst.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The best because I got to travel, because I really love to hit
the ball, it's an aesthetic thing, and because it gave me the
chance to make social change, to be the mother of modern sports.
The worst because the sport discounted me, its lack of embrace of
new ideas that could rejuvenate it, and because there are all those
people in tennis who still just don't get it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
