<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-COLUMN-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: METS NEED HUNDLEY'S GRIT AND MAYBE A LITTLE LUCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By CLAIRE SMITH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No one has questioned the New York Mets' heart yet.
Not even the Montreal manager, Felipe Alou, whose Expos had won the
first two games of a three-game series at Shea Stadium before the
two teams met in Saturday night's finale.
</P>
<P>
   The ever-honest Alou did question the heart of the
dead-in-the-water Baltimore Orioles after his Expos swept the
Orioles at the end of June in an interleague match between the
game's highest and lowest payrolls.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is the Mets, not the Orioles, who are proving fruitless
against the Montreal Expos, one of the youngest, most inexperienced
teams in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one should question the Mets' heart. Especially when
Todd Hundley, the player who epitomized the Mets' grit of a year
ago, was expected to return to the lineup Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   When the applause for Hundley's return dies, however, what
happens when the reality of the Mets' fade reemerges? What happens
when assurances that Hundley's obvious heart still exists is
overwhelmed by questions of whether enough overall talent and luck
still do exist on this team?
</P>
<P>
   There has been such a dearth of the former and such questioning
of the latter that the combined assault on the Mets' sensibilities
has dulled the enthusiasm that should have greeted Hundley's
return. The losses haven't helped. The Mets lost an inept 11-inning
game Thursday, then an 8-6 heartbreaker on a ninth-inning Expos'
rally Friday, defeats that pushed the once-promising Mets 13{ games
behind the Atlanta Braves in the National League East.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen is leakier than a sieve. Even John Franco, once the
only reliable reliever, has been saddled with the last three Mets
defeats, almost unheard of for closers this side of the woeful
Seattle bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Franco lost the two games to the Expos while awaiting appeal of
a three-game suspension drawn because of a bumping incident with
umpire Angel Hernandez during a controversial loss in Atlanta last
Sunday. The way Franco has stumbled into the second half, the
left-hander not only must question his timing, but his wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Franco is only a small doubt on a team devoid of reliable
setup men, a competent leadoff hitter and underachieving yet
expensive and therefore untradeable hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Friday the Mets reacquired Franco's old setup man, Greg
McMichael, who had gone to L.A. in the deal for starter Hideo Nomo
on June 5. However, that will be but a Band-Aid to all that ails a
team now in a 2-9 free fall.
</P>
<P>
   And now, instead of looking at Hundley as a welcome addition,
the Mets are looking at him as a life preserver, a big burden for a
surgically repaired player fighting off the rust. Hundley has been
out since Sept. 26, 1997, because of surgery to his medial
collateral ligament, a major reconstruction that once seemed
guaranteed to deprive the Mets' most potent hitter of the entire
1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley should be applauded for such stubborn insistence on
returning. And not only because he fought injury. He also survived
the team's awkward handling of the acquisition of a second All-Star
catcher in Mike Piazza as well as organization-fed innuendoes about
alleged drinking problems.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Mets need Hundley to do what no offensive hitter,
including the increasingly enigmatic Piazza has been able to do _
wear both heart and hits on his sleeve, pick up the team and carry
it out of its current disastrous path.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets need the player who set a home-run record for catchers
with 41 in 1996 to not only bond with Piazza, who hit 40 homers a
year ago. They need Hundley to re-energize Piazza, the player
originally thought to be an energizer unto himself.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, the longtime Dodger and short-term Marlin, appeared to
need no help, just supporting players, when he first arrived in a
trade May 22. With Piazza in the lineup, the Mets won nine straight
as stagnant hitters like Carlos Baerga and Bernard Gilkey
rediscovered long-lost strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, almost every hitter this side of Baerga soon returned to
his trance and the Mets suffered through moribund play that
consumed June and now threatens to spoil July as well. Amazingly,
Piazza rather than continue to lift the downtrodden too often has
mirrored the struggles of the lost and downtrodden.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, the catcher who was supposed to complement Bernard
Gilkey, to conspire with John Olerud to destroy pitching, has yet
to drive in a run in any game in which Gilkey and Olerud have runs
batted in.
</P>
<P>
   Now come Piazza and Hundley, the new tandem and the new hope, as
the Mets desperately cling to wild-card dreams, not to mention a
tenuous hold on second place in the National League East (the
rebuilding Philadelphia Phillies pulled within a half-game of the
Mets after defeating Pittsburgh Friday). And Hundley is the human
rabbit's foot of choice.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley has been on the periphery of the Mets' picture for weeks
now.
</P>
<P>
   Because his return has guaranteed an almost welcome angst
because the Mets would welcome anything that would rekindle the
competitive nature and juices of outfielders Butch Huskey, Gilkey
and Brian McRae.
</P>
<P>
   All three entered the second half seemingly bent on being less
conspicuous as disappointments, with Gilkey intriguingly
contributing as a leadoff hitter, something most every other
auditioning Met has failed to do.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Gilkey contributed four hits and two runs batted
in during the first two games against Montreal and the Mets still
lost underscores that the luck and talent are still too often
coming in a trickle, not nearly good enough because the Mets need a
flood.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets can now only hope that Hundley is the first wave of a
flood of good fortune they so desperately need. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
