A0580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-STRIKE-ASSESS-600&AMP;     07-11 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-ASSESS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: GM STRIKE DRIVEN BY LOCAL ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Ohio)  (Eds: This will be updated in the event of breaking news) 
(mk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ A 37-day strike against two General Motors auto
parts factories here has proved hard to settle as the company and
the United Automobile Workers union continue to raise the stakes,
making it harder and harder to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes are about very local issues: work rules, equipment
investments and job security at the two factories here and at
several other GM factories where workers have also been talking
about striking.
</P>
<P>
   But GM has presented the showdown to Wall Street as a struggle
over productivity and competitiveness. The union has cast the
strikes to its members as a showdown over GM's plans to expand
operations in Mexico, Brazil and Southeast Asia to take advantage
of lower labor costs there.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when questioned, top negotiators for both sides acknowledge
that a settlement is still likely to focus on local issues rather
than on GM's growing expansion abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Knechtel, GM's vice president for North American
personnel, said at a news conference here on Friday evening that
the company was seeking a settlement of issues at the two factories
here and at several other factories where workers have also been
talking about striking.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Shoemaker, the UAW's vice president for GM issues, said
a few minutes later that there was no sign that GM was
reconsidering its factory-building plans overseas, nor are these
part of the talks here.
</P>
<P>
   Local union officials say that the UAW is not even objecting in
negotiations to GM's moving production overseas of a few of the
parts made here, but rather demanding that GM replace those parts
with other work rather than continuing to allow the work force here
to erode through attrition.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street auto analysts in particular, who are widely quoted
as experts on the strikes, have tended to see the showdown in broad
terms: whether GM will be able to reduce its manpower nationwide.
But the negotiations here and at several other factories only
involve amendments to local union agreements, participants from
both sides agree, and not to the UAW's national agreement with GM,
which will not expire until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Agreements at any local union set no legal or negotiating
precedents at other factories. GM has gone through a dozen local
strikes at other factories over the last five years over similar
issues of local work rules and factory investments without making
any broad changes either in its relationship with the UAW or in its
overall costs of building cars or light trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street is concerned with issues that aren't issues in
this strike,'' Shoemaker said.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes here still might hold a few wrinkles not seen in
other local strikes against GM. The automaker has been talking
about reopening a few assembly plants with outside parts, for
example, and Shoemaker said Saturday that GM might be able to
reopen a few plants just with parts it has been able to scrounge by
checking warehouses over the last few weeks. But any such move
would likely send only a trickle of vehicles to dealers starved of
popular models.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations for the strike's outcome have become inflated
partly by the walkout's broad effects on factories elsewhere and
partly by the unusually strong language here. The UAW and GM both
studied carefully last year's Teamsters strike against the United
Parcel Service and concluded that swaying public opinion was
important. But in trying to woo reporters and the public, both
sides have sometimes overstated the strike's issues and raised new
issues that have complicated a settlement.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When GM publicly threatened three weeks ago to close some
American factories permanently if the UAW did not become more
cooperative, Shoemaker mentioned that workers at parts factories in
Indianapolis and Dayton, Ohio, also might go on strike later this
year, and that workers at a car and engine assembly plant here also
had grievances. Now GM is demanding that these disputes also be
resolved before any deal is concluded here.
</P>
<P>
   It is far from clear that strikes were ever really likely at the
other factories. The UAW's national leadership maintains strict
control over its local unions, which can stage strikes only with
the leadership's approval. Workers at the car and engine factory
voted last autumn in favor of a strike, while workers in
Indianapolis are scheduled to vote on Sunday, but UAW leaders
privately tend to view such votes as a chance for workers to vent
their frustration at the company, rather than any reason actually
to authorize a strike.
</P>
<P>
   Through many years of an often tortured relationship, and
through more than a dozen other local strikes over the last five
years, GM and the UAW have conducted their strike negotiations in
great secrecy until now, leaving the public and even the UAW's
members in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   The only partial exception to the secrecy in labor talks came
during a 17-day strike at two GM brake factories in Dayton in 1996,
when GM executives briefly said the strike was about the company's
long-term competitiveness, while UAW leaders stayed mum.
</P>
<P>
   That strike also was heralded as a historic showdown between the
UAW and GM, and like the current strikes, it closed 26 of GM's 29
assembly plants. But the dispute itself involved GM's commitment to
buy certain anti-lock brake systems from a nonunion supplier in
South Carolina instead of assembling them in Dayton, and the
union's demand that GM invest in equipment to build other parts in
Dayton so as to replace the several hundred jobs being lost. In a
compromise typical of such struggles, GM ended up promising some
investments that would replace half of the lost jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But the union and GM soon fell to squabbling again over whether
GM had followed through on its promises. So just 27 months after a
showdown in Dayton that was supposed to transform labor relations
in the auto industry, all-night talks are again being held in
Dayton now to resolve the latest squabbles before a deal is sealed
here. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 1533EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
