<HEADER>
A0581 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEV-BULL-RUN-NYT &LR;      07-11 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEV-BULL-RUN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BULL RUN STIRS FANS AND CRITICS IN NEVADA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Will update after running of the bulls) 
(jw) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESQUITE, Nev. _ To believe the Internet site set up to promote
it, the spectacle scheduled to unfold here is nothing short of
epochal. ``Never in the history of America,'' the site reads, ``has
an event occurred of this magnitude.''
</P>
<P>
   That just might be overreaching. This would not: In a state
renowned for unconventional entertainment, what was to happen on
Saturday on the outskirts of this tiny town, about an hour's drive
from Las Vegas, qualifies as particularly unusual.
</P>
<P>
   More than 350 people have paid $50 each for the dubious
privilege of lining up on a quarter-mile stretch of dusty ranch
land, beneath a punishing desert sun, to be chased by 1,000-pound
bulls. Hundreds more have flooded Mesquite's handful of large
hotels to be on hand to watch them.
</P>
<P>
   And Nevada officials and animal welfare advocates have vowed to
keep close tabs on what they said was the first attempt by anyone
in the United States to replicate _ well, sort of _ the running of
the bulls in Pamplona, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The man who dared to do so is Phil Immordino, a rodeo promoter
from Phoenix, who described Running of the Bulls America as a
chance for thrill-seekers to savor the ultimate rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get anywhere near a bull,'' Immordino said, ``and the
adrenaline starts flowing, the heart starts thumping. You're going
to be excited. You're going to have a blast.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, of course, unless you wind up with a horn through your
midriff or some other fatal injury. Such a fate has befallen more
than a dozen people in Pamplona in this century, and at least five
people, including an American, were in the event this year. The
prospect of similar bloodshed here has aroused the concern of many
city and state officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about liability,'' said Alice Fessenden, one of
five members of the Mesquite City Council. Ms. Fessenden voted
against holding the event, but was joined by only one colleague;
the three others, she said, argued that the event would put
Mesquite on the map.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fessenden said the city, a remote oasis of 10,000 residents
in a patch of desert about 70 miles northeast of Las Vegas, was
already there. ``Our high school golf team just won state's,'' she
said. ``Our little Miss Mesquite has been named Miss Nevada. We
really don't need this.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bob Miller also questioned the wisdom of the event and said
in a telephone interview that he supported the state Transportation
Department's decision last month to deny Immordino the use of the
main street, Mesquite Boulevard, through the center of town for the
Running of the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   The event was moved to a private ranch three miles east of town,
along the Arizona-Nevada border.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an event based on sensationalism that has a serious risk
of injuries,'' Miller said. ``It's ill advised.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greatest outcry came from animal welfare advocates,
who said they distrusted Immordino's assurances that the 24 bulls,
all of which usually participate in rodeo events, would not be
pinched, poked, prodded or provoked in any other cruel way to rage
down the quarter-mile track.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's under some pressure to make it an exciting event,'' Wayne
Pacelle, senior vice president of the Humane Society of the United
States, said. ``If the animals are just standing around while he's
yelling and clapping his hands, it becomes a petting zoo.''
</P>
<P>
   Immordino said that several men on horses behind the bulls, and
the promise of alfalfa at the end of the track, would get the
animals moving in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   The people, Immordino said, would be required to be at least 21,
sober and in decent physical shape. Unlike in Pamplona, Immordino
said, there are escape routes for scared runners. Even so,
participants were asked to sign liability waivers. Emergency
medical workers will be available.
</P>
<P>
   Participants said the potential danger of the event was what
made it thrilling, and that it would be an experience they could
always crow about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something to tell the grandkids, if I live,'' Tim Pindel,
28, a construction worker from Las Vegas, said with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Sullivan, 39, a waiter in Las Vegas, who was checking out
the bulls in their pen near the starting line and taking snapshots
of them, said he was here ``just for the thrill of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear the people in Spain talk about the thumping of your
heart as you hear the hooves behind you,'' he said. ``I want to
feel that thumping.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was concerned for his safety, he added, ``I'll just
pull out some old basketball moves, fake left, go right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
