A0583 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MISSING-MILLIONAIR     07-11 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE GET TIPS IN WEALTHY WIDOW'S DISAPPEARANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By KIT R. ROANE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Twelve hours after publicizing a reward for
information about the mysterious disappearance of Irene Silverman
from her Upper East Side Manhattan home, police said they had
received up to a dozen tips from residents in New York and New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Mode, a spokeswoman for the New York City Police
Department, refused to discuss the details of the information
provided, saying only that detectives were ``following up on
numerous leads.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting good information, but it's going to be a
while,'' she said. ``We are sorting things out.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Silverman, a wealthy 82-year-old widow who rented out
expensive apartments in her East 65th Street mansion, disappeared
last Sunday morning after an argument with one of her tenants,
Kenneth Kimes, said an investigator who spoke on the condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Kimes, 23, and his mother, Sante Kimes, 63, are being held on a
federal charge of writing a bad check in Utah. At the time of their
arrest last Sunday, officials said, the Kimeses were carrying
several pieces of Mrs. Silverman's identification. And a search of
their green Lincoln Town Car revealed a loaded 9-mm handgun, a box
of .22-caliber ammunition, 10 wigs and $30,000, police said.
</P>
<P>
   In the trunk of the car, police also found fraudulent business
documents, including a power of attorney form similar to a document
that investigators say Kimes tried to make Mrs. Silverman sign on
the Wednesday before her disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say the Kimeses are suspects in the March slaying
of an Los Angeles businessman and the 1996 disappearance of a bank
auditor in the Bahamas, both of whom had connections to the pair.
</P>
<P>
   The businessman, David Kazdin, who once owned a house with the
Kimeses, was found in a trash bin near the beach in Venice, Calif.,
shortly after Sante and Kenneth Kimes obtained a fraudulent
$280,000 loan on his home and transferred it to an off-shore bank
in the Bahamas, said investigators in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Bahamian authorities say they want to question the Kimeses about
the disappearance of a Middle Eastern banker, Syed Bilal Ahmed, who
had befriended the Kimeses.
</P>
<P>
   The police are also assembling a list of business associates
from the trunk of the car but have yet to find evidence of anyone
else who has been bilked or is missing.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said at a news conference Saturday that
the far-flung accusations against the Kimeses had made the inquiry
logistically complicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obviously a very intense investigation _ it involves
four jurisdictions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police in the Bahamas have been investigating the Kimeses since
1996, when Ahmed disappeared. According to Superintendent Douglas
Hanna, the banker worked for Cayman Island Gulf Union Bank, which
is now closed, and was sent to the Bahamas to audit one of its
branches where the Kimeses had an account.
</P>
<P>
   He was introduced to the Kimeses by a bank employee and was seen
with the couple two days before being reported missing, said
Superintendent Hanna. He added that it appeared the Kimeses were
offering to rent him a home in the area, though investigators have
yet to assertion whether they actually owned the property he was to
occupy.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators in the Bahamas said that it also appeared the
Kimeses were trying to form a corporation there, though they did
not know if the banker was involved in this deal. They said that
two former bank employees also figured as possible suspects in the
banker's disappearance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
