</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-RIVALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FITTING FINAL FOR CENTURY'S LAST WORLD CUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ With all due respect to the protocol-conscious people
across the English Channel who essentially invented soccer,
Sunday's final between France and Brazil is an appropriate finish
to the last World Cup of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the nation that launched the globe's most popular
sporting event against the nation that has been the most successful
in it. It will be South America against Europe; Ronaldo and the
world's most technically sound attacking players against Marcel
Desailly and the world's most tactically sound defense.
</P>
<P>
   It will be Brazil's Cafu against Bixente Lizarazu on one wing;
Brazil's Roberto Carlos against Lilian Thuram on the other. It will
be every man against his own nerves and his own limitations, and
when the last whistle of an exhausting, emotional month is blown
Sunday sometime between 10:45 p.m. and midnight, there will either
be a familiar champion and dancing in the streets of Rio de Janeiro
or a first-time champion and the biggest party the Champs-Elysees
has seen since Liberation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a child and you play soccer, you always dream
about being in a World Cup final,'' Thuram said. ``I remember
playing games with my friends: France against Brazil, but I was
always on the Brazilian team.''
</P>
<P>
   It is often that way on the playgrounds of the world. Brazil is
a symbol, a soccer state of mind. But this time, France will have
the home-team advantage, if there is one.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the first time that a host nation and a defending
champion will meet in a World Cup final. One reason France is host
to this event at all is because a Brazilian, FIFA's outgoing
president, Joao Havelange, put his weight behind its bid. Havelange
will be rooting against the French on Sunday as he sits near French
President Jacques Chirac. This is not the first time their nations
have met with much at stake.
</P>
<P>
   In 1958 in Stockholm, the Brazilians defeated the French, 5-2,
in the World Cup semifinals. Pele, then 17, scored three of the
Brazilian goals, but the match might have been less lopsided if the
French captain, Robert Jonquet, had not injured his knee in the
35th minute. This was in the stiff-lipped era before substitutions
were authorized, so Jonquet limped and soldiered on.
</P>
<P>
   The French would get a measure of revenge in the 1986
quarterfinals in Guadalajara, Mexico. After 90 minutes of
regulation and 30 minutes of overtime, the score was tied, 1-1, but
the French prevailed on penalty kicks, 4-3. The team was widely
considered the finest in French history, but for all their flair
and experience, the French would prove unable to solve the riddle
posed by a fresher West German side in the next round.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years later, French soccer has a new high-water mark, and
Coach Aime Jacquet's team has reached this level for some of the
same reasons Brazil ended its 24-year championship drought at the
last World Cup. The French, like the Brazilians, have put new
emphasis on defensive rigor at the expense of attacking brilliance.
The French players, like the Brazilians, have fled their
underfinanced, underexposed domestic league and signed big
contracts with clubs in the leagues in Italy, Spain, Germany and
England.
</P>
<P>
   ``By changing teams we changed mentality,'' said the French
midfielder Emmanuel Petit, who plays for Arsenal in England.
``Before, everybody knew that the French had some great qualities
and wonderful players, but we never quite had the mental strength
that this sort of competition demands. By going abroad and playing
for the best clubs and under great pressure, I think we have
learned what it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the fourth consecutive final in which a European team
will face a South American team. In the first three meetings, the
team playing closest to home has always prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   To keep that streak alive, the French know they will have to
keep Ronaldo from having time to turn with the ball. They know they
must mark the Brazilians tightly to keep them from making
fast-twitch transitions from defense to attack: either up the wings
with outside fullbacks Cafu and Roberto Carlos or up the middle
with Rivaldo. They also must avoid leaving too much space between
their lines: space that their more potentially dangerous opponents
are well-equipped to exploit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Brazilian team has been in some awkward situations in
this cup, but they have players with so much talent that they can
resolve problems all by themselves,'' said Didier Deschamps, French
midfielder and captain.
</P>
<P>
   What the French can potentially exploit is Brazil's central
defense, which proved vulnerable to well-timed crosses against the
Dutch in the semifinals, and a certain lack of consistency. Can it
be a coincidence that in four of its six matches, Brazil has taken
a lead and then allowed its opponent to equalize? Another question
is whether France and its Brazilian-style playmaker Zinedine Zidane
can turn these relative weaknesses into goals. Zidane has yet to
score, and since the second round began, all three French goals
have been scored by defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is why Brazilian Coach Mario Zagallo has had little
trouble laughing in the face of precedent this week. ``We have won
all of our World Cups outside the country,'' Zagallo said. ``I
respect very much the French team, but I am not afraid of it. We
are too used to big finals and big matches to approach them with
apprehension. If any players should have goose bumps before the
kickoff, it should be the French, not the Brazilians.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The only World Cup final Brazil has lost was at home in 1950,
when a crowd of 200,000 at the Maracana Stadium in Rio de Janeiro
had to watch Uruguay's team celebrate. Zagallo, then in the midst
of his military service, was one of the mourners in Maracana that
July.
</P>
<P>
   But since moving from the stands to the field, he has become a
talisman for his nation. He was a fine player on the team that won
in 1958 and 1962, the coach in 1970 and an assistant coach in
1994. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 1548EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
