<HEADLINE>
RICHARD BULL, 67, CHOREOGRAPHER WITH LONG ACADEMIC CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., N.Y., N.J.)   (bl)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Richard Niles Bull, a dancer, choreographer and
educator, died July 4 at his home in Manhattan. He was 67.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was lung cancer, said Gill Wright Miller, a friend.
</P>
<P>
   A genial man who stood by his aesthetic convictions with a wit
that was at times cantankerous, Bull was known as a pioneer in the
development of structured improvisation in dance. He used jazz
improvisation techniques in his choreography and incorporated
material like texts into his dances.
</P>
<P>
   Bull presented concerts and festivals of dance improvisation
regularly in his Warren Street Performance Loft in Tribeca.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Detroit, Bull began his career as a jazz pianist, moving
to New York City in 1948 to work with Lenny Tristano. He supported
himself by accompanying dance classes at the Juilliard School,
where he was exposed to modern dance and began studying with Alwin
Nikolais. He performed in the mid-1950s with the Munt-Brooks Dance
Company.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, Bull began a long academic career as co-coordinator of
undergraduate dance students at New York University; then he became
chairman of dance at the State University of New York at Brockport,
where he was a teacher and mentor to Lois Welk and Bill T. Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Bull's loft theater opened in 1978, and he directed the graduate
studies program in dance at Wesleyan University from 1983 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Bull's wife, Cynthia Jean Cohen Bull, professionally known as
Cynthia Novack, died in 1996. He is survived by a daughter, Katie
Bull Pritchett, and a sister, Joanna, both of Manhattan, and a
brother, Dan, of Montclair, N.J.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
