</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BKO-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: KEEPING TEEN-AGERS AWAY FROM THE FAST LANE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is nothing so extravagant to report about J.M.
Gold's first two weeks as a professional baseball player, except
for the telephone bill. ``He calls every day, sometimes twice, if
we're lucky,'' said his father, Larry, which doesn't account for
the calls the homesick teen-ager makes to his girlfriend, Lisa
Miller, among others back home in Toms River, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for the 18-year-old first-round draft pick, his room in
the home of the nice Wehr family out in Ogden, Utah, includes a
private line. ``I just got off the phone with him,'' Larry Gold
said the other day. ``But don't get me started; I'll start
crying.''
</P>
<P>
   East and West, there are emotional whirlpools two weeks after
the prodigy boarded his first flight, bound for a rookie league
outpost in the Wasatch Valley. Jon-Michael Gold, or J.M., a
right-handed strikeout artist out of Toms River North High School,
was committed to St. John's University until the Milwaukee Brewers
made him the 13th pick of the amateur draft last month, followed by
an offer and opportunity he couldn't refuse.
</P>
<P>
   The father, who drives a tractor-trailer for a supermarket chain
and hoped all three of his boys would go to college, hugged his
middle child when he said he wanted to turn pro, perfectly
understanding the part about the fantasy-come-true. No one in the
family, the community or even in the newspapers was going to
challenge the wisdom of J.M. Gold's decision either, the way people
do, with both knees jerking, when it is the young basketball player
from the inner city who somehow looks beyond the wisdom of a
bachelor's degree.
</P>
<P>
   When the sports columnist called, Larry Gold was watching an old
high school tape of his son, wistfully telling his wife, Diana,
that the house seemed so quiet now that the agents have stopped
calling and the scouts have gone. There is anxiety about his son's
being away, about his pro debut sometime next month, but at least
there is no mystery. There is only the time-honored logic of young
dreamers crammed into buses, touring minor league America,
beginning what they hope will be the climb to the top. There is
only the issue of practicality, no cliche-strewn sermons on
morality.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took me fly fishing one day,'' J.M. Gold said on the
telephone, with a Jersey-sounding chortle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wasn't much fun, but it got my mind off baseball for a while,
and missing home.'' Oh, and one other thing, dear diary: Alvin
Morrow _ he's an outfielder from St. Louis _ has become a friend,
someone to pass the 10-hour bus rides to Butte and Billings, Mont.,
with.
</P>
<P>
   There is no guaranteed storybook progression _ professionally or
socially _ but failure in most cases will not be attributable to a
warped assimilation process that places teen-aged innocents in hot
cars, fast lanes and, ultimately, in the path of the hardened and
covetous adults. If a sports cycle is changing and the country is
turning back to a reverence of baseball while taking a more
apprehensive look at the part of pro basketball that doesn't
include Michael Jordan, it is at least partly because baseball's
foundation was built to last. Basketball's is on the verge of
falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   This was never more obvious than at one of those dreadful high
school meat markets last week at Fairleigh Dickinson University.
One day, you had Dick Vitale imploring the kids to stay in school.
Another day, the shoe company sponsor was trotting out the likes of
Tracy McGrady and Jermaine O'Neal as jewelry-bedecked role models,
even if their last dazzling moves were from high school right to
the end of a National Basketball Association bench.
</P>
<P>
   The most revealing aspect of basketball's labor talks is that
they are never about what the sport most needs _ significant
investment in an instructional minor league venture. That would
mean less money for David Stern and Patrick Ewing but would help
get the sport back on a sane developmental track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any kid who is drafted in the first round of any sport is
going to be offered a lot of money,'' Larry Gold said. ``But how do
you take a kid who is 18, give him $5 million and just throw him
out there when he hasn't had any chance to mature?''
</P>
<P>
   His son eats meals with his host family, which also loans him a
car to get to his morning physical therapy appointments to
strengthen his shoulder. He is due back for workouts at the ball
park by 3 p.m. Game time for the Ogden Raptors is 7:11 (the team's
leading sponsor is the convenience store chain). The games end
around 10, leaving J.M. Gold time for a snack in the Wehrs'
kitchen, a cooling-off shower and a couple of late-night calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get him tonight, after the game in his room,'' Larry
Gold told the sports columnist the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Into the morning New Jersey hours, however, and well past
midnight in Utah, J.M. Gold's telephone line was busy. At least it
is cheaper to call at night. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 1602EDT &QL; 
