<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CREDITCARD-CONTRAC     07-11 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CREDITCARD-CONTRACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIDDING FOR STATE-SPONSORED CREDIT CARD RAISES QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del.)  (mk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In late 1995, Gov. George Pataki's administration,
looking for innovative ways to promote and profit from the state's
image, decided to sponsor an ``I Love New York'' credit card. The
idea was to sell the rights to the slogan to a bank, which would
emblazon it on a standard Visa card or Mastercard along with
pictures of scenic New York.
</P>
<P>
   The contract went to MBNA Corp. of Delaware, a large credit-card
issuer that in the last four years has been one of the biggest
political contributors to the New York Republican State Committee
and to Republican Sen. Alfonse D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   It is perhaps no surprise that MBNA received the contract, since
it was the only bidder. While the administration went through a
formal process to solicit bids, an examination of the way it was
handled shows that officials did not aggressively pursue other
credit-card issuers, raising questions about whether they got the
best deal possible.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Economic Development said it solicited bids
from only nine banks. Two of them are so small that they do not
issue credit cards. Those two, as well as three others, said they
had no record of having received a bid request. While the
department said that it had hoped to give the contract to a bank
based in New York, it did not solicit bids from several obvious
candidates, like Chase Manhattan and Citibank.
</P>
<P>
   MBNA received the three-year contract on March 15, 1996. The
following month, just as the credit card program began, it donated
$50,000 to the Republican State Committee, according to disclosure
records.
</P>
<P>
   Since that time, MBNA has distributed 109,000 of the ``I Love
New York'' credit cards, officials said, making it a successful
line for the company's so-called affinity-card business.
</P>
<P>
   Banks typically produce affinity cards in partnership with a
range of groups, from alumni associations to sports teams to
government agencies. The number of ``I Love New York'' cards ranks
it as a medium-size affinity issue, marketing experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki administration, MBNA and the Republican State
Committee said there was no link between political contributions
and the contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Economic Development defended the method that
it used to find a card issuer, saying that it was fair and
impartial. The department's commissioner, Charles Gargano, used to
be Pataki's chief fund-raiser, but he said he stopped raising money
for the governor and the state party after Pataki took office in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the department, Caroline Quartararo, noted
that the state had collected $388,000 in fees from MBNA. The
company pays the state $1 for each new card, $1.50 for each card
that is renewed and 25 cents for each charge.
</P>
<P>
   The department said it sent applications to eight banks in New
York and to MBNA. Among them was Olympian Bank of Brooklyn, which
has only two branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't recall ever seeing such an application,'' said Joseph
Baldasare, senior vice president of Olympian Bank. ``We don't offer
credit cards ourselves. We are a very small, little bank in Bay
Ridge.''
</P>
<P>
   The department did not request bids from a number of
out-of-state banks that, like MBNA, issue affinity cards.
</P>
<P>
   Several big banks in the state and elsewhere said they did not
know whether they would have bid on the contract had they been
notified about it, and some pointed out that affinity cards were
not their focus.
</P>
<P>
   But they all said they would have considered it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of programs that we look at, and there are
probably very, very few that we would reject out of hand,'' said
George McCane, a senior vice president for corporate affairs at
First USA, which is based in Delaware and is the biggest rival of
MBNA in the affinity market.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain how it chose the banks that received the
applications, Ms. Quartararo said at first that the eight banks in
New York were all the banks that were chartered in the state. She
said MBNA was asked for a bid because it was a major issuer of
affinity cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted the business to stay in New York if possible,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   When told in a subsequent conversation that more than 150 banks
are chartered in the state, Ms. Quartararo said she had been
mistaken, explaining that the department had sent out applications
to the largest banks chartered in the state.
</P>
<P>
   It was then pointed out to her that some of the banks that
received the applications are very small or have their headquarters
in New York but are not chartered in the state. ``What can I tell
you?'' she responded. ``There is this bureaucrat who works in our
finance office who just did it like that. It sounds ridiculous, but
that's what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that the department had announced the bidding in a
newsletter published by the state that lists available state
contracts. Any bank that had seen the listing and asked for an
application could have bid, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $50,000 contribution, the Republican State
Committee has received two others from MBNA: one for $20,000 on
Oct. 22, 1996, and another for $100,000 on March 5, 1997. MBNA and
its executives have also given more than $300,000 to political
committees controlled by D'Amato. The senator is chairman of the
Senate Banking Committee, giving him great influence over any
banking legislation that MBNA supports.
</P>
<P>
   In response to questions about the card contract, Terry O'Brien,
a spokesman for the Republican State Committee, said in statement,
``The State Committee does not involve itself in governmental or
policy decisions, nor will it.''
</P>
<P>
   David Spartin, an MBNA vice chairman, said there was
``absolutely no connection'' between the contract and
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we were selected is not that unusual,'' he said.
``We have 5,000 organizations that endorse us.'' But he
acknowledged that the ``affinity market is very competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Quartararo said the search for an issuer was done
properly, some credit card consultants disagreed. Michael Auriemma,
president of Auriemma Consulting Group in Westbury, said it was
likely that other issuers would have sought the account.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they did it right, they would have gotten a lot more than
one response,'' Auriemma said. ``In order to guarantee that you get
the best deals, you want to talk to different players.''
</P>
<P>
   Other credit-card issuers said they would not discuss the fees
they paid for affinity cards, or comment on those in the ``I Love
New York'' deal.
</P>
<P>
   But when South Orange, N.J., began sponsoring an affinity card a
few years ago, it received $5 for each new card in the first year
of the deal from Valley National Bank, said the village president,
William Calabrese. After the first year, South Orange's fee has
been 1 percent of sales on the card.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Giuliani administration considered sponsoring a New
York City affinity credit card, though it eventually decided not to
because it was concerned that people might think that the city was
the actual issuer of the card or was responsible for debt on it.
</P>
<P>
   But before the plan was canceled, several issuers had said they
would consider bidding for the card, said John Dyson, a senior
adviser to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a healthy interest in it,'' Dyson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 1606EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980711.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0601 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT &LR;      07-11 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG SCANDAL OVERSHADOWS TOUR DE FRANCE PROLOGUE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By SAMUEL ABT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ Whatever was troubling Chris Boardman
obviously cleared up overnight as he opened the 85th Tour de France
here Saturday with an easy victory in the short prologue through
the Irish capital. But it won't be as easy for the world's premier
cycling race to overcome news of a drug scandal involving one of
the top-rated teams, Festina of France.
</P>
<P>
   Although Boardman has also won the Tour's prologues in 1994 and
1997, he hadn't liked his chances in Dublin. ``I'm surprised,'' he
said moments before he donned the yellow jersey of the leader of
the three-week bicycle race.
</P>
<P>
   For the previous two days, he had been complaining about his
lack of form, his ``depression'' and unspecified personal problems
that he said were interfering with his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at my best,'' the British leader of the Gan team from
France explained simply. ``And I was lucky with the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   What a foreigner considered an intermittent sprinkle but what
the Irish regard as an integral part of the air, like oxygen, ended
early in the afternoon, a couple of hours before Boardman set off
in the 189-man field. The roads were mainly dry for his run of 6
minutes 12.36 seconds over the 5.6-kilometer (3.5-mile) course.
</P>
<P>
   That was four seconds better than Abraham Olano, a Spaniard with
the Banesto team who is regarded as much more of an overall
favorite in the Tour than Boardman. Olano is far stronger in the
many mountains that fill the race's course before it ends Aug. 2 in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Third, five seconds back, was Laurent Jalabert, the leader of
the ONCE team from Spain, the French national champion and the
world champion in the time trial, or individual race against the
clock.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth, also five seconds behind in a splendid performance, was
Bobby Julich, an American with Cofidis from France. Julich, a
native of Glenwood Springs, Colo., and a resident of Philadelphia,
is a strong rider in long time trials, not usually prologues.
</P>
<P>
   He is also a fine climber who finished 17th over all in the last
Tour, his first, and said before his start Saturday that his sights
were set higher. ``Last year I didn't know what to expect and this
year I do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tour officials certainly did not expect the drug scandal that
broke Friday night. It was a major embarrassment, and Festina did
little to deflect attention Saturday by turning in the best team
performance, with three riders in the top 10. One of Festina's
unexpectedly strong performances came from unheralded Christophe
Moreau, who led for much of the race and finished fifth in 6:17.32.
He was competing while petitioning his positive test for steroid
use at a race in June.
</P>
<P>
   The facts of the scandal were few: A masseur for the Festina
team, Willy Voet, was arrested late Wednesday night at the
French-Belgian border when his car was found to be carrying a large
quantity of such banned drugs as steroids and EPO, a chemical that
increases red blood corpuscles and thus provides more oxygen for
muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno Roussel, the directeur sportif, or coach, of the Festina
team insisted at a news conference this morning that the masseur
was not part of his crew at the Tour. ``Let the French police do
their work and find out what's going on,'' he said. ``We know
nothing about this. End of statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Marie Leblanc, the director of the race, was equally terse.
``It is a doping case,'' he said, ``but it's not directly connected
to a rider and not directly connected to this race. It happened
hundreds of kilometers from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Appealing for calm, Leblanc said there was no question of
disqualifying the Festina riders or making any judgment until more
facts are known. That is unlikely to happen before the race reaches
France on Tuesday and Tour officials can confer with the police
there.
</P>
<P>
   The Tour de France administers drug checks on up to five riders,
including the leader and the day's winner, after each stage. The
Tour has not had an announced failure in this decade and has not
had a doping scandal since 1988, when Pedro Delgado, the eventual
winner, was charged but then cleared on a technicality.
</P>
<P>
   Spot checks for high levels of red blood cells, and an
implication of the use of EPO, have been carried out before some
races for the last two years. Nearly a dozen riders were found
guilty and suspended for two weeks each last year and a half dozen
have been similarly penalized this season.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Festina team includes Richard Virenque, second over
all last year in the Tour and the king of the mountains the last
four years; Laurent Brochard, the reigning world road race
champion, and Alex Zulle, second over all in the 1995 Tour. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
