<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-STEINBRENNER-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN ITS RECORD IS 63-20, A TEAM CAN STAND PAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Yankees officials met for two long days
last week in the club's Tampa headquarters, reviewing every player
on their major league team, according to George Steinbrenner, the
principal owner. They also reviewed every minor leaguer who could
find his way into the majors by the end of this season.
</P>
<P>
   But what they didn't spend a lot of time discussing,
Steinbrenner said, are players on other teams who could end up in
pinstripes by season's end. With a 63-20 record, the best in the
majors in 96 years, upgrades aren't paramount.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always look for ways to improve,'' said Steinbrenner,
``but when a team is this focused and performing this well, there
aren't a lot of changes to be made. We've just got to keep it
going; we haven't won anything.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the Yankees will monitor the possible movement of several
players _ most notably Randy Johnson of the Seattle Mariners.
Executives around baseball believe Seattle will trade the
left-hander before the July 31 deadline, despite the fact that
general manager Woody Woodward is reportedly under orders not even
to field offers. Because Johnson is capable of pitching shutouts
and dominating in the postseason, some in the Yankees organization
are concerned he could swing the balance in a short series.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if the Mariners traded Johnson to Cleveland _ the
team the Yankees may play in the first round of the playoffs _ the
Indians would be in a position to start Johnson in Games 1 and 5,
Bartolo Colon in Game 2, Jaret Wright in Game 3 and Charles Nagy in
Game 4. Cleveland would have the type of pitching to beat any team
in a short series, including the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   According to one American League executive, Seattle has interest
in several of the Yankees young players. Having decided that Russ
Davis isn't good enough defensively, the Mariners would like to
have Mike Lowell, the Yankees' third baseman at Class AAA Columbus;
Ramiro Mendoza could immediately be plugged into the Seattle
rotation, and Ryan Bradley is a dominant-type pitcher currently
throwing for the Yankees' Class A affiliate in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, is also checking
the market for late-inning relievers, pitchers who could serve in
set-up roles for Mariano Rivera. Cashman had discussions with
Cincinnati about Jeff Shaw before the right-hander was traded to
Los Angeles last week. But with their bullpen in relatively good
shape, it's unlikely the Yankees would give up a few top prospects
and overpay for anybody. A 63-20 record provides comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, the Yankees have not lost since the third game of
their series at Shea Stadium; they are undefeated in the month of
July, with a 7-0 record.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd's Excellence Continues
</P>
<P>
   Graeme Lloyd hadn't pitched in 17 days, because of the
effectiveness of the Yankees' starting pitching. ``It's tough to
get any work around here,'' he joked last week.
</P>
<P>
   But Lloyd got an opportunity Friday, replacing Irabu in the
sixth inning with runners at first and third and one out. Lloyd
retired the next two batters without permitting any runs to score;
he has allowed only two of 25 runners he has inherited to score,
and opposing batters are now 1-for-25 (.040) against him with
runners in scoring position.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Irabu Saves His Spot
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu, showered and dressed in street clothes, waited for
his teammates at the clubhouse door in the moments after the
Yankees beat Tampa Bay, 8-4, Friday night. When Joe Girardi, his
catcher, walked into view, Irabu wore the broad grin of a man
redeemed.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi saw him. ``Thataboy,'' Girardi said enthusiastically,
patting Irabu on the chest. ``Thataboy.''
</P>
<P>
   Irabu saved his spot in the rotation Friday with an adequate
performance of five and one-third innings that was enough to break
his month-long losing streak. ``Better,'' said Joe Torre, the
Yankees manager. ``He's not all the way back, but his velocity was
more consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Torre did not rule out the possibility that Ramiro
Mendoza would replace Irabu in the rotation. After all, Irabu had
allowed eight home runs in 11 2/3 innings in his last three starts
before facing Tampa Bay Friday, and beyond that, he seemed unsure.
Torre seems convinced Irabu is healthy, but was concerned about the
diminished velocity of his fastball, and his growing reliance on
his secondary pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu had a good fastball at times Friday night, though his
split-fingered fastball was entirely ineffective and he sometimes
had no command of his curveball; Irabu threw one that didn't stop
breaking, Girardi joked, until it bounced against the backstop, a
wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up seven hits, four walks and struck out five, needing
102 pitches. Inconsistent as he was, Irabu made the pitches he
needed to win. Rather than feeling the pressure of losing his spot
in the rotation, Irabu explained through his interpreter, George
Rose, ``I felt more pressure to keep the ball down and throw
strikes. That's the pressure I felt, as a major league pitcher.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
