u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MARATHON-SWIMMERS-     07-11 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MARATHON-SWIMMERS-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KICKING PAST LANDMARKS, TO WIN A PRIZE OR FULFILL A DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Missie Hersey pushed through a half-dozen marathon swimmers
gathered at the Battery Park pier Saturday morning and called out
for a new friend she had met the night before, over heaping plates
of pasta, as they loaded up on high-energy carbohydrates before the
big race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's my best friend Duncan?'' said Ms. Hersey, a
50-year-old owner of a picture frame shop from Richmond, Va. She
then turned and hugged Duncan Adamson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tight,'' Ms. Hersey said. ``But when we're in the water,
forget it, I'm out of here.`
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hersey was one of 27 swimmers who slipped into the chilly
Hudson River Saturday for the city's 17th annual Manhattan Island
Marathon. The grueling, 28.5-mile course _ 2.3 miles longer than
the New York City Marathon _ circled the city counterclockwise, to
follow the currents, starting from Battery Park.
</P>
<P>
   For up to 10 hours, the swimmers kicked and drifted past New
York landmarks like the Statue of Liberty and the U.N.
headquarters. They were swept along by the currents in the East
River, past Roosevelt Island, into the Harlem River and underneath
the George Washington Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to experience New York City _ this is part of being
here,'' said Benn Kramer, a 41-year-old trailer park manager from
Hornby Island, British Columbia, near Vancouver, who was about to
swim in his 13th marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Each swimmer paid about $1,000 to enter and rent a boat for a
support crew. They underwent physical exams, including optional
hepatitis and tetanus shots, and proved their swimming fitness by
staying in 68-degree or colder water for at least four hours. The
winner received a silver bowl from Tiffany and Co., and others took
home plaques and T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   But for most of the swimmers, the rewards were less tangible _ a
challenge met, a promise kept, a dream fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just hoping to finish,'' said Gerald Vance, 55, a school
bus driver from Westmont, N.J. ``It's an honor to be on level with
some of the great swimmers in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   An hour before the 9 a.m. race, dozens of well-wishers crowded
the pier and clapped and cheered for the swimmers. A few passers-by
shook their heads in disbelief. Lila Ambar paused on her daily bike
ride to ask Ms. Hersey, ``Can you swim in that cold water?'' When
Ms. Hersey nodded, she said, ``I admire you, you have gumption.''
</P>
<P>
   But a few moments later, Ms. Ambar muttered, ``It's malarkey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they need their heads examined _ every one of them,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hersey grimaced at the remark. ``People who ask those
questions, they're never going to get it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hersey, the oldest woman to swim Saturday, had returned for
her second marathon around Manhattan; in her first, seven years
ago, she placed 20th in 8 hours, 11 minutes and 16 seconds. ``This
year, I figure I'll be first in my age group,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she plunged into long-distance swimming on her 40th
birthday, when she swam 400 laps in a pool. She has entered 10
marathons since then. ``It's addictive,'' she said. ``You can't do
something this much, to this degree, unless you're ambitious and
compulsive.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge of the marathon was what attracted Adamson, 28, an
account executive for a software company in Wilton, Conn. Before
last year's marathon, the farthest he had swum was two miles.
``You're on a high for two months afterward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's race, Adamson kept track of nearby swimmers even
though he did not expect to win. ``You create little races within
the race,'' he said. ``You have to create your own place. You can't
just swim for eight hours because it's fun.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Meryem Tangoren, a 26-year-old industrial designer from the
Upper East Side, found another reason to swim. She raised $1,740 in
pledges from friends and family that she plans to donate to a city
swimming program and a charity for multiple sclerosis. Last year,
she ran alongside a deaf and mute man in the New York City Marathon
to help guide him through the course. Each year, she picks a
different event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's really important to do things for other people,''
she said. ``For some reason, I have an addiction for endurance
sports, and this combines both things.''
</P>
<P>
   At 8:30 a.m. the swimmers pulled on rubber gloves and slathered
Vaseline and lanolin on their bodies for added warmth in the
70-degree water and protection against skin chafing. ``Did I miss
any spots?'' asked Kramer, as he turned around for the third time.
Another swimmer smeared a glob on his back.
</P>
<P>
   A few swimmers recited their best race times down to the minute
and second. Others drifted away to prepare themselves mentally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so nervous,'' Ms. Hersey said. ``That's the worst part,
the waiting. When I did this before, everybody seemed bigger than
life. Now they're just like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, who was stretching his arms and legs, looked over the
other swimmers. ``That's the one thing about this,'' he said.
``Age, size, sex don't matter. Water is the great equalizer.''
</P>
<P>
   At 9 a.m., the swimmers pulled on their bright orange and pink
swim caps and lined up on the gangway. Ms. Hersey impulsively
hugged her new best friend, Duncan, and then laughed as they both
shook their Vaseline-greased arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goodbye. Maybe, I'll see you next year _ maybe,'' she called
out. Then Ms. Hersey walked down the gangway and disappeared into
the Hudson River.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
