<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-GOV-KENNELLY-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNELLY TALKS OPENLY ABOUT HER CAMPAIGN'S PROBLEMS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILTON, Conn. _ Rep. Barbara Kennelly, the Democratic candidate
for governor of Connecticut, has startled supporters and opponents
alike by breaking a cardinal rule for surviving poor poll showings.
Instead of dismissing them, she has acknowledged bluntly that they
spell trouble, and she has agonized publicly about how to fix them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a long summer,'' she told a group of
supporters during a recent road trip. ``Has it been rough? It's
been rough and tough.'' Later, when a caller to a statewide radio
program told her it was time to get moving on her campaign, she
asked: ``What would you suggest I do?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly, 62, is challenging the one-term incumbent, John
Rowland, 41, a Republican who is the nation's youngest governor.
The governor's race will officially begin Monday, when Rowland
leads a caravan across the state on a four-stop tour to formally
announce his candidacy. On July 18, Mrs. Kennelly is to be
nominated at the Democratic State Convention. But Mrs. Kennelly is
already quick to acknowledge problems.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, financial reports revealed that Rowland had already
broken the state record for fund-raising for a gubernatorial
campaign, collecting $4.3 million, or more than twice as much as
Mrs. Kennelly had. During the last three months, normally a time to
hoard cash for television commercials in the fall, Mrs. Kennelly's
campaign just broke even.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly, the fourth-ranking Democrat in the House, started
her race in a dead heat with Rowland. But recent polls showed
Rowland with a huge lead in a state where Democrats substantially
outnumber Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   A University of Connecticut poll taken from June 23-July 1
showed Rowland leading Mrs. Kennelly 55 percent to 27 percent. A
Quinnipiac College poll taken from June 16-22 put Rowland at 56
percent and Mrs. Kennelly at 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Munching calamari during a break in 14 hours of campaigning on
Tuesday, Mrs. Kennelly said that polls are more significant to
candidates than most let on. ``Everything runs off the polls,'' she
said. ``They drive media coverage, and they drive fund raising. The
cliche is that the election isn't held until November. But that
isn't modern politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Johnson, associate dean of the Graduate School of
Political Management at George Washington University in Washington,
said it was very unusual for a major candidate to offer such a
pessimistic public face. ``Voters don't want to hear a candidate
whine,'' he said. Johnson, who is completing a book about modern
campaign practices, said recent history is replete with examples of
candidates who have turned around 20- and 40-point deficits in the
polls. ``Voters like a leader who's tough and breaks through the
barriers,'' he said. ``You're not going to catch fire if you make
it sound like it's over.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly, a lifelong Hartford resident, is no political
novice. Her father, John M. Bailey, was the national Democratic
chairman under President Kennedy. Her late husband, James Kennelly,
was speaker of the Connecticut House of Representatives. Her
brother, John Bailey, is the chief state's attorney. She was
elected to the Hartford City Council in 1975 and as the Connecticut
secretary of the state in 1978. She won a seat in Congress in 1982.
She continues to hold her seat in Congress, where she was so happy
working behind the scenes that she did not have a press secretary
for the first 13 of her 16 years on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Mrs. Kennelly announced that Joseph Courtney, a
former state representative, had agreed to run as her choice for
lieutenant governor, after a string of better-known Democrats had
taken themselves out of the running. The announcement should have
generated political excitement. Instead, Mrs. Kennelly faced a
grilling when she stopped on Tuesday night here in Fairfield County
for the monthly meeting of Wilton's Democratic committee.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Redman Becker, an architect and developer in Wilton, began
the question-and-answer session by saying, ``What I'm eager to hear
is what magic strategy you have to shake things up.'' Mrs. Kennelly
replied that she and Courtney ``love substance; we love policy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult with the press to get attention in that
direction,'' she said. ``We're trying very, very hard. I wish I
could buy $1 million on New York City television right now.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Mrs. Kennelly said her candor was deliberate.
``I am not a politician's candidate,'' she said. ``What your
political pundits would say is my problem is I don't spin. What you
see is what you get. What you hear is what it's about. I'm probably
brutally honest, with myself and with others.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry P. Michael, the executive director of the Washington
Center for Politics and Journalism, a nonpartisan group, said Mrs.
Kennelly's candor could be effective. ``You can be unslick,'' he
said. ``Voters relate to that _ that's a good message. But you have
to communicate that as a strategic message.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
