<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VAN-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATAL CRASH OF DAY CAMP VAN UNDER INVESTIGATION
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Pa, NY) (js) 
By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN with MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The van that crashed Friday evening on a Pennsylvania
highway, killing two Brooklyn girls on their way home from a day
camp outing, was overcrowded, and few, if any, of its occupants
were wearing seat belts when the driver fell asleep and crashed,
camp counselors who were in the van and state troopers
investigating the accident said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The accident, on Interstate 80 in Jackson Township, Pa., about
80 miles northwest of New York City, killed two 5-year-old girls
who had been crowded with 18 other children and four adults into a
van designed to carry only 15 people, the Pennsylvania State Police
said. Most of the occupants were asleep, and many were thrown from
the van when it crashed at about 5:25 p.m., witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Bedford-Stuyvesant Restoration Corp. in
Brooklyn, which operates the day camp that the children attended,
declined to identify the driver of the van but described him as a
23-year-old employee on the corporation's security and
transportation staff. The driver, who was not injured, had returned
home to Brooklyn, and, distressed by the accident, was placed under
heavy sedation, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the van's passengers remained hospitalized in
Pennsylvania on Saturday, including a 5-year-old girl who was
breathing with the help of a respirator, said Donald Sutton, a
spokesman for the Restoration Corp. Hospital officials would not
disclose the condition of the other five who remained under care.
The remaining passengers were treated and released from
Pennsylvania hospitals and returned to Brooklyn Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   One camp counselor, Patricia Parrish, 22, said that the adult
supervisors had given little consideration to the number of
children in the van and that it had not appeared to be overcrowded.
The van had contained the youngest campers on the trip, most
between the ages of 5 and 8, she said, while older campers had
ridden on a larger school bus that was not involved in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were small children _ they all fit,'' Ms. Parrish said in
an interview at Community Medical Center in Scranton, Pa., where
she was waiting to have surgery on her left hand, which was broken
in two places. ``Now I think there should have been less kids,''
she said, holding her daughter, Shaquasha Chambers, on her lap.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton declined to comment on the reports that the van had been
overcrowded and that the children had not worn seat belts, saying
he first wished to read a complete accident report by the
Pennsylvania State Police. He said the driver of the van had a long
affiliation with the Restoration Corp. and had attended the same
camp as a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``As best we can see, he is an experienced driver,'' Sutton
said. ``He is under sedation. He is obviously very, very distressed
about what has happened.'' The driver, he said, had not been
charged ``with any infraction in Pennsylvania.''
</P>
<P>
   A state police dispatcher in Pennsylvania said the accident
remained under investigation and further information would not be
released until the investigation is completed. Officials would not
release the names of the dead girls pending further notification of
family members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
