A0618 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-HITTING-400AVG-55     07-11 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HITTING-400AVG-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
62 HOMERS? MAYBE. A .400 AVERAGE? FORGET IT. 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The answer: ``That is a good question. I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The question: Why in this offensive season are players
threatening to break the records for home runs and runs batted in
but no one is threatening to hit .400?
</P>
<P>
   That elusive batting average, which has withstood challenges
since 1941, appears to be safe for the 57th straight season. Mark
McGwire, the leading threat to the home run record, was the person
professing ignorance as to why, but no one else came up with a
sure-fire answer.
</P>
<P>
   Don Baylor offered the best observation, but it was not an
answer to the question. ``The bar is where Tony is,'' the Colorado
manager said, meaning Tony Gwynn, the National League's perennial
batting champion. ``Tony's my barometer. Where he is, that's where
everybody else has to go.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if Gwynn is not challenging .400, no one is, and
Gwynn is not. He reached the All-Star Game break at .329, the
fourth-lowest average at the break in his 15 full seasons in the
major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The highest average at last week's break was .353, and it
belonged to the Yankees' Bernie Williams, who has not played since
June 10. That is the lowest break-leading average since 1992, when
John Kruk's .346 was No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The next season, John Olerud was hitting .395 and Andres
Galarraga .391; the year after that, Gwynn and Frank Thomas reached
the All-Star Game each at .383. Last year, Gwynn was hitting .394,
Larry Walker .398. So what has happened this season?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I knew,'' Gwynn said. ``I think what you're seeing is
maybe that pitching is a little bit better than they're getting
credit for. The pitchers are doing a pretty good job on the
hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   It is easy for the San Diego slasher to say that, but pitchers
have not stopped McGwire, Ken Griffey Jr. and Sammy Sosa from
hitting home runs, or Juan Gonzalez from driving in runs. Why have
they stopped Gwynn from hitting 70 points higher?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just haven't been consistent,'' he said, shunning injuries
as a reason. ``If I was consistent with my approach, I think I
could be hitting 20 points higher than I am. But still, that's not
going to allow you to hit .400. I've been there before and still
fell short. It just hasn't happened this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, en route to his fourth successive NL batting title
and his eighth overall, Gwynn reached .402 on July 14, six days
after the All-Star Game, but slowly slipped backward and finished
at .372, a figure eclipsed in his career only by his .394 average
in the strike-shortened 1994 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly felt this is my best crack at it,'' Gwynn recalled.
``Even when I was hitting .380, I thought if I could stay around
.380 and get hot the last month, I still could do it. It didn't
happen, but it convinced me you can't have any ruts. You got to be
solid the whole six months.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 38-year-old Gwynn to finish at .400 this season, he
would have to hit .488 after the break. So much for that idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to do it at the beginning,'' said Gwynn, whose career
average after the break is .336, compared with .343 before.
``You've got to come out of the chute firing and be consistent,
because if you're not, when you get to where we are now, you're not
going to make up 60 points in two months with all these at-bats.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gwynn said he believes he remains capable of challenging the
.400 barrier and mentioned Walker as another candidate based on his
performance last season. The Rockies' star hit .400 through the
first three months of the season and did not slip below it for good
until July 19.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what has happened this season _ he was hitting .331 at the
break _ Walker said, ``I woke up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fluke,'' he said of his final .366 average. ``I'm not
a .360 hitter, a .370 hitter or a .380 hitter by any means. I'm not
over .300 for my career. You have years where you say that was his
year. That's how it worked out for me last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker has been playing with an elbow that is not completely
healed following surgery. If it were sound, might he have
threatened .400? ``I guess it would be a possibility,'' he said.
``With a bum elbow, I'm hitting .330 now, so with a good elbow,
whether my average would stay there or go higher or lower, I don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Some others who were asked about the disappearance of the .400
threat suggested that players have become more infatuated than ever
with home runs. ``Big home run hitters are being paid a lot of
money,'' Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove said, ``and I think a lot
of people are concentrating on homers.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield of Los Angeles said the number of new pitchers
could be a factor. ``I see a guy for the first time, and it takes
me two at-bats to get adjusted to him,'' he said. ``I might hit one
home run that day or two home runs. But you're not going to have
four hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Robinson, the Hall of Famer, said there was no connection
between home runs and runs batted in on one hand and a high batting
average on the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four hundred is a very special number,'' he said, ``and it
takes an awfully consistent hitter to even approach .400 even for
the first half of the season. No one this season has been that
consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown, who does not have to pitch to Gwynn because they
play for the same team, is thankful that the .400 mark, at least,
appears safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many records can you expect to fall at any one time?'' he
said. ``Our plates are full enough without having that to worry
about, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
