<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-AUTOPSY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABIOLA AUTOPSY IN NIGERIA INDICATES HEART ATTACK 
 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria _ American and other Western doctors who
completed an autopsy on the body of Moshood K.O. Abiola, the
Nigerian opposition leader who died in detention Tuesday, said
Saturday that they had found no evidence of poisoning and had
concluded that his death was caused by heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary findings, anxiously awaited by an angry and
troubled nation, showed that ``there was severe longstanding
disease of the heart of a type and severity that can cause
unexpected death,'' said James G. Young, the chief coroner of the
province of Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   The results, confirming the official account of Abiola's death
given by the Nigerian military government, seemed unlikely to
assuage the many Nigerians who have reacted with fury to the
unexpected death of the opposition leader on the eve of his
promised release by the recently installed military ruler, Gen.
Abdulsalam Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who headed a five-man team including two American doctors
and an American technician, said after a detailed examination of
the body, including the abdomen, chest and brain, and conversations
with witnesses present at the time of death, ``We believe that
poisoning is extremely unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that for the sake of complete certainty
toxicological examinations of samples taken from the corpse would
be performed at the Center of Forensic Science in Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Tissue samples will also undergo microscopic examination in
London and a final report will be issued in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's irrelevant,'' Kola Abiola, the opposition
leader's son, said of the autopsy report. ``You don't have to
poison a man, you don't have to spike his tea, to kill him. My
father was locked up for four years without proper medical
treatment, and that is what leads to death. We know who is
responsible for locking him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Kola Abiola presided at the tumultuous burial of Abiola in the
front yard of his large house in Lagos on Saturday. Women sobbed
and men wailed as the body, swaddled in white cloth, was laid to
rest in the red earth just eight hours after the completion of the
autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   Military police, carrying automatic weapons, were heavily
deployed outside Abiola's house, but no violent incidents were
reported. After several days of rioting, Lagos appeared calmer.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola incarnated Nigeria's long-frustrated hopes for democracy,
a rare state of political affairs since Africa's most populous
nation gained independence in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   As he appeared poised to emerge victorious in a 1993
presidential election, the poll was annulled by the country's
military ruler and, a year later Abiola was thrown in jail.
</P>
<P>
   His death, just as it seemed he would be freed, has left many
Nigerians with a sense of deep frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who arrived here Friday, said: ``There was longstanding
disease of the heart of a type and severity that can cause
unexpected death. The disease was of two types.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was severe narrowing of the main coronary arteries by
fatty plaques. In addition, there was very significant enlargement
of the heart due to longstanding hypertension.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
