<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK: VAUGHN UNFAZED BY YANKEE REJECTION; EL DUQUE VS.
TYPHOON; ALOU FAMILY TREE STILL FRUITFUL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Yankees traded for Greg Vaughn a year ago, then killed the
deal because they said a physical the outfielder took for them
revealed a tear in his right rotator cuff. This season, that
shoulder has contributed to 30 home runs and 74 runs batted in for
San Diego, both more than any healthy Yankee has produced.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn shrugged when asked about the Yankees' rejection of him
and his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took a picture of it, did some tests,'' he said. ``I've
had four surgeries on my right one. It's not going to look like my
left one. It was a situation where they were making an investment
and they felt they wouldn't get the money back on their
investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who at the time was in the first year of a three-year,
$15 million contract, said he thought nothing of the development.
</P>
<P>
   ``With everything else that happened to me last year, that was
just something else,'' he said. ``I went home, took a few days off,
came back, worked hard and tried to get ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Would he have liked to play for the Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from California, growing up there, the Giants and the
A's were my favorite teams,'' he said. ``The Yankees are right
there with the A's as my American League favorites. I'd have loved
to play in New York, but it didn't work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the guy upstairs'' _ he didn't mean George
Steinbrenner _ ``has a reason for everything, and everything has a
tendency to work out. It's just a situation where you might not
understand why it happened, but it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   A Nickname to Remember
</P>
<P>
   Rolando Arrojo of Tampa Bay and Orlando Hernandez of the Yankees
will not oppose each other in their teams' series in St.
Petersburg, Fla., this weekend. The rookie pitchers, however, have
encountered each other before _ in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time they have playoffs, it was between him and El
Duque,'' said Luis Isaac, a Cleveland coach, acting as interpreter
for Arrojo at the All-Star Game. ``One time he got him, another
time El Duque got him.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo, however, seemed to lack something. Why, he was asked,
doesn't he have a snazzy nickname like El Duque? But he did have a
name, Arrojo responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``They called him Typhoon,'' Isaac said after listening to
Arrojo recall an element of his baseball life in Cuba. ``Nobody
knows that here.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo took a 10-5 record into the game against the Yankees
Saturday night. He has pitched impressively enough to earn back his
Cuban name. Coming in September, maybe, the next time the teams
play: El Duque vs. Typhoon.
</P>
<P>
   A Name to Remember
</P>
<P>
   First came Felipe Alou, then brother Matty, then their brother
Jesus. Next was Moises, Felipe's son, now a Houston outfielder.
Still, the Alou well has not run dry. The Kansas City Royals
recently signed another son of the Montreal manager, outfielder
Felipe Jr., their 42nd-round pick in last month's amateur draft.
</P>
<P>
   Next up: Luis Alou. ``Remember that name,'' Moises said of ``my
little brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis, a third baseman, is a 16-year-old high school sophomore, 6
feet 2 inches and 200 pounds. ``Twenty scouts are after him,''
Moises said. ``General managers call my dad. My dad wants him to
graduate from high school, and then he's going to see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, remember that name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
