<HEADLINE>
KANSAS RED WHEAT HARVEST EXPECTED TO BE ON THE RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICTORIA SIZEMORE LONG  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ This year's Kansas hard red winter wheat harvest is
expected to be the second-largest ever, thanks to favorable weather
late in the growing season.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department on Friday estimated the Kansas crop
at 494.9 million bushels, compared with last year's record 506
million bushels.
</P>
<P>
   The current projection was based on July 1 conditions and is up
sharply from the June 1 estimate of 393.9 million bushels.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas is the top producer of hard red winter wheat, which is
used for making bread and similar products, such as hamburger buns.
Texas and Oklahoma also are big producers. Hard red winter wheat is
planted in the fall and harvested in the summer and is a leading
U.S. export.
</P>
<P>
   Sherri Hand, an agricultural statistician for the Kansas
Department of Agriculture, said early projections for this year's
crop were conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farmers are naturally pessimistic anyway, but even our surveys
were coming out low,'' Hand said.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, farmers planted fewer acres to the crop this year
at 10.7 million, compared with last year's 11.4 million. Farmers
actually harvested 11 million acres of wheat a year ago and are
expected to have harvested 10.1 million acres this year.
</P>
<P>
   Hand said this year's early projections for the crop also were
affected by cold weather in March that included blizzard
conditions. In May, tens of thousands of acres were damaged by
heavy winds and hail.
</P>
<P>
   But the crop fared well as the harvest approached, helped by hot
and dry weather that allowed wheat to ripen earlier than normal and
the harvest to start early.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned around and here we are,'' Hand said.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, wheat farmers are expected to harvest 1.9 billion
bushels of all classes of winter wheat this year, up from the
previous estimate of 1.71 billion bushels, but down slightly from
last year's 1.94 billion bushels.
</P>
<P>
   Production of all classes of U.S. wheat this year is estimated
at 2.52 billion bushels.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, early projections for the U.S. corn crop this year
call for 9.6 billion bushels to be harvested. The soybean crop was
projected at 2.8 billion bushels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 1715EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980711.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
