<SLUG> BC-POLL-GRAVES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSANS FAVOR GRAVES FOR RE-ELECTION, POLL SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN PETTERSON  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA _ Gov. Bill Graves has a commanding lead over his
Republican primary challenger, former GOP state Chairman David
Miller, a statewide poll of likely voters shows.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, conducted for /{The Kansas City Star/} and released
Friday, also indicated that in the general election, the governor
would have no trouble defeating the likely Democratic candidate,
state Rep. Tom Sawyer of Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   Based on responses from 638 likely Republican primary voters,
the poll showed Graves winning 66 percent of the GOP vote, compared
to 22 percent for Miller, an insurance agent from Eudora. The
remaining 12 percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Poll results from all voters, Republican and Democrat, showed
Graves would defeat Sawyer, the House Democratic leader, 67 percent
to 16 percent in the general election, with 17 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bill Graves is a strong favorite to win his
Republican primary race and appears to be in great position to win
re-election in Kansas,'' the polling firm said in its analysis of
the data.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 804 registered Kansas voters from all parts of the
state was conducted by telephone from July 6 through July 8. For
questions relating to the Aug. 4 Republican primary election, 638
likely Republican primary voters were sampled.
</P>
<P>
   Mason-Dixon Political//Media Research of Columbia, Md.,
conducted the poll for /{The Kansas City Star/}. It carries a 3.5
percent margin of error for the sample of all Kansans; the margin
of error was 4 percent for the Republican sample. The margins were
different because the samples were different.
</P>
<P>
   Among Republicans, all of whom recognized Graves' name, 71
percent said they had a favorable opinion of Graves, a high rating
for any candidate. Only 12 percent said their opinion was
unfavorable and 17 percent were neutral.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, only 18 percent had a favorable opinion of
Miller and 9 percent had an unfavorable opinion. Of those polled,
32 percent didn't recognize his name at all, and of those who did,
41 percent were neutral.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like further evidence that voters in this primary
prefer a tax cutter to a tax increaser,'' said Mike Matson, a
spokesman for the Graves campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In Graves' first term, taxes were cut in each of the four years.
He has also promised to eliminate property taxes on cars and small
trucks. Miller plans to outline his proposal for cutting taxes next
week.
</P>
<P>
   At the Miller headquarters, spokesman Eldon Girdner predicted
that Miller will gather momentum as the campaign progresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``David has bold ideas that are the traditional Republican
plan,'' he said. ``I think they will see that Bill Graves supports
the traditional Democratic plan on many issues that are important
to Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   He said name recognition is always a problem for challengers,
but he predicted voters will tune in to the campaign as election
day approaches and begin comparing the records of the two
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been talking about taxes, and we believe firmly in a
plan that true Republicans support,'' Girdner said.
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters said taxes and government spending is the top issue
among all voters. Nearly a fourth of them said that issue would be
most important when they went to the polls. Education ranked second
with 20 percent, followed by the economy and jobs at 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Moral decay and moral issues placed fourth among the issues at
13 percent. Abortion, at 4 percent, was eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Miller's campaign focuses on moral decay of society and
his promises to focus on its repair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Graves has a strong record of service to the people
of Kansas on each of these issues and I think that's reflected in
this poll,'' Matson said.
</P>
<P>
   Early in June, /{The Wichita Eagle/} published a poll it
conducted that also showed Graves far outdistancing Miller. In that
survey, Graves had 66.4 percent to Miller's 15.2 percent, with the
remainder undecided or refusing to participate.
</P>
<P>
   The Mason-Dixon poll showed that Graves was known by 99 percent
of all Kansas voters, and 66 percent of them regarded him
favorably. Only 15 percent had an unfavorable opinion, and 18
percent knew his name but had no opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Among all voters, 11 percent had a favorable opinion of Miller
and 5 percent viewed him unfavorably. Half of the voters didn't
recognize his name. Of those who recognized it, 34 percent had no
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since his election as governor four years ago, Graves'
favorable name recognition has increased 20 points, from 46 percent
to 66 percent,'' pollsters said in their analysis of the data.
</P>
<P>
   While likely voters were being polled, Graves' TV ads were being
broadcast in most parts of the state. Miller's television ads
didn't start until Tuesday, the second day of the polling, and were
broadcast only in selected western Kansas markets.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also asked Kansans how they would vote on a
Sawyer-Miller matchup in November. Such a race would be a tossup,
with Sawyer ahead of Miller, 35 percent to 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Del Ali, a Mason-Dixon pollster, said one could conclude that
Miller is ``too extreme'' in the minds of voters because they
appear to prefer Sawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was this huge conservative tide, not only would
Miller be competitive with Graves, but he ought to be trouncing
Sawyer,'' Ali said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the governor's race, the poll also tested some of the
other statewide races and found:
</P>
<P>
   Republican U.S. Sen. Sam Brownback would win re-election over
Democratic state Sen. Paul Feleciano, 56 percent to 26 percent,
with 18 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Attorney General Carla Stovall, also seeking
re-election, would defeat Democrat Dan Lykins, 62 percent to 12
percent, with 26 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   In the race for state treasurer, Republican House Speaker Tim
Shallenburger had a 10-point lead over the Democrat, Shawnee County
Treasurer Rita Cline, 36 percent to 26 percent, with 38 percent
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Insurance Commissioner Kathleen Sebelius would have
little trouble defeating either of the Republican candidates. In
the matchup with Republican Dan Martinez, she had 48 percent to his
26 percent, with 26 percent undecided. Against Bryan Riley, she
also had 48 percent. He had 25 percent and 27 percent were
undecided.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
