<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-TRACK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS COURT UPHOLDS SPEEDWAY LEGAL PROVISIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN T. DAUNER and STEVE NICELY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: The Kansas Supreme Court on Friday wiped away the
biggest legal challenge to an automotive speedway in western
Wyandotte County, effectively clearing the way for construction of
Kansas International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Voting unanimously in Topeka, Kan., the high court upheld the
constitutionality of all legal provisions covering track
development.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling came in a ``friendly'' challenge that Wyandotte
County District Attorney Nick Tomasic had filed in an effort to
resolve the issues quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court's ruling gives us the momentum we need to
proceed and complete the project,'' Mayor Carol Marinovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Tomasic's lawsuit encompassed all the legal points at issue in
other lawsuits filed by property owners resisting the forced sale
of their homes. Tomasic said Friday's ruling rendered those issues
moot.
</P>
<P>
   One key issue is whether the Unified Government of Wyandotte
County and Kansas City, Kan., can use condemnation powers to obtain
private property to be used by a private company. Another is
whether the Kansas Legislature's decision to reimburse displaced
homeowners at the rate of 125 percent of fair market value, instead
of 100 percent, is legal.
</P>
<P>
   Under the ruling, powers of eminent domain can be used, and the
25 percent premium is legal.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Borich, a lawyer representing the owners of about 30 parcels
who oppose the development plan, said he planned to meet with his
clients to discuss asking the U.S. Supreme Court to review the
case.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Grant Lynch, president of Kansas International
Speedway Corp., the developer, said the ruling ``should remove any
doubt about the project moving forward.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have 78 contracts with property owners,'' Lynch said.
``Many of the property owners have been extremely patient while
their lives have been put on hold waiting for this decision. The
ruling resolves the pending legal issues, and now we can move
forward with closing on those contracts as well as take other
acquisition options in order to stay on track for racing in
Wyandotte County in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   About 150 families live in the 1,200-acre tract northwest of
Interstates 70 and 435.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of the 1.5-mile oval speedway, designed for
NASCAR races, is to have 75,000 seats and cost $208 million. The
second phase, to be built when the market warrants, would double
the seating capacity and cost an additional $56 million.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase includes, among other things, $71.7 million in
Tax Increment Financing revenue bonds; $23.2 million in STAR bonds
that would be paid off by sales taxes from the project; $58.8
million in ``cash equity commitment'' from the developer; and $33
million in state highway funds.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Hays, Unified Government administrator, said he expected
financing to be in place by early August. Closing on land
acquisition contracts already executed will begin immediately
thereafter, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the city-county Unified Board of Commissioners is
expected to consider an ordinance authorizing the use of
condemnation, where necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Offer letters will be sent to property owners who have not yet
entered contracts on their property, Hays said. Condemnation
proceedings will be filed to acquire property that cannot be
obtained any other way, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, at least one resident who has been fighting the plan,
Virginia Miller, seemed resigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just ready to get on with the rest of my life,'' she said.
``I can't do anything else except turn it loose and go.''
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Howard Miller, have lived in a home near
110th Street and Interstate 70 for 52 years. They have not agreed
to sell.
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal also will continue for Eric Vaught's extended family,
who live in three homes on 80 acres homesteaded by his ancestors
about a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like the city and the state both want (the speedway)
and no matter what it takes, they're going to make it go through,''
Vaught said.
</P>
<P>
   The Vaughts have not reached an agreement to sell their
property.
</P>
<P>
   Although disappointed with most of Kansas court's rulings,
Borich said he was pleased that the court upheld the 25 percent
premium, which he supported on behalf of all property owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a blessing; it really helps everyone who hasn't
settled,'' Borich said.
</P>
<P>
   Borich said that getting the U.S. Supreme Court to accept the
case was ``a long shot, unless there is an issue of national
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But a government taking private property and transferring it
to another private owner for a racetrack to promote tourism is
something that might be of interest to the court,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Development of the track could proceed, even if the U.S. Supreme
Court accepted the case, Borich said.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's 41-page opinion, written by Justice Bob Abbott, the
court upheld the constitutionality of the Tax Increment Financing
plan approved for the track, as well as the agreement between the
developer and the Unified Government.
</P>
<P>
   The court held, among other things, that including a motor
speedway in the definition of a ``major tourism area'' was
appropriate. That designation is a prerequisite for issuing TIF
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The court also held that it was legal to repay the bonds over 30
years, instead of the customary 20 years. The Kansas Legislature
approved that change, along with the 125 percent reimbursement,
earlier this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
