<HEADER>
A0631 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAZZ-SANBORN-KAN &LR;      07-11 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZ-SANBORN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASING SANBORN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CALVIN WILSON  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ David Sanborn still plays alto saxophone his
way. Considering what he has to deal with, that's no small
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   It's just about impossible to tune into ``smooth jazz'' radio
without hearing some guy wailing away in shameless debt to Sanborn,
whose sound on the horn is arguably the most influential since
Charlie Parker drew his own slew of imitators a half century ago.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the stupefying smooth groove and
Sanborn's hefty blend of R&AMP;B, funk and blues should be obvious when
he performs July 18 at the Kansas City Blues &AMP; Jazz Festival _ if
only in the invigorating and innovative variety of his sound.
</P>
<P>
   Sanborn, who grew up in St. Louis, credits blues- and
R&AMP;B-influenced jazz saxophonists with sparking his interest in
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the music that got me excited,'' he said the other
day from New York. ``I always related to the more overtly
blues-based players, people like Jackie McLean and Hank Crawford.''
</P>
<P>
   The blues, however, turned out to be just the beginning. Where
most of his imitators rely on formula, Sanborn, 52, is a musical
searcher. He has worked not only with a wide range of rock and pop
artists _ in the 1970s and '80s, he was the alto saxophonist of
choice for session work _ but with jazz musicians from the
straight-ahead to the avant-garde.
</P>
<P>
   All in the interest of keeping his own music fresh and
surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ever rule anything out,'' he said. ``I'm not really,
in the strictest sense, a jazz player. But I try to do things that
are challenging for me.''
</P>
<P>
   That philosophy came through most memorably on ``Another Hand,''
a 1991 album with an acoustic emphasis that featured such jazz
luminaries as bassist Charlie Haden, guitarist Bill Frisell and
pianist Mulgrew Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Sanborn said he relished the context _ largely straight-ahead
jazz _ which he compared to a basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're doing is, you have a certain set of ground rules.
But you're adapting to an ever-changing situation, and you're
reacting to the other people around you. You use your reflexes and
your knowledge to, in a way, transcend yourself and the game and
the music. And I think that when you do that, that experience is
indescribable.''
</P>
<P>
   In musical terms, ``Another Hand'' was radically different than
Sanborn's electrified pop-jazz albums _ such as his most recent
album, ``Songs From the Night Before'' (1996). But those
bread-and-butter projects are, in their own way, just as ambitious,
combining smart production values with inspired playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``His fusion albums are superior fusion records,'' said Carl
Woideck, a saxophonist and author of Charlie Parker: His Music and
Life.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, they're what fusion should be: A mix of modern
technology, beautiful melodies and good hooks, with really
interesting chord progressions.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the raspy, urgent sound of Sanborn himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can play alto saxophone without having to
deal with David Sanborn,'' said Marcus Miller, a bassist who has
produced and performed on several Sanborn albums. ``Even if you
don't want to go that way, it's something that you have to avoid.
He's definitely a presence.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a long and illustrious road for Sanborn, who
accompanied blues stars Albert King and Little Walter while still
only a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   After studying music at Northwestern University and at the
University of Iowa, he landed his first professional job, playing
and recording with the Chicago-based Paul Butterfield Blues Band
from 1967 to 1971. In 1973 he began a long association with the
late jazz arranger Gil Evans, performing on the albums ``Svengali''
and ``Priestess.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career, Sanborn has demonstrated not only
exemplary musical taste, working as sideman to both Stevie Wonder
and David Bowie, but an interest in pushing the envelope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I operate more out of an R&AMP;B rhythmic base, I also
try to incorporate elements of jazz and of other music as well,''
he said. ``Jazz musicians are being influenced by many kinds of
music outside the idiom of jazz, and there's so much music going on
that people are just not being exposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sanborn's view, commercial radio is at least partly to blame
for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get a lot of the music that falls in the cracks,''
he said. ``And I think that ultimately has a very negative
influence on the audience, and on music in general. It certainly
doesn't reflect the way most musicians think.''
</P>
<P>
   On behalf of this unheard music, Sanborn occasionally lends his
support to projects outside the commercial mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   From 1987 to 1990, he was host of ``Night Music,'' a syndicated
TV series on which musicians from different genres performed
together. More recently, he performed on ``Diminutive Mysteries,''
a 1993 album by avant-garde saxophonist Tim Berne. The album
focused on compositions by the late saxophonist Julius Hemphill,
whom Sanborn had met years before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hemphill and I played together a lot in St. Louis,'' Sanborn
said. ``He was very instrumental in the forming of my opinions
about music, and I'd always been a big fan of his work.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanborn brought a vivid imagination and formidable skill to the
project, Berne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important to me that it wasn't just a case of, `Hey,
let's use this famous saxophone player.' He really knew his music,
and was genuinely interested.''
</P>
<P>
   The abstract, difficult compositions on ``Diminutive Mysteries''
offer convincing evidence of Sanborn's willingness to try out new
things. But he may not be getting adequate respect for playing the
music he's best-known for, Berne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really believes in what he's playing, and I think that's
what makes the difference. That's what makes him convincing, or
Hank Crawford, or Grover Washington. It's not just, `OK, I'm going
to sell some records, I'll play like this.' That's really how they
hear it. That's their thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed Sanborn has enjoyed considerable success by playing music
his way. His only qualm is that people who have heard him only on
smooth-jazz radio may not have the right idea about his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my case, the smooth-jazz format will find one small slice
of what it is that I do, and play that,'' he said. ``So when people
come to hear me play, they may be surprised or disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may want to hear what they heard on the radio, and not
the other stuff. Or maybe there are people who would like to hear
the other stuff but are not aware that I'm playing the other stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times it's frustrating. But whose life isn't?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
