<DOCNO> NYT19980711.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0632 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-SCOTT-KANSAS-     07-11 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-SCOTT-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUSHING THE ENVELOPE OF THE RUNWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   From all family accounts, Jeremy Scott was barely past baby
steps when he put his foot down on the subject of style.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had to have a part in the decision about his training
pants,'' says his mother, Sandra Scott, of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   He was such a label-conscious toddler that only Carter's brand
would do. At 8, he chose a red satin jacket off the Kmart racks in
Kansas City and wore it until it was in shreds, his sister Barbara
Scott recalls.
</P>
<P>
   And in his junior year at Hickman Mills High School, he made the
clothes he and his date wore to the prom.
</P>
<P>
   Now 24, he is no less obsessed. Settled into an atelier in the
center of Paris, Scott is designing avant-garde clothing.
</P>
<P>
   He is dressing the Icelandic singer Bjork and attracting fashion
notables such as Anna Wintour, the American Vogue editor, to his
runway shows. He has the social support of Parisian fashion maven
Isabella Blow, previously associated with English designer
Alexander McQueen. He was twice named young designer of the year by
a French fashion organization.
</P>
<P>
   And, perhaps most important, he is getting a startling amount of
press. In the last year he has been in such publications as The New
Yorker magazine, The International Herald Tribune newspaper, Vogue,
the British magazine Frank and The Atlanta Journal and
Constitution. People magazine is reported to be planning a piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never had so many calls from the international press
about one person. Never,'' says Nicole Fischelis, the New
York-based fashion director of Saks Fifth Avenue stores. The
retailer bought pieces from Scott's spring '98 collection, a
whimsical monochromatic white group based on a T-shirt theme.
</P>
<P>
   He has attracted attention in part because he is pushing all the
traditional boundaries of form and design and also because he is
energized and determined. He is unconventional in an arena that
values the offbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``My clothes have never been done before,'' he says in a
telephone interview from Paris. ``I'm doing new volumes. New
silhouettes.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when Americans and the English are boosting the
re-emergence of Paris as a creative force, Scott may be in the
right place at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   Nurturing family
</P>
<P>
   His talent, he says, was nurtured by his early family life in
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother was a woman of the farm,'' he says. ``She made
things. She was always sewing and painting. That's part of where my
thrift-shop bent comes from. It was a natural thing to change
things into something else.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother says he is much like his grandmother and his father,
a civil engineer, in many ways. He has their tenacity and fortitude
to focus on a project and follow through to completion.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in the Midwest, far from the major cosmopolitan
cities, Scott had only his imagination to fill his dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``My vision was so extreme,'' he recalls. ``I was living through
magazines, thinking of Paris and New York, thinking of women
walking on the streets far more done than they really are ...
taking things and modifying them.''
</P>
<P>
   At 14, he made up his mind to go to Paris. He started going to
night school at Rockhurst High and the University of
Missouri-Kansas City to study French and Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   When he finished high school, to the dismay of his mother, he
announced he was going to New York to study at the Pratt School of
Design.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to encourage him to do something with the languages,''
says his mother, who teaches children with learning disabilities.
``I think you tend to want your kids to do something you're safe
and familiar with. I didn't think it was very practical, but I was
not able to dissuade him.''
</P>
<P>
   Three months after he finished Pratt, he decided on a date,
Sept. 18, and bought an airline ticket. Once in Paris, he set about
looking for an apartment and a place to have a fashion show.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a year later he opened his first collection at the
Bastille. Made mostly from paper and embellished with beading, the
clothing was inspired by plastic surgery, car accidents and a
French artist doing performance art with her own body, or what
Scott calls ``kind of a tragic glamour.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the idea of it being very fragile ...'' he says. ``I
was taken with the instant, that moment and that you could rip it
up.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to do an all-black show, followed by the much
acclaimed white group. ``It was the idea of coming out of the
darkness. It was clean and modern,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Saks' Fischelis remembers the T-shirt show last fall as ``kind
of magical. It had very good energy. I was impressed with the
whimsy and the charm.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother, dressed in her own black dress, was in the audience
that day, and for the first time she realized the magnitude of her
son's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk every week, often. I just talked to him a few minutes
ago,'' she says. ``But when I was seated at the show, met people
who were there, saw the camera crews, saw the security to keep
people from mobbing him, I thought, `Oh, my gosh. I had no idea.' I
kept thinking I should give up my seat so some of the people
standing could be seated.''
</P>
<P>
   In March his fall show primarily involved gold leathers, lame
and furs. He toyed with asymmetry, raising one shoulder high above
the other and adding abundant padding. He was inspired, he says, by
Russia's rebirth ``in elegance and glamour'' and by a French doll.
</P>
<P>
   This time the reviews were mixed, some very negative. But Scott
is somewhat reconciled to the inevitable criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK,'' he says. ``It's a process of time ... It's going to
take some people some time (to understand).''
</P>
<P>
   He recalls how, in the 1940s, Christian Dior changed the fashion
silhouette. Scott is comforted by the praise of Vogue's Wintour and
the support of Bjork.
</P>
<P>
   He believes adamantly that people are in need of something new
and that ``established fashion is no longer valued.'' The end of
the century, he says, is triggering the creative forces of the
avant-garde. ``Paris is buzzing with the millennium. Everyone is
excited by it.''
</P>
<P>
   For now he is convinced he is on target. Sales have doubled,
moving beyond Parisian boutiques to stores in Hong Kong, Japan and
an East Village boutique called Horn in New York.
</P>
<P>
   And the future remains promising. Late last year he flew to
Milan to meet with Donatella Versace about the possibility of a job
with the house of Versace. He has been mentioned in connection with
job openings at other houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a talent,'' says Saks' Fischelis. ``They have to be
watched, looked at. We have to show them we're interested. That is
our role. He is so individualistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Scott's greatest joy, he says, is ``pleasing my mom in
the front row.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
