<SLUG> BC-FASHION-WHITE-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK OUT! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not your uncle's tattoo
</P>
<P>
   The lacy delicate body marking has been seen on celebrities
including Demi Moore, Madonna, Naomi Campbell, Liv Tyler and Drew
Barrymore. Never mind that mehndi art (or henna painting) has been
part of rituals in India, Africa and the Middle East for thousands
of years. It's been a fashion trend across the United States the
past year.
</P>
<P>
   So it is no surprise to find how-to books such as Mehndi: The
Art of Henna Body Painting (Three Rivers Press, $11) by Carine
Fabius. A native of Haiti, Fabius is a co-owner with her husband of
a Los Angeles art gallery and mehndi studio. She received so many
requests for information, she writes, she was driven to produce the
book that offers a history of the art and facts such as: In India,
widows are forbidden from wearing henna because they are never
supposed to have fun again.
</P>
<P>
   Henna, which grows on bush or shrub with bright green leaves, is
seen in some cultures as a lucky charm, with the power to protect
and ward off evil spirits. Fabius says it's magical. The high
interest now comes at a time when tattooing and body piercing among
the cutting edgers are getting, well, old. And in the fashion
arena, austere minimalism is being nudged aside by more elaborate,
decorative embellishment.
</P>
<P>
   Fabius provides a recipe for the paste using powdered and sifted
henna, black tea and eucalyptus oil. Once the design is applied and
dried, the paste should be left on 12 to 20 hours during which time
you apply powdered sugar and lemon and stay warm in the sun (easy
enough about now) or by drinking hot tea. She also adds
illustrations to consider.
</P>
<P>
   The book is available at major book stores, or by calling (800)
793-BOOK (2665) or through the Web site, www.randomhouse.com.
</P>
<P>
   Frame-up
</P>
<P>
   On the magazine watch: GQ says the dark-top, clear-bottom
eyeglass frames in Chuck Close's giant-sized nerdlike portrait,
``Keith,'' have become the guy frames to have.
</P>
<P>
   The acrylic-on-canvas painting was on display recently at the
Museum of Modern Art in New York, and now Calvin Klein, Tommy
Hilfiger, Yves Saint Laurent and Ray-Ban are marketing the frames.
Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Seventeen magazine says Sarah McLachlan is launching
her own catalog. You can buy T-shirts, a hemp backpack, the
singer's jewelry designs and sunglasses as well as CDs. To order a
catalog, call (800) 764-3472.
</P>
<P>
   Say bye to same-old ... Are clothing consumers bored with the
classics and craving something new. If you need proof that old
stuff may be a tad ho-hum these days, consider that Keds, the
all-time most basic shoe, is updating with bright colors, platforms
and even cloglike sandals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
