<SLUG> BC-PROSPERITY-ADVISORY-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   A series on prosperity in America has begun to move from Cox
News Service. The Dayton Daily News is publishing the five-part
series on prosperity and how it is changing the way we live,
starting in the paper of Sunday, July 12. A budget follows. For
more information, call CoxNet at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   Day 1:
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-MAIN _ Not since the '50s have things been this good
this long. Not only are most people living better, a DDN poll shows
a majority believe the best is yet to come. With things going so
well, cities throughout the country are looking for ways to sustain
the good times. Seattle is one of the leaders in the sustainability
movement, which seeks to identify the strengths and weaknesses in a
community and target problem areas for future growth. (Dempsey,
Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-PROFILE _ Profile of Mike Wood, who quit his job as a
vp to spend more time with his family. Wood still works the same
number of hours, but not necessarily on the job. He's on the verge
of earning a PhD. And he has upped his quality time with his
family. More and more U.S. workers are choosing the same route.
(Dempsey, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-HOUSING _ The changing American family has changed
the look of houses. More garage space, master baths with
whirlpools, cathedral ceilings over plush family rooms. But with
talented students attracted more to technology than working with
their hands, there are fewer skilled craftsmen available to build
houses. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   Day 2:
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-POLL _ Most of us are better off, but few of us are
frivolously spending our money, vacationing in the Riviera or even
flying off to Vegas in the middle of the night. Results of DDN
poll. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-PROFILE _ Three years ago Glenn McGee was young,
uneducated and homeless. In June he graduated from Sinclair
Community College and is headed for a job at a machine shop. McGee
has taken advantage of the demand for skilled labor in this
economy. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-JOBS _ Dayton's economy was one of the strongest in
the nation in the 50s and 60s, and it was largely an economy built
on blue-coller work. Today, jobs that can pay as much as $50,000 a
year after a two year apprenticeship are going begging. (Dempsey,
Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   Day 3:
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-RICH _ Used to be, you were a millionaire if you
earned that much during your lifetime. Now, the definition is
changing as even ordinary people are making millions off the stock
market in a single year. (Shepard, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-TAXES _ As the Republican-controlled Congress moves
to cut taxes, the truly wealthy Americans are benefiting the most,
while the mere high-income wage earners are shouldering the lion's
share of the tax burden. (Shepard, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-US _ How we have changed. Today's subject: The rich.
How many true millionaires do we have in the Miami Valley and how
are they spending their money? Are we reliving the 50s or have we
surpassed it? (Gulliver, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   Day 4:
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-POOR _ Not everybody is riding the prosperity wave,
and even many of those managing to get by are skeptical about the
future. (DeBrosse, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-PROFILE _ Profile of somebody struggling to get by.
(DeBrosse, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-US _ How we have changed. Today's subject: Schools.
The 50s classrooms were far different from today's. It's not just
technology. Teaching methods have changed as well. But are we doing
any better at preparing our children for the workplace? According
to our poll, not many of us think so. (DeBrosse, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   Day 5:
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-SUSTAINABILITY _ How can we best prepare for tomorrow
in today's booming economy? President Clinton's Council on
Sustainable Development has become a blueprint for how things will
work in the 21st century. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-HOME _ How to cut down costs and improve the
environment in your home, such as installing water-saving plumbing
or lighting fixtures that use less energy. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily
News).
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-PROFILE _ Profile of Gary Couch, a former head of
development for General Motors who stepped down to pursue the
high-tech world of composites, viewed as a cutting-edge technology
that could put Dayton back in the forefront of automobile
manufacturing. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-US _ How we have changed. Today's subject: Gadgets.
They're everywhere. From cordless phones, fax machines, beepers,
etc., we have become slaves to our technological toys. (Dempsey,
Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
