<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUC-COLLEGE-REMEDIAL-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING ACADEMIC AND SURVIVAL SKILLS FOR COLLEGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.Y., Calif.)  (mk) 
 By MARIA NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LODI, N.J. _ When Adam Padron was 16, high school bored him. ``I
wasn't paying attention,'' he said last week. ``I lost interest.''
And so he dropped out of Bloomfield High School his freshman year.
But, he said, ``I always wanted to go to college.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam worked for a year and a half, got his general equivalency
diploma, and then applied to Felician College, a small Roman
Catholic college here in Bergen County. But because he had dropped
out of high school just as his classmates were about to begin
algebra, Adam scored poorly on math entrance exams.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the college accepted him. Admissions officials did
suggest, though, that he take part in a new four-week program
called Jump Start, designed to help incoming freshmen catch up to
their classmates.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, as other high school graduates are enjoying their
last vacation before college, many borderline students like Adam
are enrolled in classes or programs that help students sharpen the
academic skills they should have gotten in high school, and learn
survival skills for college.
</P>
<P>
   The colleges are motivated, at least in part, by the need to
address declining admissions. The investment to provide remedial
programs, said Susan Chalfin, director of admissions at Felician,
is worthwhile because the students are less likely to drop out
later.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, 78 percent of America's colleges offered such remedial
classes, up from 73 percent in 1988. The programs come in a variety
of forms. Some colleges offer the programs only in the summer, and
others run them throughout the year, with a variety of requirements
for how often students should check in with supervisors. Ivy League
universities offer tutoring programs for weaker students who need
help.
</P>
<P>
   Quinnipiac College in Connecticut has been running the Academic
Assistance Program for 28 years for the kind of students who are,
in the words of Helen Beril, the program director, ``salvageable,
or maybe they're late bloomers.'' Quinnipiac accepts marginal
students with the proviso that they must take part in the program,
Ms. Beril said.
</P>
<P>
   At Felician, the Jump Start Program provides more than just
intensive math and English instruction. It is also something of a
boot camp for college survival. In addition to brushing up on the
basics, students learn about taking notes, listening effectively,
stress management, study skills and even money management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of our students are first-generation college students,
and they don't have the kind of support at home as some of our
other students,'' said Jane O'Brien, the co-director of Jump Start.
</P>
<P>
   The program, similar to ones at many other colleges and
universities, is intended to help students who might require
remedial courses later, an issue that has been the subject of
considerable debate among educators recently. At the City
University of New York, in spite of strong protests from faculty
and students, trustees recently voted to phase out remedial courses
from their four-year colleges and set higher entrance standards.
</P>
<P>
   The situation at City University, many college officials say,
focused the debate too narrowly on the very broad issue of how to
teach students who are ill prepared for higher education. Educators
throughout the region and the country say that predicting a
student's ability to succeed in college goes beyond merely looking
at results of entrance exams.
</P>
<P>
   At programs like Felician's Jump Start, officials say they are
providing students with a wider approach to college life by
teaching them skills that students who went to better high schools
may have learned from their teachers, or from parents who
themselves went to college, or from mentors or advisers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It's our business to educate those students,'' Ms. Chalfin
said. ``That is what we're about. We have to have a way for those
students to come in. We have a moral obligation to provide courses
for those students.''
</P>
<P>
   During the four-week session, the 20 students in Felician's
program will be taught computer technology, reading and writing
skills, oral communication and algebra. But they will also learn
how to understand a course description in a syllabus, how to manage
their time and money, how to balance school work and out-of-school
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Quinnipiac program runs throughout the school year and
students must check in with advisers periodically to let them know
their progress in school.
</P>
<P>
   When students enter the program, the director said, some resent
having to sit through the classes. ``The first month they sit there
relatively negatively, until their first round of tests,'' she
said. When they see how much help they actually need, they start
taking the program more seriously, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics of these services say that students who are not
prepared for college should not be there and that colleges should
not be offering remedial help.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you call it remedial if many of these students have
never been presented with the information the first time?'' said
Caron Mellblom, an associate professor in graduate education at
California State University at Dominguez Hills, near Los Angeles,
who argues that students from poorer high schools may not have been
exposed to a college culture.
</P>
<P>
   Students in the Felician program are commuting the first two
weeks, and will live on campus dorms the last two weeks. The
program is free to students, but, Ms. Chalfin said, it costs the
college about $2,000 per student.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the first week at Jump Start, several of the
students said, they were glad to be in the program. Chris Guterl,
18, who graduated from Lyndhurst High School in New Jersey, said he
found the computer classes helpful. ``I had my girlfriend type up
my term papers in high school,'' he said. ``I'm definitely afraid
of computers. But I'm starting to feel more comfortable now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
