<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAILING-TRANSATLANTIC-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH CREW AIMING AT TRANS-ATLANTIC RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ A team of 11 French ocean racers _ a Top Gun
entourage of long-distance sailors if there ever was one _ joined a
core group of big boat sailors here last week. Their mission: to
prepare for an unprecedented assault this September on the
trans-Atlantic record from New York to England.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Loick Peyron, one of France's leading ocean racers, the
group practiced off Newport for eight days on Mari-Cha III. As if
to goad them, the monohull trans-Atlantic record was broken during
their preparations last Tuesday by another French team under
Christophe Auguin. That time of 9 days 22 hours is considered
unofficial since it was not properly ratified by the World Sailing
Speed Record Council, but as far as Mari-Cha III is concerned, it
is the time to beat.
</P>
<P>
   For the 38-year-old Peyron and crew, getting an upper hand on
Mari-Cha III, the new 147-foot ketch they were muscling offshore
here, has been no easy task. With two grinders on each of four
winch pedestals, trimming the huge sails left the most fit among
them exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really impressive,'' Peyron said of the challenge of
sailing Mari-Cha III. ``It's a crazy machine with big winches, and
big blocks. But it still takes human power to keep it under
control, and we will see if that is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a huge sailboat by any standard, but that makes Mari-Cha
III the Frenchmen's weapon of choice. Perhaps more than any other
sailboat since 1905, when the yacht Atlantic sailed from New York
to England in a record 14 days, the huge new boat seems up to the
task. One of the largest sailboats in the world built entirely of
carbon fiber, Mari-Cha III has the body of a glider in the guise of
a Boeing 777.
</P>
<P>
   So, most onlookers are apt to think of Mari-Cha III as one of
the lavish super-yachts that flock to Newport the way thoroughbreds
are drawn to Saratoga. Indeed, its towering, 150-foot white mast of
painted carbon fiber dominates the harbor skyline. Beyond that, the
giant monohull has high topsides, teak decks and plenty of velvety
wood trim. But its beauty is its deception. ``The teak is very,
very thin on deck,'' said Jef D'Etiveaud, the boat's captain. Wood
trim permeates the boat, but composite materials such as carbon
fiber, which are far lighter, form the core of this ocean
speedster.
</P>
<P>
   Its lavish woodwork also extends below deck, including a main
saloon with mahogany raised-paneled walls and intricate cabinetry.
Marble sink tops make the heads look like bathrooms at the Ritz.
But it's all part of the masquerade. Most of Mari-Cha's elaborate
interior is made to be lifted out for racing.
</P>
<P>
   The shelves, cabinets and wall panels release with the turn of a
screwdriver. Even the washer and dryer get put into a storage
container ashore. From stem to stern, the hand craftsmanship masks
a lean machine under skin-thin veneer. Even the marble sink tops
are only the thickness of linoleum.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The huge yacht was commissioned by Robert Miller, a business
tycoon from England who owns a worldwide network of duty-free
shops. Designed by Philippe Briand of France, the $15 million yacht
comes with a water ballast system that moves 7.5 tons of water in
14 minutes from one side of the hull to the other as the boat
tacks. It is the equivalent of having more crew members than the
boat could fit sitting along the rail.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is also an elaborate cruising boat. ``That's where the
challenge was,'' D'Etiveaud said. ``To make a light racing boat is
easy. But to make a light cruising boat is very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   But the priority is to beat the trans-Atlantic record. In
setting the nine-day mark, Auguin crossed the imaginary finish off
Lizard Point in England aboard his 60-foot sloop, Geodis. The
previous record, set last year by the 80-foot monohull, Nicorette,
was 11 days 13 hours. ``Ah, that's good news for us,'' D'Etiveaud
said, on hearing of the faster time, ``because it's not very
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The French crew will prepare the boat in New York on Sept. 18.
With three days' work, the yacht will be stripped down to its bare
bone _ a carbon fiber shell with 24 crew members and a single
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   MAKING WAVES
</P>
<P>
   About 300 sailboats are expected to be at the starting line off
Chicago Saturday for the 100th anniversary of the Chicago Yacht
Club's Mackinac Race. The 333-mile overnight competition along Lake
Michigan ends off Mackinac Island, Mich. The record _ 25 hours 50
minutes _ was set in 1987 by Pied Piper, a Santa Cruz 70 that
finished second for line honors last year to Cynosure, also a Santa
Cruz 70.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
