<HEADER>
A0641 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-HOME-REAL-800(2TAK     07-11 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: PITFALLS IN LUXURY DECONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Under a law passed in 1993 and amended last year,
rent-stabilized tenants who pay $2,000 or more a month for their
apartments and whose annual household incomes were more than
$175,000 in each of the two preceding years are not entitled to the
protection of rent stabilization.
</P>
<P>
   But as a result of strict interpretation of the luxury decontrol
law by the New York state Division of Housing and Community Renewal
_ and some recent court decisions confirming that interpretation _
even tenants whose incomes are below $175,0000 can suddenly find
themselves subject to luxury decontrol and its high free-market
rents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that this is one of the most serious issues facing
tenants in the city of New York that I have seen in 30 years of
practicing law,'' said Errol A. Brett, a Manhattan real estate
layer.
</P>
<P>
   Brett said that since luxury decontrol was signed into law in
1993, an increasing number of clients he has been asked to
represent have had their rent-stabilized apartments deregulated
despite the fact that their incomes were well below the maximum set
by the law. And by reducing the limit from $250,000 to $175,000
last year, he said, the state Legislature placed even more tenants
at risk of losing their regulated status.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been telling everybody I know that if their rent is more
than $2,000 a month they should put a lawyer on retainer and send
him every piece of mail they get from their landlord or DHCR,''
Brett said. ``And I tell them the advice stands no matter how much
money they make.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, he said, results from the complexity of the luxury
decontrol law and the inevitable confusion created by the various
forms and certifications that criss-cross back and forth among
landlords, tenants and the DHCR.
</P>
<P>
   The process starts, Brett said, with the income-certification
form that landlords send to tenants by May 1 of each year in an
effort to determine whether any apartments renting for $2,000 a
month or more may be eligible for luxury decontrol.
</P>
<P>
   The form, Brett said, requires tenants to declare whether their
total household income in each of the two preceding years exceeded
the $175,000 limit. In most cases, he said, tenants complete the
form and return it to the landlord within the 30-day time period as
required by law. Some tenants, he said, even attach income tax
returns to the certification as proof of their income.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, however, is that though the form is sent by the
landlord to the tenant and then back to the landlord, it bears the
official letterhead of the Division of Housing and Community
Renewal _ a factor that could lead a reasonable tenant to believe
that the form, and the information it contains, will ultimately end
up in the files of DHCR. As a result, Brett said, tenants who
believe they are safe from decontrol and return the form on time
generally forget about luxury decontrol _ at least until the next
year's income certification arrives in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   By law, however, landlords can dispute a tenant's
income-certification by filing with DHCR an Owner's Petition for
Deregulation. When the division receives the landlord's petition,
it sends another income-verification form to the tenant along with
a request for supporting tax returns. The form also advises the
tenant that failure to return the certification within 60 days of
receipt will result in automatic deregulation of the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   And that's when things get tricky.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of tenants ignore the second form,'' Brett said. The
reason, he explained, is because the income verification form
requests essentially the same information as the previous form that
had been returned to the landlord. Thus some tenants believe that
since they filed the initial form they do not have to bother filing
a second time.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to file the second form within 60 days, however, is
considered a default on the part of the tenant and nearly always
results in an order of deregulation being issued by the division.
In some cases it may take several months for DHCR to issue an order
of deregulation. In others, the orders may not reach the tenant
until sometime in the following year _ overlapping new income
certifications being filed for that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets so confusing it can drive you crazy,'' Brett said,
adding that what is most disturbing is that once a tenant has
failed to file a required form on time, there is virtually no way
for the tenant to rectify the error and avoid an order of
deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do is miss one deadline, and you're out of
luck,'' he said, explaining that the DHCR has consistently
interpreted the default provision of the statute in the strictest
terms possible.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a recent ruling that was highly critical of the division's
strict interpretation of the procedural requirements of the luxury
decontrol law, state Supreme Court Justice Phyllis Gangel-Jacob
wrote that the DHCR policy places a ``heavy burden'' on tenants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Failure to keep a hawk's eye on the mail for year after year
into the indefinite future can cost any tenant the valuable
protection of the Rent Stabilization Laws, without regard to what
their income may be,'' Ms. Gangel-Jacob wrote. ``The continuing
vigilance that is required to obtain and act on the form is
daunting.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no responses to telephone messages left at the
litigation section of the Division of Housing and Community Renewal
seeking comment on the agency's policy. But Jeffrey Turkel, a
Manhattan lawyer who represents landlords, said that as harsh as
the division's position may seem, it appears to be simply applying
the law as it is written.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that a lot of tenants don't return their
petition within the 60-day time period,'' Turkel said. ``But what
you have here is a statute that says that if a tenant doesn't
respond within 60 days, the agency must issue an order of
deregulation.''
</P>
<P>
   And while some state Supreme Court justices like Ms.
Gangel-Jacob have found in favor of tenants when it is clear that
the tenants' incomes are below the statutory maximum, Turkel said,
those cases that have been appealed have resulted in decisions
upholding the DHCR's strict interpretation of the law.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, landlord-tenant lawyers say that at present the
only way tenants can protect themselves from an inadvertent loss of
their regulated status is to exercise the ``continuing vigilance''
referred to by Ms. Gangel-Jacob.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me that means that tenants have to read and understand
every single document they receive,'' said William Gribben, a
Manhattan lawyer who represents tenants. ``You have to become an
expert on how the whole process works. You have to clear a space on
your desk, get a nice clean legal pad and make a note of every
docket number on every form and the dates when the forms were
received and returned.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, every form should be copied and every form
that is mailed should be sent certified mail, return receipt
requested.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be incredibly diligent,'' said Gribben, ``because
if you make one mistake, it can all go down the drain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
