<SLUG> BC-KAN-SPRINT-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT IS BUILDING MIDWEST'S LARGEST OFFICE COMPLEX 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By SHIRLEY CHRISTIAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ While other telecommunications companies
compete to pull off the biggest mergers and acquisitions, Sprint
Corp. can claim bragging rights of its own for the world
headquarters campus it is building on 200 acres in this booming,
affluent suburb of Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   With 3.1 million square feet of space _ at an estimated cost of
$700 million over four years of work _ the campus is the largest
corporate office construction project in terms of square footage
ever undertaken in the Midwest, according to executives of Sprint
and the construction firm, and the largest currently under way
anywhere in the United States. A possible later phase, not yet
approved by Sprint's board, would bring the total to 3.9 million
square feet with space for 14,500 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The campus will provide what Sprint and its employees say will
be the ideal working environment for the new century, and it is
highly reminiscent of a model that has been around for a long time:
the leafy college campus with low-rise, red-brick buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The work that began last July and is scheduled for completion in
late 2001 will create 18 four- and five-story buildings, one of
them a training center called the University of Excellence; a
175-foot clock tower; covered walkways; an outdoor amphitheater for
3,000 people; parking garages for 12,500 cars; athletic fields, and
hiking and biking trails that connect to public trails outside the
campus.
</P>
<P>
   Some other amenities will take this project beyond the
traditional collegiate model: a full fitness center, a child-care
center, private rooms for nursing mothers next to the women's
restrooms, ``war'' rooms, ``solitude nooks'' and online menus from
the three food courts. Sixty percent of the site will be green
space, for which there is a $10 million landscaping budget. The
campus will have 5,000 trees and will require more than 6 million
bricks.
</P>
<P>
   That is not bad for a corporation descended from a little
country telephone exchange that started business a century ago in
Abilene, Kan. Today, Sprint has 51,000 employees worldwide and had
revenues last year of $14.87 billion. It is the largest private
employer in metropolitan Kansas City, with about 10,500 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Though best known as the nation's third-largest long-distance
carrier, Sprint also provides local service to 7.4 million
customers in 19 states, the heritage of its small-town past, and it
is a leader in wireless personal communications systems. It is
proud of its all-digital, fiber-optic network and is a major
carrier of Internet traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Faye Manker, Sprint's vice president for real estate, said that
many features of the design and facilities for the corporate campus
emerged from employee focus groups and surveys and the more than
300 meetings she and others on the project team held with
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In three surveys, we had them list things they wanted,'' she
said, ``in terms of amenities, parking and technology. We had focus
groups on retail, food and wellness facilities. We got great
questions and ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   A video camera mounted on a pole overlooking the construction
site allows Daniel Euston, project manager for the J.E. Dunn
Construction Co., the general contractor, to observe the site from
his office in the temporary building housing the project management
team. He can zoom in on any worker or any place. Every hour, a
picture is taken from the video and posted on the company intranet,
allowing thousands of employees to check construction progress
regularly.
</P>
<P>
   A 5,000-square-foot mock-up of interior office space has been
built in a warehouse a few miles from the site. Serving as a
laboratory for office design, it allows the planners to try out
ceiling tiles, lighting, movable furniture and other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity for someone in the
construction business,'' said Euston, adding that the real size of
the project could be better understood by taking into account that
construction costs in this part of the country run 30 to 50 percent
below those in the metropolitan areas of the Northeast and
California, with cheaper land prices making an even greater
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Manker said this showplace campus will not only bring
together employees now in about 60 buildings scattered over many
miles of the bistate Kansas City area but ``will have a physical
presence that represents Sprint to our investors and partners.''
She predicted that it would aid in recruitment of employees, both
locally and nationally. ``Recruiting is very difficult today,'' she
said. ``It's a buyer's market. With only 2 percent unemployment in
this area, we are pleased to see that there's been a lot of
attention from potential employees interested in coming to Kansas
City to work at the new headquarters.''
</P>
<P>
   Before plans were drawn, the project team _ about 25 people
representing Sprint, Dunn, Hillier Group, which is the principal
architect, and other architects, engineers and consultants _ looked
for ideas by visiting 15 corporate headquarters around the country,
including those of Microsoft, Monsanto, Ameritech and Sears,
Roebuck. Much of the inspiration for the Sprint campus appears to
have come from the collegiate-styled Microsoft headquarters, which
is slightly larger than what the finished Sprint headquarters will
be but was built piecemeal over many more years.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Manker said that a high-rise headquarters was ruled out
``because communication doesn't happen as well when offices are
vertical instead of horizontal.'' She also said the elevators will
not be of the high-speed variety because the planners want to
encourage employees to use the stairs, which is seen as another way
to ease communication.
</P>
<P>
   As it occupies the new campus, Sprint will vacate 2.5 million
square feet of leased space in several steps beginning August 1999
and continuing into 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Many people involved in real estate in Kansas City and the
suburbs fear that those vacancies will have an adverse effect on
local real estate prices. Ms. Manker argued, however, that any
damage will be temporary because the space is widely dispersed,
most of it in areas with strong and growing demand for class A
office space.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the question of the vacated space, however, Sprint's move
is expected to give a huge boost to the already nonstop commercial
and real estate development in the area surrounding the campus for
several miles. Euston said at least five hotels are scheduled for
construction or in the planning stages near the campus. Residential
real estate agents said that many homes in nearby subdivisions,
where most of the houses are 3,000 square feet and up, are being
sold to Sprint employees. The upscale Town Center Plaza shopping
area, with 73 shops, restaurants and theaters in 750,000 square
feet, opened last year across the street from the eastern boundary
of the Sprint site.
</P>
<P>
   Euston said that 300 to 400 construction workers are now on the
site, where three office buildings and four parking garages are
under construction. By fall, he said, at least 12 buildings will be
under construction, as the work force reaches 1,000. It will remain
at that level for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the serious shortage of skilled construction workers in
Kansas City and many areas of the country, he said it would require
constant juggling to coordinate Sprint's lease expirations in
existing buildings with the availability of craftsmen to complete
new buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Even cement, he said, is in short supply nationwide, with
contractors in some areas able to pour cement only four days a
week. Sprint has dealt with that problem by setting up its own
cement plant at the site.
</P>
<P>
   These headaches may help explain why Ms. Manker, even after
talking about how exhilarating it was to work on such an ambitious
project, said the wall chart that plots the progress of the
undertaking had sometimes been referred to as the ``wall of pain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
