<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: LOOKING FOR RETAIL GOLD IN THE OUTER BOROUGHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bruce Ratner made a big splash when he moved the
7.2-million-pound Empire Theater 170 feet on 42nd Street to serve
as an anchor for the entertainment and retail complex he is now
building.
</P>
<P>
   Cameras recorded the event as balloons resembling the comedians
Bud Abbott and Lou Costello, who met at the theater while it was
called the Eltinge, appeared to tug the building westward.
</P>
<P>
   Ratner has other high profile Manhattan developments in the
works as well. He is seeking approval to build a hotel on 41st
Street over the complex and is about to break ground on a 460-room
Embassy Suites hotel in Battery Park City.
</P>
<P>
   While such projects have brought the former commisioner of the
city's Department of Consumer Affairs public attention, he has been
quietly working at another, perhaps more significant, task _
developing modern retail and entertainment centers in the populous,
but underserved, boroughs of the city outside of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Ratner, whose company, Forest City Ratner, developed the
11-building, 6-million-square-foot Metrotech office building
complex in downtown Brooklyn, said he had become interested in
retail development when it became clear that the overbuilding of
the late '80s and early '90s would preclude more office development
for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The core of our business was office buildings, but over the
last three to four years we have shifted to urban retail,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not think the office market would rebound,'' said
Sandeep Mathrani, a senior vice president of Forest City Ratner and
its director of retail development, ``and we wanted to continue
development in the boroughs.'' He said the company had conducted a
study of stores and neighborhoods and concluded that there was a
large market for modern stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our study found that there is a spending deficit in the
boroughs of $10 billion a year,'' Mathrani said. ``Three billion of
that involves automobiles, so we set that aside. Of the remaining
$7 billion, $3 billion leaves the city for the suburbs and $4
billion is not spent.''
</P>
<P>
   Brokers specializing in retail development agree that many parts
of the city could support large, modern stores whose selections are
more varied and whose prices are typically lower than the small
stores that operate in many neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brooklyn and Queens are clearly understored,'' said Faith
Consolo, a senior managing director of Garrick-Aug Associates, a
retail specialist. ``Nobody thought the boroughs were chic and they
were not developed for national retail. But now Ratner has done
Atlantic Center and it shows the demand is there.''
</P>
<P>
   The development is a three-story, L-shaped structure at Atlantic
and Flatbush Avenues in Brooklyn that opened in the fall of 1996.
Tenants of the 393,000-square-foot center include Pathmark, Caldor,
Sports Authority, Old Navy, Office Max and Circuit City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruce Ratner was the first developer to recognize the strength
of the middle class in the city,'' said Benjamin Fox, a partner in
New Spectrum Realty Services, another retail specialist. ``For
retailers the outer boroughs offer tremendous staying power and
stability because there are families with combined incomes of
$50,000 to $60,000 a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ratner's own research shows that there are about 130,000
people living within a one-mile radius of the Atlantic Center and
that the average household income is almost $53,000 a year.
Lengthening the radius to two miles encompasses 437,000 people, but
the average household income drops to about $44,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Ratner said the Atlantic Center site had been selected for a
replacement for Ebbets Field before the Dodgers defected to the
West Coast. ``The land was cleared by Robert Moses, but it just sat
there for 40 years,'' he said. He said city officials concluded
that office projects would not happen and offered the site for
retail development.
</P>
<P>
   The results at Atlantic Center have been favorable enough that
the company has recently opened a second center diagonally across
the street. Called the Shops at Atlantic Center, its tenants are PC
Richard &AMP; Son and Sneaker Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Forest City Ratner, a partnership between publicly owned Forest
City Enterprises and Ratner's company, now has projects under way
in all five boroughs and in North Bergen, N.J. It has 1.1 million
square feet of retail space in operation, 800,000 square feet in
development and 725,000 square feet in the planning stages.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Atlantic Center, some of the projects currently
in operation include a 175,000-square-foot Home Depot at Gun Hill
Road and Ely Avenue in the Bronx; Maspeth Center at Grand Avenue
and 74th Street in Queens, a 100,000-square-foot neighborhood
shopping center anchored by an Edward's Supermarket; the Shops at
Northern Boulevard on Northern Boulevard and 48th Street in Queens,
a 214,000-square-foot center with Edward's Supermarket, Marshall's
and Old Navy as major tenants, and the Shops at Richmond Avenue at
Richmond Avenue and the entrance to the Staten Island Mall, a
76,000-square-foot center with Circuit City and Staples as major
tenants.
</P>
<P>
   And if the boroughs outside of Manhattan were considered
understored, they are also underscreened, Ratner concluded. So the
company is building a combined bookstore and movie theater called
the Heights, at Court and Schermerhorn Streets in Brooklyn, as well
as two theaters on Staten Island, Hylan Cinemas, at 101 Quintard
St., and Forest Avenue Cinemas, at Forest Avenue and South Street.
</P>
<P>
   One of the difficulties of building large stores in the city was
to translate concepts that were developed in suburban malls to the
urban environment. ``We had to learn the business, because nobody
had ever done it before,'' Ratner said. ``There were issues
regarding parking, security, financing and the micromanagement of
goods depending on the neighborhood.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
