<HEADER>
A0646 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-RATNER-PROFILE-REA     07-11 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RATNER-PROFILE-REAL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: the neighborhood.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One conclusion was that it was simply not possible to provide as
much parking as is available in the suburbs. A typical suburban
mall has five parking spaces for every 1,000 square feet of
shopping space. In the city that ratio is 1.5 to 3 cars per 1,000
square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Another was that with land scarce and expensive, shopping was
going to have to be vertical. Atlantic Center, for example, is
three stories high, with the Pathmark food store on the first floor
and Caldor on the third, with Marshall's and Sports Authority in
the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Finding sites in the city is difficult, company officials said.
``There are no vacant sites, you have to create them,'' said
Mathrani. He said the company had videotaped the city by helicopter
and identified major street and traffic patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it was a matter of knocking on the doors of people who
own large tracts of land and convincing them to sell,'' Ratner
said. None of the land was being offered for sale when the Forest
City Ratner people came calling, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Financing the projects was another obstacle. Since no one had
done these types of stores in an urban setting before, there was no
track record to demonstrate they could be economically successful.
``Four years ago you couldn't get banks to lend on these
projects,'' said Ratner, adding that ``we went to every one of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he said, Credit Lyonnais agreed to finance Atlantic
Center, and the success of that undertaking has made financing less
of a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the density of the population in the city, he said,
many of the stores are doing very well compared with their suburban
counterparts. He said one Caldor store in the city had $50 million
in sales in one year, compared with $25 million to $30 million for
a typical suburban Wal-Mart or $20 million to $22 million for a
suburban K-mart. He said one of the supermarkets sold $800,000 of
groceries a week compared with about $200,000 a week in the
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the advantages of developing in New York, Ratner said, is
that the city has not lost population, like his hometown of
Cleveland or Detroit. As people have moved to the suburbs they have
been replaced by more recent immigrants eager to partake in the
material aspects of the American dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-seven percent of the city's population is made up of
immigrants and it is 50 percent if you count immigrants and their
children,'' Mathrani said. ``Many of them have been deprived of
basic necessities like television and a refrigerator, so they have
a propensity to spend more than people who have been here for
awhile.''
</P>
</TEXT>
