<SLUG> BC-NJ-RETAIL-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: IN A HEALTHY ECONOMY, A SQUEEZE IN RETAIL SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By RACHELLE GARBARINE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year is shaping up to be another good one for New Jersey's
retail sector, giving rise to a burst of new and renovated
shopping-center projects across the state.
</P>
<P>
   A robust economy continues to increase consumer spending, and
financing for development is available. Some retailers are
consolidating or closing stores, but others are expanding and new
ones are entering the state. This has resulted in an increase in
demand for space at a time when the vacancy rate in the 11-county
northern and central New Jersey market is low, developers and
industry analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the activity are four projects, together totaling
1.3 million square feet of new and renovated space, that are moving
forward or are soon to begin in Clifton, Bridgewater, Riverdale and
North Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are seeing now are development deals coming on line
after two very strong retail years with the growth spurred by a
number of aggressive retail tenants,'' said Matthew Harding, senior
vice president of Levin Management, based in North Plainfield.
</P>
<P>
   His concern, which manages some 4.6 million square feet of
retail space in New Jersey, puts the retail vacancy rate in centers
in northern and central New Jersey, excluding regional malls, at 5
percent, down from 7 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Kraus, who heads TKL/The Dealmakers, a retail consulting
firm in Mercerville, puts the vacancy rate even lower, at 3
percent. ``Despite the competition Jersey continues to be a great
retail state because of the vast amount of shoppers and buying
power that exists here,'' he said. He added, however, that the
upshot was that ``weak tenants shall perish.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rickel Home Center chain, for example, filed for bankruptcy
last year and closed its 53 stores, 42 of them in New Jersey. Most,
however, have since been leased by Staples, the office-supply
retailer. At the same time Lowe's, another home-improvement chain,
based in North Wilkesboro, N.C., is making a foray into the state
with a store planned as part of a 421,000-square-foot shopping
center under way in Piscataway, while Home Depot continues to add
new stores. Over the last 18 months Home Depot opened seven stores
and plans to open three more by next July for a total of 29 in the
state, said Katrina Blauvelt, a spokeswoman for the Atlanta-based
chain.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, other ``big box'' retailers like Wal-Mart and Target,
the discount department store chain and a relative newcomer, are
also expanding in the state. Their growth, in turn, has pushed up
rents; Harding of Levin said the rents have risen 5 percent to 8
percent over the last year depending on store size. Large blocks of
100,000 square feet or more average about $15 per square foot a
year, up 7 percent from 1997, he said. He added, however, that
while he does not see ``any abrupt changes in the market in the
near future there could be flattening in rent increases.''
</P>
<P>
   The amount of retail space in the state has also increased,
putting some downward pressure on retailers' sales volume. Data
compiled by Grubb &AMP; Ellis, the national commercial brokerage, show
144 million square feet of space in 1994 in all shopping centers,
excluding regional malls, with retailers averaging $150 a square
foot in annual sales. As of Jan. 1, 1998, the latest figures
available, there were 158 million square feet and retailers were
averaging $139 a square foot in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that retailers are making less money, they
continue to open stores, ``keeping the market healthy,'' said Jerry
Putterman, senior vice president at the West Orange office of Grubb
&AMP; Ellis. But, he said, if interest rates rise and money gets tight
there ``could be a real reversal, spurring more consolidations
within the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, construction continues. Brokers said that along with
big-box retailers the big space takers are supermarkets and movie
theaters. They are being constructed in free-standing locations
like the one on West Central Boulevard in Palisades Park where a
65,000-square-foot Shop Rite opened last month or they are moving
into key spots within retail centers, often as anchors.
</P>
<P>
   But sites for new centers are becoming more difficult to find,
prompting the recycling of land once occupied by industrial or
office buildings into retail use. In the process, ``new retail
pockets'' are being created, said Arthur E. Weiss, senior retail
associate at the Teaneck office of CB Richard Ellis, the national
commercial brokerage. The creation of such a location, he said, is
occurring on 33 acres along Route 3 in Clifton.
</P>
<P>
   There, a 285,000-square-foot retail-entertainment center is
rising on 11 acres formerly occupied by Automatic Data Processing
offices and 22 acres of the adjacent 62-acre property once used by
ITT for its headquarters. Called Clifton Commons, it is the first
phase of a larger 73-acre mixed-use project planned by Related
Retail Corp., an affiliate of the Related Companies, a large
Manhattan development company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The site is the hole in the retail doughnut between Paramus,
Secaucus and Wayne,'' said James Jarosik, executive vice president
at Related Retail, adding that whatever the market, ``having land
with frontage along Route 3 is irreplaceable.''
</P>
<P>
   Clifton Commons, scheduled for completion next spring, has been
nearly fully preleased and will be anchored by an
80,000-square-foot, 16-screen General Cinema complex along with a
65,000-square-foot Edwards supermarket, 130,000 square feet of
stores and two restaurants. Eventually, the remaining 40 acres, now
home to a 950,000-square-foot building that the avionics division
of ITT Industries has leased back from Related Retail until 2002,
will also be redeveloped into up to 1 million square feet of hotel,
housing and additional retail uses, said Jarosik.
</P>
<P>
   In Riverdale, construction is under way on a 240,000-square-foot
open-air retail strip that replaces a former swim club on 35 acres
along Route 23, one-half mile north of Interstate 287.
</P>
<P>
   The center _ where Staples, Home Depot and BJ's Warehouse Club
have signed on as tenants _ is being developed by Starwood Heller
LLC, a joint venture of Heller Enterprises of Edgewater and
Starwood Opportunity Fund IV, an affiliate of Starwood Lodging of
Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a new retail location in a growing area not yet served
by these types of tenants who see it as a way to increase their
market share,'' said Todd Heller, vice president of leasing and
marketing at Starwood Heller.
</P>
<P>
   The partners also see Edgewater's Hudson River waterfront as
another retail growth area and are planning to develop at least
250,000 square feet of stores as well as a 14-screen National
Amusement movie theater in three projects along River Road there,
said Heller. A key reason, he said, is that more than 4,000 new
residential units are under way or planned at the river's edge in
Edgewater as well as nearby West New York.
</P>
<P>
   In Bridgewater, site work began last month on a
625,000-square-foot shopping center on 70 acres at Route 28 and
I-287 that were once part of the American Cyanamid corporate
campus. Bridgewater Promenade, as the center is called, will have a
75,000-square-foot hotel with up to 175 rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The area is in desperate need of this kind of mixed-used
project and the site, in terms of location, access and
demographics, can support it,'' said William Krame, president of
Krame Development Co. of Paramus, which is developing the center in
partnership with the Kimco Realty Corp. of New Hyde Park, Long
Island, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Krame said the project was fully leased to such big-box
retailers as Target, Babies `R' Us and Home Depot as well as to
smaller tenants, including a bank, a video store and three
restaurants. Completion is expected by the summer of 1999, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Older centers are also being redeveloped to remain competitive.
An example is the 145,000-square-foot North Village Shopping
Center, on 12 acres where Routes 1 and 130 meet in North Brunswick,
which Levin Management plans to begin renovating this fall. The
center, built in the '60s, is now mostly vacant due to the closing
of a 30,000-square-foot A&AMP;P and an 80,000-square-foot Bradlees.
</P>
<P>
   The work includes reducing the size of the center to 130,000
square feet, dividing the former Bradlees for two or three users
and giving the reconfigured center a new facade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking outmoded space and renovating it into a
`mini-power center' to attract a few mostly big-box retailers,''
said Matthew Harding, Levin's senior vice president. He added that
deals for that space were being negotiated with such tenants as a
bookstore and an office-supply chain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
