u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ELECTION-BOS &LR;      07-11 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE DESPERATE TIMES, RULING PARTY EXPECTED TO PREVAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japanese voters go to the polls Sunday as &UR;  &LR; the country's
once-invincible economy is facing its worst recession and highest
unemployment since World War II, the deficit is ballooning, banks
are teetering, and fewer than one in three people approve of the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   In most democracies, this would be a golden opportunity to throw
failed politicians out. But in Japan, where the opposition is weak,
the ruling party is backed by powerful business &UR;  &LR; interests, and the
populace turns conservative in times of crisis, the LDP is
predicted to &UR;  &LR; win more contested seats than anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``The LDP has done a rotten job in the last few years. But the
good news for them is there's no competition,'' said Richard
Jerram, chief Japan economist at ING Baring Securities. ``At any
given time, there seem to be 101 opposition parties. They shuffle
the pack, but it's still the same jokers.... If you want to vote
for someone other than the LDP, who do you vote for?''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the election for half the seats in the Upper House
of parliament represents a potential vote of confidence _ or the
lack thereof _ in the LDP and Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto. His
party had hoped to win 69 of the 126 seats up for grabs, to gain a
majority in the Upper House. After dismal showings in polls, LDP
officials scaled back expectations, saying the party would declare
victory if it held onto the 61 seats it controls already.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's vote will determine how strong a mandate the LDP can
claim _ and the party's ability to implement painful economic
reforms. A strong showing could leave the LDP smug and unwilling to
shake things up, and could kill off some opposition parties. A poor
showing could force Hashimoto to step down, which could cripple his
party with infighting and stymie the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The LDP controls the more powerful Lower House, of which
Hashimoto is a member, so it should remain in charge regardless of
Sunday's results. But votes cast on Sunday will shape the face of
parliament for a long time, since members elected Sunday will serve
until 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, the financial crisis that has pummeled
Asia this year makes it more critical than ever that Japan yank its
economy _ the world's second-largest _ out of a nearly nine-year
slump.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the stagnant economy has become the sole campaign issue.
Increased government spending has postponed suffering, but since
the first recession in 23 years was declared last month, the
long-patient public is finally getting fed up.
</P>
<P>
   The LDP realizes this, and its campaign pitches have
turned &UR;  &LR; desperate. On the first day of the campaign, Hashimoto
begged voters: ``Please believe in the LDP. Please help us to make
the situation stable.'' Last week, he called for permanent tax
cuts, after twice changing his stance within a few days. Other
officials also flipflopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes these guys look like the Keystone Kops, running
around with everyone saying something different.... It further
undermines the already questionable credibility of the ruling
party,'' said John Neuffer, a political analyst at Matsui Marine
Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The LDP has governed Japan for all but two years since the end
of World War II, and it has a loyal voter base among big business,
farmers, and construction, to whom it has awarded projects and
subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest opposition force, the Democratic Party of Japan
(DPJ), has a popular leader, but his two-year-old party is weak.
The Communists have dedicated loyalists but are still viewed by
most Japanese with suspicion. These two are the only parties
besides the LDP that are expected to gain seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``After World War II, the LDP was great, because they brought
our GDP (gross domestic product) to second place in the world. But
the world has changed, and what we need are new ways of doing
things, new parties that can adapt to a new reality,'' said Banri
Kaieda, a DPJ member of the Lower House.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cut long advocated by his party, Kaieda said, is a
bitter pill for the LDP, because it would mean cutting spending
that supports loyalists. But in the end, the LDP has called for
long-term tax relief, an example of how it neutralizes the
opposition by adopting its platforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats call themselves middle-of-the-road. The LDP is
the whole road,'' Neuffer said. ``Its strength is that it's not a
party based on policy or principles, but a party with a number one
goal of getting elected.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an old joke in Japan that the real opposition is the United
States, which has held considerable sway over Japanese policies
since the postwar period. ``I'd say there's a new opposition party
_ the (global) financial markets,'' which rate Japan's performance
through stock and currency showings, said Ronald Bevacqua,
economist and vice president at Merrill Lynch Japan Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The best outcome, he said, would be for the LDP to do well
enough ``to quiet opposition within the party, but for the markets
and the US to keep holding their feet to the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States recently increased the heat on Japan to reform
after its currency, the yen, dropped precipitously. US observers
worry that if the yen collapses, it could set off a round of
competitive devaluations across the region, destabilizing Asia and
sending ripples as far as Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election is very important because it will have a great
influence on unemployment, health insurance, prices, even the
environment,'' said Kaoru Okano, a political scientist and former
president of Meiji University in Tokyo. But Okano lamented that
politicians here are so tied to special interests that it is hard
to envisage anyone brave enough to undertake drastic changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If 5 percent of candidates are statesmen and 10 percent are
politicians, (then) 85 percent are wheeler-dealers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The former minister of construction recently said publicly and
without embarrassment that reiki yudo, or ``getting votes in return
for projects to help the constituency,'' was a politician's most
important job.
</P>
<P>
   In that context, it is easy to see why many voters are
disillusioned. A poll last week showed 85 percent of people were
fed up with politics.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys this month suggested turnout might hit record lows of 40
percent, which could boost the LDP and the Communists, who have
dedicated supporters. But a poll published Thursday predicted a 64
percent turnout, which could mean more protest votes than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting for change, but nothing has gotten any
better. I no longer ... trust the LDP,'' said Akiko Saito, 42, a
secretary who prefers the Social Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   But many young voters interviewed Saturday said they would stay
away from the polls entirely. ``Whatever those politicians promise,
they're not going to do anyway, so why bother voting?'' said Kaori
Kawamoto, a 26-year-old student.
</P>
<P>
   If the LDP gets trounced Sunday, Hashimoto, who is not up for
reelection, could be forced to resign and the Lower House could be
forced to call new elections. Markets could also lose confidence,
causing the yen and stocks to drop.
</P>
<P>
   There are some analysts who say an LDP defeat would be good for
the nation, because it would scare them into making radical
reforms. But others say a tattered ruling party would be hindered
from undertaking unpopular changes.
</P>
<P>
   Still others say that even with a big win, there's no evidence
the LDP, the bureaucracy, and the public will bite the bullet and
implement reforms that would cause short-term pain but long-term
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We often blame the government, but I think all Japanese people
should be blamed. We have lived without the courage to face
economic reality,'' said Teizo Taya, managing director of Daiwa
Institute of Research. ``Unfortunately, this election won't change
that. We haven't yet suffered enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
