<HEADER>
A0653 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-BOS &LR;      07-11 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE FACTIONS NEAR DEAL ON FINANCE CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Opposing House factions are near a pivotal
agreement that would limit the long, winding debate over rewriting
the nation's campaign-finance laws and force a final vote on the
issue before the House begins its summer recess.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the effort to limit big money's influence over
politics say that meeting the Aug. 7 deadline is crucial to give
the Senate enough time to act on the measure before Congress
adjourns for the year in early October.
</P>
<P>
   The push for change comes as the major parties and candidates
scurry to raise an estimated $800 million they will spend this year
on congressional election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, House Republican leaders would reduce the
number of proposed amendments _ to 34 from 258 _ to the most
prominent overhaul bill sponsored by Representatives Martin T.
Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat, and Christopher Shays, a
Connecticut Republican. Overall debate on the issue would be
limited to about 20 hours, split over many days and nights.
</P>
<P>
   For seven weeks, GOP leaders have relegated the unwieldy debate
to so many late-night sessions that backers of the overhaul plan
are calling the effort ``vampire reform.''
</P>
<P>
   But the pending pact means an end may be in sight to the
late-night drama. Meehan said he hopes to seal the agreement with
Republican leaders on Tuesday, when lawmakers are scheduled to
resume the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all part of getting through the legislative minefields
that have been set up to try to defeat this bill,'' Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after House Speaker Newt Gingrich agreed in a highly
publicized handshake with President Clinton to address problems in
the campaign-finance system, Gingrich has helped devise special
rules for the debate that Shays-Meehan backers described as a
blatant attempt to kill the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules, GOP leaders are permitting the House to
consider 12 campaign-finance bills, including the Shays-Meehan
measure. But in a rare procedural free-for-all, the bill that
receives the most votes will prevail in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the Shays-Meehan measure say they have assembled a
coalition of at least 225 House members. But their fragile majority
remains threatened by several rival plans and the pending
amendments, some of which could alter their proposal enough to
siphon off vital support.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Shays and Meehan have failed to persuade GOP leaders
to stop scheduling the campaign-finance debate in intermittent
late-night sessions, which generally receive little public
attention. Shays-Meehan supporters say the GOP strategy makes it
difficult to maintain momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, I don't think this debate is going to be held
at a time when Americans will be focused on it,'' Meehan said.
``It's going to go late into the evening many nights.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan bill would ban large, unregulated contributions
known as soft money that have increasingly influenced state and
national elections. The proposal also would tighten disclosure
requirements and regulate spending by corporations, unions, and
nonprofit groups on advertising that influences federal elections.
</P>
<P>
   The measure's leading foe, Representative Tom DeLay, a Texas
Republican who is the House majority whip, is scheduled to offer a
major amendment next week that would eliminate the Shays-Meehan
proposal to regulate advocacy campaigns against elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, groups are not required to disclose who gives
them money and how they spend it on advertising that does not
specifically call for a candidate's election or defeat. Advocates
for changing the law say special-interest groups spent more than
$150 million in the last federal elections on such unregulated
advertising, including so-called voter guides.
</P>
<P>
   Citing Supreme Court decisons, DeLay said the advocacy efforts
are protected by free-speech rights. In a speech on the House
floor, he referred to a position paper by the National Right to
Life Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such commentary is not an abuse or evasion of federal law,''
Douglas Johnson, the group's legislative director, wrote in the
paper. ``Rather, it is fully protected by the First Amendment,
which is not a loophole but, among other things, the nation's
paramount election law.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote on DeLay's amendment is expected to be sensitive for
many House members because the Christian Coalition and National
Right to Life Committee plan to record the roll call in their next
voter guides.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big hurdle for Shays-Meehan,'' said a senior House
aide. ``If the amendment passes, they could lose the coalition
behind the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   The alliance also is threatened by another amendment scheduled
for consideration this week. The measure, sponsored by
Representative Vito J. Fossella Jr., a Republican who represents
Staten Island, N.Y., would ban noncitizens, including legal
permanent residents, from contributing to federal election
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Current law permits legal permanent residents to contribute. And
the effort to deny them the privilege is strongly opposed by the
Congressional Hispanic Caucus and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this does is prohibit legal residents who are living in
the United States, working, paying their taxes, fighting in the
military, giving up their lives, from exercising their right to
participate in the political process in this country,'' said
Representative Patsy Mink, a Hawaii Democrat. ``It's absolutely
unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   Shays-Meehan backers hope to preserve their coalition by
defeating the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   But Meehan said he might agree to adopt several other amendments
without a vote to try to maintain support for his bill. Notable
among those measures are GOP-sponsored salvos at the Clinton
administration over fund-raising irregularities, including an
amendment that would ban the use of White House meals and
accommodations for political fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Vice President Al Gore have faced widespread
criticism for hosting White House coffees for many donors and
permitting some to stay overnight in the Lincoln Bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has denied soliciting contributions in the White House,
although he said he could not recall if he made telephone calls
from the Oval Office asking for donations.
</P>
<P>
   Gore acknowledged making fund-raising calls from his White House
office, but he asserted the practice was not prohibited by any
``controlling legal authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan said current law prohibits fund-raising in the White
House and described the Republican amendments as duplicative. ``If
we can reach accommodations on bills that are meant to embarrass
Democrats but make no change in the present law,'' he said, ``we
will try to do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
