<SLUG> BC-BKO-WORLD-USA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
U.S. team roster trimmed to 16
<TEXT>
<P>
   By EDDIE SEFKO &QL; 
CHICAGO _ The list of hopefuls for the U.S. World Championship of
Basketball team was trimmed to 16 on Saturday as Rudy Tomjanovich
and his staff sent 12 players packing.
</P>
<P>
   Most notable among the cuts were former NBA players Larry
Stewart, Acie Earl, Gerald Madkins, Tim Kempton and Randy
Livingston, who played one season with the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an easy task because the guys were so competitive and
the level of talent was very close,'' Tomjanovich said. ``There are
several guys who played very well who are not here. I feel bad
about those things, but they happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Left to battle for the 12 roster spots for the team that will
play in Athens, Greece, starting July 29 are 16 players of diverse
backgrounds and abilities. The survivors include 10-year pro David
Wood and college underclassmen such as Mateen Cleaves and Trajan
Langdon, European refugees such as Warren Kidd and Wendell Alexis
and athletic NBA fringe players such as Jimmy King and Jason
Sasser.
</P>
<P>
   Also making the first round of cuts was Tim Breaux, who sat out
most of the first three days of workouts with a sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich is pleased with those who made the cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We move on from here,'' he said. ``Out of these 16, I believe
we have some versatility because we have players who can play a
couple of different spots. I'd like to say that we can get real
big, but we just don't have a big team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main focus coming is that we have to push the ball and get
some easy transition baskets. But we can't forget about the
execution of the half-court game, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some really good kids. They're very receptive and
they play hard, with their hearts. And I think we're going to have
a determined team, a team that feels honored to go out and
represent the USA and it's going to be a great challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich said he's unsure whether the roster will be cut
further before the team leaves for Monte Carlo on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a chance we could make another cut,'' he said.
``There's a chance that we could take more than 12 over there and
make the final cuts in Europe. There's an outside chance we could
pick up another player.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``outside chance'' probably would not be a marquee player
with NBA experience. More likely, he would be a member of the
Goodwill Games team that will scrimmage the U.S. squad Monday and
Tuesday at Chicago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
