<HEADLINE>
ABOUT WICHITA FALLS, TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's in a name: The city gained its name from a Wichita Indian
encampment near a small waterfall along the Wichita River. A flood
washed away the five-foot tall waterfall in the late 1890s. Nearly
100 years later, the falls are back. A man-made ``falls'' were
built by the citizens of Wichita Falls during the city's centennial
in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay: Wichita Falls is home to 26 hotels, from staples
such as Holiday Inn and Ramada Inn to the Henrietta Township Bed
and Breakfast on the Square. Guests of the Henrietta can enjoy hot
bubble baths in an antique claw-footed tub and be catered to with
hot tea served in the room, gourmet breakfasts, homemade muffins
and a cup of hot chocolate before bed. Visitors choose from a
Pioneer room, Victorian room, Maw Belle Telephone Room, Cowboy Room
and Miss Katy Train Room. The hotel also features murder mystery
weekends; the mysteries are based on actual happenings in the area
and include period costumes.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat: Wichita Falls has 93 restaurants, ranging from
cafeterias to barbecue to Mexican, Italian and Oriental cuisine. In
addition to places such as Uncle Lynn's Catfish and Fat McBride's
Steakhouse, there is a dual fare establishment, Bubba's Burgers &AMP;
Christy's Mexican, that should keep everyone happy.
</P>
<P>
   What to do: In addition to 12 shopping centers, Wichita Falls
has a set of popular attractions. The Wichita Falls Symphony
Orchestra, the Wichita Falls Ballet, the Wichita Falls Museum and
Arts Center and Wichita Theatre and Arts House should satisfy the
tastes of the art-starved.
</P>
<P>
   Historical sites include a World War Memorial, the Wichita Falls
Waterfall, the Spanish War Veteran Memorial and the Littlest
Skyscraper. Three lakes are within a 30-mile radius of the city,
including Lake Arrowhead State Park, which has 106 miles of
shoreline and offers camping, swimming, fishing, boating, wildlife
observation, hiking and horseback riding.
</P>
<P>
   The nightlife offers a bevy of country and western clubs, such
as Lonesum Dove and Little Brothers, which features the Lone Star
Six Pack band. The American Legion Post 202 offers dances every
Saturday. Graham Central Station has become the biggest attraction.
It has five clubs in one building, including a country dance area,
a karaoke show bar, a nostalgic dance area, a top 40 dance area, a
game room and a sports bar.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers crunch: Wichita Falls has a population of 103,312, until
Wednesday. It is a two-hour drive east from the Fort Worth-Dallas
area and two hours south of Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Company is coming: Approximately 100,000 visitors are expected
to Wichita Falls during the month-long training camp. They won't be
empty-handed, either. Austin's Visitors Bureau said that the
Cowboys' presence in Austin represented an economic impact of $3
million per year.
</P>
<P>
   How hot is it? Wichita Falls is home of the Hotter 'N Hell
Hundred bicycle criterium. It's a moniker that city officials spend
plenty of time trying to downplay when luring tourists to town. So
how hot does it get? Officially, the normal temperature during July
and August ranges from 71.4 to 97.2 degrees, with an average high
reading of 96.6. Going out on a limb here, the Cowboys will be able
to count on one finger _ maybe with room to spare _ the number of
70-degree days they encounter during camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
