</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALNOTES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American League Notes
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   East
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Little-known Yankees general manager Brian Cashman is
starting to sound get a little cocky. Not that there's anything
wrong with that, but when asked recently about his team's 61-20
record in the first half, Cashman said, ``I honestly believe that
if you took one of these two All-Star teams and they played our
schedule, they'd be hard-pressed to do 61-20. It's not meant to put
anyone down; it's just a statement of how special our first half
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Even with their disappointing Incredible as it sounds
with a 40-50 record, the Orioles have made the fewest errors in
baseball, with 36. But they are 0-10 in games when they allow an
unearned run. ... The Orioles have used 11 different starting
pitchers this year, second only to the Cardinals. ... A leftover
from a game last weekend between the Red Sox and White Sox: The two
clubs managed to throw 378 pitches, but there were just four
strikeouts. ... Tampa Bay's Randy Winn, the 3,000th strikeout
victim of Roger Clemens, said, ``It's really not a shame, because
I'm going to strike out a lot more times.'' ... The Devil Rays have
faced Cy Young winners in 13 games this season for a 4-9 record.
... The Yankees are trying to work out a long-term deal with third
baseman Scott Brosius. ... The last time the Yankees had five
players at the All-Star Game but no position starters was in 1965,
when Elston Howard, Mickey Mantle, Joe Pepitone, Bobby Richardson
and Mel Stottlemyre were there.
</P>
<P>
   Central
</P>
<P>
   Typically, Most switch hitters typically don't stick switching
to just one side of the plate. But Minnesota's Dennis Hocking is
having trouble from the left side, and manager Tom Kelly met with
his young shortstop and strongly suggested a change. What was
Hocking's response? Said Kelly, ``I think he's receptive to the
idea of staying in the major leagues,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: There are problems with White Sox starter Jaime Navarro,
who said, ``Maybe this isn't the right team for me. Maybe I should
just get out of here, go to the bullpen or do something. I know I'm
not getting it done as a starter, and I don't know why. Maybe I'll
go in and ask for a trade, because it's not working out for me
here.'' Navarro is 7-10 with a 6.04 ERA. ... No wonder the Indians
have a 10 1/2-game lead in the division. They are 15-5 against
teams in the division this year. ... Cleveland's Kenny Lofton on
playing left field in the All-Star Game instead of his natural spot
in center: ``(Ken) Griffey. He's the man. He got 4 million votes.
Wherever he wants to play, it's up to him.'' ... Royals
right-hander Kevin Appier, who has been out since undergoing
surgery on his shoulder in March, is down in Florida throwing
simulated games.
</P>
<P>
   West
</P>
<P>
   Next time Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr. thinks that he's going to
get some rest and skip decides to at first not to participate in an
event the fans want him to man who lived out a love-hate
relationship with the city's sports fans frequently attempted to
convince the populace he was ``for real.'' Few heeded Sanders'
words. At the ``Prime Time Tuesday'' study sessions, though, he has
no such problem maintaining attention, drawing a big crowd,
manifesting his humanity or detailing his shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Even last week, when the service was moved without notice from
the Grace Outreach Center to the more intimate Willow Bend Church a
few miles away, his followers found him, a small Christian convoy
snaking into the parking lot just before the 7 p.m. start. Only a
tiny van ferrying a contingent from the National Federation of the
Blind failed to locate the service.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders does not actively advertise the Bible study. There are
no fliers, no billboards along the North Dallas Tollway. Even a
recent article in a national magazine didn't give away the
location. ``People just sort of find their way somehow,'' said
Dallas Cowboys free safety Omar Stoutmire, who with Sanders and
tailback Emmitt Smith was baptized last October. ``Every week there
are new people who wander in here.''
</P>
<P>
   The worshippers last Tuesday included evangelists Jane Willhite
and Rosalind Baker of Kalamazoo, Mich. The two were in town to
visit The Potter's House, one of the country's fastest-growing
congregations. The interdenominational church was founded by the
Rev. T.D. Jakes, the man who baptized Sanders, Smith and Stoutmire,
and who last Thursday and Friday brought his message to large
crowds at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Sanders donated $1 million to The Potter's House to
help fund ``Project 2000,'' a wide-ranging social service ministry
instituted by Jakes, the church's bishop. The donation included his
$465,000 advance for ``Power, Money and Sex: It's a Man Thing,''
his first book, which is to be published in October.
</P>
<P>
   The book, Sanders hopes, will be an extension of his burgeoning
lay ministry. His work includes weekly speeches at Dallas-area
schools, frequent visits with prison inmates and occasional
television appearances. But the Tuesday sessions, and the feeling
of grass-roots outreach which resonates from them, are closest to
his heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through word of mouth, (Sanders') service is talked up,''
Willhite said. ``And we didn't want to leave Dallas without seeing
it. It's a powerful thing, very inspirational.'' Said Syrenna
Joseph, a first-timer from the adjacent suburb of Carrollton:
``Deion, he has a message all people ought to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who will be 31 next month, readily conceded he was one
of the last to pay attention to the message. ``It is ironic, I
guess, that all these people can find Deion, and it took him so
long to find himself,'' said Viola Murphy of Irving, Texas, after
hearing Sanders preach at the Calvary Temple there.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime friends and teammates, past and present, have confirmed
Sanders' claims that he has never touched alcohol, recreational
drugs or cigarettes. Only in moments of frustration has he cursed,
and last week he took offense when an article in ESPN magazine
featured the word ``damn'' in a headline. Close friend and onetime
Cincinnati Reds teammate Lenny Harris describes Sanders as ``the
most boring guy in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Sanders' vice was sex _ and plenty of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delilah and Jezebel, they are real,'' said Sanders, admitting
to his weakness. ``Maybe I wasn't always looking for (women), but
they were finding me. But I wasn't closing the door, either,
really. I heard them knocking, and I didn't bolt the latch, you
know? I caved in to my biggest weakness. I surrendered to it. I
climbed into the pit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have had another car, (but) that wouldn't have made me
happy. More jewelry or another (expensive watch)? Uh-uh. Really,
all the women didn't make me happy, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' epiphany coincided with his arrival at rock-bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a divorce from his wife, Carolyn, and the loss of his
daughter (Deiondra Yvonne) and son (Deion Luwynn Jr.), Sanders said
he twice attempted suicide while in Cincinnati. Other than to admit
he ``rehearsed the thing out'' and then botched the efforts,
Sanders declined to discuss the incidents. They will, he promised,
be a prominent chapter in his book. ``But you don't let someone
lick the bowl,'' he said, ``until you're finished icing the cake.''
</P>
<P>
   After one of the suicide attempts, Sanders said he was awakened
from his sleep by a bright light in his Cincinnati apartment, and
his conversion commenced.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can say what they want (about his life's turnaround),''
Sanders said. ``All that's important is, I know where I've been,
who I've been and what I am now.''
</P>
<P>
   The skeptics and conspiracy theorists seeking evidence of a
Sanders scam, of course, abound in and outside metropolitan Dallas.
Despite his donations of time and money, the naysayers note that
Sanders is hardly the second coming of St. Paul. He lives in a
development with golfer Fred Couples, NBA center Shawn Bradley and
several CEOs of Dallas-based corporations, and his driveway still
features an impressive collection of automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   But when one gives over his soul to Jesus, Sanders noted, it
doesn't necessarily follow that he must sacrifice all material
possessions. And others, said Paul Crouch, founder of the Trinity
Broadcasting Network and a new fan of Sanders' work, must reconcile
for themselves the seeming dichotomy of Sanders' obvious wealth and
the fact he plays in the NFL for the Cowboys _ a team that has led
the league in arrests _ and his new vocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just listen to Deion for a few minutes, and there can be no
doubting his sincerity,'' said Crouch, who recently hosted Sanders
as a TV guest.
</P>
<P>
   Broad appeal
</P>
<P>
   If there are doubting Thomases, they are not present at the
Willow Bend Church, where Sanders' conversion is viewed as a major
Christian turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings such a spirit to this place,'' says Jane Decker, who
attends the Bible study every week. ``The one week, when he was
visiting a prison and wasn't here ... there was a real void.'' Adds
fellow regular Patricia Howard: ``He's an instrument that brings in
the people, especially the young people.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the fiery rhetoric of Sanders and David Forbes, the
pastor, in fact the most striking element of ``Prime Time Tuesday''
is the manner in which it appears to cut across demographics of
race, religion and socioeconomics.
</P>
<P>
   Most newcomers arrive expecting to see an assembly primarily
made up of African-American and Southern Baptist worshippers. But
on this Tuesday evening, the congregation is about 65 percent white
upper-middle and upper class and includes no fewer than five
denominations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we're here for everyone,'' says Forbes, who every Tuesday
flies from his Columbus (Ohio) Christian Center to Dallas to team
with Sanders. In fact, while Sanders is the magnet that gets people
into the church for the first time, it may well be Forbes who draws
them back time after time.
</P>
<P>
   An eloquent and emotional speaker, Forbes' style is equal parts
Elmer Gantry revivalist tent meeting, hip-hop jargon, clever
word-play and evangelism. His points of emphasis are alternately
mesmerizing, sobering and knee-slapping funny, interrupted by the
assembly's very verbal approval.
</P>
<P>
   Seated in the middle of the front row, stripped down to his
T-shirt at one point, a rapt Sanders is a willing student. Sanders
is in a gray area right now in his study _ a ``Bible baby,'' Jakes
calls him. He is learned enough to have authored an articulate
dissection of 2 Timothy, but still struggling to grasp the entire
message.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he is integral to the session, and the worshippers
clearly enjoy Sanders' verbal byplay. At one point, he asks local
home builder Steve Roberts, a recent convert, to rise and
concluded: ``With Steve in our camp now, I know all his homes will
have strong foundations.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the session, Sanders hums to the tune ``Lean
on Me,'' digresses briefly into his conversion and asks the
congregation to find a partner on whom to lean.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who met Sanders last year when agent Eugene Parker asked
his own pastor in Fort Wayne, Ind., to help him find help for his
client, concludes the service by asking all those who suffered from
depression or ever contemplated suicide to come forward and pray
with him. Sanders leads the small parade.
</P>
<P>
   It is a scene that those who knew Sanders in his wilder days
might find unthinkable. In Atlanta, where Sanders sported his
trademark doo-rag, most fans might not recognize the guy who has
replaced it with a blue headband that has ``Jesus'' written across
it.
</P>
<P>
   They might be surprised to know that Sanders, who once got into
a slapping match with wide receiver Andre Rison at the Georgia
Dome, last year knelt in front of the fan who had dumped beer on
him in Washington and prayed aloud. The cornerback, who once high
stepped with interceptions, steps more gingerly now, he says, ``in
the footsteps of the Lord'' and greets opponents he once taunted
with scripture passages.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Romo, a friend and weekly visitor to the Bible study
class, concludes Sanders has ``recreated his soul.'' As the organ
blares out a snappy recessional and the night's amens begin to
fade, Forbes leaves little doubt he considers a reborn Sanders the
real deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember this,'' Forbes says. ``You cannot clone a soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
