r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NLNOTES12-COX     07-11 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NLNOTES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National League Notes
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   East
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- While everyone has praised Atlanta's Greg Maddux for
his pitching this season, his hitting has been overlooked. At the
All-Star Game, his .302 batting average was better than 15 players
there, and that's not including other pitchers. The group included
Juan Gonzalez (.293), Ken Griffey Jr. (.299), Kenny Lofton (.282)
and All-Star MVP Roberto Alomar (.291). Maddux went into the season
as a .173 hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Here is something that may interest Maddux and David
Wells of the Yankees: Going into the All-Star Game, pitchers over
the years that started the game were a collective 716-264 in the
first half for a .731 winning percentage but after the break fell
off to .576 (407-300). ... Interesting that Mets pitcher Rick Reed
went to the All-Star Game but won't benefit from the revenue from
it. Reed was a replacement player and has not been allowed to join
the players union, so he won't get a pension when he retires. The
money the union receives from the All-Star Game goes into the
pension fund. ... The Phillies were upset that the Cardinals gave
J.D. Drew a $7 million deal. It has hurt Philadelphia's
negotiations with their first pick, the No. 1 choice in the draft,
Pat Burrell. The Phillies had picked Drew last year and, said
general manager Ed Wade, ``He never played professional baseball
and ended up with those numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Central
</P>
<P>
   Concerning his chase after the Roger Maris home-run record, Mark
McGwire put out this warning before the second half began:
``Everything people are talking about is a projection. There's
always projections at the All-Star break and nobody realizes the
second half is the toughest part of the year. Let's be realistic,
there's a long way to go and a lot of things may happen. My goal is
to finish the season without having gray on my goatee.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: While McGwire has MVP numbers, some feel Astros leadoff
man Craig Biggio had a better first half. Biggio was hitting .323
at the break, .373 with men in scoring position and .425 with
runners on base. His on-base percentage was .398 and he leads the
league in runs with 75. He also is a Gold Glove. ... One of the
best quotes from the All-Star Game came from injured Cubs slugger
Sammy Sosa, who said, ``I have to control myself from wanting to
take batting practice. I'm just a bat boy and a hitting coach
trying to have a good time.'' Hitting coach? That's interesting
coming from a player whose strategy is simple: Swing as hard as you
can at all times. ... A team to watch in the second half is the
Reds, who won nine of 10 going into the break and picked up
talented young players Paul Konerko and Dennis Reyes from the
Dodgers.West
</P>
<P>
   While the Dodgers found themselves 13 1/2 games back at the
break, they can take heart from the fact such deficits have been
overcome before. Take, for instance, the 1978 Yankees, who were 14
games back at the break but went on to win the World Series. And
the Braves in 1991 were 9 1/2 games back and won the division,
catching and passing, you guessed it, the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The Diamondbacks have been showing slow improvement,
going 7-20 in April, 10-19 in May and 12-15 in June, although they
are 1-5 this month. ... One leftover from Andy Ashby's 75-pitch
complete game last Sunday. Here is the San Diego right-hander's
inning-by-inning pitch count: 8, 6, 5, 8, 7, 9, 11, 11, 10. ... The
Rockies realize they are not going to the postseason, but pitching
coach Frank Funk has come up with a reason to play better in the
second half: ``We can come back in the second half and make life
miserable for the opponents that think they are going to run away
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
