<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-WICHITAFALLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WICHITA FALLS RUSHING TO EMBRACE THE COWBOYS, BUT ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (set ital) They're holding the big dance here beginning this
week, and the local girl is both all excited and more than a little
bit nervous. See, she can't quite figure out if her date is really
interested in her for who she is, or whether he's just using her
before moving on to someone a whole lot flashier. (end ital) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ To understand the psyche of a city, you
really have to live in it for a while. But to appreciate the
ambivalence many Wichita Falls residents admit feeling about the
arrival this week of the Cowboys, all you need do is talk to a few
of them. Folks such as David Gaines, a 52-year-old graduate
research assistant at Midwestern State University, where the
Cowboys open training camp Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Gaines about the last time this many media crawled around
town and he recalls the day in May 1995 when a plane crashed into
an apartment building and parking lot on the north side of town,
killing two people. The accident, he remembers, attracted reporters
and camera crews from all the TV networks.
</P>
<P>
   The time before that, it was the killer tornado of 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the kind of attention you want to get,'' he
testifies. ``We're hoping the Cowboys will be more of a positive
thing for the town.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the not-small matter of the Cowboys' reputation.
What kind of culture clash shall ensue when a group known for
trashing dorm rooms and making more court appearances than Judge
Wapner meets a town that touts family values over excitement?
</P>
<P>
   Gaines remembers going to see a touring production of ``The Best
Little Whorehouse in Texas'' nearly 20 years ago at a local hall.
When the actors let loose some pastel-blue language early in the
play, he recalls, ``There was a distinct take of breath in the
theater.''
</P>
<P>
   You couldn't blame the 100,000 or so people in this city 120
miles north and west of Fort Worth-Dallas for holding their breath
for the duration of training camp. Outside media, who have
portrayed their community in an unflattering way before, are back,
complaining about too much heat and too little to do after hours.
And a football team known nationally in recent years for its
gun-toting coaches and drug-abusing players will be stuck in the
middle of their conservative home until the middle of August.
</P>
<P>
   So, of course there are some mixed feelings about the Cowboys
coming to their town.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they've acted in the past, well, I'd like for them to
act more like role models,'' says Juanita Westmoreland, 72,
speaking of the Cowboys character issue. ``I have four grandsons.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she says ``90 percent'' of the people in her community
are excited about their coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're known as a little hick town,'' Westmoreland says
bluntly. ``This gives us a little prestige. And maybe with a new
coach, it'll be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Another resident, Greg James, 45, understands full well the
conflicting feelings of his fellow towns people.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear the stories from Austin,'' he says, recalling the
room-trashing incident at St. Edward's University.
</P>
<P>
   He also wonders, as do many residents, whether Cowboys owner
Jerry Jones will pack up his summer place caravan and take it west
to El Paso next year. A bigger town, a better deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our city's bent over backwards for these guys,'' James says.
``I hope they're not just using us.''
</P>
<P>
   Too, there is talk of traffic congestion, exacerbated by nearby
road-construction projects, and parking problems in and around the
pleasant, leafy campus.
</P>
<P>
   Such collective anxiety make sense when put into the larger
context of civic history. The city's namesake falls, really just a
drop-and-a-splash at about five feet in height, were destroyed
around the turn of the century in _ irony of ironies _ a flood. A
``new'' falls was built, far taller and in three levels, about a
decade ago to satisfy inquiring tourists who found a bone-dry town.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the rebuilt falls has all the charm of an
oversized miniature golf prop. Even residents deride it and its
murky water.
</P>
<P>
   Who wouldn't hope for the best, but have concern for the worst?
</P>
<P>
   But if Wichita Falls residents are worried about the Cowboys'
behavior, or the team's possible departure after a single summer,
they're not showing it in their hospitality. It is difficult to
turn a street corner and not see a shop bearing a ``Welcome
Cowboys'' sign in the window.
</P>
<P>
   At the Midwestern school bookstore, fans bought the 700
available training camp commemorative T-shirts in less than a week.
Another 800 have been ordered.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Penney opened a Cowboys merchandise store in a vacant
auto-repair garage
</P>
<P>
   near the campus and filled it with team logo items ranging from
bait lures to helmet serving bowls to soap dispensers to shower
curtains. Business is brisk.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the objective is, naturally, to make a buck.
Restaurants, bars, Sikes Senter Mall, the hotels and motels all
expect to earn their share of the estimated $3.5 million that is
spent in any city holding Cowboys training camp. Even a bed and
breakfast in Henrietta, 20 minutes away, is offering training-camp
weekend specials complete with tours of the area. But much of the
greeting seems sincere enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Texas way of doing things, to welcome people,''
explains Rick Brown, 38, manager of Jerry's Scoreboard, a local
sporting-goods shop.
</P>
<P>
   Optimistic as Brown is that the Cowboys' visit will help his
city's economy and image, he still fully expects Jones and company
to pull out next year. His mix of hopefulness and self-deprecating
realism seems common.
</P>
<P>
   Residents suggest visitors will be pleasantly surprised by what
they see in Wichita Falls. Yet, they add, it might not be as much
as they would like to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``People know where we are,'' says Meredith Nolan, a 21-year-old
Midwestern student, ``but they don't know what we have, which isn't
much compared to Austin.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents appear equally modest when asked about rubbing the
padded shoulders of Cowboys players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm realistic,'' says 20-year-old Midwestern student Joey
Heenan. ``They probably no more want to talk to me than the man on
the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the jokes about Cowboys players having nothing to do at
night, because there's nothing to do, are met good-naturedly.
</P>
<P>
   Says Gaines, ``If the idea is to return the franchise's image to
the way it was in the days of Tex Schramm, this might be a good
place to start.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald J. Mertens, president and chief executive of the Wichita
Falls Board of Commerce and Industry, says his city is used to
handling big events, pointing to the annual bike race, the Hotter
'N Hell Hundred. The difference, he admits, is that training camp
lasts a month, not a weekend.
</P>
<P>
   If Wichita Falls can pull off its role as host to America's
Team, it will provide the town a big boost, Mertens says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major morale builder,'' he says. ``The community is
given a sense of accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Wichita Falls residents, such as Chris Scheer, owner of
The Plum Thicket, a Sikes Senter store, have somewhat lesser
expectations, the kind you might expect from a nervous girl
awaiting her big night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll just be nice to have something different in town,''
Scheer says. ``Things never really change much here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
