r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-ATTHETURN-     07-11 2528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ATTHETURN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PRETTY FACE' GORDON DRAWS CHALLENGE FROM FRESH FACE OF MAYFIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Same as last summer, Jeff Gordon leads the NASCAR Winston Cup
points chase at the midseason turn.
</P>
<P>
   And this could be a good thing. The second half of the 1997
season produced the tightest three-way finish in Cup history, with
Gordon bagging his second championship in three years by a 14-point
margin over Dale Jarrett and a 29-point advantage over Mark Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen races into 1998, the fresh face of Jeremy Mayfield has
emerged to join Martin, Jarrett and the usual suspects in pursuit
of Gordon. Much like Jeff Burton in 1997, Mayfield is in the midst
of a breakthrough season that has seen him win his first Cup race
and lead the standings for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the way it feels up there,'' said Mayfield, who is 40
points behind Gordon heading into today's Jiffy Lube 300 at New
Hampshire International Speedway. ``A lot of guys told me that once
you get a taste for winning _ once you get a taste for leading the
points _ you'll never be satisfied with second again. I'll tell you
what. I was never satisfied with second to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to win again and to do what we can to get that
points lead back.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield's rise to worthy contender rates as the headline story
of the first half, which reached 16 races June 28 at Sears Point
Raceway in Sonoma, Calif. Seventeen events, including the
rescheduled Pepsi 400 on Oct. 17 at Daytona International Speedway,
remain to decide a championship worth a guaranteed $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon earned his series-leading fifth pole position on the
redesigned road course in Sonoma, and went on to his fourth victory
of 1998, tying him with Martin in that category.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield, meanwhile, became the eighth different and only
first-time winner June 21 at Pocono International Raceway.
Mayfield, 29, has eight top-five and 10 top-10 finishes. That run
has allowed him to upstage Penske-Kranefuss Racing teammate Rusty
Wallace, the 1989 champion who paced the points race for eight
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, driver of the No. 24 DuPont Refinishes Chevrolet Monte
Carlo, tops the series in laps led with 864 of 4,962. But Mayfield
does not have a DNF _ Did Not Finish _ completing an amazing 4,953
of 4,962 laps (99.8 percent). Similar consistency carried Terry
Labonte, Gordon's teammate at Hendrick Motorsports, to his second
Cup title at Gordon's expense in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we have been this year is consistent,'' said
Paul Andrews, crew chief of Mayfield's No. 12 Mobil 1 Ford Taurus.
``The fact that we won Pocono doesn't automatically make us `the
guys to beat' the next week. But we think we've become one of the
guys to beat on a fairly regular basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, whose victories include the Texas 500 at Texas Motor
Speedway in Fort Worth, is third _ 10 points behind Mayfield and 52
in back of Gordon. Jarrett, a two-time winner, also is within
striking distance, 74 points back of Gordon. With 17 races
remaining last year, Jarrett also was fourth _ but 172 points
behind Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Same time last summer, Mayfield stood 10th in points _ 569
behind Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're liking what we're doing right now,'' Mayfield said. ``We
have kept our nose right in the thick of things.'' THE RUMOR MILL
</P>
<P>
   Five items that might come to pass in the second half of the
NASCAR season:
</P>
<P>
   1. The 1999 Winston Cup schedule will expand by only one race,
to 34, with the addition of the reconfigured Miami-Dade Motorsports
Complex in Homestead, Fla. Best guess on a second race at Texas
Motor Speedway in Fort Worth is for the 2000 season, after NASCAR
completes its three-year commitment for non-points events in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   2. High-profile crew chief Larry McReynolds, dumped by Dale
Earnhardt and paired with Mike Skinner, will not return to work for
team-owner Richard Childress in 1999. Skinner, who has only one
top-10 result in 13 starts, could be axed sooner. One scenario has
McReynolds joining Joe Gibbs Racing as Winston Cup rookie Tony
Stewart's crew chief in '99.
</P>
<P>
   3. Jeff Gordon and crew chief/confidant Ray Evernham are
planning to form a team that will run a very limited, five-race
Busch Grand National schedule in 1999. Gordon's wife, Brooke, also
is expected to be a part owner. Gordon would drive, and Evernham,
who has been vocal about not wanting to be a crew chief forever,
will test the waters as team owner.
</P>
<P>
   4. Current Busch Grand National points-leader Matt Kenseth, a
protege of Roush Racing star Mark Martin, will join the Wood
Brothers as teammate to Michael Waltrip in 1999. The deal would be
an extension of the recently announced alliance between Wood
Brothers Racing and Roush Racing, in which the latter is providing
marketing, management and engine manufacturing services to the Wood
organization.
</P>
<P>
   5. Roush Racing could field a six-car Cup stable next year.
Current rookie-of-the-year contender Kevin Lepage has been signed
for a full ride in 1999. The final size of the Ford Taurus team
depends on whether Ted Musgrave is retained for another season.
RUMOR OF ALL RUMORS
</P>
<P>
   The rumor that Dale Earnhardt's storybook victory in the
season-opening Daytona 500 was ``manufactured'' by NASCAR refuses
to go away.
</P>
<P>
   Recall that Earnhardt, the sport's second seven-time champion,
had been 0-for-19 in NASCAR's Super Bowl until his dominating
victory Feb. 15. Conspiracy theorists contend that NASCAR officials
allowed Earnhardt some sort of rules advantage _ most likely a
little larger restrictor plate atop his Chevrolet SB2 engine _ as a
payback for all ``The Intimidator'' has meant to the sport.
Earnhardt's emotional victory also served as a proper kickoff to
NASCAR's 50th anniversary season.
</P>
<P>
   An intriguing theory. But whom among the doubters wants to be
the first to run it past Earnhardt, face to face? WHO'S HOT, WHO'S
NOT
</P>
<P>
   A look back at the headline news makers from the season's first
half: Hot, hot, hot
</P>
<P>
   1. Bruton Smith, Eddie Gossage and the management of Speedway
Motorsports Inc. All deserve kudos for the bold reconstruction of
Texas Motor Speedway. Told by NASCAR president Bill France Jr. on
April 5 to fix the track's water seepage problem or risk losing
their Cup date, Smith had the track torn up, a new drainage system
installed, the banked turns reconfigured and the entire surface
repaved in time for NASCAR Craftsman Truck/Pep Boys Indy Racing
League practice June 4. The track has yet to receive the Papal
Blessing, or Rusty Wallace's. But apparently, SMI got it right this
time.
</P>
<P>
   2. Jeremy Mayfield and crew chief Paul Andrews. Mayfield has
finished 15th or better in 13 of 16 races, and is the only driver
to post a top-25 result in every race in 1998. Andrews, who was
crew chief for dictatorial owner/driver Alan Kulwicki when he won
the Cup championship in 1992, deserves credit for his Ray
Evernham-like influence on young Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   3. Mark Martin and crew chief Jimmy Fennig. Martin has recorded
seven consecutive finishes of seventh or better, including
victories at the California and Michigan speedways. Martin also
goes into the record book as winner of the last Cup race at the
``old'' Texas Motor Speedway. Martin has matched series
points-leader Jeff Gordon in bonus points (75) and victories (four)
and has no DNFs compared to Gordon's two.
</P>
<P>
   4. Jeff Burton and crew chief Frank Stoddard. The latter has
taken some heat after replacing the popular Buddy Parrott as
Burton's chief wrench. But Burton said Stoddard was the team's
``hands-on'' chief last year when Burton won three races and
finished fourth in points for team-owner Jack Roush. A preseason
championship favorite to many, Burton has six top-10 finishes in
the past seven races to climb to eighth in points.
</P>
<P>
   5. Bobby Labonte and crew chief Jimmy Makar. Usually driving the
only Pontiac Grand Prix worth watching, Labonte has five top-10
finishes in the past six races and has improved a spot, to sixth,
from last year. That's stout, considering Joe Gibbs Racing has more
DNFs (3) than victories (2) this season. Not, not, not
</P>
<P>
   1. The Brothers Bodine. Todd Bodine was fired by team owner Bob
Hancher on Wednesday after failing to deliver for new and
big-dollar sponsor Tabasco. Bodine, the 1997 Busch Grand National
points runner-up, qualified for only seven Cup events and had only
one top-10 finish. Meanwhile, big brother Geoff Bodine has finished
23rd or worse in the past six races.
</P>
<P>
   2. Johnny Benson Jr. Has five consecutive finishes of 18th or
worse. In a Ford Taurus. Owned by Jack Roush. Cue up The Who,
because crew chief Steve Hmiel can't explain.
</P>
<P>
   3. Kyle Petty. With 14 finishes of 22nd or worse in 16 races,
Kyle, in the Not-So-Hot Wheels Pontiac, is among seven drivers who
have not scored a bonus point in 1998. Even Robert Pressley has
scored five bonus points.
</P>
<P>
   4. Derrike Cope. Has only one top-15 finish and five DNFs in his
Pontiac. But he lead four laps at Atlanta Motor Speedway, scoring
five bonus points.
</P>
<P>
   5. Kenny Wallace. His six DNFs tie him with fellow Taurus-driver
Geoff Bodine for the lead in that dubious category. RACES TO WATCH
</P>
<P>
   1. Aug. 1, Brickyard 400, Indianapolis Motor Speedway. Talk
about your one-groove racetracks: This is it. But 300,000 fans and
the sound of the V8s reverberating off the ancient grandstands is a
rush. 2. Aug. 9, The Bud at The Glen, Watkins Glen (N.Y.)
International. Have a bad day on the second and last road-course
race of the season, and your championship hopes could turn to junk.
3. Aug. 22, Goody's 500, Bristol (Tenn.) Motor Speedway. Touted as
the toughest ticket in NASCAR, thanks to night racing on the
half-mile oval's 36-degree banked turns. 4. Sept. 6, Southern 500,
Darlington (S.C.) Raceway. What's more traditional than Labor Day
Weekend at NASCAR's oldest superspeedway? Pass the chicken, son. 5.
Oct. 11, Winston 500, Talladega (Ala.) Superspeedway. Break out the
superspeedway shocks and restrictor-plate engines, and hope to
avoid that inevitable ``One Big Wreck.'' 6. Oct. 17, Pepsi 400,
Daytona International Speedway. Rescheduled from July 4, this will
be the first time teams are forced to run back-to-back
restrictor-plate races. May the best driver, and engine shop, win.
7. Nov. 8, NAPA 500, Atlanta Motor Speedway. A championship chase
involving two, three or four drivers will pack them into the
lightning fast 1.54-mile quadoval. THE REAR-VIEW MIRROR FACTS AND
FIGURES FROM THE FIRST HALF: RECAPPING THE SEASON
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon has 13 top-10 qualifying efforts, including five Bud
Poles. Both are tops among all drivers. Gordon has won five poles
in the past seven races.
</P>
<P>
   Ward Burton has five top-10 qualifying efforts in the past seven
races.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt has posted only two top-10 starts in 1998 and has
qualified in the first round (top 25) only five times. But three
have come in the past three races.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Bodine, Steve Grissom and Darrell Waltrip are the only
drivers who have qualified for all 16 races without posting a
top-10 start.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Irwin Jr. has been the top finishing rookie nine times.
Kevin Lepage has topped the rookie class six times and Jerry Nadeau
has done so once.
</P>
<P>
   Ten drivers have led the most laps in a race this season. Mark
Martin (four times), Jeff Gordon (three) and Jeremy Mayfield (two)
are the only drivers to lead the most laps more than once.
</P>
<P>
   After posting only one finish better than 30th in the first
eight races, Darrell Waltrip has finished 20th or better in seven
of the past eight events.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Musgrave and Kyle Petty are the only drivers who have
competed in all 16 races without leading a lap.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett has led at least one lap in 13 of 16 races, most of
all drivers.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no back-to-back victories in the first 16 races.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-eight drivers have led laps in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Mark Martin's total of $1,823,630, eight drivers have
more than $1 million in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The first eight races produced eight different pole winners, a
modern-era record. There have been 10 different pole winners in the
first 16 races. TOP-FIVE PERFORMANCES
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-five of the 80 top-five finishes of 1998 have been scored
by multi-car teams. The breakdown is Roush Racing (19), Penske
Racing (16), Hendrick Motorsports (15), Robert Yates Racing (11),
Richard Childress Racing (two), Team Sabco and Petty Enterprises
(one each) and Elliott Racing (zero).
</P>
<P>
   All five Roush Racing drivers have scored a top-five finish, as
follows: Mark Martin (eight), Jeff Burton (six), Johnny Benson Jr.
(three) and Chad Little and Ted Musgrave (one each).
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon has 10 of the 15 top-five finishes scored by
Hendrick Motorsports.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt has both top fives for Richard Childress Racing.
</P>
<P>
   Of the seven drivers comprising Team Sabco, Elliott Racing and
Petty Enterprises, only Joe Nemechek and John Andretti (one each)
have a top-five result. SUPERSPEEDWAY ACES
</P>
<P>
   Twelve races have been run on superspeedways, tracks measuring
one mile or longer. Jeff Gordon leads all drivers with points
earned on those tracks with 1,788. Jeremy Mayfield is second, three
points behind.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin has nine top-10 finishes in 12 superspeedway starts,
most of any driver. Martin also has earned 70 lap leader/bonus
points on those tracks, most of any driver.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the top-10 drivers in the superspeedway rankings are
involved in a multi-car team arrangement. The exceptions are Bobby
Labonte and Jimmy Spencer. CAR WARS
</P>
<P>
   All three manufacturers have posted at least one victory this
season. Ford and Chevrolet each have seven victories, and Pontiac
has two.
</P>
<P>
   A Ford Taurus has claimed 50 of the 80 top-five finishes. A
Chevrolet Monte Carlo has scored 23 top fives and a Pontiac Grand
Prix has only seven.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has led 2,611 of the 4,962 laps raced. Chevrolet has led
1,971 laps, and Pontiac has paced 380 laps.
</P>
<P>
   The road-course event at Sears Point Raceway marked the first
time in 1998 that two Pontiac drivers _ John Andretti (third) and
Bobby Labonte (fourth) _ finished in the top five. STILL WINLESS
</P>
<P>
   Five drivers who scored victories in 1997 are winless at
midseason: Jeff Burton (three victories last year), Ricky Rudd
(two) and John Andretti, Ernie Irvan and Rusty Wallace (one each).
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen active drivers remain winless during their Winston Cup
careers. The top five in 0-fers are Michael Waltrip (378 races),
Dick Trickle (268), Rick Mast (261), Ted Musgrave (232) and Wally
Dallenbach Jr. (146).
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt ended a 59-race winless streak, the longest of
his career, with his victory in the season-opening Daytona 500. The
driver who has won at least one race now mired in his
career-longest winless streak is Rusty Wallace, who has gone 45
consecutive races without a victory. NUTS AND BOLTS
</P>
<P>
   Terry Labonte leads active drivers with 585 consecutive starts,
a Winston Cup record.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin has been running at the finish in the past 32 races.
</P>
<P>
   Owner/driver Ricky Rudd has won at least one race in each season
from 1983 to 1997, a stretch of 15 consecutive years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
