<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CART-CLEVELAND-ADVANCE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Vasser has financial incentive in Cleveland Grand Prix 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By TERRY BLOUNT &QL; 
Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Starting from the pole is always nice, but winning
the pole for the Medic Drug Grand Prix of Cleveland gives Jimmy
Vasser a financial opportunity no CART driver has ever had.
</P>
<P>
   If Vasser wins today's race on the runways of the Burke
Lakefront Airport, he will claim the official $100,000 purse for
the victory. But he also will add a $265,000 bonus from the
Marlboro Pole Award, making a pole-to-checkered flag-finish worth a
total of $365,000.
</P>
<P>
   It's the largest amount of bonus money in CART history, but
Vasser said it won't be on his mind when the race begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money is great and it would be fantastic to win it, but it
won't change the way I do things in the race,'' said Vasser, who
drives the Target Reynard/Honda. ``I will have the same motivation
and determination I have in every race.''
</P>
<P>
   Vasser's lap of 134.385 mph from Friday's first qualifying
session held up when the drivers took the course again Saturday. At
road courses, CART drivers have qualifying attempts Friday and
Saturday, but it's rare when the speeds Friday hold up for the
Saturday session.
</P>
<P>
   Warmer weather made the speeds slower Saturday, but two drivers
managed to move up near the front. Dario Franchitti turned a lap at
133.868 mph to qualify second. Alex Zanardi, the defending champion
at Cleveland and Vasser's teammate, moved up to third with a speed
of 133.658 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Zanardi, the 1997 CART champion and the current points leader,
won the pole last year at Cleveland, and Vasser won the pole in
1996 on his way to the CART championship. The two men who drive for
Chip Ganassi have dominated the event, but Zanardi teased his
teammate about why Vasser won the pole this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy is still angry with me because I told him Americans are
better at everything except motor sports,'' Zanardi said. ``I think
it fired him up, so he should thank me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really happy for Jimmy. Our cars have been running almost
identical, so the only thing he had better than me must have been
his right foot. But I'm still going to kick his tail tomorrow. I'll
probably get by him on that first turn of the race.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the pole-winner won a CART event was one year ago
when Zanardi won on the Lake Erie shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   Never before has the circuit gone an entire year without a
pole-sitter claiming victory, which is why the Marlboro Pole Award
is at a record total. The previous high for the pole bonus was
$160,000, which was claimed by Al Unser Jr. in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Any driver who wins a race at an event where he won the pole
earns a bonus worth $15,000. But that bonus money rolls over to the
next race if the man on the pole does not win the race, building up
to an ever-increasing amount until someone accomplishes the feat.
</P>
<P>
   As the pole bonus has increased this season, the importance of
qualifying has increased with it. Drivers are working harder and
taking more chances in qualifying runs to try to earn the pole and
get a chance at the money.
</P>
<P>
   Many CART drivers have contracts worth millions of dollars, but
the chance to take home $365,000 is more than all but two drivers
have earned in prize money this season. Zanardi has claimed
$590,000 in purse money and Greg Moore has earned $383,250.
</P>
<P>
   Vasser, 32, has won $359,250 this year, so the Californian can
more than double his 1998 earnings with a victory today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never easy to win a race,'' Vasser said. ``So many things
can factor into the outcome, but the money won't be one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gil de Ferran, who qualified 11th in the Valvoline
Reynard/Honda, thinks Vasser might be trying to hide his true
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wouldn't like to get that kind of money,'' de Ferran said.
``And this is a track where the guy on the pole has a good chance
to win the event. If you're fast, you have a chance to put some
distance on the field when you are out in front.''
</P>
<P>
   Vasser and Zanardi have been in front of the other drivers for
most of the past two months. Zanardi has won three of the past four
CART events, and Vasser won the other, so it's a good possibility
one of the Target cars will be in front at the end today. But only
Vasser has a shot at an extra quarter of a million bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assure you I will give it everything I've got,'' Vasser
said. ``But I'll do it for the points, not for the money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
