</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-TRACK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home venue attracts Adkins
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Another time and place, Derrick Adkins would call in
his regrets. But tender hamstring and all, the Atlanta Olympic
hurdles champion returns home to New York to compete in the
Goodwill Games, which begin next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't here, I probably wouldn't be running,'' said
Adkins, an Atlanta resident and Georgia Tech graduate who grew up
four miles from where the track competition will be contested on
Long Island. ``I'm not in top condition right now. I think I'll be
able to have a good race, but not an Olympic performance or
anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The four days of track competition, kicking off next Sunday with
Adkins in the 400-meter hurdles and Marion Jones headlining the
women's 100 meters, is the marquee sport of the Games, which offers
competition in 14 other sports as well over a two-week period. The
track meet will feature at least nine Atlanta Olympic gold
medalists, including Michael Johnson (400 meters), Dan O'Brien
(decathlon), Gail Devers (100) and Donovan Bailey (100).
</P>
<P>
   To attract top track athletes, the Goodwill Games is putting up
$1.8 million in prize money and a lucrative bonus program.
Officials are promising as much as $100,000 for a world-record
performance and $40,000 to winners in a half-dozen events,
including the men's and women's 100 meters, both 400 meters, the
decathlon and heptathlon.
</P>
<P>
   For Adkins, though, it's just a chance to run on the same
Mitchell Athletic Complex track where he trained as a high school
kid and competed in the Nassau County schoolboy championships.
</P>
<P>
   After an injury-riddled season _ and with U.S. champion Bryan
Bronson and runner-up Angelo Taylor, a Georgia Tech sophomore, in
the field _ Adkins says he'd be content to finish in the top three.
At this point, he's not even sure if he'll run again this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really important for me to run here,'' Adkins said.
``I've been looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Adkins is one of several top athletes who are ailing. Johnson,
star of the Atlanta Games, has dropped out of the 200 because
nagging leg injuries have cut into his training. Chances are he
won't be favored in the 400, having finished third last week at the
Bislett Games in Oslo, Norway.
</P>
<P>
   The status of Atlanta sprinter Gwen Torrence is in doubt.
Because of a severe strain of her left hip flexor and quad muscle,
Torrence has withdrawn from the 100 and 200. If she runs at all, it
will be the 400 meters.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's still not healed, and she's about 90 percent at
practice,'' said Manley Waller, her coach. ``She can't do anything
fast. So she might need to leave the shorter sprints alone for a
year or so. At least the 400 allows her to gradually pick up speed
as she goes.'' Even with Torrence out of the 100, the race figures
to be closely watched with Olympic champion Devers and Jones, who
has ruled the event since joining the circuit last year. The men's
race offers a rematch of the 1997 World Championships, with Maurice
Greene and Bailey again headlining a field that could challenge
Bailey's world record set in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The meet also features O'Brien in his first decathlon since
capturing gold in Atlanta, while the incomparable Jackie
Joyner-Kersee competes in her final heptathlon before retiring
after this season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
