<HEADER>
A0667 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MELVIN-TEX     07-11 1894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MELVIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MELVIN THRIVES BY RELYING ON ATTENTION TO DETAIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Inspiration lies readily available at Doug
Melvin's fingertips in his stately center-field office overlooking
The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   His desk and bookshelves are lined with biographies and how-to
books written by or about some of the great minds of the 20th
century, including Winston Churchill, Pat Riley, Red Auerbach,
George Will and Don Shula.
</P>
<P>
   The Churchill biography, which has been in Melvin's office since
he was hired as Rangers general manager in 1994, could be
particularly useful should he want to give his team a rousing
speech about fighting the American League on the hills, beaches and
in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually I haven't read that one yet,'' Melvin said with a
smile. ``I've been meaning to, but I haven't gotten to it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Will, the Pulitzer Prize-winning political analyst,
Melvin said, ``I've read his baseball books. He sends them to me. I
knew him in Baltimore. But I haven't read his political books;
they're a little hard to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin's vast collection of baseball books are not, and they
don't have the layer of dust that covers Churchill's life story.
``Branch Rickey's Little Blue Book'', a baseball primer written by
a pioneering Hall of Fame executive who built championship teams
for the St. Louis Cardinals and the Brooklyn Dodgers, gets plenty
of use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in there is pretty interesting,'' Melvin said. ``It
just shows you how brilliant he was and how far ahead of his time
he was. I think it's good to know as much about the past of
baseball as you can. I'm a big believer in managing by
storytelling, and baseball is great at that. It helps you sell an
idea a lot more.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I wanted to give Dave Stieb a chance, some people thought
I was nuts because he hadn't pitched in four years. I remember
though when Fernando Valenzuela hadn't pitched in a while in
Baltimore, but we thought he could get people out with his
knowledge of pitching. He won some big ballgames for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting next to Rickey's 50-year-old book are two more recent
books about baseball managers, a biography of Hall of Famer Connie
Mack written in 1950, a biography of Rogers Hornsby and ``Lords of
the Realm'', the definitive history of baseball's labor troubles.
On a coffee table are 40-year-old copies of ``Baseball Digest''.
Stat books, scouting folders and media guides are piled on a
cupboard behind his desk.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin also has access to numerable studies done by his baseball
people, including one about the on-base percentages of all Rangers
minor-leaguers, one about all major-leaguers who have had to repeat
a season in the minors and one
about termination pay owed by every major-league team the past
three years.
</P>
<P>
   The office is a portrait of a baseball junkie but also a person
who, Arizona Diamondbacks vice president Roland Hemond said, ``has
a great feel for the game. He has very good analytical mind, he's
very thorough and he's always well-prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Others confirm that opinion of the man who is currently focused
on trying to arm the Rangers with more starting pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``In dealing with Doug, he has always been very
straightforward,'' Florida Marlins general manager Dave Dombrowski
said. ``He knows what you need and what his desires are and what
are the strengths of each organization. That shows you he's always
well-prepared and organized.''
</P>
<P>
   Any baseball man would learn to be meticulously prepared if his
first job in baseball was working for George Steinbrenner, the most
demanding owner in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin started with the New York Yankees by doing menial tasks
and eventually worked his way to the key position of scouting
director. Melvin knew being unprepared when Steinbrenner calls is
the fastest way to have a budding baseball career come to a
premature end.
</P>
<P>
   ``George kept you on your toes,'' Melvin said. ``If he was
talking about a trade with someone, he would want to know who the
top 10 prospects in the organization were. And he wanted to know
right away. He didn't want you to go look it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers president Tom Schieffer isn't quite as demanding, but
the work habits haven't changed. Under Steinbrenner, Melvin left
for work at dawn and didn't get home until the wee hours of the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   His day usually doesn't end until the last out of the last game
on the West Coast, sometime after midnight. He has a satellite
system at home, which allows him to watch any and all major-league
games. It's probably why he hasn't delved into Churchill yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to read for 30 minutes or so every night after the
family had gone to bed,'' Melvin said. ``Now, I go home after our
game, and the West Coast games are on. Plus they have that Classic
Sports Network. I like watching that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the family gets neglected. Melvin has watched many a
game in the family room while pitching a foam ball to his son,
Cory. While Cory takes batting practice and whacks the ball off the
walls, Melvin keeps an eye on the television for a player who might
eventually help the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin has also consummated two trades while attending family
reunions in Canada and has talked to agents on a cellular phone
while taking Cody and his daughter, Ashley, swimming at a local
water park. He even coached third base for his son's Little League
team, although sources said Melvin's performance suggested he
should not quit his day job.
</P>
<P>
   His children don't need a bat or glove to get their father's
attention. On a recent road trip to Arizona, Melvin and the two
children rose at 4 a.m. to take a one-hour hot-air balloon ride in
the desert. Branch Rickey probably never did that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to see the sun come up, and it was absolutely quiet in
the desert,'' Melvin said. ``We were a mile high, and you could
hear a dog bark on the ground below.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers then went on to San Francisco, allowing Melvin and
his family to spend Friday afternoon touring Alcatraz Island and
the notorious prison. On Saturday night, they took a cable-car ride
then had dinner in Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very family-oriented person,'' Schieffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Road trips also allow Melvin to catch up on some actual
recreational reading. He just finished ``Into the Wild'', a true
account of a boy who leaves his privileged eastern upbringing and
sets out on his own into the Alaskan wilderness. Next on his list
is ``Into Thin Air'' by John Krakauer, the true story of an
ill-fated climb of Mount Everest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do read some,'' Melvin said. ``I've read all of John
Grisham's books. I like mysteries, those kind of books. But I'm a
slow reader. My kids are always getting on me about that. I'll
start a book in spring training, then here it will be the All-Star
break, and they'll say, `You haven't finished that yet?'''
</P>
<P>
   Besides reading and movies, Melvin has few hobbies outside
baseball. His one other passion is basketball. Melvin loves pickup
games but not always for their recreational benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very competitive,'' Ellen Melvin, his wife, said. ``He
called our daughter, Ashley, the other day and said he and
(assistant general manager) Dan O'Brien were going to go play
basketball. She said, `Daddy, don't you know what's going to
happen? You're going to be hurting for three days.' You're going to
be saying, ``Oh my back, oh my knee.'' ' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Melvin has ulterior motives. He said he can tell much about
a person just from the way they play basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell how competitive a person is,'' Melvin said. ``You
watch when they lose. Do they say, `That's enough for today,' or do
they say, `Let's go again?' I like to see their reaction or if they
take all the shots or if they congratulate a teammate after making
a shot. You can learn a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin doesn't come across as competitive. He has an easy-going
air about him, and friends describe him as patient, level-headed
and even-tempered.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really have to push him to get him past his breaking
point,'' Ellen Melvin said. ``He doesn't panic. I do that enough
for everybody. But he's always calm.''
</P>
<P>
   He is also driven. He was a mediocre minor-league pitcher who
never got past Double A. Realizing his limitations, Melvin was
preparing himself for a front-office job in baseball even before
his playing days were finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I recognized I wasn't going to be a major-league pitcher,
I used to watch the other team take infield while my teammates
would go inside,'' Melvin said. ``I would sit there and try to
identify who were the prospects and the players. My manager, Mike
Ferraro, would come up to me and ask, `All right, who is going to
be in the major leagues?' ''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates in the minors called him ``Scoop'' because he
would devour daily newspapers and ``The Sporting News'', analyzing
each transaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would quiz him on the bus,'' said Arizona manager Buck
Showalter, a teammate in the minor leagues. ``We would ask him,
`Were is this player now?' Doug would know. He'd say `New Britain'
right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin did hold a variety of off-season jobs outside baseball.
He worked in a factory machine shop, picked apples, delivered
furniture and was a school janitor, working the graveyard shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked that job,'' Melvin said. ``After I got the rooms
cleaned up, I'd go into the gym and shoot baskets for a couple
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   But he never has considered a career outside baseball, even if
his first job with the Yankees was pure drudgery. He started with
the Yankees in 1979 compiling scouting reports for Yankees manager
Bob Lemon, charting pitches and throwing batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Lemon told me way back then,'' Hemond said. ``He told me,
`Roland, there's a fellow with the Yankees who if you ever get the
chance, you should hire him.' He's got a real good baseball mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemond would find out first-hand. Melvin was already with the
Orioles when Hemond became general manager in 1988. Melvin would
become his assistant. Hemond would become his mentor. Together,
they rebuilt a once-proud franchise that suffered through an
extremely embarrassing 107-loss season in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   When Rangers president Tom Schieffer went looking for a new
general manager after firing Tom Grieve in 1994, he solicited
opinions from a number of people in baseball as to who would be a
strong candidate. Melvin's name was on everybody's list.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the Rangers won their first division
championship, and Melvin was honored as American League executive
of the year in a survey of fellow general managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be successful,'' Melvin said. ``I want to be one of
the best. You have to take pride in it, because this position is
only one of 30 in the game. I don't live in fear of losing my job,
but I realize we better win, and I understand Tom Hicks wants to
win. But I feel my job is to make sure this club is competitive
year after year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it the John Elway Theory. The Denver Broncos were
always competitive year after year, and last year they finally won
it. That's what I'd like to see happen here.''
</P>
<P>
   If it doesn't happen, it won't be because the general manager
was brushing up on the life and times of a certain former British
prime minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
