<SLUG> BC-JAKES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In praise of women: Author, preacher T.D. Jakes rocks Georgia
Dome
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Bishop T.D. Jakes glided across the pulpit like a
dancer, his shirt soaked in sweat, and raised his arms in
exultation as 52,000 screaming women rocked the Georgia Dome on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women!'' Jakes growled, ``thou art loosed!''
</P>
<P>
   Loosed they were. Screams erupted. Women crumpled to the floor
in tears. Some pounded their chairs in relief or turned to give
strangers high-fives. A squad of women bolted toward the stage
where, feet furiously pumping, they did a Holy Dance.
</P>
<P>
   On a sticky Saturday where the mercury topped 90 degrees, Jakes
unleashed some heat of his own. Jakes preached a 90-minute sermon
on the final day of his ``Women, Thou Art Loosed!'' conference that
solidified his standing as one of the country's top preachers.
</P>
<P>
   The sermon's theme _ building a woman's self-esteem _ was simple
but powerful because no other preacher has bothered to zero in on
the angst of Christian women. Jakes, who has already written nine
Christian best sellers, has just released another book for women,
``The Lady, Her Lover and Her Lord'' (G.P. Putnam's Son, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   Jakes demonstrated his ability to connect with women at numerous
times during his sermon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you when real prayer starts,'' Jakes said. ``You start
praying when your rent is past you due, you can't get your kids to
school and you're hoping that Freddy doesn't call you tonight
because you're lonely. That's when you pray.''
</P>
<P>
   And in one particularly touching moment, Jakes called his wife,
Serita, to the stage to profess his admiration for her. As she
rested her head on his chest, Jakes turned toward the women in the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``She made a lot of sacrifices to make me available to you,'' he
said. ``All those nights when I was writing about love I would
rather have been making love.''
</P>
<P>
   The women in the crowd roared their approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I be real?'' Jakes responded as they roared even louder.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes' ability to be real is part of his popularity. His
television show, ``Get Ready with T.D. Jakes,'' airs three times a
week on Black Entertainment Television and the Trinity Broadcasting
Network. His church in Dallas, The Potter's House, has gained
14,000 members in the past 18 months. Even celebrities such as NFL
star Deion Sanders have professed their admiration for Jakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's real, He doesn't polish anything,'' said Christine Ward,
58, who traveled from Savannah to hear Jakes. ``He takes the Word
and makes it vibrant.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward said she first heard about Jakes from her daughter _ who
called from Egypt where she had seen a broadcast of one of Jakes'
sermons.
</P>
<P>
   As she read Jakes' books, Ward said she was struck by Jakes'
humble beginnings. He grew up poor in a small West Virginia town
and struggled to cope with the early death of his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of preachers are puffed up,'' Ward said. ``But men like
T.D. Jakes, you can reach them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jakes' humility is what also brought Leisha McDaniel to the
Georgia Dome on Saturday. McDaniel, 33, said she was moved by
Jakes' struggle to lose weight (he recently lost 100 pounds).
``He's human,'' McDaniel said. ``He worries about things everybody
else worries about.''
</P>
<P>
   He is human, but Jakes is also something else _ a preacher on
the rise, said Noel Erskine, a associate professor of theology at
Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jakes is an icon,'' Erskine said. ``Jakes is like the new
Martin Luther King. He sets the tone. All the preachers, black and
white, are trying to preach like him now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
