<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUDOLPH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bombings suspect leaves agents still on the hunt
 &HT;    By Kathy Scruggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The team of federal agents still searching western
North Carolina for Eric Robert Rudolph has been there long enough
to watch the seasons change and encounter a new set of obstacles:
With freezing temperatures long gone, summer foliage makes mountain
forests even denser.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Southeast Bomb Task Force still believe Rudolph,
wanted in the Jan. 29 bom-- ing of a Birmingham abortion clinic, is
in western North Carolina. That conviction is based in part, they
say, on reports that Rudolph told people that if trouble ever came,
he would hide among the familiar shadows, crags and cliffs of the
Blue Ridge, where he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph, 32, hasn't been seen beyond the foothills since Jan.
30, federal agents said.
</P>
<P>
   But ``there have been numerous reports of sightings in western
North Carolina, none of which resulted in apprehension,'' said Jack
Killorin, head of the Atlanta office of the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms. ``Some can be eliminated _ that it was not
him. In other cases, we don't know whether it was him or not. The
people who were calling in believed they saw him.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Elvis, Rudolph has been reported spotted in cars, in
stores, and crossing the road, only to disappear into mountain
meadows. Unlike Elvis, Rudolph is believed to be alive and well,
and information leading to his capture is worth $1 million in
federal rewards. Agents want witnesses to especially look for the
scar that crosses Rudolph's chin. The number to call is
1-888-ATF-BOMB. In Atlanta and Birmingham, agents with the ATF,
FBI, GBI and Birmingham Police Department continue gathering
evidence in bombings at Centennial Olympic Park in July 1996, a
Sandy Springs abortion clinic in January 1997, an Atlanta gay
nightclub in February 1997 and at the Birmingham abortion clinic,
which killed an off-duty police officer and maimed a nurse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is that the investigation is all one
investigation,''said Woody Enderson, the FBI inspector in charge of
the bomb task force. ``And that's true from both the substantive
standpoint in trying to develop evidence and from a fugitive
standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph has not been charged in the Atlanta bombings and neither
Killorin -- or Enderson would say if they have been able to place
Rudolph in metro Atlanta during the time of the bombings here.
</P>
<P>
   Enderson said agents have studied a possible courtroom
presentation in the Birmingham case that could include thousands of
pieces of evidence and hundreds of witnesses. ``We want to be ready
when he's arrested to move as quickly as the prosecutors want to
move,'' Enderson said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has brought in Terry Turchie to command the North
Carolina search. Turchie helped direct the search for the Unabomber
from the bureau's San Francisco office and has a background in
counterterrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a person who is a team builder,'' said his former FBI
boss, Jim Freeman, who is retired. ``He's someone who can have the
respect of the agents with the FBI and other agencies. It's one of
the hardest things to do _ work in multijurisdictional
situations.'' About 35 agents have made Murphy, N.C., and Andrews,
N.C., second homes. They lease an office in Andrews, they rent
apartments, attend church and are invited to cookouts at the homes
of locals, agents say.
</P>
<P>
   And they are chipping away at the distrust of local residents
with this message: They are not looking for moonshiners, poachers
or marijuana growers. They are not the advance team for the New
World Order.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have given one consistent message to the people in the
area, and that is we're here for one reason and one reason only _
to find Eric Rudolph,'' Turchie said. ``When we finish our job, we
will leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
