<HEADER>
A0677 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWDEMS-COX     07-11 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWDEMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South searching for `New Democrats'
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- After a disastrous year recruiting Southern
Democrats to run for Congress, especially in Georgia, the
Democratic Party is looking to a handful of ``New Democrats'' from
North Carolina to Texas to lead the party back from near extinction
in the South.
</P>
<P>
   No one is predicting that Southern Democrats will regain the
ground lost in 1994 when Democratic incumbents dropped like weekend
joggers in the Peachtree Road Race. Rather, the party is looking
for ``symbolic'' victories in a few House races and an upset or two
in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was in Atlanta Thursday to drum up some
campaign cash for Democratic Senate hopeful Michael Coles, a
self-made millionaire hoping to topple Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.)
and one of the South's new crop of Democratic challengers.
</P>
<P>
   As a general rule these so-called New Democrats are more likely
to be business people than lawyers; less likely to rely on labor
union support; and arguably more conservative than even Clinton on
a handful of social issues such as abortion, sex education and gun
control.
</P>
<P>
   They embrace Clinton's call to devote budget surpluses to the
Social Security trust fund and praise the president's handling of
the economy. But they also are trying to cultivate independence
from Clinton, who coined the term New Democrat when he chaired the
Democratic Leadership Council (DLC) in 1991 and prepared to run for
president as a conservative Southerner from Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats are much freer to run truer to their own beliefs and
closer to their districts and not feel as though they have to mold
themselves to any particular ideology, which traditionally has been
a little bit out of touch with where Southern Democrats really
were,'' says Simon Rosenberg, director of the New Democrat Network,
a political action committee planning to distribute $1 million to
new Democratic candidates this year. ``It's the end of the old
liberal Democrat orthodoxy.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain of the team
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton passed through the Cincinnati airport recently,
Democratic House candidate Ken Lucas of Boone County, Ky., went to
the airport to tell the president he shouldn't have vetoed
legislation banning late-term abortions and urged him to spend some
time with Kentucky tobacco farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm for Clinton when I think he's right and I'm against him
when I think he's wrong,'' says Lucas, judge-executive of Boone
County, the equivalent of county commission chairman.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the 64-year-old Lucas could be the captain of the
Southern New Democrat team. Campaigning to fill the seat being
vacated by Rep. Jim Bunning (R-Ky.), who is running for Senate,
Lucas is a financial planner with longstanding ties to the northern
Kentucky business community. He was both chairman of the local
chamber of commerce and a member of the state chamber of commerce
board, positions that have helped him reel in checks from such
traditional GOP sources as the associations representing home
builders, bankers and wholesale distributors.
</P>
<P>
   He is anti-abortion, defends the right to bear arms and supports
term limits, pledging to serve only three terms himself if elected.
His opponent, Kentucky state Rep. Gex ``Jay'' Williams, is the
favorite of religious conservatives and is being advised by former
Christian Coalition director Ralph Reed of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could be comfortable in our party,'' said Rep. John Linder
(R-Ga.), chairman of the National Republican Congressional
Committee. ``I don't think he'll win, but if he did he could switch
because he stands for pro-life and pro-gun and his stands on a
balanced budget may make him very uncomfortable with a party that
doesn't agree with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Blanche Lambert Lincoln, the Democratic nominee for Senate in
Arkansas, also is pushing her conservative ties with voters.
Lincoln, a former member of Congress from Arkansas, was a so-called
Blue Dog Democrat in the House, a group of fiscally conservative
Democrats who championed a balanced budget.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln reminds voters that she opposed the Brady Bill mandating
waiting periods to buy handguns, and boasts that she is a frequent
duck hunter. She also supports voluntary prayer in school.
</P>
<P>
   In the June 9 Arkansas primary runoff, Lincoln triumphed over a
Democratic opponent who had the endorsement of the AFL-CIO, the
nation's umbrella labor organization.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman (D-Conn.), chairman of the DLC and a
Democratic moderate, says the party has been forced to accept more
conservative candidates _ particularly in the South _ out of
political necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about electing people,'' Lieberman says. ``Being
in a minority will tend to make you more tolerant.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the year Georgia's congressional delegation went from
majority Democrat to majority Republican, exit polls in the South
showed that Democrats were supported by only 20 percent of voters
who described themselves as conservatives, according to Rosenberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll never win a majority of those folks, but if we are down
in the 20s we are going to be the minority party in the South for a
long time,'' Rosenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to turn the tide
</P>
<P>
   Probably no Southern Democrat has been more aggressive in trying
to reverse that trend than Joe Turnham, a self-described
evangelical Christian who until recently was executive director of
the Alabama Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Under his leadership, the state party hired a director of faith
outreach, published faith-and-values voter guides and adopted a
plank in the state party platform on ``Judeo-Christian values.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Turnham is running to unseat Rep. Bob Riley (R-Ala.) in a
district around Auburn, Ala., that had always been represented by a
Democrat until Riley won it in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll either discuss issues or do Bible sword drills; I'm
prepared to do either one,'' says Turnham. ``We'll talk about
prayer, the Ten Commandments or what to do with the long-term
funding of entitlements. I'm willing to do it, want to do it, can
do it. And I'll talk Auburn-Alabama football or hunting or adult
literacy rates. I think that's what a New Democrat is.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's Coles, who lost to House Speaker Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.)
in 1996, is a little more difficult to pigeonhole. As the founder
of the Great American Cookie Co. and a man worth upward of $50
million, Coles has the business credentials that put him in a
league with Republican gubernatorial candidate Guy Millner, founder
of Norrell Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Coles says he favors low taxes and small government. But he is
also championing a $1 per hour increase to the minimum wage, one of
the top issues of organized labor. To date, Coles has received more
than $85,000 in campaign contributions from labor unions, or 12
percent of the money he has raised (excluding personal loans to
himself of $500,000).
</P>
<P>
   Coles favors engagement with China, but opposes giving the
president fast track trade authority _ one of the top issues for
most so-called New Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen firsthand factories close,'' Coles says. ``I've
seen real people lose their jobs. We have to have free trade, but
we've got to have fair trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
