<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-DAFOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NOW, DAFOE IS SAVING HIS STRENGTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you have to be on the mend, there are worse places in which
to heal than Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins goalie Byron Dafoe underwent surgery on his left shoulder
June 18 in Los Angeles and has been rehabilitating near his home in
Manhattan Beach. A Los Angeles King doctor, Ronald Kvitne,
performed the operation _ a bankart repair _ at Kerlan-Jobe
Hospital, which is well known for repairing the injured shoulders
of major league pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe injured the joint in his catching glove arm late in the
season, but he played through the pain. Trainer Don Del Negro said
Dafoe never complained much and used ice packs to deal with the
soreness. As the playoffs approach, players seldom talk about
injuries; they're worried about giving an opponent any edge. Dafoe,
who helped lead the Bruins into the postseason, didn't want to miss
playing time with what he thought was a minor injury.
</P>
<P>
   A month after the season, Dafoe realized things weren't
improving, so he had the surgery to stabilize the shoulder and
prevent it from slipping out of the socket. Ironically, it's the
same procedure that ended Bruins goalie Jim Carey's season. Part of
the reason the Bruins retained Carey was their concern over Dafoe.
It takes 12-16 weeks for a complete recovery, and Dafoe said he's
hopeful he can be ready for training camp. He plans to begin
skating in August, as he always has.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surgery went really well,'' said Dafoe. ``It was the same
doctor who did my knee surgery last year. I was under about four
hours. I had a needle (for the pain) in my neck for about 12 hours
after I woke up. Then I was in a sling for several days.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe started his rehab with stretching exercises, which he said
were excruciating. Last week, he used weights for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm over the hump now,'' he said, ``I'm able to do more and
more.''
</P>
<P>
   He will be best man for the wedding of Washington goaltender
Olaf Kolzig in Arizona, and next month he and his fiancee, Kim,
will visit family and friends in Vancouver. There's only one thing
Dafoe really wants to do that he can't right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just waiting to play volleyball on the beach,'' he said.
``It's hard watching everyone else and not being able to play.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Stop the insanity. The Dallas Stars opened the financial
floodgates for  &UR; Brett Hull  &LR; just over a week ago as the Blackhawks
were doing the same for  &UR; Doug Gilmour &LR; . Now comes word that
defenseman  &UR; Uwe Krupp  &LR; has signed a four-year deal with the Red
Wings that will pay him an average of $4.1 million a season. If
Krupp is worth that much, what must  &UR; Ray Bourque  &LR; be worth?
Unbelievable. Especially when you see  &UR; Steve Duchesne  &LR; sign with
Los Angeles for $3.75 million. The Flyers signed goalie  &UR; John
Vanbiesbrouck  &LR; to a two-year $7.25 million contract. A third year
is possible, too, for $3 million if the club picks up the option.
If the Flyers don't, Vanbiesbrouck still walks away with $1.25
million ... A possible deal that would have sent goalie  &UR; Felix
Potvin  &LR; from Toronto to Edmonton apparently has fallen through.
Reportedly, the Maple Leafs wanted to dump Potvin's $2.7 million
salary (US funds) and use that money (and much more) to sign
free-agent goalie  &UR; Curtis Joseph &LR; . The Oilers reportedly were going
to give up  &UR; Boris Mironov  &LR; and  &UR; Boyd Devereaux  &LR; to the Leafs in
exchange for Potvin. The reason for the death of the deal is said
to be that Oilers general manager  &UR; Glen Sather  &LR; didn't want to be
the one to help the Leafs get Joseph, who walked away from the
Oilers at the end of the season. Toronto associate GM  &UR; Mike Smith
 &LR; said there are no other takers in the league for Potvin. ``I'm
tired of the Felix Potvin fiasco,'' said Smith. ``He's one of the
best goalies in the league and yet we have received nothing but
poor offers from other teams. It's an embarrassment to us. We now
have no intention of trading him. He will be our goaltender next
year.'' ... Speaking of Krupp, his family pronounces his first name
like ``Oo-vay,'' though his name in hockey circles has been
pronounced ``Oo-we.'' Seems that the change in pronunciation came
courtesy of Wings coach  &UR; Scotty Bowman  &LR; who signed Krupp to his
first contract in Buffalo in 1986. ``He handed me this paper and
said, `Sign this, Oo-we,' '' said Krupp. ``How was I going to argue
with Scotty Bowman?'' ... The Sabres signed former University of
Massachusetts-Lowell goalie  &UR; Dwayne Roloson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was a free
agent, to back up  &UR; Dominik Hasek &LR; . The 28-year-old last year played
39 games for Calgary, earning an 11-16-8 record, a 2.99 goals
against average and .890 save percentage ... Speaking of
netminders, it will be interesting to see how things shake out in
Tampa when training camp opens.  &UR; Daren Puppa &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has been
plagued by back problems, was limited to six games in 1996-97 and
26 this past season. ``I'm in better shape now than I've ever been
in,'' said Puppa, 33. ``They need some talent. We need some
centers. We still need to get some guys who can put the puck in the
net.'' ... Look for Bowman to be back behind the bench as the Red
Wings defend their second consecutive Stanley Cup championship.
Bowman recently had a thorough health exam and the veteran coach,
who turns 65 in September, said he'll find out the results this
week. ``They let me out, so I guess that's a good sign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Doug MacLean &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was fired as coach of the Florida Panthers
last fall, is loving life as president/GM of the Columbus Blue
Jackets, who will begin play in 2000-01. ``I definitely don't ever
want to coach again,'' the 44-year-old MacLean told reporters. ``I
want to build an organization. This is too big an opportunity.''
MacLean has plenty of time to put together his staff, which he'll
do about a year from now. He said he'll hire a coach in the next
year ... Devils GM  &UR; Lou Lamoriello  &LR; reportedly has ordered all of
his players to wear gloves with cuffs that extend six inches beyond
the wrist. What prompted him to take that step was an accident that
resulted in  &UR; Jason Arnott  &LR; being cut by  &UR; Randy McKay &LR; 's skate as
McKay climbed over the boards in a playoff game. Arnott is still
being treated for nerve damage ... Even though Phoenix GM  &UR; Bobby
Smith  &LR; pulled the team's latest offer to  &UR; Keith Tkachuk  &LR; off the
table and suspended talks on a restructuring of the player's
contract, Tkachuk is saying he believes everything is going to be
fine. ``I'm not worried or frustrated about it at all,'' Tkachuk
told reporters. ``I still believe it will get done in time. My
prediction is that I'm going to sign with the Phoenix Coyotes and
be there for a very long time.'' Reportedly, Tkachuk is seeking an
average of $8 million a year and has already rejected the club's
offer of an average of $6.5 million a year. He has indicated he
would sit out until he gets what he wants despite having two years
remaining on his current pact. ``Obviously, it wouldn't be smart
for the player or for the team, I know that,'' Tkachuk said. ``It
doesn't make any sense, so let's get a deal done. There's still
plenty of time left.'' Tkachuk said he realizes he is probably
taking a public relations hit with his firm stand. ``But people are
hearing only one side of the coin,'' said the Coyotes' captain. ``I
know I'm getting portrayed as a bad guy, but I know I'm not. People
don't know what's going on in the marketplace. They don't
understand what's gone on behind the scenes. The only people who
really know are Bobby Smith, myself, (owner)  &UR; Richard Burke  &LR; and my
agent ( &UR; Bob Murray &LR; ).'' ... Hard to believe that  &UR; Alan Eagleson  &LR; is
already out of jail. He served just six months of an 18-month
sentence for fraud. It's hard to determine which was the bigger
fraud, the sentence or Eagleson himself ... The unbalanced schedule
came out last week, and it didn't take long for some teams to cry
foul. The Senators have expressed dismay at the way their schedule
is structured. ``No hockey team is ever happy with the schedule _
ever,'' said Vancouver GM  &UR; Brian Burke &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who swapped his league
duties at the end of the playoffs for a job with the Canucks. ``But
overall (the Canucks' schedule) is a schedule we can live with.
We've got a couple of tight spots. It's unfortunate we don't get
Gretzky; we'll get him the next year. But I wouldn't be surprised
at all if in the future we get a conference-only schedule. I know
some owners are pushing for that already.'' Gee, maybe even more
trips to Buffalo in the dead of winter someday soon? Sign me up.
</P>
</TEXT>
