<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-NOTES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Students compete for medal, scholarship in contest
 &HT;    By Raven Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The spotlight was missing but the corridor of the
Georgia World Congress Center was DeShay Carter's stage.
</P>
<P>
   Awaiting her turn to perform for the judges in the 20th annual
NAACP ACT-SO competition, DeShay, 15, reviewed the motions of her
dance routine for what seems like the hundredth time.
</P>
<P>
   ACT-SO (Afro-academic Cultural Technologial Scientific Olympics)
features 850 high school students sponsored by local NAACP branches
from across the country, and is one of the first events on the
schedule for the 89th annual NAACP convention. Saturday kicked off
two days of competition in academics and the arts. The awards
ceremony is Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As DeShay gestured and swayed, her grandmother Angela Harper
offered tips along the way. The pair had a long wait ahead of them.
DeShay had number 77; the judges were watching participant number
30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the gold medal,'' said DeShay, a high school junior
from Pittsburgh. She said she is trained in various dance forms and
has been taking lessons for five years. ``I have a lot of
expectations for the weekend. I hope it will increase my
self-confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   DeShay was not the only participant having an impromptu
rehearsal. The strains of singer Desree could be heard through the
hall while another performer perfected her routine. Many
participants were in costume and could be found stretching and
twirling _ any last-minute preparation that might help them capture
the coveted gold medal and scholarship prize.
</P>
<P>
   Free day offerings
</P>
<P>
   With no workshops scheduled to start until Monday, NAACP
delegates were free to do as they pleased on Saturday, the first
day of the civil rights group's annual convention. Delegates could
take a picture with Kweisi Mfume, NAACP president, or visit the
vendors fair at the GWCC, where the smell of collard greens hit
delegates at the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Glory Foods, one of 150 vendors, hawked samples of greens,
macaroni and cheese and chicken and dumplings. L'Eggs products
hosted a drawing for a year's supply of pantyhose.
</P>
<P>
   Denny's Restaurants offered root beer floats.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates could even test their strength on an eight-foot
``chin-up'' exercise bar provided by the U.S. Marines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen some people do 20 today,'' said Capt. Corey Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
