</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIK-TOURDEFRANCE-IRELAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IRISH TOUR DE FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ The last time somebody hightailed it out of here for
Paris, James Joyce had gone into exile and was well on his way to
becoming immortal.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, on the first leg of a three-week journey to Paris, 189
riders dashed through the narrow streets of this city that Joyce
described in such exhausting detail that if it ever burned down,
they could rebuild it by using the pages of ``Ulysses'' as a
blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday was just the prologue, a short sprint to establish
a leader for the exhausting Tour de France. The first stage of the
world's biggest bicycle race begins Sunday, setting off for the
first time from Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason that the world's third biggest sporting event is
beginning in Ireland is because the biggest one, the World Cup
final, is taking place in France. Given their druthers, the Irish
would prefer to host the World Cup, but the country simply doesn't
have the facilities. But it does have the enthusiasm and the
requisite punishing hills to host the prologue and first two stages
of the Tour, which will conclude Aug. 2 on the Champs Elysee.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is thrilled the Tour has arrived. This is a small
country, and getting around it this time of year, with its narrow
roads and bed &AMP; breakfast joints chockful of tourists, is hard
enough. Saturday's time trial shut down a city that has in recent
years developed a traffic problem to rival Boston's. Downtown
retailers estimate they lost about $7 million in business. The
first and second stages Sunday and Monday will shut down almost
half of the eastern seaboard at the height of the tourist season.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of grumbling. But most people seem proud to host
the race. Easing the pain are estimates that the Tour and its
entourage _ 2,000 journalists, 1,500 race officials, and untold
thousands of fans _ will pump about $40 million into the Irish
economy. This after a government investment of just about $3
million to get the Tour here.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the Tour is as much a rolling celebration as it is a
bicycle race, leaving festivals and parties in its wake. The Irish
hardly need an excuse for a celebration, and can rival the French
in stamina and joie de vivre.
</P>
<P>
   In its 85 editions, this is only the seventh time the Tour has
started somewhere other than France. Because the World Cup final in
Paris coincided with Sunday's launch of the Tour, the race
director, Jean-Marie Leblanc, thought it was a good time to take it
abroad again.
</P>
<P>
   After a successful start in Britain in 1994, Ireland was a
logical choice, especially given Ireland's connections to the Tour.
In 1963, Shay Elliott, Ireland's first professional cyclist, became
the first English-speaking rider to wear the yellow jersey that
signifies the Tour leader. When Leblanc was a teenager, he got
Elliott's autograph in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Leblanc points to the more recent contributions of the greatest
Irish cyclists of the last generation. Sean Kelly, a Tipperary man,
rode in 14 Tours, a feat bettered by only two other riders in the
Tour's history. Kelly never won the Tour, but in 1987, Stephen
Roche became the first and only Irishman to win the race. About a
third of the 3.5 million people who live in the Irish Republic
turned out to welcome Roche when he returned home from Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Pat McQuaid, an Irishman and former Tour rider who is credited
with getting Leblanc and the rest of the Tour organizers to go for
the idea to come here, said, ``it wouldn't have happened without
Sean and Stephen.''
</P>
<P>
   But, much to the disappointment of this cycling-mad country,
this is one of the few years in the last two decades in which there
will be no Irish rider in the field. Among the favorites are last
year's winner, Jan Ullrich of Germany, Bjaarne Riis of Denmark,
Marco Pantani of Italy, and Abraham Olano of Spain. The French, who
haven't won their own race since 1985, will be pinning their hopes
on Richard Virenque, who finished second and third in the last two
years.
</P>
<P>
   McQuaid is responsible for the mind-boggling logistics of
bringing the Tour entourage here then getting them on a ferry for
France. He has traveled to every town and village through which the
Tour will pass, getting local communities to sign on and get in the
spirit. He said it hasn't been hard.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the roads fixed, however, is considered a minor miracle,
even in this land renowned for its saints. Local authorities have
spent $9 million _ or three times as much as the national
government kicked in _ to upgrade Ireland's notoriously bad roads.
It will be the Tour's most lasting contribution to Irish society.
</P>
<P>
   The prologue course, which began at Trinity College and ends in
the heart of O'Connell Street, Dublin's main thoroughfare, was
chosen to show off some of city's most impressive Georgian
architecture. Sunday's first stage heads through the dramatic
Wicklow mountains. Monday's stage will finish in Cork, mainly
because that was the shortest route by ferry to France.
</P>
<P>
   The routes have been mapped out not only to challenge riders
with Ireland's rolling hills, but to honor the country's three
greatest cyclists. The first stage starts in Dundrum, Roche's home
village. Monday, the racers will pass through Elliott's hometown of
Bray, and his grave at Kilmacanogue in Wicklow. Monday's stage also
passes through Carrick-on-Suir, Kelly's hometown.
</P>
<P>
   As in France, the biggest bicycle race in the world will pass
through some of the smallest villages in Europe. Monday's second
stage will pass through Glenmore, population 68, which is a
metropolis compared with Meyrignac l'Eglise, population 50, the
village in central France where the seventh stage will begin.
</P>
<P>
   Some villages, including Glenmore, are spending as much as
$75,000 to put on festivals to draw crowds that will stay on long
after the cyclists race past in a blur. In any given town or
village this weekend, you can see some of the best traditional
music acts, from De Dannan to the Clancy Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of organization and viewing audience, the Tour is the
third largest sporting event in the world, behind the World Cup and
the Olympics. With an estimated television audience of 900 million
viewers in 163 countries, the Tour will have more people getting a
look at Ireland than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   William Power, who owns the Tinakilly Country House Hotel, a
charming hostelry in Rathnew, a village in County Wicklow where the
race will pass, said the Tour will do more to expose Ireland to the
world more than anything previously, including the writings of
Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   ``This race will benefit every single person in the country,''
he said. Not everyone is as enthusiastic. Besides the
inconvenience, some can't understand the agonizing routes, and why
so many people follow it so rabidly. Tom Humphries, the acerbic
Irish Times sports columnist who brings to cycling the same
enthusiasm Dan Shaughnessy does to soccer, says ``only the French
could have come up with something as impractical.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there anything less practical, more grand, any crazier in
the wide world of sport?'' he asks. ``Is there anything built to a
scale less comprehensible to the ordinary human?''
</P>
<P>
   But Joe Brady is more typical of the Irish who are excited about
the Tour. An insurance broker from Dun Laoghaire, a Dublin suburb,
Brady gave up running because of his creaky knees and is one of
myriad middle-aged Irishmen who keep in shape by cycling. They are
everywhere here, daredevils riding on country roads and the
shoulders of major highways.
</P>
<P>
   Brady will take his two young sons to ``watch a little history''
Sunday, just a few miles from his home.
</P>
<P>
   And, he notes, they'll be back home in plenty of time to watch
Brazil vs. France.
</P>
<P>
   ``A perfect day,'' said Joe Brady.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
