<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0685 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-DRAFT-BO     07-11 2325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-DRAFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAFT-PICKING CAN BE RISKY BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The great thing about football is that one expert's opinion is
usually rebuffed by another expert.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks ago, Joel Buchsbaum's Pro Football Weekly named
the 10 riskiest picks in the draft. The list was based on an
anonymous polling of NFL scouts. A few of the Patriots' selections
were mentioned prominently. In fact, the publication selected
Syracuse defensive back Tebucky Jones as the riskiest pick of them
all. Even the Patriots admit that Jones was a ``risky'' pick, but
they absolutely covet him as a player.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots vice president of player personnel Bobby Grier wouldn't
respond then and he won't respond now. The opposing view comes from
ESPN draft guru Mel Kiper Jr., recognized as one of the nation's
top draft experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tebucky Jones isn't a risky pick at all,'' said Kiper, who
claims he hasn't seen Buchsbaum's poll. ``In fact, it may be the
least riskiest. At least he has a safety net in that if he doesn't
make it as a corner he can be moved to the inside. He's a big guy
who could be the next Jason Sehorn. If that doesn't work out, the
kid can play safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiper also likes the Jones pick because it was made by coach
Pete Carroll, whose area of expertise is defensive backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every coach has their own area of expertise, and sometimes
they see things in a player at that position they feel is really
special,'' Kiper said. ``Tebucky Jones is a heck of an athlete.
He's going to play somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiper's comments support what Grier said just a few weeks ago:
If you ask 30 different people, you may get 30 different answers.
Grier said he didn't give a damn what anybody thought.
</P>
<P>
   The Pro Football Weekly poll created some panic in the eyes of
some Patriots fans, especially considering the team passed on North
Carolina defensive tackle Vonnie Holliday to take Jones.
</P>
<P>
   While Kiper stamped his approval on Jones, he didn't completely
validate the rest of the team's draft. He recently graded out all
teams and gave the Patriots a C-plus. That's at least better than
the C-minus he gave them last season when he thought the team could
have done better than Chris Canty, Brandon Mitchell, Sedrick Shaw,
and Chris Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Kiper wonders why the Patriots passed up the chance to solidify
their defensive line with a big guy in the middle in addition to
selecting Jones, who gives them the aggressive player Carroll wants
in his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest guy they have on their line is Ferric Collons,''
noted Kiper. ``They could have taken Holliday and Jones and then
taken a chance with a running back later on.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Kiper doesn't dispute Pro Football Weekly's poll
regarding running back Robert Edwards, who was ranked the third
riskiest player; second-rounder Tony Simmons, a receiver from
Wisconsin (sixth riskiest), and Alabama tight end Rod Rutledge
(eighth).
</P>
<P>
   On Edwards: ``He's a kid who has durability questions attached
to him,'' said Kiper. ``We've seen in this league that you can pick
up a decent running back later in the draft. Twenty of the starting
30 running backs in the league were taken after the second round.''
</P>
<P>
   On Simmons: ``He comes from an offense that wasn't a pro style,
therefore his route running and knowledge of the position isn't as
good as it should be for a second-rounder. He's got a lot to learn.
He's probably not a guy who's going to be able to step right in,
but one who needs to learn with a year or two under his belt.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiper sees Rutledge more as a fourth-rounder than a
second-rounder. He said tight ends picked this high should be able
to help the team as a ``pass receiver as well as with their
blocking.'' Rutledge appears more of a blocker right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an injury question with Rutledge and he doesn't have
great speed,'' said Kiper. ``I wouldn't say he's risky, but he's a
reach in the second round. He has good hands and maybe that part of
his game develops, but for a guy who's limited like he is, he
projects more as a fourth-rounder.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiper thinks third-rounder Chris Floyd from Michigan was an
acceptable pick, but he joins the chorus on the team's second
third-rounder, Greg Spires, because of his size (6 feet 1 inches,
273 pounds).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the big physical prototype end that everyone is
looking for,'' said Kiper. ``You don't see many guys in his size
range make it in the NFL. But what you might get is situations
where he can beat some offensive linemen because he's a little
quicker and because those linemen don't see too many guys Spires's
size.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiper thinks University of Houston defensive tackle Leonta
Rheams is a ``developmental'' player in the fourth round. He said
fifth-round linebacker Ron Merkerson of Colorado would have
projected as a third-rounder because of his quickness if not for
some injury questions. He said both Southern Mississippi running
back Harold Shaw and seventh-rounder Jason Andersen, an offensive
lineman from Brigham Young, were taken where they were projected.
</P>
<P>
   Conclusion?
</P>
<P>
   None, really. Just someone else's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   It would be maddening if, for example, Miami got better
production from running back John Avery, taken with the 29th pick
of the first round, than the Patriots did with Edwards (No. 18), or
if Washington got better value with Skip Hicks in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   Then the skeptics and second-guessers could have a field day.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise the ``what if'' stuff is jibberish, good fodder for
talk shows and football columns, but not very meaningful. Until the
players are in pads, it's nearly impossible for even coaches to
know how good they are.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots did take risks, no doubt. But risky picks aren't
always bad picks. The Patriots wanted to improve their athleticism,
their overall team speed, and add players who can help now and in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they did that. Maybe they didn't. The experts are split.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Canty and Shaw are two among the sophomore class who are staying
away from the media, feeling they were singled out for their lack
of contributions to last year's team. Shaw did do a Patriots
Football Weekly interview in which he said he thought the media was
unfair. They are using the ``me vs. them'' mentality to get
themselves psyched for the '98 season. Fellas, as one former
Patriots coach would say, that stuff doesn't work ... Carroll
thinks Canty is in better shape than he was last year as a rookie.
The cornerback was one of the more loyal participants of  &UR; Johnny
Parker's  &LR; strength and conditioning program, and the coaching staff
took note of his work in the minicamps. Shaw was also faithful to
the program and is stronger and bigger than last year. Running
backs coach  &UR; Kirby Wilson  &LR; said Shaw made big strides throughout
the year in practice, after a less-than-stellar exhibition season
... In one of the minor issues in camp, it'll be interesting to see
how much of a shot  &UR; Mark Gagliano  &LR; gets to become the team's
kickoff man if  &UR; Adam Vinatieri's  &LR; kickoffs don't improve. Gagliano
is the nephew of former Red Sox and Cardinals infielder  &UR; Phil
Gagliano  &LR; and showed some good leg strength on punts during the
minicamps ... One Patriots official said about Northeastern
quarterback  &UR; Jim Murphy &LR; , &UR;  &LR; ``He's a kid you'd want to go to war
with.'' Now the big test: Murphy has to show during the exhibition
season he can play quarterback in the NFL ... The Patriots haven't
responded to a proposal made by  &UR; Ted Johnson's  &LR; agent,  &UR; Jack
Mills &LR; . &UR;  &LR;  The proposal is similar to the five-year, $28 million
deal given to Pittsburgh Steelers linebacker  &UR; Levon Kirkland &LR; .
Mills would rather not discuss a long-term deal with the team after
training camp starts Sunday at Bryant College in Smithfield, R.I.
If the proposal is rejected, he currently has no counter-proposal
planned.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati Bengals coach  &UR; Bruce Coslet  &LR; likes to have a
high-powered offense. He had it with  &UR; Boomer Esiason  &LR; last season,
but didn't have a defense to match, and with Esiason gone, he is
hoping to create enough competition at quarterback to achieve his
desired result. Thus, the Bengals gave  &UR; Jeff Blake  &LR; competition by
adding  &UR; Neil O'Donnell  &LR; to the mix. With Blake, O'Donnell, and the
underrated  &UR; Paul Justin &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was signed to a $2.5 million deal in
the offseason, there should be lots of competition. The job is
Blake's to lose. In the past he's been electric, but he became
complacent last year and Esiason took over. O'Donnell, a good guy
and a winner, is looking for a rebirth after a horrible experience
in New York under  &UR; Bill Parcells &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who recently replaced the
former Steeler with  &UR; Vinny Testaverde &LR; . O'Donnell was afraid to
make a mistake under Parcells; now he'll be able to let loose in
Cincinnati's wide-open offense, which already has a good back
( &UR; Corey Dillon &LR; ) and two fine receivers in  &UR; Carl Pickens  &LR; and
 &UR; Darnay Scott &LR; . ``He's not gonna be the guy who loses the game for
you,'' said Coslet. ``He's gonna lean toward safe and sane rather
than risky and flashy, and that's the kind of guy I want.'' As for
Blake, his agent,  &UR; Ralph Cindrich &LR; , says his client is up for the
challenge. ``He's never once complained about it,'' said Cindrich.
``He'd heard rumors about different quarterbacks all summer long
and he knew he'd have to be on top of his game to keep his job. I
think at this point that challenge is really driving him. I think
he wants back what he believes is his.'' ... Which brings us to
44-year-old  &UR; Steve DeBerg &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who will join the Atlanta Falcons
following a five-year absence in the NFL. It appears teams are
becoming less tolerant of younger quarterbacks in backup roles
because in the NFL, you have to step in and produce when the star
QB goes down. It's one reason the Patriots have held on to  &UR; Scott
Zolak &LR; , &UR;  &LR; now in his eighth year in the league. He has spent five of
those backing up  &UR; Drew Bledsoe &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who hasn't been injury prone.
``There are some situations out there where Scott could have played
more and contributed,'' said Cindrich, who also represents Zolak.
``He's always wanted to play, but it's never been a problem for
him. He's always been recognized as a team player and when teams
have a veteran, experienced quarterback like Scott, they don't let
them go. They're valuable. It's a position where the backup is
becoming crucial given the number of injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Veteran running back  &UR; Rodney Hampton  &LR; is still unemployed, but
he has begun to receive some inquiries. A proven inside runner, the
Patriots have not expressed interest in the veteran ...  &UR; Terry
Kirby's  &LR; agent,  &UR; Mike Battle &LR; , &UR;  &LR; said he's moving ahead with
negotiations with another AFC team (believed to be the Chiefs)
since he hasn't heard from the Patriots. It was thought Carroll
wanted Kirby, a good pass receiver who could assume the role of
third-down back, but the Patriots are still waiting until training
camp to pull the trigger ... One player who probably isn't in their
mix is former Bears running back  &UR; Raymont Harris &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is
reportedly asking the Packers for $2.5 million a year. The Packers
were interested in Harris as their negotiations with  &UR; Dorsey Levens
 &LR; went nowhere. Levens recently reduced his demands, but not by much
... Some agents are griping that teams should have a uniform
vacation policy in which the entire league breaks up for a summer
respite. ``We see teams who are going forward trying to sign their
draft picks right away and other teams who are on vacation and
won't even begin talking to guys until later,'' said one agent.
``It's hard to get a guy signed.'' One player who may go right to
the wire is Carolina defensive tackle  &UR; Jason Peter &LR; . The Panthers
are up against the salary cap, so it will take some creative work
to get him in camp on time ...  &UR; Jimmy Johnson  &LR; did something rather
surprising this week. First, he decided to back  &UR; Lawrence
Phillips &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has been accused by a woman of assaulting her at a
Pembroke Pines nightclub June 27. Johnson said he spoke to Phillips
and came away believing him. In fact, Johnson said, ``The incident
is history.'' That comment didn't sit well with the Broward County
chapter of the National Organization for Women, which is angry that
Johnson made that statement before the police investigation has
been completed. If Phillips is innocent, he's going to have to
prove that a friend of the woman is lying when she says Phillips
not only struck the alleged victim in the mouth, but also chipped
two teeth and caused swelling in her face. There are also pictures
of the woman taken at the hospital showing facial bruises ... The
Dolphins are going to head into camp trying to find a left guard
and a defensive end in house. These are their two major needs. It
appears Northeastern's  &UR; Josh Taves &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who had a big year in NFL
Europe, will get the chance to be that find on defense ... The
Dolphins are already calling Avery their third-down back and not
looking for a veteran ... The Raiders, who are involved a stadium
mess with the city of Oakland over naming rights for the Coliseum,
hired an old-time quarterback of their own this week, signing
39-year-old  &UR; Wade Wilson  &LR; to back up  &UR; Jeff George  &LR; and  &UR; Donald
Hollas &LR; . Wilson is being called the third quarterback, but you know
if George goes down (and there's a chance he will as Raider
quarterbacks were sacked 58 times last year) coach  &UR; Jon Gruden
 &LR; probably would feel more comfortable with Wilson ... Despite the
feeling that the Patriots' defense will be much better this season
than last, one thing both Carroll and defensive coordinator  &UR; Steve
Sidwell  &LR; are emphasizing starting in training camp is for the
defense to play tough in their regular package. The Patriots
certainly were tough with their blitzing packages a year ago, but
Sidwell wants the defense to be just as effective without the
gimmicks. We shall see.
</P>
</TEXT>
