<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-CROATIANETHERLANDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUKER GIVES CROATIANS THIRD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Davor Suker pulled into a tie for the World Cup
goal-scoring lead Saturday in somewhat dramatic fashion, converting
the winner as Croatia took a 2-1 victory over the Netherlands in
the third-place game at Parc des Princes last night.
</P>
<P>
   When Suker scored in the 36th minute to put Croatia ahead to
stay, it was his fifth goal, equaling tournament leaders Gabriel
Batistuta of Argentina and Christian Vieri of Italy. Brazil star
Ronaldo, who plays for the championship Sunday, has four.
</P>
<P>
   The Croats were the surprise of the tournament, eliminating
Romania in the second round and Germany in the quarterfinals, then
taking the lead against France before falling, 2-1, in the
semifinals. This was the best finish by a nation making its World
Cup debut since Portugal finished third at England '66.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Prosinecki, returning to the starting lineup for the
first time since the first round of the tournament, scored the
game's first goal in the 13th minute after spinning away from three
defenders in the penalty area, then shooting low past Dutch
goalkeeper Edwin Van Der Sar.
</P>
<P>
   The Netherlands tied the score in the 21st minute when Boudewijn
Zenden, a 21-year-old midfielder from PSV Eindhoven, dribbled up
the right side, cut across the middle, and sent a left-footed shot
over goalkeeper Drazen Ladic.
</P>
<P>
   Suker, who had been relegated to a reserve role with Real Madrid
by the end of last season, scored the deciding goal after the ball
had gone from Prosinecki to Aljosa Asanovic to Zvonimir Boban. When
it finally came to Suker, he blasted a shot through the legs of
Manchester United-bound defender Jaap Stam.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch appeared to have tied the score in the second half
when Clarence Seedorf headed in an errant clearance by Mario
Stanic. But Seedorf was ruled offside.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Croatia held on for another upset.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
