<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VAN-CRASH-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVORS REMEMBER THE CRYING AND SHOUTS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST STROUDSBURG, Pa. _ In the pediatric unit of Pocono Medical
Center here, two young survivors of a van crash on Friday _
Shaquasha Chambers, 6, and Jalea Moses, 7, _ were covered with
bruises and gauze as they fanned themselves with silvery ``Get Well
Soon'' balloons.
</P>
<P>
   For Shaquasha, whose mother also survived the crash, the tears
ran afresh on Saturday when she discovered that emergency workers
had sliced her beloved pink bathing suit to ribbons while treating
the slashes to her forehead, chest, back, left knee and right foot.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquasha, Jalea and Jalea's older sister, Janee, 8, had enjoyed
a summer day at Knoebels Amusement Park with their fellow campers
from a day camp run by the Bedford-Stuyvesant Restoration Corp., a
community development organization in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   After a rented school bus had been filled with the older
campers, the 3 girls were among the 20 youngest campers, between
the ages of 5 and 10, who were crowded into a van owned by the
corporation and driven by one of its employees.
</P>
<P>
   On the ride home, several of the children, exhausted by the
thrill rides, fell asleep. So did the driver, the police said, and
the van crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquasha's mother, Patricia D. Parrish, a 22-year-old
counselor, recalled sitting on the highway in shock as a 7-year-old
girl stumbled toward her, crying for help. ``I couldn't move so I
told her to lay down,'' Ms. Parrish said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what her injuries were,'' she said. ``She came
and laid on my lap and she just kept crying.'' Nearby, she could
hear Shaquasha crying as well. ``I just told her, `Lay down, don't
get up.' ''
</P>
<P>
   From a bed in the trauma center of Community Medical Center, a
counselor, Mwando C. Bailey, 17, remembered some children shouting:
``I don't want to die,'' and ``I want to go to the hospital.'' He
added, ``I was screaming for help, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
