<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0690 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     07-11 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'78 BAD KARMA HAS SURFACED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The temptation was too great. I know what the folks
back home are thinking because a lot of the folks back home are
here in Baltimore this weekend. And they are getting nervous, as
Sox fans do.
</P>
<P>
   So I had to go to Dennis Eckersley's locker and ask, ``What do
you think, Eck? Too early to start having flashbacks to 1978?''
</P>
<P>
   Eck was there, you know. He was part of the apocalyptic Red Sox
collapse against which all others must be measured. He was a
20-game winner for the Manila Folders of 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, too early,'' he said. ``I don't think we're going to
blow a 14-game lead over the Orioles.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles, reeling before the All-Star break, Saturday beat
the Red Sox by one run for the third straight day. All the good
feeling the Red Sox engendered back in Boston before the break has
dissolved in three well-played games in which the Sox simply
haven't hit. Straight sets _ 3-2, 3-2, and 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Now only the Jin Ho Cho Trail separates the Red Sox from a
four-game sweep. It's said that the kid has ice water in his veins.
Here's hoping Cho is not the Korean Bobby Sprowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he doesn't know about the Boston Massacre,'' said
Cho's teammate Jim Corsi, who was learning his trade at Newton
North High when the wheels came off in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   And does it mean anything that Jesse Orosco, who was standing on
the mound when the Red Sox finally lost the 1986 World Series, has
two wins and a save in this Lost Weekend? Or that this series
opened under a full moon?
</P>
<P>
   Bad mojo, man.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are still wild-card favorites, still leading the Angels,
Rangers, and Blue Jays for that fourth playoff spot. But the team
that scored 45 runs in three days at Fenway has scored five in
three games in the hitters' paradise on Camden Street. That's five
runs in three games against the team with the second-worst (5.04)
ERA in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   There are hundreds of Red Sox fans hanging out at the Inner
Harbor this weekend and several made their feelings known during
Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nation is getting nervous,'' said one guy in a Boston cap.
``If we can't hit here, where can we hit?''
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams, sounding more like Chance the gardener every day,
said, ``Three tough games. We pitched good and played good. We just
can't seem to get enough hits. But we start tomorrow, 0-0. That's
the way you play baseball, the way the game is. We're a good
hitting ball club. We hit. We have good hitters and they're gonna
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Anybody seen Jim Leyritz?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always concerned about the offense,'' acknowledged Mo
Vaughn. ``But we'll keep it together.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be a mistake to overreact to this little bump in the
Baltimore-Washington Parkway. But that, gentle readers, is what we
do in Boston and the Hub representatives who have invaded the
shores of Maryland made it very clear that they expected more from
their team this weekend. The bars on Pratt Street last night were
littered with thirsty Sox fans convinced that the big slide has
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The longest losing streak of this Sox season was six games (four
to the Yankees, two to the Jays, all brutal) and it was heroically
stopped by Bret Saberhagen May 30 in New York. The streak was the
most serious threat in this feelgood campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But now the Sox face another mini-crisis. And the veteran
ballplayers know that if the losing continues, there will be talk
of second-half folds, 1978, and trades that could or should be
made. Vaughn's All-Star break contract story will be cited as a
distraction.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox get to play their Tampa cousins the next two days,
then face a heavy dose of Cleveland and Toronto before the
ever-dreaded West Coast (plus Texas) trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second half is no joke,'' said John Valentin. ``In the
second half, every team you play is going to bear down. It's going
to get a lot tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   These have been tough losses, but not poorly-played games. The
worst thing you can say is that Boston wasted three solid pitching
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday the Sox and Orioles will break the Camden Yards four-game
series attendance record. The representatives of Red Sox Nation
will be easy to spot in the stands. They'll be the ones sitting on
their hands, hoping none of that bad history is coming back to
haunt them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
