<HEADER>
A0692 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ORIOLES-REDSOX-BO     07-11 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ORIOLES-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIOLES QUIET RED SOX BATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Man the barricades, keep the powder dry, and say a
prayer for Jin Ho Cho.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday afternoon's 2-1 loss in Camden Yards, the Korean
rookie is all that stands between the Red Sox and a four-game sweep
by the Baltimore Orioles, which is not the way to stamp yourselves
as legitimate playoff contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Given the Red Sox' history of failure that is anticipated long
before it becomes reality, perhaps it's best that Cho's language
skills don't allow him to read either the team's media guide or
newspaper sports sections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's probably good he doesn't know that he has to be our
stopper tomorrow,'' said reliever Jim Corsi after the Red Sox lost
by a run for the third straight game. ``Those are three pretty
tough losses right there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every loss is tough, but in the last three games the team is
doing what it's supposed to do. We've gotten good pitching, played
good defense, but they've outpitched us.''
</P>
<P>
   The one thing the Red Sox haven't done is hit, which left Tim
Wakefield in the same predicament as Bret Saberhagen and Pedro
Martinez. All three pitched well enough to win, with Wakefield
Saturday playing the part of a bow-legged tightrope artist,
allowing 11 hits in 6 2/3 innings but just two runs, on Joe
Carter's home run and Jeff Reboulet's bases-loaded sacrifice fly in
the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Sox answered with just four hits off Orioles starter
Scott Erickson and lefty nemesis Jesse Orosco, the 40-year-old
rally-killer who needed just one pitch to induce Mo Vaughn to tap
the game-ending ground ball to Reboulet at second.
</P>
<P>
   That's a total of five runs and 17 hits for the Red Sox in three
games in the hitters' playground that is Oriole Park at Camden
Yards, or 10 fewer runs and three fewer hits than they scored in
their last game in Fenway Park before the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second half is no joke,'' said John Valentin, whose 12th
home run leading off the eighth inning accounted for Boston's only
run Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin is one of the few Sox players swinging the bat since
the break, with five hits, including two home runs, in 10 at-bats
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think the Orioles are a bad team because of their
record?'' he said. ``They're very good, they just haven't played
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half, every team you play is going to be bearing
down and it's going to get a lot tougher. You can see that just
from these games the last three days.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles hadn't won three straight games since the first
three days in June. The Red Sox hadn't dropped three straight since
falling to the carpetbagging Phillies from the National League June
22-24. But Saturday, Erickson struck out the side in the first and
set down the first 13 Red Sox hitters in order until Troy O'Leary
blooped a single into right field with one out in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Leary was quickly erased attempting to steal and the Sox
managed only singles by Scott Hatteberg in the sixth and Nomar
Garciaparra in the seventh before Valentin's home run.
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg then drew a walk and pinch runner Donnie Sadler
advanced on pinch hitter Midre Cummings's chopper to second, but he
would get no farther as Darren Bragg tapped to the mound and first
baseman Rafael Palmeiro made a nice backhanded pickup of Darren
Lewis's grounder.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a tough game to lose,'' said Wakefield, who maneuvered
out of a second-and-third situation with no outs without allowing a
run in the third, and after Carter's home run, loaded the bases
with no out in the fourth and allowed just one more run on
Reboulet's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rare to see three ballgames decided by one run here,''
said Wakefield, now 10-4 after his first loss in six starts dating
back to June 6. ``But we'll get something rolling tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be a new experience for Cho, who lost his big-league
debut on the Fourth of July when the Red Sox were shut out by the
White Sox, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Erickson) threw the ball as well as he's thrown, today,''
Vaughn said. ``The pitching has been there for us, and we're going
to hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we've got to stay patient, not get excited, no
added pressure. It will change for us.''
</P>
<P>
   No time for a history lesson for Cho, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just going to go out there and pitch,'' Vaughn said,
``and not get caught up in all this stuff. That's a great thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
