<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday 7/11/98. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- July 11, 1998 -- NY-CENTRALPARK-CONCERT,
7-11 -- The conductors of the Centennial Concert in Central Park,
from left: Skitch Henderson of the New York Pops, Wynton Marsalis
of the Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra and Kurt Masur of the New York
Philharmonic. Commemorating the consolidation of the five boroughs
of New York was reason enough for a big concert and fireworks - or
so 25,000 revelers, the Parks Department estimates, seemed to think
- on a cool and lovely evening on the beautifully restored Great
Lawn. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- July 11, 1998 -- NY-MARATHON-SWIMMERS-2, 7-11
-- Before the 28.5-mile Manhattan Island Marathon, which was
expected to last up to 11 hours, swimmers prepared by lathering
Vaseline and lanoline on their bodies to prevent skin chafing and
heat loss in the 70-degree water. Each of the twenty-seven swimmers
paid about $1,000 to enter and rent a boat for a support crew.
(Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- July 11, 1998 -- NY-MARATHON-SWIMMERS-1, 7-11
-- Twenty-seven swimmers start the 17th annual Manhattan Island
Marathon. The grueling, 28.5-mile course - 2.3 miles longer than
the New York City Marathon - circled the city counterclockwise, to
follow the currents, starting from Battery Park. The winner
received a silver bowl from Tiffany and Co., and others took home
plaques and T-shirts. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- July 11, 1998 -- NY-SUMMER-MOTORCYCLES, 7-11
-- Bikers hang out in front of the Ear Inn in SoHo. The Ear Inn and
other motorcycle-friendly bars in the city are seeing larger crowds
of bikers this summer. Veteran riders, for whom it has never been
uncool, say interest has actually been building in New York for the
past four or five years, driven by some of the same factors that
have pushed motorcycle sales up 43 percent around the country since
1991. (Michelle V. Agins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- July 11, 1998 -- TEN-LIPSYTE-COLUMN, 7-11 --
This year marks the 25th anniversary of Billie Jean King's match
with Bobby Riggs - the most spectacular public event of the modern
women's movement. King believes that tennis has failed to embrace
new ideas that could rejuvenate it. Her most consistently
interesting vision, World Team Tennis, began its 18th season last
week. Its combination of elite athletes having fun and families
playing recreationally, has yet to catch on. (Chester Higgins
Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) YUGAWARA, Japan -- July 11, 1998 -- JAPAN-FINN-POL, 7-11
-- Marutei Tsurunen campaigning at Hiratsuka train station in
Kanagawa prefecture. Born a Finn, Tsurunen overcame tremendous
obstacles to become a Japanese citizen in 1979 and now hopes to
become a member of Japan's Upper House of Parliament. ``I want to
open the political system and make it work for the people who live
here. And because I am foreign and yet also Japanese, I think I can
more easily push for that,'' he says. (Stuart Isett/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ORANGE BEACH, Ala. -- July 11, 1998 --
GULF-SNAPPER-CRISIS, 7-11 -- Nick Bouzsis, mate on the Necessity,
cleans red snapper in Orange Beach. The government may halt fishing
for snapper in the Gulf of Mexico, a move that could have a
devastating economic impact on this community that bills itself as
``the red snapper capital of the world.'' (Carl Hulse/New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- July 11, 1998 -- DEECEE-VOTER-LAWSUIT, 7-11
-- Officials in the District of Columbia say they have finally
found the best way to gain voting rights in Congress for more than
500,000 district residents - sue the government. ``The lawsuit is
based on the argument that citizens of the district are entitled to
be represented in Congress by the Constitution. It's strictly a
constitutional argument,'' says John Ferren, corporation counsel
for the District of Columbia. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LAS VEGAS -- July 11, 1998 -- VEGAS-BUFFET-LIFESTYLE-2,
7-11 -- Customers return from the pastry counter at the Main Street
Station's $9.99 buffet, one of dozens of casino buffets in Las
Vegas. While local residents have become experts on which buffets
offer the best bargain, perhaps the most ardent pilgrims are
retirees, who get coupons, discounts and other breaks that often
put the price of a limitless meal for two below $11. That includes
non-alcoholic beverages and as much pie, cake and pastry as a body
can manage. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LAS VEGAS -- July 11, 1998 -- VEGAS-BUFFET-LIFESTYLE-1,
7-11 -- Not for the faint of heart, the Rio Suites Hotel and Casino
in Las Vegas has a buffet that spans 50 yards with more than seven
ethnic sub-buffets. Overstuffed, underpriced smorgasbords have long
been a staple of Las Vegas' tourist trade, an enticement and reward
for spending money in casinos. But a lure for heavy rollers is
becoming a lifestyle for heavy eaters as the city's resident
population swells, in more ways than one. (Monica Almeida/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
