<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-BULLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER READING ON THE BULLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As we move into the nuclear summer, let's take one more look at
some Chicago stories:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE NEXT COACH:  &LR; We've heard that the Bulls have narrowed their
list of candidates to five, but don't be surprised if general
manager Jerry Krause has something else in mind. He's been known to
do the unexpected, hiring both Doug Collins and Phil Jackson with
neither having NBA coaching experience. With many rumors swirling,
here's what we think is absolute: The Bulls want assistant coaches
Frank Hamblen, Tex Winter, and Bill Cartwright back on the bench.
(The Chicago assistant coaches' contracts usually run until
August.) Winter has mentioned retirement, but that apparently is an
annual exercise. Krause not only wants Winter back, he expects to
continue to run the famed triple-post offense, with or without
you-know-who. If Tim Floyd gets the head job, that would likely
signal Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen that the rebuilding is
about to begin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LAST COACH:  &LR; It has been three weeks since Jackson left on
his motorcycle and said good-bye. ``I'm not surprised he did that.
Not one bit,'' said Joe Kleine, who spent last season with Chicago.
``He looked relieved when it was all over. It was like he was
freed. The whole season wore on him. As controlled and together as
he can appear to be, I think getting that last championship was a
real relief. He's looking forward to being away for a year.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUPERSTAR I:  &LR; You may recall that Jordan decided to return to
basketball when the baseball labor situation was at its
ultra-messiest. Could the same thing make him decide to leave the
NBA? ``One thing is not going to force Michael either way,'' says
David Falk, Jordan's agent. Jordan already has eased off his
earlier, unequivocal, no-room-for-second-guessing remarks that he
wouldn't play for anyone other than Jackson. ``If they can get
Scottie back and a coach he approves of, I think Michael would do
it again,'' Kleine said. ``But if they don't, I don't think there's
a chance. He won't be a part of any rebuilding program, and if
Scottie doesn't come back, that's what it will be.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUPERSTAR II:  &LR; As for Pippen, Kleine doesn't think it's a lost
cause in Chicago. ``I think it would take at least three years, or
two years at Michael Jordan money,'' Kleine said. ``At his heart,
Scottie is a businessman and it makes sense to listen to Chicago.
But he's like Mike in that he doesn't want to be there for a
rebuilding situation, either. He knows he can probably get $50
million to $60 million in the open market. And without Phil,
there's a lot of uncertainty. This past year was very, very
frustrating for him.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BOOR:  &LR; Dennis Rodman was in an ideal situation in Chicago:
a veteran team with a hip head coach who allowed him to be himself.
``He's not evil. He's not a bad person,'' Kleine said. ``But if you
put him in a situation like Los Angeles (Lakers), he could be
disruptive. He is going to do his own thing, and you have to
understand that. In San Antonio, they tried to treat everyone the
same. That won't work with Dennis. He has to be treated
differently.'' Kleine said the team wasn't all that upset when
Rodman blew off practice during the Finals to go to a wrestling
promo. ``It wasn't going to disrupt that team,'' he said. Only an
incentive-laden deal, along with the return of Jordan and Pippen,
would probably even bring Rodman's name up for discussion for
1998-99.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AFTERMATH:  &LR; What was it like in the Chicago locker room
immediately after Game 6, when the Bulls had beaten the Jazz to
annex title No. 6? ``There was some jubilation,'' Kleine said,
``but mostly, there was a huge feeling of relief. A lot of people
were simply glad it was finally over, there had been so much stress
and pressure. I mean, people said we had a terrible year and we won
62 games. That's why I think guys were more relieved than anything
else.'' Meanwhile, Kleine was definitely in the jubilation mood. It
was his first title.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE 13th MAN:  &LR; Kleine was left off the playoff roster, and he's
still upset about that. ``Well, you know, I'm like a lot of NBA
guys. If I don't have anything to complain about, I complain about
that. It could have been worse. A lot worse. I realize that.'' The
Bulls told Kleine that he was left off the roster because of
matchups, a curious explanation given their likely bruising battle
with Indiana. ``In my opinion, I was the new guy,'' he said. ``I
think Phil felt more comfortable with the guys he knew. But it was
very disappointing to me because that's what I went there for.''
Kleine is a free agent and will wait and see what happens. ``I may
have to move on to Chapter 2,'' he said. ``The only problem with
that is that it hasn't been written yet.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SHEEP:  &LR; When the Bulls' season-ticket holders got their
playoff ticket applications, they were given the following
``options.'' They had to purchase tickets for the maximum number of
games at playoff-inflated prices; in Chicago's case, that would
have been 15 games. There was a box you could check that offered a
refund if the team didn't play all 15 games. But the application
warned that if you took the refund, you were deemed to have
cancelled your season tickets for next season. According to agent
Herb Rudoy, a Bulls' season-ticket holder, it was an easy decision.
He re-upped, and so did most everyone he knows. ``Most people are
not going to turn their tickets in with the possibility that Jordan
might be back,'' he said. Rudoy said he was told by Bulls director
of ticket operations Joe O'Neil that the renewal rate for 1998-99
is close to 100 percent. Meanwhile, one season-ticket holder with
four seats at halfcourt, five rows up, was offered $10,000 per seat
for his seats for what everyone thought would be the clincher, Game
5 against Utah. The ticket holder said ``no thanks,'' and the Bulls
went out and lost the game.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HDsub1,s5,14 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Short story
</P>
<P>
   &UR; xr &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rick Pitino's  &LR; already short free agent list may soon get
trimmed in half.  &UR; Zan Tabak  &LR; is ``95 percent'' certain to sign this
week with a team in Istanbul. (That would make  &UR; Popeye Jones  &LR; the
only Celtic free agent; we're excluding late-season fill-in  &UR; Reggie
Hanson &LR; .) Tabak's deal is comparable to $2 million a year, says
Rudoy, who represents the Croatian center. ``Zan loved Boston, but
we had no assurances from the Celtics,'' Rudoy said. ``Zan is a
very realistic guy, and this is a fabulous deal for him. These
Turkish teams have money, and he can't afford to wait. He has no
problem playing over there.'' The Celtics did call Rudoy to say
that Tabak was in their plans. ``That wasn't enough,'' Rudoy said.
Boston also could do nothing once the lockout was imposed on July
1. ``You may see more of this as the summer goes on,'' Rudoy said.
 &UR; Jayson Williams  &LR; is saying he's been contacted by an Italian team
offering large lire. But it won't be as much as he'll get when he
re-signs with Jersey or goes elsewhere in the NBA ...  &UR; Walter
McCarty  &LR; started 64 games for the Celtics last season, second only
to  &UR; Antoine Walker's  &LR; 82. Those starts were at small forward,
which, we're being told, is the place being held for rookie  &UR; Paul
Pierce &LR; . Not so fast, says McCarty. ``Let's wait and see what
happens when we get out on the court,'' he says. ``I'm not
conceding anything to (Pierce) or to anyone else.'' McCarty has put
on about 16 pounds already and is, according to Pitino, ``in
terrific shape.'' McCarty knows it's best to stay that way, too.
``You had better be ready because when it (the lockout) ends, camp
is going to be tough,'' he said. Pitino, meanwhile, worked out
Pierce in Los Angeles just prior to the lockout and said that the
rookie was calling out the name of every player drafted ahead of
him when he went up to take a shot. ``I was impressed by what I
saw,'' said Pitino ... Former Celtic Assistant Coaches Update:  &UR; Don
Casey  &LR; has an offer from Detroit to join  &UR; Alvin Gentry's  &LR; staff.
It's a two-year offer with a slight bump in salary, and the Nets,
Casey's current employer, have him on board for only one more year.
If Casey does go to Detroit, look for  &UR; John Calipari  &LR; to bring in
old friend  &UR; Bob Hill &LR; . Ironically, when Cal first took the Nets
job, it was Hill, then the coach of the Spurs, who arranged for
Calipari and Casey to get together ...  &UR; Dennis
Johnson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; meanwhile, has been helping Toronto coach  &UR; Butch Carter
 &LR; work out some Raptors and also was involved in preparing  &UR; Jason
Williams &LR; . &UR;  &LR;  DJ had Williams, a point guard from Florida, for about
three weeks prior to the draft. ``I had him on the floor, getting
him to think, putting him through drills, stuff like that,''
Johnson said. ``He was supposed to be a low lottery pick and he
ended up going seventh. I'd like to think I had something to do
with that.'' Johnson says he is hoping to catch on with someone
this year, possibly in a scouting position. There's nothing firm
with Toronto, but, as he put it, ``I'm going to call (general
manager)  &UR; Glen  &LR; ( &UR; Grunwald &LR; ) and see if I can't extend it into
something.'' He also said he threw out his name to  &UR; Elgin Baylor
 &LR; for the Clippers' opening and for an opening with a CBA team in
Idaho. ``You have to let people know you're available,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HDsub1,s5,14 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Up and down
</P>
<P>
   &UR; xr &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution got ahold of an FBI affidavit
in which Hawks backup  &UR; Cadillac Anderson  &LR; admitted to being
involved in a cocaine operation. Anderson already has been charged
with several counts relating to possessing and distributing the
drug. He told the newspaper last week that he would ``get through
it.'' He is a free agent ...  &UR; Dee Brown &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a Reebok fixture
throughout his NBA career, has not been totally jettisoned from the
shoe company, a la Shaq. But his new offer is worth half as much as
the old one, another indication that the shoe companies are cutting
back when they can. Then again, with Brown in Toronto, you may
wonder why Reebok is interested at all. Brown is elated with the
changes the Raptors have made, namely the acquisitions of veterans
 &UR; Charles Oakley  &LR; and  &UR; Kevin Willis  &LR; and the drafting of  &UR; Vince
Carter &LR;  ... The Beantown Basketball League over at Boston College
has some interesting participants, including  &UR; Marcel Anderson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a
6-foot-6-inch bruiser who has quite a few passport stamps. He
played at Northeastern in the 1980s, had two appearances at the
Celtics rookie-free agent camp, and has spent the last two years
playing in China. ``The first year was fine,'' Anderson said.
``Last year, it wasn't so great. The league kinda got postponed.''
Postponed? ``They started this second league and it was financed by
the government, and if you're going to make it over there, it's no
secret that you have to do business with the government.'' Chinese
rules allow four Americans per team, twice as many as Europe, but
no more than two can be on the court at the same time. They play
NBA rules, with a 24-second clock and no zone defenses. ``It was an
experience,'' Anderson said. He also has played in Turkey and
Portugal. His memories of Celtics camp in the late 1980s and early
1990s? ``I didn't have much of a chance. That was when they had the
family all together.'' And now? ``Tell them I'm available. They
could use a good shooter and defender.'' Consider it done.
</P>
