<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-BRITISHOPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROYAL OPEN TEST LOOMS AT BIRKDALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The presence of Ian Baker-Finch will be felt only peripherally
next weekend at the 127th British Open at Royal Birkdale. Just
seven years ago at Pleasant Valley, Baker-Finch lost to Bruce
Fleisher in a playoff that lasted seven holes before he hastily
crossed the pond and won the championship. He would return to the
Greater Hartford Open, the claret jug in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Baker-Finch was sitting on top of the world of golf, an unknown
Australian a few years earlier when he jumped into the British Open
hunt before fading on the last day. But as soon as his star
ascended at Royal Birkdale, it fell out of the golfing skies, and
he has now given up competitive golf.
</P>
<P>
   The last straw was at Royal Troon last year when he withdrew
after an opening round of 92. He had missed 32 consecutive cuts and
was finding it increasingly difficult to hit his ball in the
fairways. ``Really,'' he said earlier this year, ``what I would
like to be able to do is to change my name, come back in a
different body, and go play without the pressure of being Ian
Baker-Finch.'' Next weekend he will be doing commentary for ABC-TV.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Birkdale is a baby in the rotation of courses selected for
the game's oldest championship. The British Open was contested
there for the first time in 1954, when Australian Peter Thomson won
the first of his five Opens. He also won his last title (1965) over
the rugged links course on England's Lancashire Coast. The others
on Royal Birkdale's honor roll of champions are Arnold Palmer
(1961), Lee Trevino (1971), Johnny Miller (1976), Tom Watson
(1983), and Baker-Finch. It's the US 4, Australia 3.
</P>
<P>
   Watson has fond memories of the course. ``I remember the last
full shot I hit was a 2-iron on the 72d hole,'' said Watson at the
recent Children's Charity Pro-Am at Willowbend. ``I had 215 (yards)
to the flag, and I had to really flush it to get there. It was into
the wind.'' Watson then had to wait for David Graham to finish out.
``He was slower than molasses,'' said Watson. ``It was about the
best 2-iron I ever hit, and when I did, the crowd went on a full
run. They used to allow them to run up and circle the green. It was
like a freight train. The ball's in the air and they're running up
to the green. I didn't know how close it was. I couldn't hear the
crowd. I heard them clap. I wanted it 2 feet from the hole so I
could two-putt to win. It was 15 feet, so I two-putted from 15 feet
to win by one shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The golf course is typical links golf. It's one of my
favorites. Most of the holes sit down with dunes on either side.
The course fits into the low parts of the land form. The first hole
is a very difficult par 4. I started off with a triple bogey in
1976 and missed the cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer won the first of his two British Opens at Royal Birkdale,
and there is a commemorative plaque on the 16th hole at the spot
where he gouged a 6-iron shot to the green en route to the
championship. This is where Jack Nicklaus conceded a putt to Tony
Jacklin for a tie in the 1965 Ryder Cup Matches. This is where a
19-year-old Spaniard named Seve Ballesteros chased Miller to the
wire. This is where Watson won the last of his five Open titles.
</P>
<P>
   They simply introduce the winner on the 18th green as ``the
champion golfer for the year.'' The latest is Justin Leonard, who
left the United States Saturday to get ready to defend his title.
Last year at Scotland's Royal Troon, there were 32 players in the
hunt entering the final round. The only player of the 32 to break
70 was Leonard, who shot a 65. That's how major championships are
won, and that is why many projected the Dallas resident out of the
University of Texas to become one of the game's elite. He went on
to finish second in the PGA Championship and won The Players
Championship in March at Sawgrass.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard's last tuneup was last weekend at the Greater Hartford
Open, where he finished joint 31st on a 71_275. ``I'm not thinking
about the British Open while I'm on the golf course,'' he said
after a third-round 66. ``I'm hitting the ball well. I haven't
putted all that well. I feel pretty good about the way things
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Royal Birkdale has been lengthened, and some 6,000 scrub pines
have been removed from the vast and sprawling sand hills. The
latter move, wrote Dudley Doust in Golf Magazine, ``has not only
returned a proper links feel to the place but rendered Birkdale the
finest viewing course on the British Open rota. Also, clearing the
trees has let seaside winds rage and frolic in the fairways that
flow through the valleys.''
</P>
<P>
   The Open will mark the end of Jack Nicklaus's incredible streak
of 154 consecutive major championships for which he was eligible
and 146 straight from his first year as a professional in the 1962
Masters. ``I wanted to end the streak on my own terms,'' Nicklaus
said Wednesday on the eve of the Senior Players Championship in
Dearborn, Mich. The ailing left hip that has dogged him in recent
years was the primary reason. He said he might need a new hip, and
realized the time had come. ``I don't want to go out and embarrass
myself,'' said Nicklaus. This isn't a farewell for Nicklaus,
however. He has said he'd like to wind it all up in the British
Open at St. Andrews in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pete Morgan &LR; , who was the surprise first-round leader of the
Greater Hartford Open with a 64, finished with a double bogey and a
73_277 worth $5,022. He grew up in Harwich before attending
Jacksonville University and settling into the Florida mini-tours.
This was the first cut the 35-year-old has made in four PGA Tour
appearances, and he left Cromell, Conn., upbeat about his future.
Morgan, who recently won the Cape Cod Open for the third time and
has won the Massachusetts Open, has made it through the first phase
of Tour Qualifying School only once in eight tries. ``I'm not going
to worry too much about the finish,'' Morgan said. ``I just know
now I can compete with these guys out here.'' ... The hardest part
of getting into the British Open is the qualifying, which takes two
days. For nonexempt US players, it can be an expensive proposition.
``I'm not in,'' says  &UR; Billy Andrade  &LR; of Bristol, R.I., who played
last year at Royal Troon. ``That's not a fun trip to go over and
miss and come all the way back. The reason a lot of guys don't go
is you have to make your hotel arrangements for a week. If you
don't make it, you're out ($4,800).'' ... Tickets for the 1999 US
Open (June 17-20) at Pinehurst CC sold out within 24 hours on June
22. The US Golf Association will be mailing confirmations or
rejections of all applications no earlier than July 31. It is the
Open's 13th consecutive sellout ... Because he failed to make the
cut at the GHO,  &UR; Casey Martin  &LR; decided to accept a sponsor's
exemption to this weekend's Quad Cities event; so he will not be
playing the CVS Charity Classic at Pleasant Valley in two weeks ...
 &UR; Brad Faxon &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has been struggling amid personal problems
including a divorce, finished on a high note at Hartford, closing
with a 66. ``I woke up,'' he said after the round. ``It was a long
wait. I played great today. It's the best round I've played, the
best round I've putted. It's the most solid I've hit it, the best
I've driven it.'' He will need it all at Royal Birkdale ... Faxon
took time to lament the passing of the PGA Tour stop at Pleasant
Valley after the CVS Charity Classic July 23-26. ``The area
couldn't keep up with PGA Tour corporate golf,'' said Faxon.
</P>
</TEXT>
