<SLUG> BC-BKO-LEBRETON-COLUMN-WRITETHRU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TEAM USA IS NO MATCH FOR THE WORLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Editors: Updates and edits thruout 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nothing like hanging your dirty laundry out for all the world to
see.
</P>
<P>
   And we do mean all the world.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the NBA labor lockout, the league's players callously
threatened to withdraw their participation in this month's FIBA
World Basketball Championships. They were taking their ball and
staying home, thus proving a point.
</P>
<P>
   That it's not the heat _ it's the stupidity. Somebody needs to
explain to me the logic behind not representing your country in
order to prove a point to owners like the Minnesota Timberwolves'
Glen Taylor, who gave Kevin Garnett a $126 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the oft-debated Dream Team concept is considered the
plaything of NBA ownership. By disbanding Dream Team IV, the
players hoped to make their point that they are the straw that
stirs the NBA martini.
</P>
<P>
   Fine, but whatever happened to ``I pledge allegiance to the flag
...'' and all of that?
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of Dream Teamers such as Grant Hill, Gary Payton and Tom
Gugliotta, the sport's governing body in this country, USA
Basketball, will be represented in Athens, Greece, by the likes of
Wendell Alexis and Ashraf Amaya.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball scabs, a good union man might call them. And they are
about to get hit on the heads with a global pipe wrench.
</P>
<P>
   Let's review the stakes. The winner in Athens gets a free pass
into the 2000 Olympics in Sydney, Australia. The other 15 teams
don't necessarily get anything.
</P>
<P>
   Each of FIBA's geographic regions _ Europe, Asia, Oceania and
the Americas _ will likely get to send two more teams to Sydney.
The constitution of FIBA, the game's world governing body, says
only the qualifying tournament winner from each region, plus the
``five or six best-placed teams,'' will round out the Olympic
field.
</P>
<P>
   It seems ludicrous any selection committee would leave out a
card-carrying Dream Team of true NBA stars, but this is FIBA. As
Munich in 1972 proved, schnitzel happens.
</P>
<P>
   And, book it, this Team USA in Athens will get drummed.
Jackhammered. It might not win as many as two games.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis, for instance, plays in Berlin, after last being seen at
Syracuse _ the school, not the island _ in 1986. Amaya plays for
the Idaho Stampede. And Gerard King, playing ball in Italy, earned
his basketball sheepskin at Nicholls State.
</P>
<P>
   The CBA thing, history tells us, will not work. Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The last time USA Basketball assembled a crew of CBA players and
outfitted them in Team USA jerseys was at the Pan American Games in
Mar del Plata, Argentina, in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The team we sent down featured, among others, Sean Gay of Texas
Tech, ex-Michigan star Rumeal Robinson and Notre Dame center Scott
Paddock. They hailed from teams like the Yakima Sun Kings, the
Shreveport Crawdads and the Mexico Aztecas.
</P>
<P>
   The Argentines, however, didn't know any better. As far as they
knew, the Pittsburgh Piranhas (Brian Davis, forward) played the
Chicago Bulls every night.
</P>
<P>
   Team USA finished 4-3, barely edging Uruguay in overtime, and
losing to the host team twice. When the Argentines won the
gold-medal game, 90-86, the standing-room-only crowd of 9,000
poured onto the arena floor, while players hugged and cried and
shouted, ``We beat the Dream Team! We beat the Dream Team!''
</P>
<P>
   The whole thing was only slightly less bogus than that game
against the aliens in ``Space Jam.''
</P>
<P>
   The point is, however, the day is long passed when we can send
over any 10 stiffs and expect to bring back the gold. Any gold.
</P>
<P>
   The United States hasn't won the men's gold medal at the Pan Am
Games since 1983. In 1991, a team that featured Grant Hill, Jim
Jackson, Christian Laettner and Eric Montross finished in third
place. And the last time a non-Dream Team of U.S. players competed
in the Olympics, 1988, it, too, could do no better than the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a disappointment that we don't have the NBA guys, but
it's happened, and the guys that are here are working real hard,''
said Rudy Tomjanovich, who is coaching Team Scab.
</P>
<P>
   It's happened, but it's wrong. This isn't an owners' thing. It's
a red, white and blue thing.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a message the NBA players are trying to send, it's
all Greek, so to speak. The ones who aren't going to Athens look
greedy, foolish and unpatriotic.
</P>
<P>
   And now, the whole world knows. Fan-tastic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
