<SLUG> BC-VINEYARD-SLAYING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOCKED FATHER DIES AFTER SON IS MURDERED ON ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAK BLUFFS, Martha's Vineyard _ An early-morning stabbing, the
first murder on Martha's Vineyard in two decades, developed into a
double tragedy for a well-known Vineyard family, police said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Moreis, 37, was stabbed in the chest in an attack outside
his home on Warwick Avenue, according to Police Chief Joseph
Carter. As Moreis was being treated at Martha's Vineyard Hospital,
his 66-year-old father, Peter, suffered a fatal heart attack while
rushing to see his son.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Moreis was transported to Boston Medical Center,
where he died at 7 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths left the town's 3,000 year-round residents reeling,
not only because of the rarity of violent crime on the island, but
also because Peter Moreis was a well-loved figure.
</P>
<P>
   Police have no suspect in the stabbing, which they said occurred
during a fight. Authorities have interviewed one witness and
recovered a knife they believe to be the murder weapon.
</P>
<P>
   While police declined to discuss a motive in the stabbing,
speculation among Vineyard residents that the slaying was
drug-related was fueled by Gary Moreis's June 19 arrest for cocaine
possession. Those charges were pending at the time of his death.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Moreis also was arrested for selling cocaine in 1986. The
charges against him and 24 others in that case were dropped because
an undercover agent had used cocaine with the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   The older Moreis, known in Oak Bluffs as ``Peter Pop,'' suffered
a heart attack at 2:35 a.m. in the hospital parking lot. He had
undergone open-heart surgery a few years ago and was in poor
health, according to a family friend. Police blame the shock of his
son's stabbing for precipitating the heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Moreis, who had a 6-year-old son and a 12-year-old stepson,
worked as an auto mechanic. His father, who had five other
children, was a former police officer who wore innumerable hats in
the community.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Moreis held the elected title of town constable for the
past decade and served as a volunteer firefighter and on several
town committees. He drove a school bus in winter and a shuttle for
vacationers in summer. He also managed the local Veterans of
Foreign Wars post and was a VFW district commander.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Williamson, a retired Oak Bluffs police chief, called the
elder Moreis one of the most popular citizens on Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if any church on the island could hold all the
people who will come to his funeral,'' Williamson said. ``Peter Pop
was very, very kind to people and always a lot of fun and full of
laughter. He could charm anybody with his blue eyes _ they looked
right through you.''
</P>
<P>
   Williamson was looking forward to sharing an annual birthday
beer with Moreis, who would have turned 67 next week. They had been
close friends since serving as patrolmen together in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Moreis, Peter Moreis's nephew, counted his uncle among the
best of men.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to call him `Peter Pop the Rotten Cop,' because he
used to chase us kids around and made sure we didn't do anything
wrong,'' Jimmy Moreis said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Rusczyk, chairman of the town Board of Selectmen, said:
``Peter Pop was a man of boundless humor, and he was genuinely
loved in our community. He had contagious laughter _ you heard it
before he even came around. His death is a real blow to this
community.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gary Moreis was lesser known around town, locals also
spoke of him with affection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary was a fun-loving guy,'' Jimmy Moreis said. ``He had some
problems, but he would take the shirt off his back for anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vineyard's last murder, in 1978, also ultimately left both a
father and son dead.
</P>
<P>
   On a Saturday night in January of that year, 20-year-old Duane
Brady sat in the living room with a shotgun, waiting for his
father, the Rev. D. Norman Brady, to return from the movies.
</P>
<P>
   The son then chased the minister out of the house and into the
nearby Charlotte Inn, where he killed his father.
</P>
<P>
   In court, the younger Brady was acquitted by reason of insanity
and committed to Bridgewater State Hospital. He hanged himself two
years later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
