u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-BARTHEZ-     07-11 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-BARTHEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARTHEZ'S GOAL IS KEEPING GAME IN PERSPECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAINT-DENIS, France _ His shaved head, shining like a cue ball
beneath the lights of Stade de France, has become a lucky charm, a
porte-bonheur, for his defenders, who rub it just before kickoff.
Fabien Barthez has been in goal for every minute of every match for
France in the World Cup, and has allowed just one goal during the
run of play.
</P>
<P>
   While the buzz in this suddenly soccer-mad country has been all
about Zizou (Zinedine Zidane), Lolo (Laurent Blanc), and Thuthu
(Lilian Thuram), the ``joyful hermit'' has been the comforting
constant, prowling the box in smooth pate, goatee, and all-black
garb, hanging up zeros.
</P>
<P>
   And if France can do what the rest of the planet deems
impossible (and they themselves concede is as unlikely as Voltaire
coming back to play stopper) and beat champion Brazil here Sunday
for the world title, odds are Barthez will be the man who made it
happen.
</P>
<P>
   He is the last line of Les Bleus' formidable defense, its
gardien de but. There are tenders of goal and keepers of goal
elsewhere, but in France they are guardians of goal, with a
responsibility that approaches the religious. ``We owe it to
ourselves as gardiens,'' says Barthez, ``to be the masters of our
18-meter domain.''
</P>
<P>
   Barthez wants to be master of more than that. He'll come well
out of the area to boom the ball downfield. He'll roam with it at
his feet like an 11th field player or hurl it to a midfielder,
looking to create something at the other end.
</P>
<P>
   Barthez's non-identical twin is Paraguay's Jose Luis Chilavert,
who'll often sally into the other half of the field and even takes
free kicks. ``I honestly believe Fabien could convert one, too,''
says Blanc.
</P>
<P>
   He may work in a cage, but Barthez is a free spirit who yearns
for open space. ``In my head, I'm a player,'' he told L'Equipe,
France's sporting daily. ``I don't want to stay in the goal all
alone. I have to be with the others, to share the game with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing behind one of the world's best defensive units actually
makes Barthez antsy. Guarding the goal in the early blowouts of
South Africa and Saudi Arabia made him feel Garboesque. ``It's
tiring not to touch the ball,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Barthez prefers the ocean to the stadium. His favorite playmates
are dolphins _ he has one tattooed on a shoulder. Onze magazine
photographed him chewing on a daisy stem, looking a bit like Pete
Townshend of The Who. He'll be the one who isn't singing ``La
Marseillaise'' during the pre-match anthem ceremony, the one who's
smiling. ``That's how I am,'' he shrugs. ``I don't want to change
my way of doing things.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people, including national coach Aime Jacquet, thought the
26-year-old Barthez was a bit too free-spirited to guard the goal
for Les Bleus in the Mondial, especially after he tested positive
for marijuana three years ago and was suspended from the French
league for four months.
</P>
<P>
   That was until Bernard Lama, who had 37 international
appearances for France, holds the record for most consecutive
scoreless minutes (800) with Les Bleus, and figured to be starting
keeper, was suspended for the same thing last year. Paris
Saint-Germain dumped Lama, who had to go across the Channel to find
a job with West Ham United.
</P>
<P>
   Though Jacquet did put Lama on the Cup roster, he decided to go
with Barthez, who'd backstopped Monaco to last year's French league
title. Once he shut out the South Africans in the opener in the
teeth of a howling Mistral in Marseille, Barthez became the
guardian angel. And as Les Bleus kept advancing and the stakes got
higher and his mates stopped scoring, Barthez simply loomed larger.
</P>
<P>
   He kept Paraguay off the board until Blanc provided ``La
Delivrance'' with a goal in the 113th minute. Then he shut down
Italy for 120 in the quarterfinals and blocked a penalty kick by
Demetrio Albertini in the shootout right after Bixente Lizarazu had
one stopped by Italian keeper Gianluca Pagliuca.
</P>
<P>
   And in last week's historic semifinal against Croatia, Barthez
finally conceded a goal, on a breakaway, but then slammed the door
time after time while Les Bleus played a man down for the final 16
minutes. Yet all the while Barthez appeared unruffled, even
tranquil. ``He's a very relaxed lad,'' says his father, who played
stand-off half for the rugby team at the Narbonne Racing Club. ``He
doesn't think he's Napoleon.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Barthez doesn't feel the squeeze, especially with Les
Bleus on a ride that's already touched off the greatest celebration
in Paris since the Liberation. ``Even if I sometimes have a relaxed
air about me, I feel the same pressure as the others,'' he says.
``But I handle it differently.''
</P>
<P>
   He may want to roam the field, to share the game with his mates,
but Barthez is a guardian alone and he knows it. The unruffled
expression is a mask.
</P>
<P>
   Barthez constantly worries about being scored on. He stewed
about the penalty kick he gave up to Denmark's Michael Laudrup for
days; he wanted to keep a clean sheet for the tournament. He says,
``I'm always telling myself: `Fabien, pay attention. No
stupidity.'''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, attention must be paid to the Brazilians _ and then
some. Ronaldo, Bebeto, Rivaldo, and the rest are out to make some
history of their own _ no country has won five Cups and none since
Brazil in 1962 has repeated. Blanc will be sitting out a red-card
suspension, and the French attackers haven't scored for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   If Barthez can keep a clean sheet tonight and put Les Bleus on
top of the world, they'll erect a statue to him under the Arc de
Triomphe _ with a daisy in its mouth. ``Whatever happens, when the
Mondial is over, the guys back home in Lavelanet will see the same
Fabien they've always known,'' he says. ``I'll stay the same.''
Napoleon, he ain't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980711.0193 </DOCNO>
