<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-ONTHENET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE A BREAK FROM THE HEAT; SURF THESE COWBOYS PAGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cowboys training camp opens Wednesday in Wichita Falls, which
means, if you're a diehard fan, you can do one of two things:
</P>
<P>
   Drive to Wichita Falls, wait around in 150-degree heat with the
sweating huddled masses for a glimpse of your heroes with hopes
that they'll sign an autograph.
</P>
<P>
   Or stay in the climate-controlled comforts of your home or
office, calling up Cowboys sites on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   If you choose the first option, fold this newspaper into a big
hat because you'll need it in that searing Wichita Falls heat. If
you selected the latter option, here's one Web surfer's guide to
quality Cowboys pages: &QL; 
BEST PAGES BEHIND ENEMY LINES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The winner: Though Gary Morris of Folsom, Calif., might be stuck
in San Francisco 49ers country, it doesn't appear to deter his
enthusiasm for the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   During the season, Morris posts from five to 25 Cowboys articles
per day on Gary's Cowboys News Site (www.jps.net/garywm). He posts
the latest updates to rosters and depth charts. He also includes a
section to find the Cowboys on satellite, a must when trapped
behind enemy lines.
</P>
<P>
   Morris personalizes his effort with game previews and reviews
and his handy ``Gary's Technical Guide to Pro Football.''
</P>
<P>
   Runner-up: Deep in Redskins country, David Braesicke of
Washington has loads of information on his favorite team at his
Cowboys page (wj.net/braesick/cowboys/cowboys.html). During the
season, the Game Day section includes box scores and statistics of
the current game and a running account of the season's best
performances. Braesicke also posts a Ring of Honor section, a
trivia section, links and a lot of media-guide data.
</P>
<P>
   Another runner-up: A fan since 1967, Keith Bauer of Menominee,
Mich., said he started Keith's Cowboys Page
(user.cybrzn.com/~keith) ``just to see if I could and to show
people that not everyone who lives in this area is a Packers fan.''
During the season, Bauer posts updated statistics for Troy Aikman,
Emmitt Smith and Michael Irvin. Bauer also has a pictorial history
of the Cowboys quarterback position and images of the team's famous
cheerleaders. &QL; 
BEST ARCHIVE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The winner: Jim Beasley of Franklin Park, N.J., has compiled a
no-frills unofficial media guide of the Cowboys since 1960 on his
Dallas Cowboys History and Stats Page
(www.geocities.com/~jrbeasley/dallas/start.html). Beasley also
posts the team's yearly draft selections and historical summaries
of how the Cowboys have done against the rest of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Runner-up: Tim Stone of Conway, Ark., pays homage to the Cowboys
who laid the franchise's foundation at his Tim's Cowboy History
Page (users.conwaycorp.net/tstone). &QL; 
OTHERS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Best fan page made by a Longhorns fan: Neil Panchal, a
19-year-old sophomore electrical engineering major at the
University of Texas, has been a Cowboys fan since birth, and it
shows.
</P>
<P>
   His Dallas Cowboys Page (lonestar.texas.net/~neilp) opens with
the theme song from the television drama ``Dallas'' blaring.
Panchal's page was selected as the team's Premier Site by
NFLFans.com (www.nflfans.com), a network of NFL fans on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   In the off-season, his page includes a message board and chat
room. During the season, he posts updates after each game. The most
interesting feature is the QB Rating, which calculates the popular
but hard-to-cypher statistic. Warning: Panchal's page is loaded
with multimedia, so it's quite the browser hog when it comes to
load time.
</P>
<P>
   Best fan page in Fort Worth: Molly Smith of Fort Worth has lots
of information at her page (amytree.com/cowboys.htm), which
includes a chat room, message board and an impressive collection of
links.
</P>
<P>
   Best one-stop source: Fred Goodwin of Austin has done fans a
favor with his Cowboys Internet Resource Center
(www.eden.com/~fgoodwin/links.htm). Goodwin has indexed more than
350 Cowboys-related sites and pages.
</P>
<P>
   Best fan page made by a guy nicknamed Hoss: Josh Saiz of
Albuquerque, N.M., started his Hoss' Dallas Cowboys Page
(hoss.unm.edu/Cowboys) in 1995. Saiz's page has the typical
guestbook and links in addition to fan polls, game reviews and
previews, and images of the team and Texas Stadium that Saiz took.
</P>
<P>
   Best Cowboys site in Iowa: Ron Hummel of Waterloo, Iowa, author
of Ron's Cowboy Page! (www.dc.prohosting.com/cowboys), became a
Cowboys fan after the Ice Bowl. Hummel's 3-year-old site includes
audio links and trivia games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
