</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NHIS-JEREMYMAYFIELD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYFIELD IS NASCAR'S NEW BIG WHEEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOUDON, N.H. _ Earl Sadler just wonders what took Jeremy
Mayfield so long to get to the top of NASCAR's racing world.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1989 and Mayfield, then 20, had gone about as far as his
own cash was going to take him driving go-carts and then race cars
and it was time to leave home in Owensboro, Ky., and get a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of ran out of money to keep driving my race car,'' said
Mayfield, inside his car hauler at New Hampshire International
Speedway Friday afternoon. ``But all I ever wanted to do was be in
racing, either on a crew or doing something else to make a
living.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Earl.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield hooked up with Earl Sadler of Sadler Bros. Trucking and
Leasing in Nashville _ Earl Sadler, who had sent a few other
drivers, Sterling Marlin and the late Davey Allison among them, on
to Winston Cup fame.
</P>
<P>
   There was no driving in the Mayfield deal. No guarantee driving
would ever be part of the deal. Mayfield was a fabricator, helping
build cars. Race cars. Fabricating, not racing. But it was a job in
the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a metal man, and he was real good at that,'' Sadler
said from Nashville the other day. ``I had some other drivers at
that time, and he started setting up their cars to race. He was
almost like a crew chief.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Mayfield was driving. He was real good at that, too.
</P>
<P>
   He ran a local series in Nashville for Sadler and did well
there. Ran the Automobile Racing Club of America series for Sadler
and cleaned up there.
</P>
<P>
   He made his Winston Cup debut with a single race for Sadler in
1993. By the end of the next year, Cale Yarborough had come along
with a better offer and Jeremy Mayfield was on his way.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   Don't know the name? You will.
</P>
<P>
   Followers of Winston Cup racing already do. His hauler here is
parked in between Jeff Gordon's and Mark Martin's. Gordon, a
two-time Cup series champion and winner of two NHIS races, leads
the points race again and thus gets parking spot No. 1 in the row
of haulers. Mayfield is next, as befits his No. 2 spot in points.
Martin, Dale Jarrett, Rusty Wallace, and the brothers Labonte are
among those giving chase.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield starts 30th in Sunday's race. He was 17th in last
July's race here and 25th in September, but in both races had
worked his way into the Top 10 before running into problems. He ran
into raindrops during his qualifying attempt Friday night and
missed out on the Top 25 and had to qualify again Saturday. ``When
you get raindrops hitting your windshield, that kind of knocks your
confidence down a little,'' he said. ``But I'm sure that we'll get
back up front sooner or later.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield got his first career Cup victory a couple of races ago
at Pocono. He led the points standings for three weeks with a
series of consistent finishes. He's the only driver to finish in
the Top 25 in every race this year.
</P>
<P>
   The name recognition is coming.
</P>
<P>
   He was back near Owensboro the other night for a hometown
autograph session that was scheduled for two hours and stretched to
four. He has enjoyed watching as his support has picked up
throughout the country. He was thrilled by the backing of his
colleagues at Pocono, where the drivers came up beside him to
congratulate him on his victory lap and their crews stood and
cheered him on pit road.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably the best feeling of the whole win for me,''
Mayfield said.
</P>
<P>
   The next week, the Cuppers were in Sonoma, Calif., when a young
fan approached looking for a Mayfield autograph and asked one of
the two guys dressed in team Mobil 1 uniforms. And then was
directed to the other _ Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield just laughed. And signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came up through in my career, you'd hear that stuff,''
Mayfield said. ``Who's this? Who's that? That's what drives me. It
motivates me. `Who's that guy?' Whatever. It gets my blood pumping.
I love that. It pushes you to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if it's not Jeremy who? it will be something else, he
figures. He and Rusty Wallace, his teammate this year, were talking
about it just the other day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rusty was laughing,'' Mayfield said. ``With me it was I
haven't won a race, I haven't won a race. Rusty hasn't won in
40-something races. It's always something. That's what makes the
sport great. But for us to get wrapped up in that, that will never
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor, he says, will he spend a lot of time thinking about a
series championship. Stay focused. It helps during a long season.
Helps on the racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a good talent for missing wrecks,'' said crew chief
Paul Andrews, who won his first Cup championship with the late Alan
Kulwicki in 1992. ``He's got a good eye for when they're getting
ready to happen. He watches the guys in front of him and sees the
cars and sees who's getting wild and who's getting crazy. Some guys
are so focused on what their car is doing, they're unfocused on
what is happening around them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield, he said, looks to get the most _ but not too much _
out of the car. Most of the time, there has been plenty to get out
of the Michael Kranefuss and Roger Penske-owned Taurus.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been pretty awesome,'' Andrews said. ``It just gets
better with more experience. To me it's a confidence level, and
ours is up. Confidence means a lot in this business, in any
business. And our car keeps getting better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a third-place finish in the season-opener at Daytona
and then shots at the first win at Darlington and Texas and finally
the break-through race at Pocono.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Mayfield, 13th in points overall last season
after staying in the Top 10 most of the season, has maintained an
even keel.
</P>
<P>
   He has worked his way up the hard way. He's humble. He has a
feel for the car and does a nice job letting his crew in on that
feel and what the car might need for adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing fancy. Nothing flashy.
</P>
<P>
   It's a style and an attitude that will likely continue to bring
him fans like Steve Black of Scituate, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to be Davey Allison fans and really haven't had
anybody to root for since,'' Black said. ``Jeremy has a good ride
and he's doing well. He's not like Gordon, running everyone off the
track. He's a pretty fair racer. You've got to give Gordon credit,
he's a good racer, but he pushes it a little too hard sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayfield is more like an old-time racer like Yarborough or
(David) Pearson,'' Black said. ``He races hard but fair. He's
climbed the ladder and he's got up there with the big guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Earl Sadler knew he would.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does it all, I want to say he's a one-man show,'' Sadler
said with a laugh. ``He's a little late in getting there, I think.
But he just hasn't had the car, that's the main thing. He can do it
all. He can sheet metal. He can paint. He's just a fine boy. And he
enjoys it. He enjoys what he's doing. You can get to the top if you
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's gotten there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
