<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-NEWPORT-CONNORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNORS FINALLY PUT IN HIS PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ The blue-collar tennis player got his eternal
blue ribbon Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   While a band played ``When the Saints Go Marchin' In,'' James
Scott Connors strode onto the lawn where the inaugural US Tennis
Championships was staged 117 years before, shortly to be anointed
as one of the game's saints himself. A sellout crowd of 3,800 at
the antique timber playground, Newport's Casino, screamed, stomped,
waved, applauded _ not exactly proper form for a canonization _
because their man was going into the International Tennis Hall of
Fame, the 59th American male to make it.
</P>
<P>
   He was everyman's champ, and knew it. Boston blueblood Dick
Sears won the first seven US titles on this sod. Connors, hardly a
kindred spirit, won five on three different footings (grass, clay,
asphalt) in rather more trying times and ``wanted to bring tennis
to the general sports fans, to make it really exciting. That's why
I put out, gave the best I had all the time. I wanted to go beyond
the usual tennis fans.''
</P>
<P>
   And he did. Way beyond. Pugnacious Jimmy Connors _ ``Jimbo'' to
his doting and demanding mom, Gloria Connors _ gave the customers
transfusions and got the same in return. ``The fans won me more
matches than I can remember _ whether they were for me or against
me. I think they liked my workmanlike style. It was work _
grinding, dedication, sacrifice. But work I loved.''
</P>
<P>
   Trim and poised as he nears his 46th birthday, but confessing he
now has to wear glasses to read, he pulled them out for his
affecting speech in which he lauded his mother, wife Patti,
daughter Aubree, 12, and towering son Brett, 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom,'' he says, ``gave me this game, along with her mom
(Bertha Thompson). They rolled balls to me when I could hardly hold
a racket. That was the start. For all these years my mom has been
three things: mom, coach, and friend. And it's still that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyful tears glistened in the sunshine on the cheeks of wife and
mother as he saluted them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to write that Patti must be a saint to put up with
Jimmy Connors. That's one thing the press got right. I was selfish,
a loner with pretty much one thing in mind _ winning. I was away a
lot. But Patti and I agreed on how we wanted the kids raised. That
they're going in the right direction, and following their own paths
as I did _ they don't play tennis _ is the important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Flying in early after beating Patrick McEnroe in a World Team
Tennis match Friday night, Connors was clearly touched by his
introduction to Newport and the Hall's museum.
</P>
<P>
   He had never set out to make this journey, not a man for
ceremony and nostalgia. But, he smiles, ``This is it. The
culmination of all those years of breaking my back to be the best.
I am truly honored. I'd only heard about the Hall, but now, seeing
all those people inducted here, I'm glad to be one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Penny David, daughter of the other member of the Class of '98,
the late Herman David, felt ``thrilled to accept for him.'' David,
once an Oxford Blue, got his blue ribbon here, cited as a bold,
thoughtful, historic English administrator. The Wimbledon boss in
1968, he was determined, his daughter says, ``that the best players
must play there, whether amateur or professional.'' Largely through
his influence and energetic persuasion, the segregation of amateurs
and pros was knocked out and ``open tennis'' came in 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   David was a rebel in his genteel way, Connors more conspicuous
in his rebelliousness _ adored or despised but never ignored. His
disputes with court officials got him thrown out, suspended, fined,
and his hand signals and antics would not have qualified him as an
altar boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a bad boy _ and I liked it at the time,'' Jimmy says,
his brown eyes mischievous at the memory. ``This didn't come from
home, but the street. I grew up with some tough people.'' Early
days in rough-edged East St. Louis and Belleville, Ill., weren't
the usual environment for tennis, but they made him a fighter. As a
boy he saw a man killed in a saloon where he had accompanied his
grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where my intensity came from, but (John) McEnroe
wasn't the only perfectionist out there. I got cranky when I
couldn't meet my own expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Connors, with his record 109 pro singles titles (eight majors)
is the most highly decorated American male to settle into the Hall
since Don Budge brought his six majors in 1964. Budge, 85, the
original Grand Slammer, was among the witnesses, and he, too, was
cheered by the throng on the 60th anniversary of his majestic feat,
duplicated only by four others: Rod Laver (1962, '69), Maureen
Connolly (1953), Margaret Court (1970), and Steffi Graf (1988).
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy slammed thousands of winners, and a few doors in the faces
of reporters, including this one. ``It was all part of the fun,
wasn't it?'' he laughs. He's right. He generated fun for anyone who
saw him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the best was the 11 days in 1991, the US Open,'' he
says. ``Wrist surgery saved my career, but I was supposed to be
finished.'' Coming in at No. 936, a wild card, he surged to the
semis. ``It was crazy. Pandemonium. It's the way I wanted tennis to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in the day of James the Great.
</P>
</TEXT>
