<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NHIS-JIFFYADV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRAVEN FOCUSING IN ON RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ It was the morning after the magical night before
and race car driver Ricky Craven, the pride of Newburgh, Maine, was
still toast of the track and the talk of the pits at New Hampshire
International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals raved about how Craven captured the moment Friday evening
and grabbed the top qualifying position for Sunday's Jiffy Lube 300
in his first competitive run in his Winston Cup car since March.
</P>
<P>
   How he grabbed the pole as the last car to go out to qualify.
Grabbed it in front of hometown fans on the track where he
established much of his fame.
</P>
<P>
   All certainly would wish Craven _ recently sidelined with
post-concussion syndrome _ luck the rest of the weekend, too.
</P>
<P>
   As long as he didn't mind luck that started with second place.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it was time to turn attention to Sunday's race.
</P>
<P>
   Craven recognized it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a perfect script as if someone had written it,'' Craven
said of his Friday night. ``You love to watch those movies. Well,
yesterday we played in it and it was pretty cool. Really the focus
now is that we've got half the job done and there's a still a lot
of work left.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also the focus of teammate Jeff Gordon, who is starting
alongside Craven on the front row and has won two races here, four
Cup races this year, and is the Cup points leader. And it is the
focus of Dale Jarrett and Chad Little, who start in the second row,
Jeff Burton and Kyle Petty in the row behind that.
</P>
<P>
   They are among the many who will make a run in Sunday's 300-lap
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're in pretty good shape,'' Jarrett said. ``If we
had to start the race right now, I think we'd have a car we could
put in the Top 5.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett and the others near the front of the pack have taken
care of step one _ track position _ for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Position on the track has always been hugely important here,
where the configuration with its tight, slightly-banked corners
make it tough to pass. Drivers can't carry a lot of speed into the
corners and thus have to worry about bringing their cars back up to
speed before they worry about passing as they head down the
straightaways.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't a place that's one of the easiest to pass,'' said Ken
Schrader, who is starting 26th. ``You need to get by people any way
you can. You try to get by them on the track, beat them in the
pits.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes a team effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to not only have a good car and driver, you've got
to really pay attention,'' said Ray Evernham, crew chief for Jeff
Gordon. ``You've got to have good pit stops. It falls on the whole
team and the crew chief.''
</P>
<P>
   Evernham and Gordon and Co. have made the track work. They won
the last race here in September when Evernham called for taking on
gas only during a late pit stop while challenger Ernie Irvan took
on tires. Gordon gained track position and Irvan could never catch
him.
</P>
<P>
   They also won in 1995, the only team with two victories here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tricky place,'' Evernham said. ``It's interesting for
fans and I guarantee one thing _ nobody is going to take off and
run away and make this a boring race.''
</P>
<P>
   Craven's crowd wouldn't mind a boring race. Or a win at the wire
for that matter. This is Winston Cup race No. 98 for Craven and
he's looking for his first victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're halfway there,'' one fan told him after practice
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he needed was to come home, right?'' another fan said to a
crew member outside Craven's hauler.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 2029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
