u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-FINALADV     07-11 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-FINALADVANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL IS CONFLICT OF STYLES, EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Regardless of the result of the World Cup final,
France's national team will be honored on the Champs-Elysees Monday
and participate in Bastille Day celebrations the next day. There is
a feeling of gratitude and relief that France has finally reached
the championship game, nearly 100 years after Frenchmen Gabriel
Hanot and Jules Rimet conceived the idea of a world championship.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's fate is not as certain. The Brazilians are 5,000 miles
from home, and the nature of their welcome is based solely on the
outcome of Sunday's game at Stade de France. Theirs is the only
country that has participated in every World Cup finals, and they
are fully expected to perform joyously and win every time.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations for France are different. Traditionally, Les Bleus
have charmed and enticed with skillful, thoughtful play.
Entertainment and style were first, results secondary. But in this
World Cup France has broken with tradition, using a pragmatic,
defensive scheme to steamroller into the championship game for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   So, what stereotyping would indicate to be an inspiring, all-out
attacking exhibition between Brazil's samba soccer and France's
champagne soccer will likely be a clash of South American flash and
European conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians, as usual, will come to play. But only after the
first 20 minutes _ which is about the amount of time coach Mario
Zagallo figures it will take for his team to find its rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   Unless an early goal is scored, there is little chance of this
game duplicating the fireworks of these nations' Mexico '86 meeting
in Guadalajara.
</P>
<P>
   France, which produced the World Cup's first goal in 1930 and
the event's all-time leading scorer, has recoiled into a defensive
shell. The French have scored 12 goals, one fewer than Just
Fontaine converted in leading them to third place in the 1958 World
Cup, and surrendered two.
</P>
<P>
   Either French sensibilities have changed, or the euphoria of
success has corrupted their appreciation of the aesthetics of
sport.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, other factors involved. After failing to
qualify for USA '94, France went nearly three years without losing,
convincing many that coach Aimee Jacquet was going in the right
direction.
</P>
<P>
   The team has also captured imaginations because of the way it
reflects the country's assimilation process. There is a strong
flavor of Africa, Armenia, the Caribbean, and Polynesia combined
with Basques, Bretons, and traditional Gallois. Jacquet has
successfully blended these players, dropping those who he
considered potential problems. That has meant the exclusion of
imaginative performers, leaving France without a playmaker in the
mold of Eric Cantona or Michel Platini. The skillful French players
_ Youri Djorkaeff, Zinedine Zidane _ do not perform efficiently, do
not make tasks appear easy, partially because of the composition of
the team.
</P>
<P>
   Jacquet has developed a group that destroys more than it
creates, earning him consistently strong criticism from the sports
daily L'Equipe. Midfielder Didier Deschamps, the captain and
France's player of the year two years ago, was described as a
``water carrier'' by Cantona. But these Gunga Dins of soccer are on
the verge of accomplishing more than the poets of the past,
prompting President Jacques Chirac to nominate the team for the
Legion of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   The domestique playing style can take a team only so far. Now,
the French must dredge up some creative elements, especially since
their defense could become vulnerable without Laurent Blanc,
suspended after being ejected from the 2-1 semifinal win over
Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil does not seem to have the same sense of purpose as the
1994 champions, whose uncompromising defensive tactics offended the
sensibilities of many Brazilians but provided the basis for a
championship.
</P>
<P>
   This Brazil team is in transition, not yet molded by the trials
of having to qualify for tournaments. Brazil has flaws _ a
vulnerable defense, lack of a true ``No. 10'' midfielder, an
unsettled striking combination. But the Brazilians have reverted to
their instincts, which means they will take chances.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, though this has been a wide-open World Cup, the best
match-ups have been when the Europeans have had to react to
unfamiliar or unorthodox tactics of African, Asian, Caribbean, and
Latin American teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play like Brazilians, creative football,'' Zagallo
said during training at Ozoir La Ferriere. ``I don't like European
football.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
