A0709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIRELAND-MARCH-NYT &LR;      07-11 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-MARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULSTER FOES IN LAST-DITCH EFFORT TO AVOID CLASH  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Protestant and Roman Catholic
officials, refusing to meet one another face to face, had several
hours of contact through intermediaries on Saturday, trying to
prevent increasing violence over the Protestant Orange Order's
insistence that it be allowed to march through a resentful Catholic
neighborhood in Portadown, west of here.
</P>
<P>
   Only slight progress was reported as the session was adjourned
until next week, possibly Tuesday. This meant that the two sides
were risking more violence among Protestants who want the march to
be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The march by the Orange Order, down the Garvaghy Road in the
Drumcree neighborhood, was blocked last Sunday by the British
government, which has deployed several thousand police officers and
army troops to keep the Protestants away from the Catholic area.
</P>
<P>
   The blockade has produced nightly violence by Protestant
protesters in Portadown, 25 miles west of here. The violence has
also spread to the rest of this predominantly Protestant British
province.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no agreement over the weekend, politicians and
security officials say, the violence will increase on Monday, when
more than 500 Orange parades are to take place.
</P>
<P>
   Protestants say the marches are a basic democratic right of
assembly and an expression of their cultural and historical
heritage, as they celebrate a 17th-century military victory of
Protestants over Catholics in Ireland. Catholics say the marches
are triumphalist and demeaning to them.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators were obeying rules that forbid them to talk to
reporters, who learned only that the talks were being held in a
local government office in Armagh, west of here. The talks were
initiated by Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain, who sent his
chief-of-staff, Jonathan Powell, to Belfast to arrange them. Two
intermediaries, called ``facilitators,'' were to shuttle between
the sides, which were in separate rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The impasse over the march was largely a matter of face-saving
for the Catholic Residents Coalition and the Orange Order. Neither
side wanted to be vulnerable to charges that it flinched or backed
down.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholics insisted that there be ``no Orange feet on the
Garvaghy Road,'' that the government ban on the march must be
enforced. Their leader, Breandan MacCionnaith, also insisted that
the Orangemen meet him face to face if they wanted to compromise.
They rejected his offer to allow a modest parade to pass down the
road next year, but not this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen object to meeting MacCionnaith because they
consider him a terrorist. He served three years in a British prison
for his role in the bombing of a Protestant meeting hall in
Portadown in 1981. He is not a member of Sinn Fein, the political
wing of the Irish Republican Army, but Sinn Fein helps him to be
elected a local councilor by not running its own candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians and security officials fear that if there is no
resolution to the dispute by tonight, tens of thousands of
Protestants from all over the province will march on Drumcree and
clash with the security forces blocking the roads connecting the
Protestant and Catholic areas.
</P>
<P>
   Catholics say the blockade, set up for their protection, is
putting them in a cage. To dramatize their contention, they have
been bringing in carloads of groceries and arguing that the
Orangemen and the army are trying to starve them.
</P>
<P>
   Since Sunday, the day the march was blocked, Protestant
protesters have attacked the police with more than 500 gasoline
bombs, hijacked and burned dozens of cars, and blocked major roads.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, protesters have broken through the first line of
three barbed-wire coils forming the defensive cordon, and they
seriously injured three policemen with homemade pipe bombs. Other
protesters shot large ball bearings out of slingshots. The police
responded by firing plastic bullets, which are rarely deadly.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday and Friday nights, the violence continued, although
news of the new talks appeared to have reduced the number of
protesters. On Thursday, the police estimated that there were
20,000; Friday night the number was down to 2,000 or 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, 20 civilians were injured, according to the
Orange Order. The police said 54 of their officers had been hurt.
They also released a film made Friday at Drumcree showing two
masked men firing rifles at the security forces. The shots hit no
one, the police added, but struck armored Land Rovers.
</P>
<P>
   Officials, Catholic and Protestant, fear that more violence is
likely over the weekend and on Monday, when tens of thousands of
Orangemen march throughout the province to celebrate the victory at
the 1690 Battle of the Boyne, which established Protestant
dominance and English rule in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The Drumcree crisis also threatens the stability of the Northern
Ireland peace agreement, approved last May, which provides the
province with a new Assembly to restructure politics to give the
Catholic minority more political power.
</P>
<P>
   If Protestant unionist members of the assembly were to resign
over the banning of the parade, the body would be weakened and this
could lead to a resumption of widespread sectarian guerrilla
warfare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
