<SLUG> BC-BRAWLEY-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAWLEY JURY DELIBERATES FOR A THIRD DAY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ The jury in the Tawana Brawley defamation
case deliberated for a third full day on Saturday without reaching
a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Deliberations of the six-member jury are to continue Monday,
after the sequestered jurors spend Sunday at a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at state Supreme Court said that the jurors sent at
least one note on Saturday, the contents of which were not publicly
described by the judge, S. Barrett Hickman. But participants in the
case said the jurors had asked for one of the many videotapes that
were part of the nearly eight-month trial in the civil suit against
three advisers to Ms. Brawley, Alton H. Maddox Jr., C. Vernon Mason
and the Rev. Al Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, these advisers said that Steven A. Pagones, a former
assistant district attorney in Dutchess County, kidnapped and raped
Ms. Brawley, who was 15 at the time. Pagones filed a defamation
suit seeking $400 million in damages after a grand jury in 1988
exonerated him and discredited Ms. Brawley's account.
</P>
<P>
   Asked on Saturday whether the lengthening deliberations were
worrisome, Pagones' lawyer, William E. Stanton, said he had not
expected a rapid verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very long case and a long verdict sheet'' that the
jurors must complete, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
