<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE TAKES AIM AT HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France A chance to make history drives both
combatants in tonight's World Cup final at the Stade de France,
although the aims, the means, even the dreams that guide the
masters from Brazil and the upstarts from France remain vastly
different.
</P>
<P>
   The final World Cup match of the century, and the 64th game of
this 33-day tournament, will either provide the Brazilians,
reigning champions and the world's most admired side, with an
unparalleled fifth title or add France to the roster of nations,
just six, that have won the title since its inception 68 years ago,
the first first-time winner since Argentina in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   It's a crown the Brazilians expect to lift indeed, nothing else
is acceptable but the French squad, whose run to the title game has
enveloped France in unprecedented euphoria, believe it has what it
takes to pull off an upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the chance to go down in history,'' says Zinedine
Zidane, the brilliant midfielder who dictates every aspect of
France's attack. ``We must grasp this chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 80,000 at the futuristic stadium in this Parisian suburb
and a television audience extimated at 1.7 billion will see the
French try to do so, a difficult assignment given Brazil's
abilities, experience and confidence. With Ronaldo and Rivaldo, two
of the world's finest attackers, running things up front, and the
rugged Dunga orchestrating from deep in midfield, the Brazilians
are a dream team, capable of striking from anyplace at any time.
</P>
<P>
   The champion may well be determined on how well France's
defense, which has surrendered only one goal from the run of play
during six World Cup matches, can contend with Brazil's
multipronged attack. The French's weapon in this regard is Marcel
Desailly, who has been flawless in the Cup; its Achilles is Laurent
Blanc, its superb libero who will watch from the bench after
receiving a controversial red card in France's semifinal win over
Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronaldo is public enemy No. 1,'' charged French captain Didier
Deschamps. ``Even if we mark him man-to-man, that might not be
enough to stop him because he is genius. ...He will cause us a lot
of problems if we let him play his own game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can stop him, but to do it we need to show real
intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   If France halts Ronaldo, at 21 acknowledged the world's greatest
player, there are plenty other weapons Brazil can call upon. They
have the veteran Bebeto and stunning Rivaldo, the best Brazilian
player in this tournament, plus wing-backs Roberto Carlos and Cafu,
and Denilson at $26 million the second-most expensive player on the
planet (after Ronaldo) coming off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   It's not rhetoric when France coach Aime Jacquet, who built a
superb team from the remnants of an ailing side that had failed to
qualify for the 1990 and 1994 World Cups, calls Brazil the
``masters of world football'' and the ``world's best team.'' And
although the French will have a decided home-field advantage, they
are aware they will be, for the first time this tournament, huge
underdogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not expected to win,'' admits Deschamps. ``A victory
would be a bonus. ... Brazil doesn't have to possess the ball to be
dangerous; tactically, we can't match up with them. We'll have to
focus on our strong points, namely defense, and I hope our defense
wins the battle, because they have the best attack in this World
Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians have scored 13 goals, four by Ronaldo and three
each by Rivaldo, Bebeto and Cesar Sampaio.Their defense is suspect,
but the French attack has been dormant since the knockout phase
began, scoring just three goals in three games, all by defenders.
</P>
<P>
   None of that may matter come kickoff. France will have the
majority of the fans, Brazil will have its history, its four
championships in 1958, 1962, 1970 and 1994 and the confidence that
success has instilled in the team.
</P>
<P>
   For the French, winning isn't everything. Getting to the final,
their first, has been a tremendous accomplishment, and the team's
responsibility in linking all strata of French society has, it is
hoped, opened doors that had long been slammed shut.
</P>
<P>
   Long considered one of Europe's most racist countries, an imaged
egged on by rightist politician Jean-Marie Le Pen's anti-foreigner
tirades, France has had a mirror turned on itself during the Cup,
primarily by its multicultural team.
</P>
<P>
   Zidane is Algerian, Desailly was born in Ghana, semifinal hero
Lilian Thuram is from Guadeloupe, and (ital) Les Bleus (end ital)
also have Armenians and Argentinians and players whose roots are
imbedded deep in the French turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``This mixed-race team says so much about who the French are
today,'' wrote Roland Castro, a leftist activist and architect, in
Liberation. ``These French people, that's France.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Prime Minister Lionel Jospin: ``Watching those we call
black and beurs (French-born North Africans) rejoicing, waving
tricolor flags and singing the Marseillaise ... made me feel these
were opportune images of the current period.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see all these French,'' Gaulist politician Philippe
Seguin notes, ``seemingly so different but in fact so similar,
sharing the same enthusiasm ... you wonder if there isn't a cement,
a principle, a solution to all our problems. And that is love of
France.''
</P>
<P>
   If the World Cup has, for once, unified the French, it has,
again, raised expectations on the Brazilians that they can not
afford to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a disaster for us if we do not win, but we will
win,'' says Coach Mario Zagallo, who as a player (in '58 and '62),
head coach (in '70) or assistant coach (in '94) has been a part of
Brazil's previous titles. ``We have reached the final of the World
Cup, but all this counts for nothing if we don't win the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not overconfident. I'm just confident, and this is what I
want to pass on to everyone. We all have our feet on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
