<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLOSERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Getting saves routinely
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Trevor Hoffman and Robb Nen, two of baseball's best
closers, are nasty pitchers: They wear goatees and snarl when they
go to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more to being a good closer than just the look.
</P>
<P>
   The two have different approaches, but they are getting similar
results.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' Nen has perhaps the heaviest workload of any
reliever. He already has thrown 55 1/3 innings in 45 appearances,
unheard of for a closer with half as many saves. Nen has allowed
only six runs and blown just one save and is striking out 1.3 an
inning. Hoffman's opponents are hitting just .177, and he has
converted 33 saves in a row, dating to last year.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's success is based on a mental approach with a strict
daily routine. For the first five innings, Hoffman sits in the San
Diego clubhouse. Then he takes a shower and heads to the training
room for an arm massage. He dresses, does eight arm exercises and
heads to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find (that) doing the same thing every game gets me into a
great routine, a pattern,'' Hoffman said. ``I also never think
about what happened the night before. If you look back, it has a
tendency to backfire. I look at it as going out and just getting
three outs, but I don't think about the second out until I get the
first one.''
</P>
<P>
   Nen also remains in the clubhouse the first five innings. In the
sixth, he puts a hot pack on his arm. In the seventh, he heads to
the bullpen, where he throws to outfielders between innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That tends to loosen me up,'' Nen said. ``I really don't try
to think about too much out there. You never think about a save you
blew the night before, or for that matter, you don't think about a
save you picked up. You take one game at a time. You focus on that
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Such routines are working not only for Hoffman and Nen but also
for a number of other closers, including Jeff Shaw, now of the
Dodgers; Montreal's Ugueth Urbina; Mariano Rivera of the Yankees;
John Wetteland of the Rangers; and Boston's Tom Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a bunch of guys throwing the snot out of the ball,''
Wetteland said.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman and Nen both say dominance can be fleeting.
</P>
<P>
   Nen has had his problems in the past, and Hoffman has had his
bad days. So there is hope for a strong return by Braves closer
Mark Wohlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is finding some momentum,'' Hoffman said. ``Once you
do, it steamrolls, and you take advantage of it. But it's just not
a one-game thing. You have to come to the park every night thinking
you are going in there, and you are going to get three outs.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
