<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ATHLETICS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALICEA LIFTS RANGERS PAST ATHLETICS, 4-2, IN NINTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ A crowd of 26,458 booed Luis Alicea at the
Oakland Coliseum yesterday over a hard-nosed play from the night
before. The Oakland Athletics would have been a more worthy
recipient of their derision.
</P>
<P>
   Two ninth-inning errors kept the Athletics from putting the
Rangers away, and Alicea made them pay for it, smacking a three-run
double to lift his team to 4-2 come-from-behind victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been booed like that before,'' Alicea said. ``It
will probably be worse tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the Rangers' third consecutive against the
Athletics, all coming in the ninth inning. They've also won five
consecutive games, going back to before the All-Star Game, a
winning streak that has pushed them back into first place in the
American League West for the first time since June 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go through a 162-game season, you go through some
downs, but in these three games, we've played a little bit
better,'' outfielder Rusty Greer said. ``Hopefully winning a game
like this, coming from behind in the ninth inning, will help
establish some confidence and momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, trailing 2-0, looked dead going into the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   They had managed just four hits off Oakland starter Blake Stein
through seven innings and had a budding eighth-inning rally snubbed
out by Athletics shortstop Miguel Tejada's dazzling double play.
</P>
<P>
   But the Athletics gave them one last chance.
</P>
<P>
   Greer started the comeback with a one-out single to right and
Ivan Rodriguez battled Fetters for a walk. Lee Stevens then hit a
possible double-play grounder to first baseman Brian Lesher, who
had just entered the game as a pinch runner in the eighth. But
Lesher fumbled the ball trying to get two and instead got none, an
error that left the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough enough in the major leagues when you've got to give
a team three outs,'' Fetters said. ``It's just about impossible
when you give them four and five outs.''
</P>
<P>
   Fetters got Kevin Elster on a soft line drive to Tejada, leaving
only Alicea. He was starting yesterday to give Fernando Tatis a day
off and was booed in every at-bat. Oakland fans were still miffed
at him for dumping Oakland catcher A.J. Hinch the night before on a
hard slide at home plate, a play the Athletics and umpire Jim Joyce
said was clean and legal.
</P>
<P>
   Alicea worked the count full, then belted one off the wall in
right-center to clear the bases. He's hitting .346 with runners in
scoring position this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a good split-finger (fastball), and he keeps the ball
down a lot,'' Alicea said. ``It was a do-or-die situation and I
just wanted to make sure I got a good pitch to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics then gave the Rangers an extra run when Rickey
Henderson dropped Tom Goodwin's easy pop fly in short left field.
The Rangers have scored nine runs in three games this series, and
eight of them have come in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the toughest one,'' Oakland manager Art Howe said.
``Our starting pitchers have gone out there for us and pitched
outstanding and have nothing to show for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Sele, continuing the Rangers' post-break run of good
starting pitching, wasn't bad, allowing only a two-run single to
Matt Stairs in the third. But it looked like it would be in a
losing effort against Stein, until the Athletics gave the Rangers a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win three straight low-scoring games, that's important,''
Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``I don't think most of these
guys realize it's OK to win a 4-1 ballgame. It looked like to me we
were out there pressing, thinking we needed to score eight runs to
win. We don't need to do that with this kind of pitching.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 2142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980711.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0748 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-MORMON-MISSIONS-A     07-11 2310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MORMON-MISSIONS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORMON MISSIONS AFFECT ATHLETES IN DIFFERENT WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Time is in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, after attending summer-school classes at Mesa
Community College, Clint Carlson lifts weights, runs sprints and
throws the football, trying to make up for lost time on the field.
</P>
<P>
   He knows that he has to prove himself to college coaches all
over again. But unlike some athletes who walk away from
scholarships for two years to spread a religious belief, the
passion to play still burns in the former Mesa Dobson High School
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest adjustment,'' he said, ``is getting back to
reality. For two years, you're separated from the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   From the summer of 1996 to the beginning of this summer, Carlson
did not touch a football. As part of his church commitment, he saw
no television. No movies. He didn't read the newspaper. He didn't
date. He rarely worked out.
</P>
<P>
   His only contact with his parents was through letters and the
two phone calls he was allowed to make to them each year _ on
Christmas and Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   In Oregon, a part of the world he didn't know before, he and a
companion studied Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints
scripture, prayed and shared their beliefs with those who would
listen _ many times getting doors slammed in their faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets discouraging,'' Carlson said. ``But the purpose of
what you're doing outweighs the discouragement and keeps you
going.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to serve the church was made easier for Carlson
after he broke an ankle after starting the first six games at
quarterback for Dixie College in southern Utah three seasons ago.
His mission, he said, was ``a spiritual awakening, the greatest
experience I ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   So great that as the time ap proached for his return to Mesa
from his two-year mission, Carlson lost 15 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my appetite,'' he said. ``I was depressed. It was hard
on me because I loved it so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he is getting used to what he calls ``civilian'' life. The
21-year-old gets up early for school. He throws spirals at night at
Scottsdale CC, where he said he may attempt to resume his football
career in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how fast I've picked things up since I left
home,'' said the 6-foot-3, 215-pound Carlson. ``I thought I'd have
to reteach myself. But I guess the Lord made up for what I lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlson said he is no different than most Mormon boys who grow
up eagerly awaiting the day they get the call to go out in the
world and teach the word. It is not required by the church, but
highly recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Some women and married couples go, but it is mostly young men
who take the call once they turn 19. They do not know where they
are going or whom they are going to be coupled with until the call
comes. They go in twos and can be sent anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   They generally save money to finance their missions by working
through high school. As a rule of thumb, it requires about $10,000
for a two-bedroom apartment. If they don't have enough saved, they
get financial help from family members or the church.
</P>
<P>
   College coaches pray their players aren't sent to Third World
nations, where they run the risk of malnutrition and disease.
</P>
<P>
   Brock Bevell, a tight end at Scottsdale Chaparral and Eastern
Arizona College, lost about 25 pounds during his mission in
Paraguay because of a parasite.
</P>
<P>
   He finally killed the parasite and regained the weight after he
returned home and began taking black walnut tablets. He played two
years at Eastern Arizona and now is a Mesa police officer.
</P>
<P>
   His older brother, Darrell, a quarterback at Chaparral in
1986-87, spent his mission in Cleveland, Ohio, a football hotbed.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell said there was much rejection, more bad days than good,
but he held onto his beliefs and said his missionary experience
strengthened him on the football field, where he later led
Wisconsin to a 1994 Rose Bowl victory over UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts life in perspective,'' Darrell said. ``When you have
guns pulled on you and dogs sicced on you, you come back to
Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   The journey isn't so perilous in most cases, and it is difficult
to find an athlete who calls his mission a waste of time and
unrewarding.
</P>
<P>
   Many return more physically and mentally mature, ready to take
on anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it was an advantage,'' said Fred Mortensen, a former
Tempe High quarterback who, after serving his church mission,
helped Arizona State beat Nebraska in the Fiesta Bowl in the 1975
season and later, spent five seasons in the NFL as a backup. ``You
learn what it takes to be happy and content and deal with the
challenges that go along with performing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rattlers Coach Danny White, a Mormon whose two sons went on
church missions, elected to play out his football career at Arizona
State instead of going on a mission in the early 1970s. He ended up
setting many school passing records and captured two Super Bowl
rings with the Dallas Cowboys. But he said he now regrets not
serving a mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't as much emphasis on serving a full-time mission
as there is now,'' White said. ``I had advice from church leaders.
Some said to stay under scholarship. I took advantage of the full
ride to ASU.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all changed now. Kids mature a lot during those two
years. If the athlete is in them, I don't think (the mission) will
take it out of them. More colleges are seeking returned
missionaries.''
</P>
<P>
   That's especially true in Utah, which has the largest Mormon
population in the world. On the Utah football team, there are 38
returned missionaries, including former Mesa High all-state center
and linebacker Steve McKane, one of four brothers who have served
missions.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Ron McBride, in his ninth year at Utah, started a
missionary program seven years ago. It basically reactivates a
player's scholarship upon his return. The NCAA clearing house is
notified, and the player's eligibility clock is put on pause once
he enters the missionary training center.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our state, you have to (accept missionaries) or forget
about recruiting the state,'' McBride said. ``Ninety-six percent of
the kids we recruit go on missions.''
</P>
<P>
   The returned missionaries leave school as grown men, at age 23
or 24, instead of 21 or 22, causing some to feel it's boys against
men on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember a Wisconsin player saying, `It was like having a
man in the huddle,' '' Jim Bevell said about his son, Darrell.
</P>
<P>
   McBride said the maturity level, the dedication and the work
ethic, pay off in the long run. Utah has played in four bowl games
in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they're on their missions, they think about the things
they want to do,'' McBride said. ``Sometimes, kids do change. The
importance of what they're doing can do that. But in most cases,
the same football guys come back with the same passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are concerns from college coaches who may have
immediate needs to fill and are more willing to give a scholarship
to a player they know is committed to athletics for four
uninterrupted seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Brigham Young quarterback Todd Mortensen, who said he will
embark on his mission in October, discovered that in 1996, his
senior year at Tempe High, where he led the Buffaloes to an
undefeated state championship season. Many schools backed off on
recruiting him once they learned he planned to go on a mission. Not
Brigham Young, which will have 50 returned missionaries on this
year's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of colleges are not recruiting missionaries in general,
because they have immediate needs at a position and they don't want
to wait,'' said Mortensen, Fred's son, who redshirted last season
and will have four years of college eligibility beginning in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had older cousins serve missions, and I've seen the
rewards in their lives and how happy they are. I can't wait to go.
I feel I'll come back much more able to focus on my goals.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU Coach Bruce Snyder, who coached eight years at Utah State,
recruited Mortensen. He signed Mesa Mountain View tight
end/linebacker Todd Heap, knowing that last year's Arizona Player
of the Year intends to serve a mission after this season. Heap's
true value in a Sun Devils uniform may not be seen for another four
years. Snyder is patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan to still be here in four years,'' Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   Heap said he wants to compete for playing time his freshman
year, then go on a mission. If he has to redshirt, four years of
eligibility await him when he returns. Provided he still wants to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big gamble for a coach, especially if you sign a kid
before he goes on his mission,'' McBride said. ``We've had a great
deal of luck with our kids. They brought a lot of maturity to our
football team. I think they learn a lot about themselves, about the
world, about dedication, about sacrifice and things that are
important. It's a huge plus for a young kid.''
</P>
<P>
   At ASU, Snyder has had only a handful of missionaries, including
safety Paul Reynolds, even though Arizona ranks among the top four
states in LDS membership. Snyder said he doesn't try to avoid the
missionary athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``You manage your numbers,'' he said. ``You look at your depth
chart and see if you can withstand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder has found the missionary athlete to be coachable and
unselfish, people he doesn't have to worry about getting in
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, when you get one back that is focused, you have a mature
person,'' he said. ``I'm not LDS, but you give yourself to a bigger
picture. That's what I like. Everybody gives up a little
individuality for the greater good of the group.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, much goes on in an athlete's head during the two years
spent living in a spiritual, rather than athletic, world.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson said he feels stronger, more confident on the field than
when he left Dixie. He said there is structure, discipline, a
mental toughness to get through a routine that wasn't there before.
</P>
<P>
   But he admitted it's a struggle at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``You pretty much know what direction you're going when you
leave for a mission,' said his father, Dave Carlson. ``You know
what to do every day, what the objectives are. For two years,
you're feeling very spiritual. When you come home, people are
pulling you in a lot of different directions.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard on the parents, too.
</P>
<P>
   Dobson football Coach Mike Clark cried the day his son, Cauley,
an outstanding tight end and trumpet player, went away to serve his
mission in Argentina nearly two years ago. He returns home July 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a happy sorrow,'' Clark said. ``I miss him every day. But
I wouldn't want him anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   There are currently more than 58,000 missionaries serving in the
world, most of whom are young men like Carlson, who left behind a
girlfriend, a loving family and an athletic dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've found that they come come back in one or two
extremes,'' Snyder said. ``One, being really committed
athletically. Or, they completely have a non-athletic direction,
like, `I've outgrown it, it was fun while I did it, but I've got
other things.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter Moore's last basketball game was played at America West
Arena in 1995, when the 6-foot-5 forward helped Mountain View cap a
31-0 season with a victory over Shadow Mountain in the 5A final.
</P>
<P>
   He received numerous offers from junior colleges to play
basketball but decided to serve a mission for two years in Omaha,
Neb., where he teamed with a BYU football player. His partner now
is having trouble returning to a field of hate, Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're taught to love everybody (on the mission), have fun,
treat people well,'' Moore said. ``On the court, the golden rule is
to do unto others before they do unto you.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that was the hardest thing, turning on that switch.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore has kept the switch off, satisfied that his athletic
career ended with a high school championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some people, the switch turns off for good and you don't
want the super adrenaline of sports rushing anymore,'' Moore said.
``While on my mission, I learned that there are other things more
important than basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore fell in love when he returned home this spring. He helps
run a florist shop in east Mesa with his fiancee, Julie, and dreams
of starting a family, not making jump shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the mission taught me the basics of life, being in a
good relationship with God, working hard, loving what you do,''
Moore said. ``It taught me to love work, to love people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if I hadn't found out what I wanted out of life, the
other side of life, I'd go after sports right now.''
</P>
<P>
   If Clint Carlson learned anything on his mission, it is how
fleeting football can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football, before, was my life,'' he said. ``Now it's real
temporary. Just like life is. Anything can end right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Bevell never let his football dream end, despite going
five years without taking a snap.
</P>
<P>
   He missed his senior season in high school because of a broken
finger, spent a redshirt season at Northern Arizona, served a
two-year mission, then transferred to Wisconsin and sat out another
year. Once he got back on the field, however, he held the starting
job for four years, a tenure highlighted by running for the winning
touchdown in the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't happen all the time,'' said Bevell, now the
receivers coach at the University of Connecticut. ``I had
confidence in my abilities. I had faith in what I was doing at the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlson hopes for a similar storybook ending to his football
career. But if it doesn't happen, Carlson feels he's already done
something for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole lot more after this life than what I'm living
right now,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
