<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0916 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITISHOPEN-ADVANCE-C     07-11 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISHOPEN-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    '98 Open returns to Birkdale
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ It is not the most glamorous venue of those
in the British Open rotation. It is not dripping with as much
tradition or natural beauty as St. Andrews, Turnberry or Royal
Troon. Yet much has transpired here at Royal Birkdale Golf Club,
where American Justin Leonard will defend his title beginning
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A seaside links course marked by huge sandhills and
rough-covered dunes _ even a clubhouse shaped like the bridge of a
giant tanker to extend the nautical theme _ Royal Birkdale is:
</P>
<P>
   Where Australian Ian Baker-Finch won the British Open in 1991,
then began a slide from which he never recovered, finally quitting
competitive play because he worried about injuring people in the
gallery. Baker-Finch will be at Royal Birkdale this week, but as a
TV analyst for ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Where Arnold Palmer prevailed in 1961, striking a bold shot out
of deep rough on the 15th hole, slashing at the ball with such
power that it defined the style that thrilled his armies for the
next decade. A plaque marks the spot today.
</P>
<P>
   Where Hale Irwin in 1983 whiffed the ball as he extended to tap
in a two-inch putt and eventually lost by a one stroke to Tom
Watson despite a final-round 67.
</P>
<P>
   Where Lee Trevino nearly blew a three-stroke lead on the 17th
tee, barely pulling out a victory in 1971 over Formosan Liang Huan
Lu.
</P>
<P>
   Where Johnny Miller shot a final-round 66 in 1976, manufacturing
a six-shot win over Seve Ballesteros and Jack Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   Major changes have been made to Royal Birkdale since
Baker-Finch's victory in '91. All the greens were rebuilt between
1992 and 1994 to improve what had been a suspect putting surface.
The turf was lifted and a ``problem layer'' about 2 to 6 inches
below the surface was replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greens are going to putt considerably harder than in
1991,'' says Michael Bonnallack, secretary of the Royal &AMP; Ancient
Golf Club. ``They are beautifully contoured and were pretty quick
even in March.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddsmakers have made Ernie Els the favorite at 9-1, followed by
Tiger Woods (10-1), David Duval (12-1), Colin Montgomerie (15-1),
Davis Love III (18-1) and Lee Westwood (18-1). Leonard is 20-1,
along with Fred Couples and Tom Lehman. U.S. Open champion Lee
Janzen is 25-1, with Masters champion Mark O'Meara 33-1.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a poor U.S. Open, Leonard will be looking for last
year's splendid memories _ a final-round 65 that ranks as one of
the finest in major championship history _ to return him to
contending form.
</P>
<P>
   A question mark for much of the last two years largely because
of putting problems, England's Nick Faldo is an even greater
unknown for Royal Birkdale. The three-time British Open champion
pulled out of this past week's Loch Lomond World Invitational
because of ``stabbing pain'' in his right elbow, which was put in a
soft cast.
</P>
<P>
   Scotland's Montgomerie has been in such a cranky mood lately,
you would think he was preparing to play in the States again. He
skipped the awards ceremony following the Irish Open and then
refused to talk about his opening round of 73 at Loch Lomond.
Montgomerie declined to talk to reporters after his Saturday round
in Ireland because of a newspaper article written about his temper.
</P>
<P>
   The British Open field will include Georgia Tech's Matt Kuchar,
who missed the cut at Loch Lomond and has been made a 99-1 choice.
While speculation continues about the 20-year-old U.S. Amateur
champion's pro plans, Kuchar will try to make it three straight
major championships successes. He finished 21st at the Masters and
tied for 14th at the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus, 58, pulled out of the British Open on Wednesday
because of groin and hip problems, ending at 154 his streak of
major championships for which he has been eligible. Son Gary,
however, could carry on the tradition if he qualifies today and
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have to try that much harder now in the qualifier now
that Dad's made his decision not to play,'' said the 29-year-old
Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
