<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0921 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      07-11 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COOLEST TACO STAND IN AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)   By E.J. MONTINI 
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
It was dollar-off-taco day at Pepe's North of the Border, and the
place was jammed with tourists _ 114 by Fran Tate's count.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Here I am wearing a halter top and short pants, and I'm still
swea tin','' she said. ``I had to go over and prop the front door
open to get some air circulating.''
</P>
<P>
   No sooner did Tate turn her back, however, than a German tourist
scurried over to the door and slammed it shut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freezing!'' said the man, who wore a fur-trimmed parka inside
the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you kidding?'' Fran said, fanning herself. ``It's
sweltering out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The man shook his head. Fran smiled and ambled over to a group
of Japanese customers. They ap peared to be a little concerned over
the menu item referred to as a ``burro.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, when the crowd thinned out and Fran had time to talk, I
asked her exactly how hot it was at Pepe's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a second,'' she said, ``I'll go check the thermometer.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 52 degrees outside,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There was a longer pause.
</P>
<P>
   `'Are you there?'' Fran asked.
</P>
<P>
   More pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the matter?'' she said. ``How hot is it down in
Phoenix?''
</P>
<P>
   I told her.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that's why you're calling,'' she said. ``Well, why don't
you just hop in the car and drive up here? Tell them you're going
for takeout.''
</P>
<P>
   It was shortly after 11 a.m. &QL; 
MISS THE SPECIAL, TOO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If I left the office right then, drove straight to the
restaurant and back, I could be sitting in front of the computer
again by, say, mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd probably miss the taco special, too,'' Fran said.
</P>
<P>
   Pepe's North of the Border is lo cated in Point Barrow, Alaska,
a town at the edge of Arctic Ocean, about 600 miles from the North
Pole.
</P>
<P>
   Some years ago I visited there.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists pass through on sightsee ing packages tied to nature
and commerce _ the midnight sun and the big oil fields.
</P>
<P>
   Just outside Barrow is the spot where Will Rogers and the
aviator Wiley Post died in a plane crash in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, Fran Tate quit her job at a drilling station
to open Pepe's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been pushing tacos ever since,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There've been a lot of changes over the years. When Fran
arrived, Barrow was home to 1,700 citizens and thousands more
caribou. Now there are more than 4,000 residents _ and thousands
more caribou.
</P>
<P>
   ``Progress,'' she said. ``But I guess it isn't so bad. One of
the oil companies painted my building re cently. Things are looking
up. And, it's beginning to feel like summer.''
</P>
<P>
   The ocean, which was frozen solid for months, has begun pulling
away from the shore. The ice is breaking up. &QL; 
TIME FOR A CALL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I think of it,'' Fran said, ``this is the time of
year you usually call.''
</P>
<P>
   I've contacted her several times over the years, mostly when the
temperature in Phoenix creeps over 100 _ and stays there _ and the
humidity slips under the door like an evil spirit, wrapping its
hands around our throats.
</P>
<P>
   Starved for a cool break but un able to get out of town, I'll
take a quick trip, by ear, to Barrow.
</P>
<P>
   They'd just been through a heat wave, Fran said. There were
record-breaking high temperatures. One day in late June it got all
the way up to 63 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   `'Must have been El Nino,'' she said, ``Or Nino El, or whatever
it is we're blaming everything on these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Other days, it's cold enough for snow flurries. I can picture
them, now, swirling gently like feathers or knifing sideways in the
wind.
</P>
<P>
   Walking in the wind at Barrow can be work. There are no trees to
hide behind. Nothing to slow down the fierce gusts. A person has to
tilt forward and fight for every step. It can use you up, make you
tired and hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Just writing about it gives me an appetite.
</P>
<P>
   I'm thinking . . . tacos. &QL; 
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
