<HEADER>
A0923 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-METROSTARS-TAMPA-     07-11 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-METROSTARS-TAMPA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROSTARS ARE AGAIN FRUSTRATED AT HOME BY LOWLY MUTINY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Tampa Bay Mutiny has the worst
record in Major League Soccer this season, but it has had plenty of
success against the MetroStars. The Mutiny has only five victories,
but it defeated the MetroStars Saturday night by 2-1 for its second
victory at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the MetroStars' losses against Tampa Bay came even
though they dominated the action. The first loss, a little more
than a month ago, was because of brilliant goalkeeping by Thomas
Ravelli. Saturday night the MetroStars simply could not turn their
domination into goals, even though Ravelli was missing.
</P>
<P>
   Ravelli was suspended by the league's disciplinary committee and
was fined $5,000 on Friday for hitting Referee Ruben Rodhas with a
kicked ball in Tampa Bay's loss to New England a week ago. Ravelli
lost his temper following a penalty kick for New England in the
75th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Petras started in goal for the Mutiny Saturday night, and
the MetroStars tested him early, taking three shots in the first
five minutes. The young goalkeeper responded well before the
MetroStars beat him in the 11th minute for their only goal.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Rooney scored on a blast from outside the penalty area,
after an exchange of passes between Eduardo Hurtado and Giovanni
Savarese and a pass by Tab Ramos, who played with more gusto than
all the other MetroStars. Ramos was a constant threat, whether he
was attacking down the right flank or through the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Prampin tied the game for Tampa Bay with a header from
close range in the 36th minute, when the MetroStars' defenders were
caught flat-footed and goalie Tony Meola was left at the mercy of
Prampin, who converted a pass from Steve Ralston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lapse of concentration by our defense,''
MetroStars Coach Alfonso Mondelo said. ``This was very frustrating
and disappointing because the playoff race is getting tight.''
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars are third in the Eastern Conference with a 9-9
record.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay scored its winning goal five minutes into the second
half when Jan Eriksson leaped high and headed the ball past Meola
after a corner kick from the right side by Paul Dougherty, who was
traded to Tampa Bay by the MetroStars last month for Mike Duhaney.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave it away on the corner kick,'' Meola said. ``You can
run all game, but if you don't run five yards to cover on a corner
kick, you pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay, which is last in the Eastern Conference, is an
improved team since Tim Hankinson took over as coach from John
Kowalski four games ago. Hankinson has made several personnel
changes and may be on the right track in getting the team in the
playoff picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed some firepower in midfield, and we had to make
adjustments,'' Hankinson said. ``We have to roll up our sleeves and
work hard. We were sitting in last place, and we knew we had to put
some things together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 2257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980711.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0925 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-N     07-11 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BEAT TAMPA BAY, 2-0  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ As the chauffeur for David Cone's
comeback, catcher Joe Girardi has uttered superlatives after many
of Cone's outings. His best stuff of the season, Girardi said after
a game in May, after another game in June, and again last week.
</P>
<P>
   As Girardi started to offer the same analysis again Saturday
night, after Cone beat Tampa Bay, 2-0, with eight shutout innings,
Girardi stopped himself. ``We talk about this every time, don't
we?'' he said to reporters, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Yes. It seems as if Cone's stuff is always getting better, he
always wins, and the Yankees cannot possibly lose a game. They have
won nine straight, their second streak of nine victories this
season, and that has not happened since the 1961 season. They are
14 games ahead of Boston, the Yankees' largest American League East
lead since July 25, 1976. Their 64-20 record matches the 1902
Pittsburgh Pirates for the best 84-game record this century. The
Yankees' last loss occurred at Shea Stadium, in the 2-1 decision
against the Mets on June 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let me look at it,'' Manager Joe Torre said of the
team's record, ``because then you start dealing with the law of
averages.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are creating new laws, new standards. Mariano Rivera
pitched the ninth inning for his 24th save, and before he allowed a
bloop single to Paul Sorrento with Wade Boggs at second, Yankees
pitchers had not allowed a hit with runners in scoring position in
39 consecutive innings. Opponents had been 0 for 32 in that
situation.
</P>
<P>
   And now Cone is 13-2 and tied for the major league lead in
victories, incredibly, after pitching so badly in his first two
starts of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu and his interpreter, George Rose, went for lunch
Saturday, and Rose relayed the view of others that Irabu had shown
great fortitude in his victory on Friday. In response, Irabu
mentioned Cone. How could I quit, Irabu explained, after watching
the way Cone kept fighting in April?
</P>
<P>
   Cone briefly thought about quitting three months ago, after
giving up 16 runs in his first nine and two-thirds innings. Since
then, however, he has a 2.72 earned run average, and it is as if he
is getting better and better. ``I'm thrilled with the way things
have gone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cone battled for command in the first two innings, and from the
Yankees' dugout, Torre could see him stomp around the mound a bit,
frustrated. Pitching in a new ballpark, on an unfamiliar mound,
Cone said later, can require some adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   But it just so happened that Cone was finishing his delivery by
landing in the same hole as the Tampa Bay starter Rolando Arrojo,
and this helped Cone find his rhythm quickly. By the third inning,
he was dominating, his fastball reaching 91 miles an hour, and he
often threw his curveball for first-pitch strikes against
left-handed batters. After Kevin Stocker's double in the third
inning, Cone allowed a single hit the rest of the game, retiring 12
of 13 hitters at one point. He walked Boggs three times, the only
three walks he permitted, and struck out eight.
</P>
<P>
   Cone pitched knowing the Yankees would be fortunate to squeeze
more than a run or two from Arrojo, the Devil Rays' All-Star
pitcher who, like Orlando Hernandez, is a defector from Cuba and a
master of many angles.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo was with Cuba's national team in the summer of 1996, and
the team stopped to play in Albany, Ga. On the night of July 9,
Arrojo called Joe Cubas, an agent who was staying in the same
hotel, and said, ``Come get me.'' In his pajamas, Arrojo slipped
out of his room at midnight, and he and Cubas drove to Miami.
(Seventeen months later, Cubas would aid Hernandez after the
pitcher escaped Cuba).
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo, who is right-handed, throws harder than Hernandez, and
when he drops his shoulder and throws sidearm, he intimidates
right-handed batters. Going into tonight's game, they were batting
.149 against him, or 168 points less than left-handed batters.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the right-handed hitting Chuck Knoblauch who was
responsible for both of the Yankees' runs. Arrojo hit Knoblauch
with a fastball to lead off the game, and Knoblauch stole second
and scored when Quinton McCracken misplayed a line drive by Paul
O'Neill into a double.
</P>
<P>
   Six innings later, Scott Brosius blooped a single and Joe
Girardi followed with a hit-and-run base hit. Brosius scored when
Knoblauch hit a fly deep to center.
</P>
<P>
   Cone flirted with real jeopardy only in the sixth. He walked
Boggs with two outs and then threw a first-pitch curveball to Fred
McGriff. The slugger anticipated this, and smashed a high drive to
right. Cone was sure it was a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neill settled under the ball at the warning track, and
Cone cruised through the final two innings, cutting down the last
hitter he faced, McCracken, with a backdoor slider that broke over
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The best pitch he threw, Girardi agreed. The best. But that is
what has been said about the Yankees all year.
</P>
</TEXT>
