<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLIONAIRES FIND THEIR DESERT DREAM BEHIND GUARDED GATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)   By CATHERINE REAGOR  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a few millionaires, Lost Canyon north of Scottsdale is a
saguaro-laden Shangri-La with a security gate.
</P>
<P>
   It's a place where they can build their own playground on their
own chunk of pristine desert.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the buyer from the East Coast who is planning a 14-car
garage with a remote-controlled turntable. Why? So he can punch a
button and rotate his vehicles into easy reach like a tuna sandwich
in a vending machine.
</P>
<P>
   A buyer from Texas paid a couple of million dollars for her
privacy. She bought 12 acres of Sonoran Desert so she can build a
home far enough from neighbors so she doesn't have to hear the ice
cubes clinking in their single-malt Scotch on the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Another landowner is installing a shooting gallery in his home.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the buyers in Lost Canyon will have their own
private desert hiking trails in their back yards.
</P>
<P>
   Don't bother trying to get a look at it. The
not-so-rich-and-famous are locked out. A guard will be posted 24
hours, making it possibly the only gated-canyon community in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's how developer Kent Heyl bills it. He bought 240
acres, or three-eighths of a square mile, from the State Land
Department for $4.2 million in 1994. Heyl, who is moving to the
canyon himself from Paradise Valley, put almost $6 million into
developing it as a private and posh retreat for those who can
afford entry.
</P>
<P>
   He got the land before the political climate changed toward
developing desert land in north Scottsdale. Several developments in
the area during the past few years have been nixed because of
opposition from desert preservationists.
</P>
<P>
   Heyl says preservation activists should not object to Lost
Canyon, because most of the land will never be developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their desert,'' Heyl says of his wealthy clients. ``If
someone buys 6 acres, they are only allowed to build on one. The
rest is untouched desert land.''
</P>
<P>
   Housing experts say that Lost Canyon, with its aura of seclusion
and luxury, is the latest hot property for the rich.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Paul Cook, a real estate analyst with Landiscor, said
years ago the exclusive areas that the rich coveted were Casa
Blanca near Camelback Mountain and the Biltmore Estates around the
resort. Then Paradise Valley became the first choice of the
wealthy. Golf course developments like Estancia and Desert Mountain
in north Scottsdale were next.
</P>
<P>
   Now, said Cook, many people with money want untouched desert
land and are willing to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Affluent buyers in Lost Canyon are shelling out up to $1.1
million for land alone. Their ``Architectural Digest''-quality
houses will cost at least another $3 million to $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a sanctuary to drive home to every night,'' said
Jim Pupillo, an executive with the investment firm Smith Barney in
Scottsdale, who is building a home on a 9-acre parcel.
</P>
<P>
   The homes planned for Lost Canyon could provide material for
several episodes of ``Lifestyles for the Rich and Famous.''
</P>
<P>
   A billionaire who recently bought in Lost Canyon is
contemplating buying a 300-year old Mexican mansion made of stone
and having it shipped to his Lost Canyon lot.
</P>
<P>
   Several homes will be equipped with wide-screen movie theaters
complete with curtains, stadium seating, soft-drink machines and
popcorn makers that use real butter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked all over the Valley and found nothing as unique as
Lost Canyon,'' said Zoran Maric, an orthopedic surgeon who with his
wife, Debbie, is building a multimillion-dollar home with a copper
roof and an unblemished view of the McDowell Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The Marics' home, going up on a $900,000 lot, will have a movie
theater with three-tiered seating, a wine cellar and a pool and
Jacuzzi built into the natural boulder formations that are part of
the back yard of their 9-acre spread.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty of the 35 lots have been sold, averaging around 6{ acres
each. Heyl had planned for 50 buyers but cut it back to get more
open space.
</P>
<P>
   The surrounding space is safe from future development because
it's been set aside to be put in the McDowell Sonoran Preserve,
while nature has provided a getaway that can be locked away.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what drew one couple, Craig and Karen Stull. The
Stulls' new home, which will feature an underground movie theater
and lagoonlike swimming pool with waterfall and boulders, is under
construction on a 3.5-acre parcel in Lost Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago, I was reading ``Phoenix Home &AMP; Garden''
magazine, when I saw this ad for the only gated-canyon community in
Arizona,''said Craig Stull, who owns a national computer consu
lting firm.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife came to Phoenix from Virginia shortly after,
drove straight to the community, even though it wasn't officially
open for sales, and bought a site.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this is the last chance to buy such a unique
property.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like oceanfront property,'' said Norm Kitzmiller of
Pinnacle Peak Realty Inc., who sells homes in the area and whose
company is marketing the lots. ``When its gone. It's gone.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Catherine Reagor can be reached at 444-8040 or at
catherine.reagor &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-98 2303EDT &QL; 
