</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT EXPOS, 8-4  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was a roar from the crowd at Shea Stadium
Saturday night when Todd Hundley's name was announced in the
lineup. There was another ovation when he emerged from the dugout
to play some catch, accompanied by a big smile and a tip of his
cap.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley doffed the cap again to the fans along the left-field
line as he made his way to the outfield for the first time in a
major league game. And he got a standing ovation as he stepped to
the plate as a Met for the first time since last September.
</P>
<P>
   The 48,006 fans on hand for Hundley's return _ there were
approximately 35,000 tickets sold since Monday's announcement that
he would play _ remained on their feet through a called strike and
two balls, before Hundley flared a single to right-center field in
his first at-bat of 1998. And that brought the biggest cheers of
all. For the first time in weeks, everything seemed to be clicking
at Shea.
</P>
<P>
   Not even a blown three-run lead could dampen the evening, as the
Mets (45-41) rallied for a pair of fifth-inning runs on their way
to an 8-4 victory over the Montreal Expos. The Mets snapped a
five-game losing streak to give Rick Reed his 10th victory of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   So what if it was not entirely a storybook evening? There were
no home runs from the converted catcher, no sensational plays in
left. Instead, Hundley, who fielded the only two balls hit his way
without incident, finished 1 for 4, and drove a ball to the warning
track in right in his second at-bat, before being removed for
defensive purposes after striking out in the bottom of the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest hits belonged instead to John Olerud and Mike
Piazza. Olerud belted a pair of home runs to become the first Met
to reach 50 runs batted in this year, and Piazza, the catcher who
has taken Hundley's place, drove in Olerud from first with an
opposite-field double in the fifth to break a 3-3 tie.
</P>
<P>
   But Hundley's mere presence in the lineup had its desired
effect. The top five hitters in the order accounted for the Mets'
first six runs. Olerud was 4 for 4 with three runs scored and three
runs batted in. He, Piazza and Bernard Gilkey each drove in a run
in the same game for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   As Hundley had said before the game, ``It's good to be back
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Gilkey had said it felt like a homecoming or a reunion.
There was his best friend, Hundley, back in the Mets' clubhouse,
wearing his old No. 9 and ready to play in a major league game for
the first time since undergoing reconstructive elbow surgery over
nine months ago.
</P>
<P>
   And with Greg McMichael back in a new locker, too, after five
weeks as a Los Angeles Dodger, the playful banter came from all
over the room:
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, it's like the first day of school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Has anybody seen Mlicki?''
</P>
<P>
   McMichael, who was traded with Dave Mlicki for Hideo Nomo on
June 4 and then back to the Mets on Friday night for Brian Bohanon,
even got the final two outs in relief.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in a couple of weeks, there was a genuine
feeling of warmth spreading around the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets might have dropped 9 of their last 11 games before
Saturday night, but their leader on the field was back in uniform,
and there was another familiar face around to bolster a struggling
bullpen. And that is why General Manager Steve Phillips remarked,
``I probably feel more peaceful than I should.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley was so excited, he barely slept on Friday night in
Indianapolis, where he had played two games with Class AAA Norfolk.
Manager Bobby Valentine asked the two-time All-Star catcher where
he felt most comfortable in the outfield; Hundley had played both
left and right in the minors. Hundley picked left field, and for
the first time since Sept. 7, 1993, Gilkey made a start in right.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, on Hundley's first day as an outfielder, Butch Huskey
became the odd man out. He did not sound happy about it, although
Valentine said that Huskey would play Sunday, so either Gilkey or
Brian McRae will take a day off.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine did not ask Hundley where he preferred to hit.
Saturday night, Hundley batted cleanup, behind Piazza and in front
of Gilkey, with Edgardo Alfonzo leading off and Olerud hitting
second.
</P>
<P>
   And the Mets responded right away with a pair of first-inning
runs, one more in the second, two in the fifth, another in the
seventh and finally two in the eighth on McRae's 11th home run of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Hundley arrived, Gilkey, Huskey and McRae had
started hitting, perhaps mindful that their playing time would soon
be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the last couple of days were any indication, it might spark
everyone into getting a couple more hits,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine sure was right on that.
</P>
</TEXT>
