</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-AUTOPSY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTOPSY SAYS HEART DISEASE KILLED ABIOLA  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update and refine)   By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria _ American and other Western doctors who
completed an autopsy on Saturday on the body of Moshood K.O.
Abiola, the Nigerian opposition leader who died in detention on
Tuesday, said they had found no evidence of poisoning and concluded
that his death was caused by heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary report, anxiously awaited by an angry and
disoriented nation, showed that ``there was severe longstanding
disease of the heart of a type and severity that can cause
unexpected death,'' said Dr. James G. Young, the chief coroner of
the province of Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   The results, confirming the official account of Abiola's death
given by the Nigerian military government, seemed unlikely to
assuage Nigerians, who have reacted with fury to the death of the
opposition leader on the eve of his promised release by the new
military ruler, Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria, Africa's most populous nation, has been ruled by
military governments for all but 10 years of its 38 years of
independence. Abiola, who appeared poised to win presidential
elections in 1993 when the armed forces annulled the vote,
incarnated the country's long-frustrated hopes for democracy. He
was imprisoned by the military government on charges of treason in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who headed a five-man team including two American doctors
and an American technician, said that after a detailed examination
of the body including the abdomen, chest and brain, and after
conversations with witnesses present at the time of death, ``we
believe that poisoning is extremely unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that for the sake of complete certainty,
toxicological examinations of samples taken from the body would be
performed at the Center of Forensic Science in Ontario. He said
that tissue samples would also undergo microscopic examination in
London and that a final report would be issued in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Family members and followers of Abiola have argued that he was
poisoned, pointing to the cup of tea he drank with the U.S.
undersecretary of state for political affairs, Thomas Pickering,
and other American and Nigerian officials shortly before he was
taken ill.
</P>
<P>
   But Young said nothing that happened on the day of Abiola's
death, or that was in his body, ``lead us to believe that poisoning
was a factor.'' He added, ``At this time, our preliminary opinion
is that death was due to natural causes as a result of his
longstanding heart disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Abiola, 60, had never had a heart attack before. Young said his
team had not been given any written medical reports compiled during
the opposition leader's four years in detention, but had talked to
Nigerian medical officials who said they had seen him in those
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's irrelevant,'' Kola Abiola, the opposition
leader's son, said of the autopsy. ``You don't have to poison a
man, you don't have to spike his tea, to kill him. My father was
locked up for four years without proper medical treatment, and that
is what leads to death. We know who was responsible for locking him
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Kola Abiola on Saturday presided at the tumultuous burial of
Abiola in the front yard of the large Abiola family compound in
Lagos. Women sobbed and men wailed as the body, wrapped in white
cloth as prescribed by Muslim custom, was laid to rest in the red
earth, beneath a palm tree, just eight hours after the autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   For a national figure of such standing, the attendance was not
huge, amounting to perhaps 500 people. Representatives of the
government were conspicuously absent. Although Abubakar said this
past week that the death of Abiola represented ``one of the saddest
moments of our life,'' he was a prominent member of the government
of Gen. Sani Abacha that jailed him.
</P>
<P>
   Given the impassioned mood of the mourners, any attempt by
military figures to appear would almost certainly have led to
bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   The army and military police officers initially deployed about
50 yards from Abiola's house, but later fell back before
protesters, taking up positions about 500 yards away from it.
Although they blocked some people, they did not use their automatic
rifles. Clearly, Abubakar had called for restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola, a man of the southwestern Yoruba tribe who had converted
to Islam, the faith of the Hausa and closely related Fulani tribes
of the north, tried to overcome the ethnic divisions of his
country.
</P>
<P>
   His death, just as it seemed he would be freed, has left many
Nigerians with a sense of deep frustration at a moment when
Abubakar is talking about the need to put the army back in the
barracks and restore democracy. Sporadic rioting, in which as many
as 50 people have died, has gripped the country since Tuesday, but
Lagos was calm Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who arrived here on Thursday, said the autopsy showed
that Abiola had longstanding heart disease of two types, both of
which could cause unexpected death. ``There was severe narrowing of
the main coronary arteries by fatty plaques,'' he said. ``In
addition there was very significant enlargement of the heart due to
longstanding hypertension.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor declined to be drawn into discussing whether four
years of imprisonment might have contributed to this hypertension
by causing extreme stress. ``Is it desirable to have the best of
diets and the most stress-free life?'' he said. ``Yes, of course it
is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
