<DOCNO> NYT19980711.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-11 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0945 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SONOFSAM-MOVIE-NYT &LR;      07-11 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SONOFSAM-MOVIE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS OF SON OF SAM VICTIM ARE ANGERED BY PLANNED MOVIE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was late one July night in 1976 that David
Berkowitz, the serial killer known as the Son of Sam, opened fire
on Donna Lauria, an 18-year-old emergency medical technician, in
front of her family's home in the Westchester Heights section of
the Bronx, near the Throgs Neck Bridge. The shooting, and those
that followed, cast a pall of fear and sorrow over the city.
</P>
<P>
   Now preparations for a Spike Lee movie tentatively called
``Summer of Sam,'' about the era and how people in the area were
affected by the shootings, which left six people dead and seven
injured, are summoning those bitter memories.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lauria's parents, Michael and Rose Lauria, and their
supporters looked on disapprovingly Saturday as hundreds of people
lined up at the American Legion Post only a mile or two from their
home at a casting call for extras in the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to make money and I'm going to make
heartaches,'' said Lauria as he stood stiffly behind a police
barricade, a picture of his lost daughter pinned to his tan shirt.
``They're exploiting us and the other victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it has been 22 years since the Son of Sam prowled New
York, Lauria still leads the local chapter of a group called
Parents of Murdered Children, at Calvary Hospital on Eastchester
Road in the Bronx on the third Saturday of every month. And on the
anniversary of his daughter's death, he said, there are always
people who come knocking at their door, asking questions.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the people in line said they felt bad for the Laurias,
but most saw little harm in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the right to protest,'' said Lauren Stoltze,
gesturing at the Laurias. ``I feel bad that people are making money
off their pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the person most unnerved by the Laurias' protest was
Victor Colicchio, who wrote the original script for ``Summer of
Sam.''
</P>
<P>
   The project had seemed a breakthrough for Colicchio. Spike Lee
had agreed to direct it. Financing was falling into place.
Colicchio said he had not anticipated the pain it would bring to
the victim's parents, whom he met for the first time Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Colicchio called the Laurias' loss ``heartbreaking,'' and
nervously smoked cigarette after cigarette as he talked about
meeting them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to let me know how they felt, and I couldn't argue
with them since I'm a father, too,'' he said. He said he could not
stop the film, but would suggest dedicating it to the victims.
</P>
<P>
   But then he shook his head. ``I feel terrible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A slender, dark-haired man in his mid-40s, Colicchio, too, grew
up in the Throgs Neck area. He said the script was, in part, an
attempt to exorcise the past, when he and a group of friends tried
to find the murderer and turn him in, but ended up beating up a man
who turned out not to be the killer.
</P>
<P>
   The movie centers on the man they attacked, who Colicchio said
was a neighborhood resident who belonged to a punk rock group. ``He
looked punkier and punkier, and we thought he was part of a cult,''
said Colicchio. ``We went after him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily, the police came,'' he said. ``And the next day they
caught the real killer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
